text: s- a very beatiful hop aroma it has a good mix of a citrus hop smell and a piney hop smell t- the smell does n't reach the bar that the smell set .  mouthfeel was super dry , yet still drinkable enough .

a very nice smell for a dry irish stout .  i never understand why beers like this always come so highly rated here on ba . plenty of caramel taste ( and flavour ) smooth and a little thick.i drank one cold and one warm to compare taste , niether was better than the other , pretty bland really overall .
really great looking beer .  a little too carbonated for my liking . a little smoothness would help .

the nose , like i 've found with the other recent nb lof releases ( super cru and le terroir ) , is very clean for something belgian in style- festive almost with a country store kind of vibe with its vibrant aromas of spiced apple jam , bread dough , caramel , raisins , poached pears and chocolate . very lush . the palate is medium-bodied and moderately sweet with a husky maltiness and a serious combo of yeasty flavors and fruity esters that smelt very powerfully to me like juicy fruit gum . there were some very tightly integrated spices , a bit of boozy alcohol and a mildly bitter coating of rich cocoa . nothing incredibly spicy , musky or unbridled .  the first sip reveals and average body with very fine tingly carbonation . the body is a little lighter than i expected and not quite as sticky as hoped .
starts out with a spectacular pour ; a clear ruby copper with a never-ending ivory pillow floating on top lacing like a boot on the way down .  very dry . a definite sipper .

a - clear caramel amber color with a foamy off-white head . great retention and lacing covering the entire glass !  could easily pass for an ipa . mf- zesty carbonation livens up the body a bit but the weight is hard to perceive .

smell was strong and citrusy and full of fruits with extra vitamin c. from oranges to orange peels to tangerines to grapefruit . the smell stuck in your senses for an unusually long time . first thing i noticed about the taste was how clean and refreshing it was . really citrusy that cleans out your nose . orange peels reign supreme with the taste .  cocoa powder taste , not too sweet , has a bite to it . not too bad for an irish stout .

22oz bomber pours a dark reddish brown with large dense tan head . long retention and tons of lacing .  m : smooth and creamy , but it does feel watery on the mid-palate , maybe i expected more with the thick motor oil-esque appearance , but i wish this was a little more beefed up . d : aside from the minor mouthfeel problems which really were n't a big deal to me , this is a very good black lager .

smell : raw cocoa , sawdust , roasted peanuts , malt , ripe plum . bold aroma . this is very nice . mouthfeel : smoothe through the start and ends with a dryness accompanied by some alcohol .  m : a little thin for my taste especially for a winter beer , but other positive aspects more than make up for it .

this has a fantastic nose . cookie dough , bready yeastiness , fermentation esters , pepper , a little lemon and the slightest of nuances of alcohol . the same nice doughiness from the nose translates nicely to the buds . good stuff .  mouthfeel enters well with strong carbonation but it fizzes out as it moves back and is quite bloating after swallow .

a battle with the cork leads to a convincing auburn beauty with two fingers of head .  a mild estery maltiness comes through , very sweet , with minimal hops . the flavor is basically all butterscotch diacetyl . nothing else comes through besides a creamy cloying buttery sugary flavor . pretty terrible . i would have rather had a budweiser .

s : believe it or not , a strong apricot smell . it smells like someone actually grabbed the fruit and cut it open . t : apricot is n't as potent as in the scent , but definitely there .  i must say i was quite surprised by this one . i am a beer buyer for a grocery store in cambridge and one of my reps passed me this and after drinking this one it will certainly be a staple in my store . its pours just gorgeous into a pint glass and just tastes like a dream just a great beer overall .
tart raspberries and sweet fruit as well . overall , an interesting beer .  m-this is just a little grainy , syrupy up front , light thin body , a little too thin .

this helles is picturesque : mounds of bright white head , and a light golden body with plenty of carbonation to make the foam rise above my stein .  m-a little light on the body , for which a higher level of carbonation revs up and slightly compensates . it 's refreshing , complex , and light .

this beer pours a murky deep brown with a explosive and billowing head ... looks nice in the glass .  mouthfeel is thin but appropriate for the style , i would like to see just a bit more of bite from the carbonation though .
great nose of winter spices and belgian candi sugar and malt . mouthfeel is medium bodied , nicely carbonated and with a very nice balance and medium richness .  mouthfeel - light on the bubbles .

a : thick black with a nice , full half-inch of cream-colored head that remains big the entire way down . generous clumps of thick lacing down the entire glass .  m - definitely this beer 's weakpoint . when too cold its too watery . it 's a little over overcarbonated as well .

nose was my favorite thing about this beer . very hops , but they were not abrasive on the schnozz . very piney and christmas . the hops are still very nice and make this a very easy beer to drink .  a dark chocolate bitterness floating right above a very light body of roasted grains . at 3.3 abv this is a very light and highly drinkable session beer . almost too easy to drink . a unique beer in a special style .

poured from the 12 oz bottle into a pint glass - noticed a surprising amount of head right away . the swirling and churning inside the glass as the head receded was quite pleasant actually .  mouthfeel : medium body , sticky , sweet , and carbonated .

pours semi-thick red with a gorgeous foamy light tan head that resembles a nitro pour ... leaves tons of rings of sticky lacing and holds a foamy cap .  t- smooth with just the right amount of hops with a slight bitterness/ dryness in the finish m- a bit thinner than i antisipated , but about on par with others in this style d- an easy drinker with a subtle complexity , will i be having this again ?

pours a clear red amber color with a nice film of foam retaining well atop the liquid the smell is fantastic , i picked up whiffs of it as i poured the beer and felt my mouth watering .  a little on the flat side .
it 's as black as eternity . a nice looking creamy brown head sits on top and recedes to a good sized collar in a minute . the lacing is sparse .  mouthfeel is dry and somewhat chalky .
great looking stout !  a little too thin and carbonated .

serving type and glassware : 1.9 pint bottle poured into 16 oz tumbler a - off-white head , not lingering , low apparent carbonation with a transparent copper color s - sweet candy-like smell , cherry lolipop comes to mind ( corny i know but oh well thats what i thought ) , really the smell is one of the highlights of this beer t - equally as sweet , some toastiness pulling through with a slight bitterness in the finish , a mildly present alcohol taste throughout m - stickiness of the malt is the feature to note here , with a medium-light body all around i bought this beer on a whim and was n't disappointed .  the body is a tad thin compared to others i 've had but smooth as can be .

nose is really nice , chewy malt , brown sugar , spicy oak , lots of dark fruit and a well integrated bourbon . all in all the flavor profile is characterized by hot alcohol that 's medicinal at times and is quite harsh . overrated .  the malt character is very subdued in this ipa . if a beer could ever be considered juicy ... this is it . not much body to this , as someone else mentioned more like a really hoppy pale ale . that said , i still find this to be quite a successful ipa the citrus flavors are really great and fresh tasting .
bomber , 2007 vintage , 6.7 % alcohol , a : pours black , with a full light tan head , great retention and lacing in my tulip .  carbonation is average .

awesome aroma of floral , hoppy goodness . soft-citrus and other fruity esters with an edge of cotton-candy or bubblegum . complexly fragrant nothing screams at you individually , but theres no mistaking some serious dry-hopping is going on but in a balanced way . caramely sweetness is candy-like and the darkish malts lend an unexpected chocolately character which im not sure im digging .  the beers appearance is average , lacks in color to be above average ( looked a little watery to be honest ) . the taste is great , smooth , hoppy , fruity all i expected and more . this is a very drinkable beer in fact i killed a 4 pack when trying it for the first time ... .great job dfh .

bomber , with the man himself on the cover , a : pours a dark red , with a thick , full , frothy white head , great retention , leaving medium lacing .  this was much like the carolina pale ale , but naturally hoppier . there was a good balance between the malt and hops ; it was quite bitter , but there seemed to be more flavoring hops than anything . unlike the carolina pale ale , i would drink this while out of the state as it is one of the more balancced ipas i have had .
a - bright copper with a bit more orange tint ; head was over 1/2-inch and receded slowly , with great lacing .  m & # 8211 ; smooth , no complaints , but it doesn & # 8217 ; t enhance the flavor .

it looks like a beautiful beer , very bright and golden , with carbonation bubbles finding their way surfaceward to take their place among a nice bubbly head that lingers a bit and lightly hugs the glass .  m - slightly thin , decent carbonation .
light for a bottle presenting itself like this . the shining points are the quality pure flavors , not fake which do make it worth a couple extra bucks .  m - this is a bit thin .

a : cracked open and thrown into a most appropriate dfh snifter.crystal clear ruby/garnet colour with a moderate head that dissapates quickly . looks very nice the way the light strikes it .  m : a little bit thin , and slightly alcoholic o : a solid belgian strong blonde , but ca n't touch duvel .

the beer pours a brownish amber with a huge off white head that dissipates into a thin layer around the outside of the glass .  tastes like a pilsner on the back end m - stays mostly in the front part of the mouth , so somewhat limited overall in this respect d - at 3 % , this is something you could literally drink all day and not feel it .
the nitrogen generated foam rises to leave a dark black body and a pale , off-white , one inch thick head .  the mouthfeel is just a touch too thin .
a : nice golden color . good head retention with small bubbles , brilliant bright filtration .  m - has a light mouthfeel , with an average amount of carbonation .
great lacing and good head retention smell : toasted malt & that 's it taste : toasted malt , slight fruittiness and iron taste .  watery coffee . some chocolate , a little dusty .

the smell is , oh my , pumpkin pie . if nothing else , they have successfully recreated the smell of a fresh pumpkin pie .  i would like to add that some reviews have compared sweetgrass to a west coast ipa ... very misleading . the malt bill on this brew is fairly complex ( idaho 2-row , german vienna , caraamber , belgian caravvienne ) as is the hop bill ( ukg , willamette , galena , amarillo , czech saaz , cascade ) . however , the ibu 's , hop flavor and aroma are not really agressive enough to hit the west coast style expectations . but i think this is a nice `` session '' style beer at 5.5 % ( 1.062 og ) . maybe east coast style yeast ?

very roasty , with hints of oatmeal , vanilla , caramel , chocolate and butter . overall impression : delivers an intense yet superior look and smell with a less-impressive yet solid flavor , finish and feel .  very interesting beer , first wiff is on a grassy pine hop , yet it is more a citrus hop taste to the tongue ? pours a orangish hazey color with a white head . enjoyed the flavors , a very unique brew ... would recomend to anyone who likes a differntly hopped beer .

fortunately , the aroma of this beer is much more pleasant than the appearance . huge silky chocolate malt presence with hints of roasted malt , coffee bean , burnt toast and oatmeal . this smells excellent ! soft carbonation tickling the tongue up front followed by a silky , slight viscous chewy mouthfeel that thins out toward the finish which is hot and dry . the silky chocolate malt notes from the aroma are very faint and are completely overpowered by the overwhelming heat . the earthy/oak barrel notes are also faint and the vanilla hints from the aroma are absent .  i can not begin to describe how completely vile and repulsive i found this beer . the aroma alone was enough to make me wretch ... i did n't vomit , but i could have , and the flavor just brought me closer . however , that said , i do understand that this is a big thing in the midwest ( they used to mix their own ! i ca n't even say it 's to style . well made , well yes , i guess . sorry a-b , i ca n't do any better .
a gorgeous cloudy amber-orange . i love when beers look like this .  a bit too light in mouthfeel .

looks gorgeous , black with a short tan head .  pours well , very little head on it and carbonation . a very dark ale , i guess i was expecting something a little more malty but i ca n't really complain about this beer .

pine branches and mint , with a touch of passionfruit and pineapple . so much promise from the appearance and aroma but i absolutely ca n't forgive the butchering of the flavour profile .  the mouthfeel is okay , but not the highlight of this beer .

the hefe-weisse poured a delightfully creamy gold it had a thin head that quickly dissipated .  m : thinner and not as heavy as i would have assumed from the appearance and smell , still leaning toward a medium feel however . very pleasant . d : the thinner than expected mouth feel and very smooth taste make this a very session-able porter .

s : a orange and citrusy sweet smell over some grainy notes and bit of spice , a very nice bouquet . if this thing tastes half as good as it smells , it 's a winner .  m : gently creamy carbonation , perhaps a little thin overall .

bought this on impulse because of the great looking bottle . the appearance was quite nice .  `` bobby bob beer , best beer in vietnam . '' there is a whole lot of something going on with the aromas in this beer , but i 'll be damned if i could tell you what in the hell they were . it reminded me of walking into high school biology class on the first day , and being greeted by the smell of old formaldehyde from the specimen jars ( yes , i too dissected a fetal pig ) . formaldhyde nose , formaldehyde finish , and very little going on in between .
the pour was pitch black with a creamy two finger head that slowly dissapated and left a thick beige cream on top of the beer .  if it tastes like paint thinner , do not drink .

the beer pours perfectly with a nice hazy orange hue to it that passes almost no light through it , a solid white foamy head , and great lacing on the glass at all time .  it 's thinner than i like , particularly for an oatmeal stout .
sweet , floral hoppy aromas . a very interesting smooth ipa with very little , if any , of the grapefruit accents inherent in the style .  mouthfeel is alright .
big piney aroma along with pineapple and grapefruit .  mouthfeel is light for the beer type .

monumental nose of honeysuckle in full bloom , beach walks at dusk and fruit-flavored marshmallows . a draught is honey-roasted peach on barn board with a side of soil covered garden greens and fallow field stones . i mean earthy , like when you were a kid and played in the lake and dug in the dirt and ate roasted corn and tasted the day on your lips . playful across the buds . a fine brew .  this beer is n't setting any records or braking any molds but it has been around for a long time and it pretty much sums up the catagory it belongs in . it is a golden american lager , crisp , clean , refreshing , it has more flavor than most of the others in the style ( in that style ) , and goes very well with lunch or if your in the mood for something easy drinking .

the lacing is there ... not super thick , but not spotty ... smells like a good dipa should ... actually reminds me of a combination of sculpin and alesmith ipa . a nice bready malt and big fresh citrus hops ... has a little alcohol bite that reminds me of a barleywine .  mouthfeel : full to medium body .
it has a slick oily look with excellent lacing .  mouthfeel was medium but the taste was very spicy , almost like a belgian wit !

1 '' first thought - the appearance is absolutely phenomenal on this one ... pours a jet-black , deep , rich purple-hue with a massive-sized foamy and frothy head that exhibited enormous staying power and left a copious amount of lacing around the head of the glass .  the mouthfeel was highly carbonated , but not in a good way .

it poured a nice opaque black with a 1/2 inch tan head , but the head had an interesting white ring around the head ( after tasting i figured it could have been cleaner sediment , but it sure looked cool ) .  average finish length , moderate sweetness . full , sticky , alcoholic body , rather astringent as well .
a - near black with a tall tan head that lasts and leaves light lacing s - majority of the scent if from bourbon , but it is not too strong .  i would like to see more body on this one .

a-reddish gold with a thick light tan head , quite a neat site actually s-i 'll be honest , it smells like something in between a heavy belgian white ale and a champagne ... leaning more towards the champagne ... unfortunately .  m : medium body , high carbonation too high , as it starts out painfully prickly before settling into a smoother frothiness .
reviewed 11/6/2009 ( bottle ) : pours a strong reddish color body , average foamy creamy off-white head , lasting .  m- a bit on the light side for a stout but still fantastic .
a - pours deep black with a one finger chocolatey head - looks fantastic s - smells of chocolatey malts and a touc of coffee .  mouthfeel is a little thin but overall a good beer .

poured a near opaque brown/black with a billowing , moussey , two-finger , cocoa colored head that faded to a creamy , lasting cap . quite impressive for a beer of such humble stature . by looks alone , this is a very deceiving beer .  d. very high , the light body and flavors would make this a great session beer .

all in all , a pretty beer with a great smell and decent taste that was not all that easy to get through .  a faint taste is present ( maybe honey ? ) . it is for all intensive purposes an average beer with a pleasant cherry taste . mainly because i think it will fill a good void of giving me the drink i need when i am not in the mood for a stronger beer .

a- pours black with no highlights . nice looking start .  looks more like a macro lager than a pale . head fades down to a soapy layer . slightly hoppy , watery smell with a bit of sweet-fruityness in the background . tastes slightly hoppy with a sourness mixed in all the way through . bit of fruity sweetness cloyingly there . really does n't taste anything like a pale ale .
on tap woodshop classix anaheim , ca clear golden and orange with a soapy , frothy white head . an incredible and overwhelming lavender explosion , and little to nothing else .  pretty thin feel .
it has a very interesting look because of the lasting head and retention .  mouthfeel is good if a bit thin and that may be one of the beers few shortcomings .

poured into a new duvel tulip a - pours a cloudy straw haze with a fluffy two finger head . just a great , great appearance . was really expecting and hoping for some sort of rose smell .  recommended by shady at the waterhuis in ghent , thanks . appearance was chestnut brown with a medium tan head and slight lacing . smell was of freshly cut hay and light spice . taste was hoppier than most browns , a good balance of bitter and sweet . very good choice , quite enjoyable and unique .

it 's lightly sweet and has a bit of an acidic tang - actually , quite a good fore-flavor - but there 's not much in the back except for the alcohol and a hint of cherries .  little carbination and just lightweight in the mouthfeel department .

pours black with hints of mahogany when held to light . rich , thick tan head makes for an inviting brew .  m thin , light , somewhat watery with decent carbonation especially at the front and sides .

12 oz can poured into a snifter fridge temp 2008 appearance : pours a cloudy brown color with a 1.5 '' head that has great retention . craterous head with plenty of lace .  m - goes down as easy as any ipa would .

very good ! after the scent , i was so excited . a strange boozy mess . a very odd blend of flavors .  carbonation seems high for an ipa but head and lacing are a bit below average . at first sip it is a refreshing / light to medium pilsner body that encourages you to gulp a little more confidently untill a few mouthfuls later you are in a caught up in the aroma all the while never minding it . this is a classy beer and makes one feel classy .

pours a dark almost black like a stout , but with a grey head . it smells very piney citrusey like a freshly brewed ipa so bitter . overall another excellent offering from stone .  smell : big cloying sweetness not appealing at all . taste : bit of smooth crispness , cloying sweetness gets to be a bit unbearable . hops are minimal and the sweetness tastes fake . lame maltiness sweetness all over the place .
a - color is positive . it 's a dark coffee / cola color . there was strong pretty lacing .  mouthfeel : lots of carbonation , feels light and airy .
the beer is topped by an enormous tan head that remains intact for quite a while . generous portion of lacing veil the side of the glass .  mouthfeel is mild with little carbonation .

pours out a cloudy lemonade with a bulbous head that leaves thick sheets of lace along the side of the glass .  i saw that it was a kenyan lager and i almost did n't even want to try it . being the ticker that i am , i gave it a shot , and this is exactly why we do n't judge a beer by its location ... appearance nothing to note ... aroma is light and sweet , corn , but you 'd expect tons of skunk and none is present ... the aroma is light and sweet , not at all a typical lager . this is n't a great beer but it exceeds expectations for a lager and a kenyan beer .

new label , dictator series , batch 13 , march 2011 pours a majestic crystal clear deep orange/red with a thick fluffy white sudsy head . gorgeous richness and clarity on the appearance .  ~can easily pick out the port-i-ness , this is a wonderfully complex beer . ~feels a bit too tingly , and is distracting .

original rating date : august 22 , 2008 great hoppy scent , pours nice and golden with a large head that is especially doughy after settling . really hoppy , but only hoppy .  m - the feel is dry but not too dry . i think the feel in this brew may have been an accident . there 's allot of carbonation making for a coarse texture , which seems to be contradictory compared to most other dry feeling beers i 've had .
crisp golden malt aroma with a generous dash of floral hop at the end . very appealing . the flavor is extremely hoppy .  mouthfeel : medium mouthfeel is okay .
very interesting and exciting looking pilsner .  m : aftertaste is rather short . body is light .
a : pours pitch black . a two finger tan head forms in my tulip glass . rings of sticky lace are left clinging to the glass .  a little thin .

great looking heart of darkness color , dark tan head .  taste starts out quite yeasty , the other flavors eventually develop where you can pick out a bit of orange and clove , carbonation is quite assertive and sharp at first , the alcohol might have something to do with that since it 's not overly well hidden .

enjoyed in my chimay goblet : rich , ruby red coloration with a thin , white head and a touch more carbonation than its brother beers ( blue & white ) . no other red brew looks this majestic , while still being mysterious and imposing .  mouthfeel is nice and oily , but too much lingering carbonation adds an almost acidic feeling on the tongue .

the hop aroma was so intense , fruity and fresh . the hop aroma was so pungent any secondary smells were buried . i would buy this beer for an air freshener it smells so good . the flavor does not quite add up to the aroma , but that should not be taken as a negative statement . very good apa , honestly the best apa i have had in a while .  m : it was thin with lots of natural carbonation . a bit weak .

i would usually assume it 's yeast but it looks like a pile of seeds . if this tastes as sweet as it smells this could be trouble . sweet , drying aftertaste ( presumably from the honey ) that lingers forever . juniper adds a little bit of resin texture that i 'm a huge fan of . sweet , but not as sweet as it smells -- delicious and drinkable but definitely a bottle for splitting . surprised to see it weighs in at 11 % abv . one of the more interesting beers i 've had as of late .  mouthfeel is a bit dissapointing because of the flavor leaving the palate all at once .

a- black/opaque body with no light perception , with a creamy rocky chocolate milkshake brown head , with excellent retention and lots of sticky lace .  flavor takes it 's initial shape with the same wonderful attributes , but seems lacking in malt richness , and comes off a little thin .
a sexy beer pour , oaken cola brown , clear - with a very sticky tan head - leaving a sheet of lace in my corsendork tulip .  feels well carbonated , possibly a bit too much to enjoy the complexity .

aroma is fantastic ! i have n't been thrilled with most jolly pumpkins , but this one is starting off great . awesome tart and funky notes , distant earthy/spiciness .  the light body is not intimidating , however makes up for flavor and aroma . the taste is smooth , dry , and nutty . this is a decent brew .

the beer looks amazing on the pour , but after that it all seemed to go downhill for me .  m - medium in body , but on the somewhat lighter side . creamy and smooth though . little to no carbonation .

a : dark brown , almost black with a light brown head that crackles away s : as the bottle says roasted barley and you can smell it along with the slight sweetness/ fruitiness .  light bodied , a lot of carbonation , no real aftertaste .
it looks perfect . the head stays around quite a while and leaves some great lacing .  m : light carbonation foaming on your mouth , medium body .

i was impressed with the appearance and feel of this beer right away .  i had this beer 1st on draft and then found it in a bottle at ht . i ca n't understand anyone grading this beer below an a the smell and the taste is just threw the roof . i have already hooked 4 other people on this beer . one of the few beers that i have had on tap and then found in a bottle that was even close to its draft flavor . this has become my new favorite . the only issue so far is i ca n't drink less than 3 of these in a session and this is truley a session beer

4.4 % abv , jun3011 a - beautiful golden beer with great clarity and a stunning white head , the three fingers of foam hung out for a while and caked the glass with thick lace .  fine pour , average beer carbonation , small head . tastes like a weak wheat beer with intense cherry flavor that exactly matches the aroma . smooth , even flavor through the finish with aftertaste of cherry .

pleasant , all in all a characteristic profile and very very good . t : slightly too bitter for my taste , but still oh so refreshing and tasteful .  smell was average , mouthfeel a bit on the thin side .

s- if i could consume this beer by smelling it ( and not drinking any ) , i would because the smell is rather impressive . the hops impart a nice citrusy aroma ( particularly lemons and oranges ) and a piney aroma as well .  i was pleasantly surprised with the smooth taste and more important .. the aftertaste . also , i liked the size of the bottle and the appearance of the label . my hat is off to the polish on this one . this beer deserves american translation about the brewery and other bottle infomation .

pours a very pretty deep rich brown with red highlights . it 's got some haze to it and really looks classic to the style . really dark body yields a light brown fluffy 2finer head that is thick and rich .  mouthfeel was watery like cola . a little thicker , and this beer could be top notch by critics standards .

sampling a 2004 version of this ale , sent to me by my buddy sulldaddy . it pours a chestnut/ruby color with a slightly fizzy head that lessened to a slight edge layer with minimal lacing on the glass ; very clean looking ale , which is always nice . aroma up front is vanilla with an underlying sour aroma with dry oak aromas throughout as well ; lots of alcohol on the sniff which killed some aromas ; reminded me a lot of a bourbon or maybe even a dry sherry . i loved this one really .  mouthfeel was light to medium in body and watery in texture with a lively carbonation .

smell was sweet , very malty . this beer smelled wonderful ... ..but it fell short on taste .  the hops come through strong on the first taste with the caramel malt and spices lingering for a crisp almost bitter finish . a rather nice offering from rogue but not as outstanding as some of their other brews .
amazing lacing .  the palate is medium bodied with an earthy malt character that is subdued by the by the fairly strong but not overpowering hops .

appearance : pours a clear amber color with two fingers of fluffy off white head that leaves some very nice lacing .  i poured this beer into my tumbler at 50 degrees then poured it out of my tumbler and into the sink . the bber was a light mahoganny color with a light orangy looking head . the smell was of sour something with a bit of a caralally smell . the taste was sour gross sour yuk ... too me . the sourness was just overpowering of rotten fruit and bout gagged me . i will not buy again .

serving : bomber poured into tall snifter appearance : almost black , ca n't see through it even when held up to light , very minimal off white head smell : first off i must say this beer has an impressive and wonderful aroma but it is all wrong for an imperial stout . black coffee , chocolate , roasty . notes : i thoroughly enjoyed this beer but i am afraid someone must have switched the labels .  the palate is perhaps a little too light and carbonated , but perhaps anything heavier could have made this cloying , so i 'll give it a pass .

dark brown , coffee color , light barely makes it through , with a rich tan head with large bubbles .  m : crisp , sticky , not that dry , medium bodied . d : a good tasting beer , but too big of a body that does n't really fit the style .

came out an almost brown clear copper under a beige one finger head with good retention and full lace sheeting .  this was another beer that i tried at a trade show . a nice head formed on the beer and it lasted through my drinking of it . it had a bit of a strong taste but not overpowering . it did n't have a pronounced hops/wheat/barley flavor , just a nice combination of them all . i do prefer the brewery 's 90 minute ipa more so , but this pulled a close second .

s- the smell of pineapple weed hops has a slight skunky note ( that is a good skunk ) with an apricot smell to it . the hops are very fresh and earthy and i ca n't stop sniffing them .  body is a touch too thin .
pours a delightful apricot . the lace is striking and the retention is glorious . a very attractive beer .  body is also average for most ales , a little light for a scottish ale .
anyway , the aroma is potent , yet very pleasant . taste is a little off balance , similar to the 120 ipa .  feels average in the mouth . nice carbonation .

my `` o-fest fest '' continues ... attractive -- clear reddish amber , nice darker yellow head of 1/2 inch .  i had this beer at the alaskan bush company . i also had it on tap at a local pub . great pour creamy head , roasty nose , i could not compare to anything , miller lite was about the only othe beer they had to offer . overall very drinkable is it available in the mid west ? ?

my gentlest of pours still created better than two thick fingers of tawny head with excellent retention . drool ! as the massive head slowly fell , it created some beautiful lacing .  m - a little thin in body , but a decent sweet , and cloying flavor .

a - a huge frothy white head sits on top of a clear copper brew . the hed dissipates in minutes leaving thin rings of lacing at every sip .  it has a plain mouthfeel , but it is smooth and delectable .

pours an apricot colour , almost opaque from sediment bomb that 's detonated in the body . head is voluminous to the max , irregularly bubbled and beige in colour , leaves a gorgeous pollock canvas of lace down the glass . colour ? tick . cloud ?  reviewed 4/15/2006 ( 12oz bottle bottled on 02/03/06 ) : pours an amber golden color body , very fizzy . has a huge head , white , good lacing , slowly diminishing . a very hoppy aroma , pale , and dry . bitter taste , semi-sweet aftertaste , semi-pale , semi-bitter . good balanced taste .

pours a nice one inch white head that is creamy with some bubbles . good retention and huge lacing .  light to medium mouth feel . tastes great.full flavor , with a little bite . for a dark beer it 's refreshing .

the huge champagne head and pink hue were beautiful , but it tasted like sour patch kids without the sweetness .  mouthfeel : nice mouth-coating , but a much weaker carbonation than i was expecting ( the tap ? ) .
initial big foamy tan head that quickly subsides to nice small layer of foam with good lacing .  m : a medium/full body with a very light , almost absent carbonation .

good lacing s : strong smell of coffee beans , smells earthy t : tastes same as smell , good strong coffee flavor .  a robust stout - on the bitter side but just right . mouthfeel : spicy carbonation on the tongue - slick , but otherwise a little watery . maybe a little too carbonated - it overwhelms everything else with a nice big drink , but it more manageable when the beer is sipped .

very inviting . t : smacks you right in the face with a smokey taste .  coffee dominates the taste but its bitter and boring , just not feeling the flavor ... the mouthfeel is almost an afterthought because its so light and boring .

very nice aroma . starts off sweet and creamy .  this was the best north american beer i 've ever had from a can . while it ca n't touch a holsten festbock , it was a very nice brown ale and offered something that others do n't . it was almost buttery once you tasted the sour/ grain notes . very complex , and very tasty . worth a try , any time .

aroma : beautiful scent , flowery , cherries , peach , cloves , spicy , fruity , oak . visuals : simple , beautiful packaging , cloudy iced tea , deep reddish brown , nearly opaque , staying white head , intricate fresh lace . a bit expensive for what it is , understandably so , but a very nice experience . http : //beercritic.wordpress.com/2009/01/04/st-bernardus-pater-6/  the mouthfeel is light and carbonation is moderate .

aromas of strong jalepeno and other hot peppers . very expressive chile pepper aroma and flavor are enticing , but the extreme heat makes it challanging to drink .  pours clear , copper with medium-dense head of beige bubbles . little lacing . hoppy , full-bodied flavor , but not floral . some sweet maltiness . my only qualm is with a bit of a sharp bite and some cereal flavor . similar to their pale ale in taste , but much more robust and flavorful .
poured a nice golden yellow with a bit of cloudyness , and a huge pillowy head , great lacing and retention .  mouf & gt ; seltzery . not fab .

received in a trade with almalkin a - poured a deep amber with a nice white head that fell moderately into a nice lacing around the glass s - this is the hallmark of this beer ... big smell..nice sweet pumpkin and spice smell with a hint of hops..very enticing t - the taste was a bit of a let down for me.admittedly i 'm not a huge pumpkin fan also though..the beer had a nice malty taste with a bit of a biscuit or bread flavor along with spice like maybe cinnimon ( sp ? ) and then pumpkin..overall it was good m - nice carbonation , but the beer was a little thick almost like a stout..coated the mouth and tongue..pretty good d - i would n't want this all the time..but it 's a great break to regular beers and certainly has it 's place in the fridge when the leaves start turning colors..  mouth is lacking in carbination expected . also a little thinner in the mouth than expected .

clear dark copper colour with a large , creamy off-white head . good lacing .  i love good double ipa 's . however this one was a huge dissapointment . beer was very cloudy , i thought they gave me a german style hefeweiss it was so bad . hops were present but were lacking for a double ipa . the beer was really out of balance , big bitterness but no flavor to back it up .

deep , rich cloudy red with about two inches of foamy , off-white head that took a while to dissolve and left noticeable lacing on the snifter .  mouthfeel is just average , the carbonation is much too low for a tripel .

a- really creamy looking , huge head with a nice cascade down the glass . a real nicely made brew s- i get a real smell of butterscotch and orange and grapefruit , very nice aroma to this one , the cask , being that its a bit warmer really brings out the smell t- much better than on regular cask , very creamy mouth feel to it , like as said the hops just come at ya , great malt profile biscuit like .  mouthfeel was a bit of a letdown- on the thin side and made the beer seem less substantial .

bought after the beer meeting - $ 96 later ... golden , big fluffy head , lacing : grade a+ ... bitter , sweet , flavourful , beehive , delicious ... like a hoppppy tripppel .. abv is well hidden ... does the dutch proud ... 'i would n't leave the bar if i could find this on tap ' .. just an enjoyable brew , but the hophead in me says 'more hops !  great looking beer . looks like carbonated orange juice or maybe a mimosa . beers do n't look much better than this . fresh squeezed grapefruit , peach , flint , light lemon and apricot . nice hop forward dipa here . major flaw is in the finish where the hop bitterness gets a little astringent and out of whack leaving a chalky , filmy residue on the palate . again the bread driven malts show some toffee notes in the middle are balanced by high alpha hops leaving a resiny citrus burst throughout . grapefruit and lemon , with some hints of orange , peach , pineapple , and other fruity flavors . if not for the finish this would have been spectacular .

poured mohogany with an inch tall head that just sat perched there the entire time . tough lacing left a ring down the glass every sip , ending with bars of lacing after the beer was gone .  mouthfeel - average weight , above average bubbles .

deep brown to dark amber with next to no bead but a creamy head that sticks there throughout .  it has some zesty lemon/lime , a bit of grain , and some mineral water . it has a lot of flavor , though it is a bit blunt . it is supremely drinkable .

the bottle poured ruby red with a large billowy light coco brown head .  served from a 2 liter flip top bottle bought at the brewery , poured into a pint glass bought from the brewery . light amber color in glass , hazy finish . big head that dissipated quickly , little lacing on glass . light aroma of citrus on pour . went down quickly , i was surprised how fast i finished the first pint . a typical wheat , but a good pint none the less .

very nice . t : unique .  the alcohol starts to peep through on the finish but is in check m : the body on the finish is a little thin for my liking but the carbonation is pleasant and tingling d : this is very very drinkable for the abv
great appearance , the best aspect of this beer no doubt .  there was some even carbonation in the mouthfeel , and a slight aftertaste , but the beer was fairly typical in this regard .

abita pecan ale pours a beautiful dark amber color , and has a big tan head .  poured this from a bottle into a standard pint glass . noticed citric tasting hops over the pale malt . i would say this leans slightly more to an ipa , just slightly . i really enjoyed this and would buy it again .
very deep and complex smell . chocolate , raisins , heavily roasted coffee .  m : relatively average mouthfeel , with nice carbonation .
appearance - big fluffy tan head . great lacing and sticking . looks great .  mouthfeel was disappointingly a bit too thin and watery in the finish for such a big beer .

a huge foamy head rises with incredible action ( not even from an overly vigorous pour ) ... small crevices begin to appear in the fluffy head , but ever so slowly ... .an incredible looking beer s- spicy ... but not one particular spice jumps out ... .sour notes come through with a slight metallic tinge ... .stilly slightly cold ... ( need to refine my smelling skills ) t- the first sip ... .as it moves over the tongue a spicy lemon flavor comes through and then hits you upside the head when as it rolls off the back the tongue m- a fuzzy tingling sensation shows up on the front part of the tongue , but does not detract from the definte smoothness that is apparent once the bolus moves on through ... salivation increases with the intense sourness ( on par with the warheads candy ) d- leaves your mouth wondering `` what was that ?  mouthfeel : light-bodied , slightly oily and a little watery .

a : rich copper color , brilliant clarity , light off-white head , all to style .  truly one of the worst craft brewed beers made out there . thick , meaty , hops way too bitter , boozy , sweet . this is like a grain alcohol , hops , and pork slurry . must be what pork soda is .

a : four fingers of bright white , stiff foamy head with excellent retention . bottle conditioning produces a light cloudiness and lots of interior bubbles .  m : average for a lager -- it 's about the only thing going for this `` king of beers . '' d : incredibly low as there 's nothing bringing me back here .
poured into my tulip glass . a - dark like a trois pistole .  m : somewhat fizzy and a tad overcarbonated .
initial blast of dried apricot blows off to reveal classic cantillon . simply a stunning nose , even for cantillon . and that nose !  body is medium full , but the carbonation is quite low .
it is dark honey colored with a nice frothy light tan head that stays .  mouthfell was abrasive yet thin .

pours dark dark brown almost black with a 1+ finger tan head that left some spotted lacing smells of cherries roasted burnt malts and chocolate taste is very close to the smell - i do find the cherries to be a bit tart but the malts are nicely burnt along with chocolate mouthfeel is a medium body beer that has little carbonation and is a bit slick drinkability is ok - i do like this stout over dark horse blueberry stout  the carbonation is a little weaker than most weissbiers ; the bubbles are small . the liquid is very smooth and a little thick . a textbook example of a hefeweissen , maybe with a slight reservation for the weak carbonation
a beautiful half inch head .  m : medium to thicker body , average carbonation .
reviewed 7/21/2009 ( 2009 bottle ) : pours a clear bright golden colored body , with a big foamy white head , lasting .  very dry , exceptionally dry , is that cotton in my mouth ?

you can not beat the appearance of this stout . a midnight opaque black with a huge creamy and cascading tan head .  s- nutty , maple syrup . t- i an normally a stout or porter guy but this one was really pleasant . you can taste the dark roasted malts and the hint of maple syrup which stays with the palette . m- .. d- i could drink a six-pack in one sitting only thing i would be wary of is the sweetness of the drink .
a : absolutely elegant mahogany to almost black hue , with an supposedly thick and tight frothy beigh head which sustains forever .  m : medium bodied with moderate carb .

a : pours a beautiful 3 finger fluffy white head with great retention . beer itself is a semi-cloudy peach color .  quite a good flavor - bitter , but not anything too strong , with an average duration . light and thin-bodied on the palate , , with average carbonation .

a - this one is a brilliantly alluring honey-gold with a big four finger bone white head . big sticky arcs of lace are deposited all over the glass , and the head shows excellent retention as it slowly creeps down towards a solid fat finger . this is one helluva pretty beer .  carbonation is a bit excessive for me but not prohibitively so .
really really dense , intriguing smell . t- far different than the smell .  the body was medium or just a bit more and lighter than expected .

11.2 oz belgian beer - into a pint glass - labeled 130711 a - golden in color - almost approaching golden brown . head formation is very strong and eggshell white . lots of hazing coming from suspended yeast and other carbonation .  admittedly it could have a much bigger body on it but at least it is well attenuated . a hop might have passed by the brew kettle but if it did , it didnt stay long .

pours beautifully with a fluffy white head and golden yellow body .  some vanilla and spicy noted develop , and the hops meld nicely with the malt flavours and create a balance across the tongue . it 's a bit too intensely carbonated for my tastes , but still a nice beer .

thick and rich hops , quite nice . t : slightly sweet tropical fruit mango/pineapple up front with bright floral oiliness .  whatever , it 's tasty and pretty nice to drink . overall , its smooth , but almost slightly sour porter . definitely worth a try .

a : black ; almost no light coming through . poured a 3 finger rocky mocha-colored head with excellent retention to a 1 finger cap .  mouthfeel/drinkability- lightly carbonated going in , it never gets interesting enough to best highlight the hop and malt features to its potential .

a - an impressive , thick pour . dark copper , rich and vibrant looking with ridiculous off-white head .  medium to thick , perhaps syrupy , though it 's tough to concentrate on the beer 's mouthfeel when it tastes like this . seems a bit under-carbed though , truthfully .
great head retention .  m - medium bodied but very thin and watery overall , even for a cask pull .
nose : fantastic bouquet here , one of the best smelling ipas i 've had to date .  m/d : a medium body , but thin and watery .

malty fresh aroma with slightly spicey twist . this smells like a winner . after such a lovely aroma , i thought i had found a winner , but i will just stick with my andechs .  just a tad too bit flat and oily for me but otherwise a great beer especially at $ 5 per bomber .

poured black as night , nice thick head , with good retention , smell was malty with roasted , chocolate , notes .  the smoked malt is a bit harsh on the palette , and the beer lacks enough body to temper the rough edges in this department .
beautiful amber color with a thick off-white head .  mouthfeel is tingly , aftertaste is of chocolate and hops .

a : pours a nice straw-yellow color with a thick white foamy head , like an ice cream float . slightly cloudy appearance , pretty much perfect for style .  mouthfeel not exceptional , some prickling from coarse carbonation .

nitro can poured a beautiful white head that is sustaining very well .  the taste follows the nose , with malt followed by piney hops . the hoppy aftertaste lingers , which i 'd normally like but i find it a little off-putting in this beer . one is usually enough for me . overall , this is a solid brew that can be had on a budget , can be found everywhere in the u.s. , and is often a lifesaver at bars and restaurants where the only other choices are bmc .

this beer is opaque black in every sense of the word , with a really impressive , pillowy tan head .  pretty much everything great about a czech beer . high drinkable , very refreshing and very crisp . you can smell and taste the hops but they are balanced nicely by the maltiness of this beer . i prefer it to urquel , but you ca n't go wrong with either .

12 oz bottle pours very dark amber , almost brown color with big pillowy offwhite head that leaves huge sticky lacings everywhere . nice !  this one remindes me of rich black coffie and hops mixed . this one is an almost black amber/brown brew that is big and malty . the mouthfeeal is heavy , almost like liquid bread . this one is realy good thank hevans for good bock i wish that this one was avalable all year long but i will get more in spring

pours very dark with ruby highlights . there is a thick , tan , half-inch head , which sticks to the glass .  only complaint with this beer is it wasnt as thick in the mouth as i would have liked , but otherwise , great
this beer pours black with a large lingering tan head that leaves lots of lacing .  mouthfeel : light to medium , but i swallowed as quick as possible to stop the overload .

pours from the nitro tap into an imperial pint glass a brilliant ruby copper .  i was hoping for a belgian strong ale with some woody characteristics , but i got whiskey instead . whiskey aromas , vanilla , bubblegum and spicey alcohol mix together in the aroma and is off putting . pretty much the same going on in flavor with vanilla , whiskey , and coriander-like flavors dominating . odd , oily - almost like mescal - flavors made me want to puke . i tried hard to like this since it was a gift and wanted to tell the gifter that i enjoyed it , but i did n't . someone wake me up when this whiskey barrell aging fad runs its course .

the brew looked great , brown and clear with small bubbly white head . smelled kind of fruity with some caramel aromas - not as clean as i would expect for a lager .  decent mouthfeel despite the taste and thinness of the beer .

rich pumpkin pie on the nose , with cinnamon and nutmeg , very sweet and very delicious . almost the same on the tongue , but not so sweet , with some hops to finish .  m : light , smooth , some carbonation -unassuming to the point of being boring and , frankly , not very good . mouthfeel is disappointing .
wonderful smell . nice and strong .  1 m : alright , not overly thin but could use body and texture .

pours cloudy orange amber color with a dense 2 finger off white head with incredible retention that reduces to a lacing cap . some very nice lacing coats the glass .  my friends and i decided to split this beer and everyone had a different take on how awful it was . one tasted horse manure , another vomit , and another just wild animals ... and not in a good way . this is the second beer i 've ever poured out . it was so horrible we could n't finish it between four people .
a - beautiful deep , matte brown with mahogany highlights when backlit . nice cream-tan head that pours a few fingers high without much effort .  mouthfeel is a bit thin but standard for pilsners .
smells very sweet and aromatic . tastes similar to it 's appearance .  mouthfeel is smooth , but lacking something .

s- strong orange rind , grapefruit , alcohol and some floral notes . t- super sweet upfront , orange , floral hops . d- real boozy , sticky and sweet , makes this one a sipper ill probably not try again .  m - low carbonation left a somewhat flat beer .

lots of mango and slightly woody . t- i wish it tasted like it smelled . definitley mango and a little bit of hops .  ) the only reason the mouthfeel was a little low was because i thought this beer was slightly overcarbonated .
i really enjoyed the overall aroma .  m : its body is kind of on the thin side and somewhat watery .

the smell is fantastic , i wish i had an air freshener that smelled like this !  i found the texture to be a little odd as it felt a little thin on the palate , reminding me more of a porter than a stout , but i could still go through a couple pints in a sitting .

smells wonderful . sweet malt , caramel , cinnamon , prunes , and lots of brown sugar . smells pretty amazing , actually .  mouthfeel : somewhat lackluster . a little too thin in the mouth . it could actually stand a little more carbonation ( just a litle ) too .
n : fresh and dopey hops , and a bit of malt . the complexities are marvelous . p/m : a bit thinner than what the nose promises . slightly watery .  mouthfeel was kind of thin for the serving style .

very little foamy white head erupts , making the appearance reminiscent of an unfiltered hefeweizen with less than normal head . wow , i everything i own to smell like this ! its quite complex , with faint mint , tea , random herbs , juniper , floral hops , and light citrus all melding together in the best way possible . overall , a very unique and delicious beer .  m : fairly full , mouth-filling body , but only a low amount of prickly carbonation ; it gets a little overbearing , especially for a lager .

a -- black in color with dark brown 2 finger head that camped out for quite a while in my 16 oz . goblet and left a nice lacing down the glass s -- nice and creamy roasted coffee scent , a bit fruity as well .  i have been known to sit and smell the beer for five minutes before i drink it . the taste is carmel with a almost pine after taste . after four beers the tart pine after taste is really noticable . i really like this beer . though sometimes they do n't taste right . i do n't know if i just have an old one or maybe it is too new and needs time to mellow .

poured an espresso brown with a dark rich head .  i 've had 2 alpine brews thus far , ph and nelson.. time for the trifecta here ... pours a pale golden with one of the more impressive heads i 've ever seen on an ipa ... this things foams like duvel ... . gentle pour produces a 4 inch head and a steady vibrant stream of bubbles from the sa perfect pint ... citrusy and spicy hops dominate here ... not overpowering or pungent or anything but very nice ... light toasted malts are present as well ... perhaps a little yeastiness as well ... definitely hoppy but i was hoping for a touch more here ... the hops are tasty but there 's not a strong enough presence for me . spicy and herbal ... the brew is overcarbonated for my tastes and i wish that would have been toned down and i might have enjoyed this one more ... it was distracting ... not bad overall but i was n't as big of a fan of this one as some others have been ... a nice beer i guess ...

pours a hazy , glowing golden orange with some suspended yeasties . it has a fluffy white head that retains well and laces the glass .  m : little or no trace of carbonation . this porter is unbelievably light , considering its heavy appearance .

frickin ' a beautiful . i shit you not . dark and rich and black and medium dark head of tiny bubbles that lasts forever . not ridiculously thick and certainly not thin and they really must have worked at this . beautiful .  m : low carbonation , could have some more body .
aroma is juicy citrus with an undercurrent of sweet and alchol .  mouthfeel : very light and watery .

pours a pitch black color with a thick , brown head into my glass . very nice head that fades down , leaving some lacing on the edges of the glass .  the taste was complex , while on the lighter side for an epa , there was a strong vanilla and toffee flavor , a bit of the oak from the ageing barrel can be tasted as well . the flavor could be a bit stronger , espically for an epa , no hops or bitterness was present . overall a very intresting beer , but very good .

s : surprisingly pleasant blend of apricot and citrus hops . it 's apricot scent for the sophisticated gentleman . 9 , and the beer 's strongest point . t : surprisingly dry , with sharp hop bitterness and , of course , dried apricot notes . teases a good finish , but it gets swallowed up by alcohol taste , especially as the beer warms in the glass . an interesting but flawed beer that is worth trying for the aroma .  this beer was quite good for a wheat . it has a medium-body , and on the nose is yeast and clove , as expected . tastes malty , herbal , and spicy , with an overall taste of banana which was really nice . it is minimally hoppy , and makes a very nice summer beer . i would very much buy this again .
aroma is very nice for the style ... brown bananas , cloves , candi sugar , lots of phenolic esters and some roasted grains thrown into the mix .  mouthfeel : this beer kind of dries out my mouth .
appearance : black , opaque , with a nice tan head that 's slow to dissipate .  mouthfeel is medium bodied and slightly over carbonated for my tastes .
theres a great smoke profile that comes out in this beer .  the body is light-to-medium , with a slick texture and prickly carbonation , followed by metallic astringency .

it was a very complex and pleasant aroma . tasting : a strong malt presence came across up front , followed by alcohol warmth and slight fruit flavors .  this was full bodied and smooth but i felt that there was a bit to much carbonation .

nose : complex . citrus , banana , yogurt-ish yeast aroma .  mouthfeel : i only had a couple mouthfuls ( did n't even make it through one bottle ) , but it felt more substantial and less watery than o'douls or warsteiner .
hazy ruby-red with a fantastic head that really sticks around . looking down into my snifter is like peering into the milky way .  mouthfeel : light weight ; medium-high carbonation .

pours very dark , nearly black with a dense foamy head that breaks down to bubbles the attractive lace .  the mouthfeel is different from what i expected . they just got ta figure out if they want their beer super carbonated or near flat .
massive crown of pure white head on a semi-opaque yellow , with hint of orange , body .  mouthfeel : kind of thin and watery and just a bit too much carbonation .

the nose is genuinely inviting , the hibiscus aromas asserting themselves just enough to be pleasing to the nostrils .  complaint with this one is the mouthfeel which feels a little thin for what i want a ris to be , i want a bit more chewy - though i suppose this lighter feel aids the drinkability which is high for such a monster , just a hint of booze .

nose on this one is very aromatic . lots of sweet ripe fruity esters . great sticky caramel malt body , works in perfect sync with other notes . aroma overall , is just perfect - lovely zesty fresh intoxicating fruity madness . very effervescent . by this , i mean huge . it 's zesty , highly sugary , and very assertive .  mouthfeel is firm and a bit spicy with the hops , but the drinkability is awful .
nice , oily floral hop aroma with a mild sweetness of pine sap and alcohol . very nice .  mouthfeel is slightly a little too carbonated for my tastes .

solid three-finger beige head with thick and chunky lace . rocky settling . the color is near black where no light shows through .  i enjoyed this beer very much . one of the few breweries in us to try and succeed with a belgian doubel which are complex to brew . i liked the spicy overtones and the rich character . a great cold weather brew .
almost smells dark . roasted notes , coffee , some licorice and vanilla in the nose .  a bit lighter in the mouth than i expected .

beautiful , dark amber glow i fell in love with .  i looked at the label `` unique hoppy altbier '' and thought the hops were gon na rip my tongue off or something , not so . to find the truth turn the bottle around simply `` water , malt , hops '' simple things are good though . now for the taste , nice and malty in the front with a hint of hops taking over . this is a very smooth and drinkable beer . skoal !

this beer looked perfect for a black raspberry beer with a big lively head and a light purple head . the nose was also very nice fully complimenting the appearance .  soft in hop bitterness , yet very well balanced . thinnish in overall body .

*best by date - 09/07/11 pint glass a : lake erie monster pours a glowing golden straw color with a nice 2 finger creamy tan head . slightly hazy and some decent window drapes of lace .  i found it very highly carbonatedalmost too carbonated ( prickly , carbonic qualities are a bit distracting ) .

settles into a light mahogany colour with a nice , creamy off-white head of foam . good lacing .  the texture of this beer is a bit thicker than many hefeweizens and with a bit less carbonation than usual .
very strong scent t-a huge burst of clean coffee .  m - due to the not-so-well-hidden booze , the feel is not quite there .
very nice . t : taste is similar to the smell , but a lot more diluted that i 'd expected .  this brew is a bit thin otherwise .

s - i had a pliny before this one , and i have to say that the aroma is not very far off . very nice . t - very much a letdown after the nose .  opens with a big scent of chocolate raspberries and alcohol . pours a good sized brown stout head over an opaque , deep brown body . chocolate and raspberries are in the taste too , along with a dryness thats part stout and part red wine . midway through , some more roast coffee stout notes come through , then a rather rough english hop profile . a great with desert , or as desert in itself .

the off amber-golden color is awesome and the smell is absolutely exceptional with hoppy goodness . if you just look at it and smell it then it is exceptional . the moment it passes the lips and then goes down your throat it lets you down a lot .  m - very light on the palette , foaming up nicely and bubbles lightly in the mouth . the finish is a bit dry for my liking though .

ok- this beer has a wonderful aroma , bringing to mind barrel-aged beers . this beer is extremely drinkable with a nice warming sensation for a cold day like today .  the mouth feel was pretty average , has a slight alcohol bite at the end of it .

aroma is awesome . huge , juicy ruby-red grapefruit from the cascade hops . taste , however , while good , was a bit of a letdown . overall , a very good dipa .  carbonation is right there and builds up , becoming harsh , slightly taking away from enjoyment and the mouthfeel is lighter that i would expect .

a - this is a very good looking brew.dark brown body with no transparency topped by a medium to dark brown head standing a couple inches tall .  it feels a little watery but the taste and the super clean finish really help this . there is no real carbonation , and that is this beers downfall .

big hop aromas are dominating- from just smelling this beer you would think it to be an ipa . not much in the way of mouthfeel but just a smooth easy to drink ale with great aromas and flavors . a very interesting aba .  the mouthfeel is a little watery for the carbonation , and it leaves a sticky residue after swallowing .
appearance : deliciously golden orange , great color . beautiful froth . looks great !  taste is alright , but the palate feel is quite weak .

once it settled down it was hazy golden/yellow color with a huge , foamy and thick white head . it excellent head retention and left some of the thickest lacing on the glass i 've ever seen .  mouthfeel is very fizzy , scrapes the tongue .
no doubt , its one of the prettiest hues of the beer rainbow .  m : medium-bodied , fairly flabby carbonation , smooth .

poured from the bomber into an `` hour glass '' pint glass the beer was a medium bronze color with a sturdy one-finger head that retained well and left some very nice lacing rings . lots of streaming carbonation bubbles .  mf : the mouthfeel here on this brew tends to thin out after the initial sip , and there is absolutely no malt backbone to this baby . d : even though the mouthfeel is lacking , this beer is still refreshing .

aroma is just amazing . citrus ( orange , grapefruit ) abounds in the nose . skunky hops , and some subtle spicing unlike traditional wheat/whit smells . starts smooth with nice wheat smoothness . ) complement nicely . hops are intriguing ; somewhat of a skunky/dirty variety that i would n't have picked for a light summer brew .  m : a lot of carbonation , i think it could have done with a lot less .

aroma is very potent blend of resiny piney hops , sweet citrus and grapefruit and a warm booziness . this produces a very thick , smooth syrupy body and hot alcoholic burn in the finish .  m-is sort of thin , much more than i would expect . d-is very nice .

s- a myriad of tropical fruits . orange , melon , lemon , and even pineapple . citric hop aroma . sweetness . no alcohol flavor is detectable .  this beer lacks some carbonation . i think if it had a little more it would n't have that chalky like feel to it .
appearance : pours a deep orange-copper with huge , frothy , khaki-colored head .  the mouthfeel is too syrupy for my tastes , with an unfulfilling bite of carbonation .

purchased last summer , covered with red foil . nice reddish amber color with a high clarity . i like the contrast between the ruby hue of the beer and the almost brown color of the head .  m - sharp carbonation is a little oveer the top .

pours a deep amber tone , capped with sticky , dimpled foam that crackles audibly .  mouthfeel : slick , but not as full as i would have expected . it pushes for full , but falls short . the carbonation is a touch high for the style , but it works with the flavor profile .

this is subtle , but if you pay attention it 's a beautiful killer . prickly bubbles on the tongue and interesting flavors and aromas make this a really nice choice for a spring or summer outdoor drinking session .  mouthfeel : closing in on medium bodied , but not quite there .

has a strong aroma of citrus and orange zest . i 've never wanted more than one of these at a time . but it is a lovely beer to relax with .  mouthfeel is fairly light with somewhat frothy carbonation .

great aroma ... tons of roasted malts , also some cherry and chocolate noticable .  light-medium body is a bit lacking due to somewhat limp and loose feeling carbonation . i really enjoyed this offering a lot despite its lacking mouthfeel .
very appealing . taste : initially , more sweet than i was expecting .  medium bodied and tingly from the carbonation .
very present aroma . smells like pure extract . good balance . d - this is a fun beer but not something i would want all night .  the feel was light bodied with light carbonation .
jet black , creamy tan head , no signs of carbonation and incredible lacing .  mouthfeel is ok and does not seem to stick to the palate .

excellent retention and good lacing - in fact , this is a damn fine looking beer ! i was expecting something a lot more insipid , and this one looks amazing .  mouthfeel : prickly carbonation , oily texture , medium body .
it looked great , very black , nice head . mouth feel was ok , it did n't compliment the appearance , should have been thicker , and slicker .  m : creamy , but kind of thin .

a clean yellow hay is yielded with a blustery bubbling to greet the eye . the head is of one and a half fingers and recedes to maintain a steady , thick foamy film . terrible sweat sock , adjuncts , limburger .  the body is spot on , lush and full . the carbonation though is a bit lackluster . do n't get me wrong , in a beer like this i 'm looking for the carbonation to be a bit on the low side , but it 's almost nonexistent here and the beer is bordering a bit on being syrupy .

[ best served in a english pint ] poured a clear medium amber with a medium sized creamy head that was fully lasting and had excellent lacing .  m - medium bodied . carbonation is where it should be . they enter like a legit good beer and go down like water . this one is very good and could only really improve on the mouthfeel . the mouthfeel remains to be this brewery 's flaw , but given the progress that i 've seen from them , i 'm sure they will address that .

a : the beer pours near black in color with a 1.5 finger medium brown head that has excellent retention and lacing .  like it 's little brother od12 , od16 is well under carbonated . it is only 8 % i would love to see this one at a higher abv and with a bunch more carbonation .

look : black and totally opaque with a brown ring on the bottom and a beautiful 1 inch tan head and great retention with a nice lace circle smell : chocolate and coffee with piney hops in wonderful balance taste : this is hands down one of the most perfectly balanced black ipa 's you will find .  the mouth feel is n't bad .

the nose is pretty impressive . wheat malt and yeast . at first , the taste is exactly what you would expect from the nose , and it 's dang good .  not as light bodied as a budweiser , but still light bodied . it is far cheaper and tastes better than any of the other macro brews out there .
it had a large foamy light tan head that left the most incredible lacing i 've ever seen . it looks incredibly delicious .  very bland and acidic . can taste the 9 % all the way through .

java stout 12 oz bottle poured into chimay chalice a - pours a very dark black color with a nice 1/2 inch dark tan head . lacing is very nice and remains for quite some time .  i thought the body was a little thin .
a full compliment of streaming carbonation bubbles race through the beer . looks like beer in a commercial . stellar presentation .  m : fair carbonation , flattens out on the palate .

from here on i 'm going to stop buying beers from brasserie dupont , unless they 're on tap at a local pub . it 's a great mystery why dupont persists in bottling their beer in green bottles . in bottle , they can still be decent but not worth the $ 10+ to enjoy a tarnished defective beer .  almost juice ? mouth was bitter , to be expected , but not a strong bitter , washed about like any other average beer . watery . i 'm impressed with the balance with this brew . one time only but sure would be good in place of lagunitas 's other ipa 's .

lacing is nose is super pungent , i could smell it as i was pouring the glass . very sweet smell , with a touch of fruit and black licorice - damn , almost like a jagermeister . then turns amazingly sweet , almost too sweet .  from the water used ? nice flavors , but a bit light and bubbly on the feel . nice canned stout
appearence : pours a dark ruby with a nice , creamy brown head that lasts the whole glass . good clarity .  m : light on the tongue . super low carbonation but that is to be expected .

appearance : pours a black color with a huge 3 '' merangue like head that lasts forever .  as this beer poured into my glass , the most noticable aspect was the big , creamy , moussy head , which lasted a good long time . good balance in the flavor ... german hops and malty sweetness . toasty , grainy . a mineral aspect to the flavor profile . overall a very enjoyable beer . not a very common style .
apperance : the color of this beer is nearly orange . very vibrant in color .  m- creamy but thin and light . some good carbonation salvages it to an extent , but it needed more body to it .
pours a bright yet dark ruby . big white head .  it 's lacking the velvety feel i like in a good stout brew . a bit too prickly for the style .

a : clear reddish amber , constant bubbles and a steady white head . looks good .  but what a treat -- a seasonal beer with a long history and an intriguing taste profile . it is nearly flat and ( ironically ) headless from its low carbonated body .

tons of carbonation is visible and this is looking quite gorgeous head retention is spectacular and as i drink this , there 's foam all over .  smells of candy and sugar . tastes of dried apricots and burnt caramel ... very buttery . this brew is rather dry to the pallet.. clean finish but not much residue on the ol ' taste buds . good beer.. ot great but worth a try .

pours a deep black with a super thick tan head that looks ultra sticky .  this beer claims to be one of the hoppiest beers in belgium , but it is n't what i expected . far less hoppy than i had hoped . i was n't disappointed by any means , because it was an excellent tasting beer . at $ 5 a pop for a 12oz bottle , forget about me buying another one .

750ml champagne style bomber poured into a snifter a somewhat aggressive pour yielded a bubbly , frothy two+ finger head that sits atop a chestnut brown body .  m - medium to full bodied with no syrupyness . could use a bit more carbonation .

orangey pour well foggy cloudy stormy topped wth a spumescent ivory statuesque pillowy head cap loaded with sporadic bubbles , leaving a magnificent lace layers .  it took me quite a while to try one because it did n't sound like it could be good . i am so happy i got dfh punkin ale to start with so i know that it is a style with potential to be awesome . this was down right gross . it tasted like i was drinking a bad pumpkin pie . sickeningly sweet . i could n't finish it .

beautiful s : tart cherry , bright citrus hop . layer of sweet caramel underneath . really interesting and inviting . dusty aspirin , a little cat pee ? overwhelming wildness . very funky . too dry and chalky and mediciney d : poor .  m : light yet substantial body , but a little watery .

smell is so pronounced : pineapple & tropical fruits , booze , under-ripe banana . floral . much going on . i sense hop flavors in the middle pushing their way through , but they 're hard to really discern amidst the myriad of things going on with this brew . bottom line , it 's a spicy , yeasty , fruity and lively beer with a little bit of heat and a mildly dry finish .  m : plain , smooth , and almost instantly forgettable .

pitch black colour , big brown head .  visiting toronto , pulled this of the local liquor control shelf as a local . i 've traveled all over , and this is about the worst beer i 've had since brewii in baltimore in 1979 . love thetaps logo , that was the only good feature of this beer . big daddy
lacing in the glass was exemplary , almost guinness-like in the pattern left behind .  lightly carbonated d- very ... does n't fill you up and tastes great .

drank from a 12 fl oz./355ml can purchased at julio 's liquors , westboro , ma served in a pint glass the beer poured a a slightly hazed , medium amber color with a frothy , off-white , three-finger , sea foam head that slowly faded to a resilient cap .  mouthfeel : foamy and somewhat thick , like a thin syrup with carbonation . puts a little bit of carbonation on the tongue , but not too much .
a firm , lasting , off white head tops the brown body interlaced with red highlights .  m-i thought it was a little on the thin side for what i was expecting .
a : this was the most gorgeous color of red i have ever seen .  mouthfeel - a smooth mouthfeel , a bit on the watery side but crisp .

20 ibu , 6.7 % abv pours out to a sparkingly clear deep garnet brown , forming a tall whipped dark yellow head with excellent retention and superior sheets of sticky lacing .  m -- moderately chewy with the chocolate and malt , but finishes thin .

the appearance of the beer is truly amazing : a towering , everlasting , rocky , white head tops a coppery-caramel colored liquid .  this beer calls itself a dubbel , but at 6.5 % and with such light body , i would n't call it that .

aroma : excellent with piney hops in the forefront some caramel coating the malt sweetness this is extremely dead on in aroma very nice . taste : people at frederick do an excellent job of recreating an english style esb just perfect caramel buttery hop mix this beer delivers in refreshingly smooth category , while still maintaining honor to england with dead on accuracy for the style .  the mouthfeel is a tad thin as a result of the filtration , since residual proteins are quite important in mouthfeel .
certainly has a fantastic look to it . ruby color with a lightly tanned head about 1cm thick .  mouthfeel : a little thin on the palate , but otherwise felt good .
appearance- deeper golden colored pour with a two fingered and creamy head . leaves behind some large sticky patches of lacing .  it seems light in the mouth .

poured into a tulip stout glass . pours very dark , held it up to the window and could n't get a ray of light through it . has a fantastic head on it very thick and creamy in appearence .  m : kind of flat , not bad , growler is only 2 days old , so it may be a factor .
opaque black color . full light brown foam .  the flavor is n't bad at first , upfront it tastes like a flavorful macro lager .

pours with a two finger head into my free imperial perfect pint glass i received with my purchase , however the head disapates to a thin ribbon quickly . perfect amber color .  m - not as thick as i expected but very drinkable d - outstanding , i could drink a couple of these pretty easily .
awesome porter nose . add a bit of acidic barnyard and it 'd be perfect . very full and malty in the mouth . still , a very nice traditional porter .  ok carbonation .

nose is a wonderfully floral and fruity melange of tropical flavoured new zealand hops . very nice , and such a classic contemporary new zealand craft beer character . lovely nose , but that 's by far and away its best character .  it 's extremely smooth , but i think the body could be a lot lot thicker - the smoothness comes from the thin character of the body . the flavor is n't over the top like some , but it could use a little more body and a little more flavor would n't hurt either .
appearance : fine-looking murky copper body with a creamy , off-white head . plenty of lacing throughout .  just slight bit high on the carbonation , and a body that 's just about right .
s-the nose is wonderful . i detect plums and grapes .  mouthfeel - very beerlike .

aroma is of sweet malts and citrusy ( grapefruit ? lots of complexity in the aroma , this smells great ! it pretty much tastes how it smells , but the alcohol is very noticeable . this would n't make a good session beer , but its a good one to sip .  m a little thin here d yah ...
beautiful opaque yellow body . you cant see anything through this beer ; its like looking at a glass of off-white orange juice .  m : full mouthfeel with a medium body to it .

the aroma on this thing was sublime : funky wooden earth paired with yeasty esthers and a citrusy , spicy hop note . although i appreciate the craftsmanship that goes into each jp beer i come across , i have yet to find one that really hits it out of the park form me .  possibly a bit thin .

22oz bottle poured into a beer mug appearance : dark amber color with a strong head at first that leaves good lacing .  before expanding my palate yuengling used to be my favorite beer . i gre up in the dc area so we had plenty of it around . i still consider this a great beer for a night full of drinking , but not one that i would drink because i want to enjoy a beer . i still love you yuengling and i ca n't wait to have you again ... stupid yuengling does n't ship to ca .
