the aroma , on the other hand , is phenomenal . rich , dark fruit notes of plum and fig surround nibs of dark chocolate and toasted toffee malts . overall , this was a good beer , it 's just too bad that it was n't properly carbonated , or else it would have been truly great .  and now i know why people say it tastes like chocolate syrup , because it kinda does . but this is really good if you like chocolate . probably 1200 calories in this bottle . but who 's drinking beer and watching calories ?
pours a dark straw color with a nice big white head .  the only complaint about this beer is that its a bit thinner than guiness or beamish , and not quite as rich or full flavored .

pours a beautiful pinkish red color with a sizeable cotton candy pink head of frothy foam that dissipates quickly . the color is really nice , reminding me of a pink champagne . this tastes like one of those mainstream beer that craft beer consumer rage against , just with a pretty color to it .  carbonation is a bit high and affects the mouthfeel a bit feels prickly with carbonation as well as a bit syrupy .

pours a light caramel color , with tons of nasty large yeast chunks floating throughout . nose is very piney , with plenty of juicy citrus hops .  this is a very enjoyable , crisp lager but more of a classic , good american-style lager than a german pilsner since it really is not very hoppy and is lighter in body . it is lightly sweet and bitter . it becomes slightly more bland and mineral-water like near the end but still retains decent flavour and body .
appearance : pours dark brown , almost black in color with a pretty mocha head that lasts throughout aroma : mocha coffee , alcohol and chocolate .  mouthfeel & gt ; effervescent . thin .

i love the bottle . the beer could be any number of central american/ caribbean lagers if you close your eyes , but i just love keeping my eyes open and on this bottle .  this beer feels a little lighter than many ipa 's , but that is not to say it has less quality .
huge 3 finger head nearly spills over the glass and huge lacing ensues at it goes down .  mouth feel is exceptionally carbonated almost to the point of obstructing the flavor .

this beer looked amazing . it was pitch black .  mouthfeel is syrupy and coating . i do n't really think i could have more than one of these per night , but i 'd be damned if i did n't try . if anything , it would be the sticky and cloying mouthfeel rather than the big booze presence preventing me from doing so , which is surprising to me .

the first impression is great , with its golden yellow color and luxuriously foamy white head that sticks around the side of the glass for quite a while .  the hickory stick stout is a slightly stronger beer than i prefer . i ca n't really drink a lot of it at once but however ... the beer had a very thick and long lasting head on it . the taste is a bit bitter but at the same time fairly smoothe going down . the aftertaste is a little stronger than i prefer but all in all it is a very smoothe and good smelling beer .
it has the mezmorising golden-brown color that makes marzen 's s appealing with a small amount of head .  mouthfeel is slick .

a - pours deep brown , cloudy with sediment , huge tan head that has very good retention , some of the best lacing i 've seen , champagne-like amount of bubbles continually floating up s - spicy and yeasty aroma , hints of fruit , alcohol evident also t - slightly sweet bitterness up front , bitterness lingers and turns into a toasty malt flavor , alcohol is evident throughout , but not overpowering , nicely balanced m - lots of carbonation , crisp , light-bodied , very dry finish d - i could drink a couple of these if i could afford it , not an overly drinkable beer however due to both the abv and dryness this lived up to the hype for me .  suprised to see the alc at 10 % . really interesting . somewhat of an acidic mid and short finish . still the aroma is outstanding . almost tannic and closed . maybe time would help this brew come around ? still very interesting . would have been better served with friends and shared , not sure even an 12 oz bottle is for just 1 person .

the first thing i noticed when i poured the beer was its exceptional appearance . the beer comes out of the bottle dark as night and the beautiful head rains top down in the glass .  the mouthfeel is rather disappointing .

a : very nice copper/ruby color with a moderate head .  i was lucky enough to catch the tail end of the batch that coopers was lucky enough to recieve ... poured unlike any cask ale ive seen to date ... fluffy , quickly receding head that didnt spiderweb at all , nice consistent lacing ... smell is more intense than the normal ipa , nice aromatic fruity hops present , touch of piney bitterness ... taste is nice and rounded , despite being somewhat complex.. oak tones meld nicely with the fruity hops , again the pine tree bitter hop oil presence is a great touch ... unfortunately the carbonation was all but gone , a little too flat even for cask ales , and it had only been tapped for two days ... oh well , the flavor is what counts and mac and jack deliver on that note ... looking forward to trying the blackjack cask-conditioned ... cheers !

slow effervescence gives the beer a very syrupy look . s : mostly citrus ( orange , grapefruit , pineapple ) and floral hops , with some pine character . it certainly smells more like a double or imperial . d : good .  the mouthfeel is a bit on the light side , but maybe that contributes to its overwhelming drinkability .

pours out a bright clear orange hue , loose frothy off-white head that leaves a thick cap . it 's okay in the flavour department , looks gorgeous , but does n't pull together in the end .  strangely light mouthfeel when it hits the tongue . under carbonated by a long shot .
the head was two fingers thick , light beige and produced beautiful lace . the color was dark , dark brown , nearly black .  m- high carbonation , very light .

it retains the phenomenal , meaty , charred scent characteristic of aecht 's brews , but with a slightly richer flavor that 's more in line with what one would expect of such a well-presented beverage .  mouthfeel was somewhat watery not at all what i was expecting .

pours a cherry pink with a big cloudy pink head .  starts smooth and slightly bitter . settles with a medium-full body and deep caramel flavor . finishes strongly bitter ; drains dry . the distinct cough suppressant aftertaste is mercifully short-lived .

pours a deep , hazy ruby/amber . great looking head , tan and thick , lots of lace .  aromas of chocolate and roasted maltiness . the flavors depict much of the same and it 's a bit more complex than many other brown ales . this is a great beer to hang around a late afternoon drinking with your buds . go for it .
d : tyranena just might make the best smelling beers ever . this had a great taste and body also .  a little thinner , but a better or no aftertaste . tastes good , a bit thin , but not much .
smell : terrific aroma , nice amount of roasted smokiness .  m : a bit on the thin side , well carbonated , dry .

bottle ( courtesy of jimbowood ) : poured a dark brown color ale with a huge foamy head with great retention .  ) but remembering from past experiences on tap a very light pleasant taste light in the mouth very easy to drink and much enjoyment has been had with this beer in my hands
a- rich brown color with copious amounts of head and lace . much better looking than i would have guessed .  mouth is heavy and bitter with a cloying finish .

s : toffee , butterscotch , light caramel , molasses , and hints of diacetyl are what i notice immediately . everything is well integrated , though a bit lacking in the deeper caramelized malts that i would expect from such a noted scotch ale producer . t : a bit of a letdown after the nose . not nearly as complex , as a bit of roasted nutty caramel takes over the beer , leaving a bit of lingering bitterness .  unlike the smell , there is no hint of milk to the beer . the only detraction is thinner body and high level of carbonation .
smell was fantastic . i could smell ripe fruit , some sweet malt and a touch of spice .  m -- nothing out of the ordinary here .
on tap pizza port carlsbad , ca near black with ruby edges and a thin light brown head . perfect for the style .  m : you can feel the carbonation and it has a nice touch of hops spice .
looks awesome . somewhere between chocolate and pure black in color .  the carbonation is present in the mouth and the beer does n't feel creamy enough for me .
the beer was a lightly hazed deep amber red .  m : spritzy , thinner , but ok. d : very good .

pours a dark , murky blood-amber color with some lighter plum highlights when held up to the light . a beautiful , fluffy , fizzy , pockmarked tan head was pushed up to its apex about two full fingers above the liquid line . a very pretty beer .  the mouthfeel is wet ( this being the weak-point of this brew ) .

a -wonderful bright honey , large head , beautiful spider web lacing .  taste : a little roasty . pretty fizzy which is n't really common to the style and was as though designed to make up for a lack of flavor . the middle is sweet cocoa and the finish is pretty dry with a hint of roastiness and caramelized malt . note : catchy name but i wish they would have put their creative juices into brewing a better beer .

a - giant two finger , lumpy , fluffy , egg-shell colored head floats on top of a clear and well-carbonated amber color leaving lots of lacing .  finishes crisp with a sort of biting feeling in the back of the throat .
a particularly impressive beer , this .  m - a little short on carbonation for a belgian , also the sweetness gives it a thick , syrupy feel .

a - beauty apricot , tons of head and lace that last a long friggin time & gt ; s - musky , light coffee grounds , some malt .  duchesse de bourgogne was my first toe dip in the water , and i found those waters foul . mouthfeel is wet . this shit is right .

this is one of the best smelling beers i 've had . taste was refreshing wheat/yeast with a very subtle sweetness ( the smell was deceivingly sweet , but i was glad to find the taste not so ) . best `` summer beer '' i 've had this year .  yuengling lager is a good choice to stock the fridge with . its actually cheaper around here than bud and other macros , and has a much better flavor . it is a fairly watery beer , but the flavor that is there is mostly of malts , with a little hops thrown in .

s : this smells amazing for a pale ale . citrus booms through this with a lovely , slight-hop pine character . tons of tastey aroma . t : taste is honestly a let down .  a little low on carbonation . clean and refreshing .
on tap at peppercorns a - nice hazy straw appearance with a fluffy one finger head that left medium lacing down the sides of the glass .  almost aggressive carbonation , crisp mouthfeel .

21st amendment back in black is a clear , dim red-brown-black ale with a dense khaki head that has outstanding retention and lacing .  mouthfeel is average . right amount of carbonation ; right amount of foaminess .

the smell is glorious . the aroma is bursting with vanilla , coconut , caramel , some light alcohol , marshmallow as well as some bourbon . the finish has a slight alcohol burn , but nothing unexpected given the abv .  m : i got a lot of carbonation in this beer .

pours with a deep reddish-brown body topped by a medium thick , lasting , off-white head with good lacing left behind .  let down a little by an overly thin mouthfeel . the soft , creamy carbonation helps out but it would have been better with some more body .

i 'm probably cracking this a little older than anticipated , but it still smells hoppy and delicious ! now this is unfortunate .  the only relative disappointment is the mf for me -- it 's too thin for a stout .

500ml bottle poured into a white wine glass fridge temp harvest season , 2011 appearance : pours a golden orange color with an aggressive 3 '' , slightly yellow head . great retention and tons of lacing . perfect so far !  mouthfeel is ok , a little flat .

a black pour with a solid brown head .  brewed just a month ago . the smell is nearly nonexistent besides a hint of malt . the flavor is paper , vegetable , malt , and a hint of herbal hops . glad it was only 99 cents because it is worth jsut a bit less .

a - pours a great foamy white head that tiers and laces quite well . slightly foggy orange color .  t- the malts definatly lead the way creamy and the coffee aromas come through in the flavor adding a pleasent bitterness tying it all togather . m- lingering tase is please n't but nothing to special d- i can nurse about four a day no problem . very good but not something i 'd just pound .

pours a dark jet black color with small tan head , no strong nose to speak of , good lacing , nice creamy mouth feel , hints of coffee , roasted malts .  the smell was great with a lot of hops and citrus . i was expecting a little more hops but i have been on quite an ipa binge recently so maybe i was affected by this . that said the general taste was pleasant and the beer was very drinkable .
superb pour ; an impressive black body with a impressive brown head , nice lacing .  the body is bit on the thin side , but that 's not necessarily out of the ordinary for an oatmeal stout .

nice dark pour . sticky carbonation that peppered the glass from top to bottom . very dark mahogany brown in color .  the mouthfeel is much too bubbly and stiff for this style , but maybe that 's what it gives it its marvelous head ... this is the only thing holding the beer back .

smell : lovely roasted nutty scent .  heavy alcohol , extreme spice , honey , grapes and pepper . oof - this is where my `` inexperiance '' as an advocate comes in . an immediate peppery sting inflames the mouth and the grapes , saffron and alcohol kill them off . wtf is saffron ? sorry dfh .

a - this beer pours a really dark brown color that lets not light shine through when held to the light . the head has excellent retention and leaves behind a big sheet of sticky lace on the glass .  smooth porter richness nicely balanced with light hops m : a bit thin for my taste but fits with the balance and delicacy of the flavor d : balanced flavors and delicate mouthfeel make this a very drinkable porter ; i definitely want another

i was actively wanting to taste this one so bad that i considered buying 12 pints of young 's ram rod to finish of a keg to get to it on saturday night , but my bank account did not let me go hog wild ... i just came back on tuesday for it . the smell is very piney even though i believe they used spruce in this years batch . i was first disappointed in the way the pine smell keep the others at bay , but have since really come to enjoy this quality .  m - a bit of a disappointment here . it leaves a nice stickiness in the back of my throat , but it 's maybe a little too carbonated for me ; it just seems too light .

this looks amazing . the head actually sticks out well over the edge of the glass , but doesnt run over . leaves a really nice lacing on the way down too . lovely looking brew .  the taste was also dominated by honey . i think i would have liked this is it had been a beer with some honey highlights since i love honey but this is basically a glass of honey with a little beer thrown in to make it flow out of the glass better . by the end the honey is just too much to take and i had to choke down the last third just to avoid a drain pour . avoid this one . ( 1.5 , na , ml , n )

the smell is outstanding , a little light in body with a nice , crispy , carbonated , cinnamon backlash on the tongue on the follow through .  mouthfeel : heavy carbonation and a light body . fizzy , with a bit of puckering bitter .

the aroma of this beer was roasted caramel malts , some dark fruits , and just a bit of oranges .  some harsh roast flavours show up in the finish and it is also sorta sorta chalky . mouthfeel is ok i guess , but who cares when it tastes this bad ? i 'm guessing this flavour comes from some sort of cheap grain/adjunct .

smells really good .  unlike dl , this puppy is thin in body & complexity and has a body nowhere like motor oil . lightly carbonated to the point that any less carbonation one could considered this aspect the beers only fault .

a- this beer pours a orange-straw color with an impressively foamy , pillowy eggshell head that seems to take forever to die down .  actually kind of thin for me . carbonation is good , but the bitterness is too dry for my taste .

pours a deep mahogany color with a rich tan head , smells strongly of coffee beans and sweetness . massive aroma . taste essentially as it smells , or mild slightly sweetened coffee beans .  mouthfeel : light , pretty carbonated , and a bit of bitterness . this one does n't get too wet on the tongue , still , a tad light for a lager but a well deserving mouthfeel .

a : this thing pours like motor oil into my glass - nice 1 finger tan head that leaves skim as it leaves the glass s : smoke , malt , mollases , coffee t : chocolate , malt , smoke , raisin , and some burnt sugar m : mild - could be a little thicker - seems thin to me considering it being from draft d : ok ... .regardless of the mouthfeel this beer is fantastic .  m : medium to high body with lower carbonation . slick finish .

pours an outstanding , craggy head . opaque throughout the glass .  the taste was crisp , sensual , malty , and generally delicious , with a whisper of chocolate . the ale was an average feel , nothing noteworthy .

smell is glorious , all english style ales should smell like this . seriously , the beer 's gone and i keep sniffing the glass and the empty bottle , its that good . hints of bread dough and alcohol , among others .  m - average mouthfeel .

s : lots of winter spice . sweet orange peel and cinnamon , light notes of honey . t : good malt flavour , the complexities of the spice is n't quite up to snuff as it was in the nose . o : there 's some good stuff in there , but something that really shines on the nose . perhaps it 's a lot harder to make a winter warmer out of lager .  m : relatively light for what it looks , smells , and tastes like , though not to the detriment of the beer . lively carbonation matches body .

modest head that dissipated quickly , which gave way to a wonderful citrus/orange aroma . mouthfeel did n't wow me as much as the smell , but that does n't diminish its high drinkability .  this beer is good . i do n't understand why people freak out with a+ ratings . for me , ninkasi 's `` maiden the shade '' is a better choice for a similar beer . i do n't get why the `` bros '' give `` total domination '' a c rating and then give this an a+ ?

pores a beautiful ruby red color with a perfect light tan head that stays threwout the whole session and leaves great lacing . everything about the appearance is perfect .  i find this to be a very clean tasting beer with good thin mouthfeel .

great retention and great lacing .  the mouthfeel is a bit sticky and the body is a little heavier than i would imagine , however , this really drinks nicely and is one of my favorite portsmouth offerings .

smell was a pleasant sourness . a very aromatic pils . i kept sticking my nose in the glass just to enjoy the aroma . taste was of zesty hops and grainy light malts .  wow , this beer looks friggin great . dark as night , huge tan head . looks like a two-layer cake . aroma is somewhat gross , like old leather and mold . someone said 'beef jerky , ' and i can see a note of meatiness . interesting , but odd . wow this tastes foul . it tastes like a suitcase that was left in the basement for years . then the basement was flooded , and the leather buckled and grew mildew in the cracks . i hate to say it , but this is going right down ye olde tadcaster draine .

the taste was quite hoppy with a clean finish . the several different hops used created a wonderful layered aroma . personally i was disappointed by this beer , being a stone limited release project i wanted more than what i got .  the mouthfeel was thinner than average for the style with a crisp , bubbly carbonation that mellowed as the beer sat .

the smell is amazing mostly hops like a black ipa a little malt an some coffee . it 's good but not great .  mouthfeel is average - nothing special ... tingly carbonation , and not overly smooth/silky .
poured a dark brown with a giant brown head .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied , and perhaps a bit too carbonated .

a : it has a very beautiful amber brown color , and it is crystal clear . lots of visible carbonation . not much lacing on the glass . i give it a 5 because it has perfect color and clarity for a brown ale .  m - a bit acidic to the tongue .
a large inch and a half fairly frothy white head . excellent head retention .  mouthfeel : nice carbonation , but a little thin in my opinion .

2008 batch , bottle # 1389 of 2028 ... pours a dark blood red , borders on a brown . a big spongey tan/pink head good retention and lacing ... the aroma is super weird , it smells like vanilla cake with cherry frosting , and as good as that sounds , just does n't really work for a beer ... the taste is borderline horrendous and its really sneaky .  m - medium low body with no noticeable carbonation .

pours out a yellow body with a thick white head that has very good lacing and retention and nice carbonation to it . has a nice smooth creamy easy drinking feel and overall it is just an average beer that looks good when pouring it into a beer mug .  mouthfeel is very light which may help explain the softness of the beer .

12 oz bottle poured into a pilsner flute - 2007 bottling - cellar temp appearance : pours a transparent golden color with plenty of active carbonation rising to the surface . off white head rises to 1.5 '' and is cakey . the lace is very sticky and clings to the glass .  a fantastic combination . thin for the style , though it does n't detract much at all from the overall enjoyment .

a good combination of biscuity malt and hop bitterness . dangerously drinkable . an excellent candidate for long ageing .  leaves a pleasant bitterness on the tongue . not a typical `` fizzy yellow beer '' in my opinion . if you find yourself in goose island territory and you either want a nice blonde ale or want to introduce your macro-swill drinking friends to a better beer , try this one .

very pretty , nice orange color with a big white head .  pour revelaed an extremely thick and long lasting creamy white head.as it reduced it left rings of lace in the glass.the color presented was orange and somewhat cloudy.mouthfeel wasnt very crisp and seemed a bit watery.the finish left a sharp sweet or tart twist that dissapeared real quick.a bit bitter in the back of the throat with a wheaty grain taste.a spicy aroma thats not too strong but is there.tastes of oranges , lemon , cloves , corriander , and honey are noted.overall good with a medium body .

bottle into a tulip glass a- pours a beautiful hazy pale golden color with an incredible four finger rocky , pillowy head that leaves lots of chunky lacing . perfect looking belgian-style beer .  m : very average .
a - clear gold with huge white head that just looks so beautiful sticking to the glass .  m : little carbonation with a decent amount of body .
on-tap at beachwood bbq , a : pours a cloudy yellow with a medium white head with good retention , thick lacing .  m.light bodied fizzy carbonation .

poured into my pilsner glass with a huge tight white head . great lacing and tremendous retention .  body is not quite as big as some imperial stouts , a little more fullness and creaminess would be nice but the flavor is good . overall , a solid example of an imperial stout .

pours a dark black color with a thick mocha three finger head that sticks around for a while , crazy head retention .  good odor of molasses and coffee and maybe a little of the roasted grains that i link to most stouts . flavor is good , with strong hops accompanied by coffee and some sweetness . the coffee and malt becomes a little more apparent as the beer warms . all in all , a good brew . i 'd drink it again if i could get ahold of some down here .

it smells very good . the hops are not overpowering but there .  mouthfeel - while i feel it adds some more to the flavor , the carbonation is a bit more on the intense side . body overall is average and the same thing goes with the overall thickness .
poured out completely black with a nice tan head leaving a very nice lacing .  m - palate is rather syrupy for the style , but that 's really the only downside to this beer .
it pours a beautiful color , a bright , vibrant , shining clear honeyish/orangeish amber . a beauty of a beer appearance-wise .  m : heavy body with a very sticky feel .

decent enough ipa ... very nice pungent hop aroma ... .bong resin , tobacco , pine , and some earthy notes ... taste is pretty bitter at first and this seems a little one sided ... then some caramel/toffee notes emerge and blend in ... body is light side of medium..carbonation is a little too low ... .finishes pretty dry and bitter .  thin to medium bodied and silky smooth on the pallet . finishes thinnish , more in the personality of a dark mild than a porter . this vintage brit held up incredibly well . aside from being flat with an expected cardboard note , it was very enjoyable .

appearance : served in an eight-ounce glass , comes with a great frothy white head , excellent retention ( at least for a barleywine ) and lacing . color is dark caramel , very opaque . looks are the winning part of this brew .  feel is not as creamy and soft as i probably expected .

a : light yellow with some hazy coloring . ample head and thick , sheetlike lacing . very nice .  man does this go down easy ... juicy orange with a bit of tanginess . in the nose of this beer . i had this after a session of lawn mowing and it was quaffable.i am just starting to venture into fruity flavors having been a hop dog for a while . i was pleasantly surprised at how quenching these beers are .

catchy label with all the lil greek guys playing around in a party atmosphere . appealing chill-hazed golden yellow pour with sticky white lacing rocky ice cream head .  mouthfeel : medium light , i would like to see a bit more body .

pours straw gold . massive bubbly white head on each pour . dissipates very slowly with nice foamy lacings clinging to the glass .  i 'm not going to do a full review from this one tasting . just wanted to note that this draft example , which i had with lunch at an uno 's chicago pizza restaurant , was a tall glass of diacetyl soup . in fact , i sent it back and the waitress brought me a perfectly drinkable half moon wheat to help wash down my pizza , and to remove the rancid-butter slick from my mouth left by the sam adams . i am normally a fan of sam adams beers -- they do a very nice job on a wide variety of brews . this one was simply yucky . however , in the previous ba reviews of this beer , i do n't see others who encountered the diacetyl bomb , so i 'll give sam a fair second chance .
pours a a cloudy looking red brown . a nice thick tan head with incredible lacing that coats the side of the glass .  m & d -- mouthfeel 's a tad too spritzy for me .

holy banana nut bread batman . at first sniff that exactly what this beer reminded me of . banana laughy taffy , cinnamon , nutmeg , a bit of ginger , with a nutty aroma added in . i 'm really digging the aroma . cinnamon comes through but the rest of the spices are muddled together . as with every osa i 've tried ( that 's 3 now ) this is a really solid beer .  tripel grain tripel , 33 cl bottle . mentioned as the same beer the brewery started producing at their 15 year anniversary . very malty taste too . aftertaste is rather sweet for a tripel . malty . the alcohol comes through quite strong , but it is n't too harsh . overall it 's a well crafted beer ... like many other tripels .

a - pours quite the head ... very think and full head , you can not pour thsi brew in one full swoop .  finished clean with a slight taste of alcohol mouthfeel : a bit thinner than i would expect for a brown .
looks terrific - almost like a guinness commercial .  m : medium bodied and medium-low carbonation . has a water like texutre that i am not fond of for a ris , but it 's still good .

a - a very pretty beer . pours up a medium frothy head with little lacing . a gorgeous honey gold color . it literally looks like honey through the glass .  presented in a clear bottle , should have known what to expect . smells of raw chicken , a terrible skunkiness , overpowers everything . does not taste very well eighter , could keep drinking it , but i do n't really want to . should not have been in a clear bottle .
the aroma is of burnt caramel , some toffee , slight apricot and fig notes .  mf : light , perhaps a bit watery , carbonation comes off slightly weak .

the pour is remarkable . a nice copperish amber body with a dark ivory head that is long lasting , and deposits generous sheet and patch lacing down the glass . this pseudo-irish red beer , that begins with such an exceptional appearance fails to impress , when it gets past its superior looks .  m : combination , lime tang drinkability : yes yes yes ... football beer
app : great ruby brown with a solid head smell : salted caramel which is on par with the style .  m- creamy and watery with booze burn d- overly sweet and skunky with booze taste .

this brew pours a rich , pitchblack color with nice brown head.the aroma is of strong black coffee , chocolate , and sweet malt.a really great aroma for a stout .  m : on the light end of medium bodied , the carbonation level is very high . its only flaw is the carbonation level - which leads to a seemingly thin and effervescent mouthfeel .
great retention on these foamy bubbles . tons of sticky lace .  very metallic aftertaste flavour is sour . i do n't know what to think . this is n't good at all . drain pour , unfortunately .

s : tropical fruits , piney hops , very sweet smelling over all . t : tangy , biscuity flavor .  m : a little on the light side of medium bodied , and i 'm afraid my somewhat rough pour put almost all of the carbonation into the fantastic head - it feels a bit flat .

pours from the bottle with a beautiful russet eggplant hued offering tooped with a frothy spumescent spongy head cap that goes on for miles .  frist sip reveals an average body but a little thin on the finish .

the aroma is quite vibrant . a big dose of sweet lemondrop as well as mix of belgian and dried fruit , cherry and prunes .  the body feels medium to light on the palate , smooth and refreshing , it carries the day .

huge rocky frothy white head , lasting a while .  just like my review of pale malt , i think it 's not right to go into a lengthy dissertation on the merits and demerits of this beer as there 's clearly something wrong at the brewery . all of the great grains beers have an intense sourness to them that 's more than just poor judgment being exercised in the brewery 's stylistic interpretation . tornado seems to suffer the worst from this infection problem of all the gg beers i 've tried . the green apple flavor that lends the beer an `` interesting '' tartness when it 's really fresh ( like the day i bought some off the brewery delivery truck ) turned into an overwhelming acid bath for my mouth after about 3 or 4 days of rest in the refrigerator . it 's really too bad that my only local microbrewery makes tainted beer ...
big yeasty smell , with some cocoa , dark candi sugar , and dark berry thrown in the aroma , too .  actually quite a bit thicker and smoother than pilsner urquell .

was excited to try this beer but as soon as i opened it got a blast of a non-appetizing smell , idk maybe i had a bad batch.it was drinkable but i thought that it wasnt hopped as well as i personally like it a friend of mine who also tried it felt the same way . i personally would n't recomened this beer but dont get me wrong duclaw has some awsome beers .  light in body , but not watery . a small amount of carbonation livens the beer , but does not define it .

has a intense but pleasant hop aroma . as with the smell , the taste is extremely hoppy with a tad of maltiness .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , a little thinner than i would prefer , perfect carbonation for a stout .

pours a slightly-hazed peach color with a good white head and loads and loads of lacing on the sides of the glass .  pours a clear burgundy with a small tan head , good lacing . smell is of sour malt , dark fruit , touch of caramel , and some woodiness . taste is dry up front , caramel , prunes , raisins , sour malt , and a little hop bitterness in the end . overall a nice old ale that improves as it warms .

floral aroma with a tiny hint of bitter chocolate . floyd 's trademark hops distinguish this beer - quite lemony with lots of floral zest . bitter but bolsters the sweetness of the malts , much like alpha king but a bit thinner , not so robust . a step down from alpha king in my book , but still very pleasing .  palate was light to medium bodied , slightly oily , lively carbonated moderately astringent in its sourness and lightly alcoholic .
semi-hazy orange amber with a very nice ivory head gently floating on top .  m-very creamy , very light bodied .

s - massive aroma of weed , weeds , dandelions , herbs ( catnip ? ) , skunk , sharp lemon peel , and as it warms up a bit sweet malt emerges . t - taste is a lot milder than the aroma , with only faint weed and herbs and a bit more sweetness . d - this was kind of awesome in that peculiar fantme sort of way .  mouthfeel : appropriate .

delicious smell ! i could sit and sniff at this all day .  i 'd say it 's medium bodied with the carbonation on the light side ; the mouthfeel is n't all that good but it 's tasty and easy to drink so i give it a thumbs up .

the pour : nice head , creamy with great lacing . the color : a fabulous red copper the smell : a refreshing hefe-weisse the taste : so good all the way down .  the beer is tasty ... not too heavy despite the high abv . here is my first complaint : i consumed 6 bottles of these plus 3 rogue dead guy ale 's and got only a slight buzz . the feel and drinkability of this beer kind of skew the rating , but if that is what you are after , then you have found your soulmate . worth a drink , ( or two or seven ) to get the full affect .

smell - alcohol , cherry , toffee , chocolate , oak . taste - sour cherry and apple , grape peels , chocolate , and quite a bit of alcohol . when i get to the second half of the bottle , i taste some yeast as well . very unique . this is a beer for someone who likes cabernet .  taste : crisp carbonation holds a light to medium body .

the beer is cascading beautifully upon arrival and presents a creamy beige colored head .  m & d : light to medium body , but overly carbonated imo . the carbonation makes for a brew that stings a bit on the way down .

intricate , detailed lace . simply a beautiful beer , yes .  m - dry feel on my tongue while the rest of my mouth experiences a wetness . there is certainly a coarse feel to this brew as well . ~ this a a very good beer .

the beer pours a blackish brown color with a head that appears to have the consistency of whipped cream . head retention was exceptional and there was plenty of sticky lacing all around . visually , this beer is a thing of beauty ... on the nose , i do n't get a whole lot , just some light licorise , burnt toast and coffee ... maybe a hint of dark chocolate .  the carbonation is above-average for a stout , which makes the mouthfeel not quite as smooth as it should be , for having oatmeal in the recipe .

appearance- darker off orange-amber colored pour . the thickest and mosr dense head i have ever seen in a beer . it was literally like cool whip .  m -- for me personally , it has the mouthfeel of a good coffee stout . a bit thick , but it works .

the smell coming off this beer as it is poured is great . my mouth got excited by the aroma of yeast , bread & fruit . the beer is definitely hazy and looks thick . but the smell and looks are deceiving . i could see myself drinking a few of these as lawnmower beers , but there are so many better wit beirs , it would have to be on sale for me to purchase more .  light body .

holding up the bottle to the light , i see some sediment on the bottom of the bottle but.. it pours , after a pretty big hiss , a deep red brown , 2+ finger head of foam , ( wow ! ) waiting for the head to calm down so i can check on any lacing . very very slowly , the foam is shrinking . looks like lots of sticky lacing . in appearance alone , i reckon this garners a perfect 5 .  this does mean that it is pretty thin on the mouth though .

this is really nice ... i do n't know if i 'd seek it out again , but i 'm glad i had a chance to try it . the nose is phenomenal and quite alive ... this beer is almost worth buying just to smell it .  mouthfeel is some-what sharp .

but the nose is something else - bubble gum , tropical fruits , hints of yeast , sherbet , and a slight alcohol complexity . not quite as complex as before - still good mind you - and now has bubble gum notes in the taste .  m - the feel was not tremendously enhancing . it was a wee bit thin , and just did n't feel terribly exciting , if that makes any sense .

mmm , smells tasty . lots and lots of citrus on that nose plus some passionfruit . taste is quite a letdown .  eli 's is n't a bottled brew . it 's made specially for eli cannon 's a pub in middletown , ct ( i called to ask ) by shipyard . while i expect it is an honest mistake , the shipyard pumpkin the previous reviewer is describing was n't eli 's pumpkin patch but a different variety ( shipyard pumpkinhead ? ) . though i have not had in years since i moved away , has remained my all-time favorite pumpkin beer . on my next trip back i 'll leave a proper review .

a - very very dark amber color . the head poured a nice 1/4 inch , and lacing is very good .  starts out sweet ... finishes with a nutty flavor with a hint of hops ... very light m- pretty typical d- extremely light and easy to drink . a very refreshing beer ... easy to enjoy on a hot day
appearance - dark brown , forms little head but appears to have a good deal of carbonation , looks gorgeous ( i would give it a 5 if it formed a better head ) .  mouthfeel - bubbly .
a - thick , cloudy , burnt-orange body with a one inch head of pale-tan that 's slow and frothy . s - very inviting hop scent that has some real potency .  mouthfeel is a bit thin .
the appearance is plain amazing . pitch black with awesome tan head and lacing .  watery mouthfeel , slick and low carbonation presence .

leaves a 2 finger tan head that has excellent retention , and it leaves excellent lacing .  m- im used to some more carbonation from my belgians , thats the only serious complaint i have about this brew .

this beer looks awesome : huge , fluffy head with an effortless pour that never quite disappears , tons of lacing , unfiltered hazy goodness with a copper hue that gets a bit lighter towards the bottom of the glass .  the beer has a medium body with a nice quick bitter sweet finish . fff 's describes this beer as a belgian ale . maybe a little bit off base for this style , but it is a beer that i could find myself sitting down and drinking again .
pours a clear yellow-straw color with two point five fingers of white head and oodles of lacing as the brew goes down my glass .  the carbonation is pretty low , would have liked a bit more .

4.5 a : black color . two fingers of creamy light brown head . retention is good and plenty of lacing is left .  stiff pour resulted in tannish head that quickly dissolved . light lacing once the beer settled down . color - nice cooper/brown , with little carbination . initial smell was of hard water/metal and hint of grain . however by mid-beer the smell had changed to pleasant carmel , which encouraged more consumption ... overall good , not great . my expectations were slightly higher than results as sprecher has solid lineup .

a tremendously chocolatey aroma . again , perfect . a sweet and bitter chocolate stout . it 's not as sweet as the nose would suggest , which i actually think is a good thing . it 's nearly perfect . chocolate lovers all over the world need to be introduced to this beer .  m : a very very mild carbonation on a medium full body .

2011 vintage . looks hazy amber , great lacing and very inviting smells subdued , slight hop aroma which is surprising considering what this beast tastes like tastes like honey , flowers , citrus and has slight ethanol in the background due to the high abv .  m : a little on the lighter side .

nice silky , black color with a tall , light brown head . very fluffy .  taste : very to the point , the dry hops and yeast bring forth a tangy-sourness ; soft at start and throughout but sour at the finish , which als has a lightly spicy lingering . overall : on point ; first experience with jpaa , ingredients are well utilized that makes for a well-sequenced , very drinkable .

appearance - very dark with just a hint of brown on the edges . poured roughly to yield a large mocha head full of froth with ribbon lacing on the sides of the glass .  m- medium body with low/medium carbonation .

pours stout-black with a very dark mocha head . retention is excellent as well .  strong carbonation and a bit of head that does n't last long . too heavy in the mouth but the carbonation is pretty decent and works .

the smell is really great on this one . dark chocolate , roasted coffee , deep-dark red cherries and roasty malts . the bourbon smell is really spot on , it overwhelms once you catch hold of it , but it 's pleasant and welcome . the taste follows the smell , but it 's a bit more muted . the alcohol is a bit overbearing , it 's a sipper but it 's good .  mouthfeel : a bit light for the style imo ; seems just a tad watered down drinkability : pretty high conclusion : not the best american porter i 've ever had , but pretty tasty overall .

bottle into a tulip pint glass . a : clear , light amber color with two fingers of eggshell-tinted foam head that diminishes to a thick half-dollar sized pad . heavy lacing remains on the glass and scattered solitary bubbles rise infrequently .  m/d - full flavored but thin and watery on the feel .
2009 release beautiful copper tint with a full white head that estelle getty would be jealous of .  light-medium ( leans light ) bodied due to carbonation levels .

s- strong fresh raspberry scent . m- high carbonation , crisp but thin and watery d- the smell and introduction on the tongue make this a very appealing beer .  mouthfeel is smooth , having been bottle conditioned , but it 's a bit too thin .
jet black body .  mouthfeel : crisp and surprisingly refreshing .

large ( for a beer ) bubbles consistantly make their way to the head from the depths and sides of the glass , giving it a seemingly permanent finger 's worth of head . absolutely gorgeous .  mouthfeel is a tad too sticky but the drinkabilty is excellent .
fantastic looking brew in my glass !  fairly thin mouthfeel and high carbonation , it fits the style , but i 'd have preferred a bit more body and less gas .

appearance : the beer comes to me in an imperial pint with a big , fluffy khaki head . as the glass is drained , a nice layer of lacing is left behind . the beer itself is a ruby brown in color .  taste : starts with a sweetness that is cut by the carbonation . mouth : smooth carbonation not harsh drink : its malty start and earthy bitterness makes this beer more enjoyable the flavor from the finish and the start mix quite well .

a - poured out an orange hue with a creamy , off-white , four-finger head . left some nice lace .  mouthfeel is full of carbonation , and has some burnt afterburn ... mf is maybe the only thing i did n't particularly care for .

pours a dark brown color with a freakin huge off-white/lightly tan colored head , fades at a really slow rate , the head almost has a nitro look to it but it 's just a regular bottle , for as much head as there was there is n't much lacing on the glass .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin as far as stouts are concerned , but it 's not so watery as to ruin the experience .

smell has a nice aroma of tart cherries and a hint of sourness touches the nose , dash of oak to add some complexity . taste is as it looks , flat and lifeless in the mouth , the saving grace is the tart/sour cherry flavor distracts from the lack of carbonation , flavor-wise this beer hits all the right notes as the cherries dance around the woody character .  smell : piney , tangy hops , with sweet velevety belgian yeast undertones . taste : begins mellow , develops quickly into piney notes , slight belgian undertones , finishes crisp with a piney bitterness . overall : nice example of a belgian ipa , well-hopped and has the best of both worlds , decent abv as well .

the nose is very active and keeps moving in a chameleon-like manner , molasses , plum , candied cherries , vinegar , the chocolate notes lurk around the borders , mulled cider , more an exercise in randomness than complex but no less enjoyable for it . full-bodied , most of its weight in the air rather than tongue-bound , like a zeppelin floating in your mouth . clean for its weight , the bubbles help scrub and refresh the palate . easy , but not that easy , to drink .  m : light and corbonated d : very drinkable pumpkin ale that is not overdone at all .

pours a pretty amber color with a few bubbles and a thick , creamy , and lasting , almost nitro like head . looks fantastic .  the mouth feel is somewhat watery , light in body but has a nice medium amount of malt flavor .

sinspalsken donker pours in with a big yellowbrown head that stays forever . color is brown but holding it into the light it shows a beautiffull & clear bordeauxred color .  palate is average , could be more carbonated .
smell is wonderful , fresh raspberries .  mouthfeel is a little on the thin side .
aroma is very inviting . taste : smooth and wheatish .  i tend to prefer it that way , although it 's not extremely strong with malts , and might be a bit thin in the mouth .
a - this beer has an incredible appearance . pours a hazy white/gold with a two finger foamy white head . the head has great retention and lacing .  m - feels like a normal ris .

a : pretty nice sour aroma . i get sour cherries , maybe some raspberries , hints of grass and wood .  poor example of a pilsner , surprised how this beer makes it out of thebrewery . lots of off flavours , both in the nose and aroma . clarity is not good either , unless they are shooting for a kellerbier which this does not taste close to . i enjoy other mill st beers but this one is sub par . it could be a great beer but needs more attention in the brewhaus .
a - great color ; really typical of style , with a deep , crystal clear red color .  carbonation is average and alcohol is invisible .

a complex and rewarding nose . yeah , it 's a hop bomb . bitterness really tingles the tongue on the finish .  only fault is perhaps excessive carbonation , but i 'm getting more sensitive to that so maybe it 's my problem .

a : this is a beautiful beer . a nice clear yellowish orange with a huge frothy white head . the head does dissipate some in the beginning but it has good retention .  mouthfeel is smooth and even , but a tad thin for an ris ( that 's really my only criticism for this one ) .

the smell is very fruity and sweet . this is probably the sweetest beer i have ever had . pretty much all i 'm getting is sugars , molasses , some fruit , and a little sour twang at the end .  the mouthfeel is medium , lightly carbonated and slightly watery .

nose is a rich malty based sense experience . including roasty coffee , and toffee notes laced with dark chocolate . this one is very good but a little all over the place .  m - near medium body : a tad too thin ; carbonation is light-medium ; near creamy , yet with a slightly dry finish .

what a beautiful appearance ! a nice huge pillowy head that stuck around and receaded to some very nice sticky lacing as i drank this beer .  what balance ? ! this is typically not the style i chase after , but being in switzerland , this was one of the few beers that i could find plenty of . the name sounded nice , so i risked trying a 1l as it would be cheaper in the long run , and i did n't expect this brew to be too offensive . it 's smell was n't rediculous , but the head was big and frothy , yet not long lasting . i would have to say this is a nicely balanced beer that i believe anyone could enjoy . if you are stranded in switzerland and see this brew , give it a try as it is quite tastey . after having another swiss beer , this one gives me hope . i look forward to trying more swiss lagers in the near future .
pours a clear golden amber color with a fluffy white head that stays for a while then sticks itself to the glass .  m - medium body - nothing remarkable , but no complaints here .
pours like engine oil , giving a reddish creamy thick head .  m : good amount of carbonation for the style .

i had read somewhere that stouts go well with raw oysters so , seeing as i was on the harbor , in baltomore , and already drinking a guinness , i thought i 'd give the guinness/oyster combo a shot . poured from a nitro tap , the legendary guinness head formed as the falling tan foam settled . the head is extraordinarily thick and creamy in appearance , texture , and taste .  mouthfeel seemed thicker than a typical barley wine should be ... i liked it but not following the style i guess .

this baltic porter from juneau is brewed with cherries , brown sugar , vanilla beans and oak chips none of which sounds bad at all . from afar , the deep burgundy liquid seems to pulse with darkness , yet a hold to the light reveals surprising clarity . the proportion of each is perfect , keeping the plate perfectly balanced . it doesnt get better than this .  it smelled like sour cheap grains , maybe a little more sour than the smell of most cheap beers . my favourite thing about this beer was the name .
a- cloudy orange-yellow . three finger white head leaving thick lacing as it disipates s- a bit on the sour side .  mouthfeel : kind of thin , which is to be expected .
beautiful to look at and very easy to drink .  m : feel was some what thin , a little less cloudy than most belgians .

the bottle is an appealing black/cobalt blue with gold lettering and a festive pink and orange wrapper . the brew itself is a clear medium-copper producing a boatload of fizz in my perfect pour glass . the foam was thick and settled to a 1/4 finger that lasted almost the whole glass .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin .
beauteous violet with rose froth that rises high , and holds well .  m- medium in body and very low in carbonation . almost seems flat and a bit dry .

very very fruity and bready .  mouthfeel might be a touch thin , and it leaves my mouth sticky , but i think holiday porter 's other qualities redeem it , and i thoroughly enjoyed both bottles from the twelve pack .

i had this beer poured from a bottle into an oversized wine glass ... a : the beer looks very nice with a honey golden look and a bit hazy with a large white head and very nice lacing ... s : the smell is lightly floral with hints of spice ... t : i definitely get some of the flower taste that went into this brew , but again , very similarly to hennepin , this is a sweeter saison and i just do n't understand it .  carbonation is average , giving this a boring mouthfeel .
aroma is of sour cherries with some roasted malt . the aroma is promising but the taste falls short of my expectations .  feels slick and under carbonated .

the 14 % is very present ; dominates the aroma . under that is sweet and spiced cherries and apples . alcohol gives an extra spice , and also warms my nose as i sniff the glass .  m : ok , not as smooth as i would have hoped , somewhat coats the mouth , medium body .

( a ) - pours a deep dark plum/sienna color . produced a nice cap of tan foam with good retention . lots of lace left behind .  m- light and watery - not much body at all d- smooth finish i recommend this one on taste alone .
creamy , dark mocha head with great retention and ok lace .  mouthfeel is much fuller but less creamy than the draught version , extremely dry and carbonation is n't overbearing .

poured a rich clear crimsion red with a thick off white head that sustained itself through the entire beer , leaving thick belgian lace on my glass .  served at `` free '' beer party - 2008 at taco mac lindbergh in celebration of the 75 anniversary of the end of prohibition . smells of malts and bourbon . no carbonation - but who cares when it tastes so good ? the barrel aging brings all of donkey punch 's normally well hidden abv , to the front of the class .

pliny the elder is mildly hazy and copper in color . there are fruity notes of apricots and oranges , malty sweetness , and toastiness that comes out on swirling . overall this beer is pretty balanced . it 's not overly sweet like a lot of other dipas . towards the finish there 's a mild peppery bite with a good slighty herbal , strongly resiny hop bitterness in the finish that lingers long into the aftertaste . pliny the elder is medium-bodied , and has a prickly carbonation that cuts the sweetness somewhat .  mouthfeel - does n't have the full on body of a double , and the carbonation is on the flatter side , making this feel that much thinner .
the beer is a translucent brownish amber with a tan head . great lacing .  the feel is pretty average , neither watery nor full nor interesting .

s= lemony . i get a lot of lemon and a lot of black pepper smell to it . a decent amount of orange rind to it as well . smells a lot like citrus peels . t= not as lemony as the smell but still lemony .  it 's pretty interesting , and good m- it 's actually a little too thick for me .
really nice , got ta rate a 5 .  the mouthfeel is kinda sticky and medium bodied , but once you drink about half of one , you feel very refereshed , even for the relative bitterness .

pours a dark ruby , eventually settling in with no light piercing its depths . a white head forms quickly , and lasts throughout the entire session , leaving lacing too thick to see through as you drink from the glass .  the mouthfeel was a bit thinner than i would have hoped .

it poured with two fingers of rocky , bone-white head that slowly fell away into a light foamy coating on top of the beer . the color was a spectacular golden yellow with ne-plus quality clarity . the finish was really metallic , however , and lingered well after the swallow .  the mouthfeel , however , was watery for a porter , the body medium and the carbonation light . highly quaffable .

leaves a two finger foamy white head that has excellent retention , and leaves excellent lacing . beautiful to behold .  i 'm suprised how fast this fades , leaves a clean mouthfeel at the finish , not a thick palette coater by any means , but all this does is make you drink it faster .

a : pours an amazing hazy amber/copper color with an outstanding massive eggshell color head that retains very well and leaves lots of sappy lacing along the pint glass .  m- tingly sensation that makes you want more .

delicious . t : there 's a creamy , light fruitiness on the front of the palate with hints of banana and pineapple .  thanks dan for bringing this one to ratman 's last night ; i 'd been wanting to try something from this brewery for a while now . i was a little surprised at how thin this one was , and incorrectly assumed its abv to be around 5 % . the bourbon does a nice job merging with the chocolate , roast malt and smoke on the palate . nice .

it pours like chocolate milk . the bubbles cascade not up but down ( at least it looks that way ) , like little grains of sand that descend into the dark abyss . a beige head is standing guard the black sea underneath it . the nitro carbonation is hardly noticeable until you think about it , this is a heavy stout , by the looks of it , but it feels like cool liquid silk . yes it 's a stout , but i can see one drinking this anytime of year .  m - rolling carbonation makes the brew pleasantly refreshing and very quaffable , though perhaps a little too effervescent . body is lighter than i would like .

this is one of the best looking beers i 've ever seen . it pours a ridiculous translucent orange .  deeper in the beer is quite a bit of caramel malt coming through but the peppery hop aroma is really taking this one away . t= the taste is less hoppy than the smell led on which i find sort of refreshing in a style that is becoming more and more hop centric . the hops that hit the tongue with a sort of spicy peppery taste as i assumed but that is swallowed fast by the delicious caramel malt flavor and a nice bready taste . m= this is the down fall of this beer i think . really just average . its sort of oddly sticky and watery despite the wicked head on it . a very friendly amber ale . tame and still extremely delicious . highly recommended amber ale .
a : it pours a great cloudy orange , with big tan head . in some parts it changes color to yellow .  body is a bit thin and alcohol is slightly burning but nothing out of control .

this is a beautiful beer.a dark coppery color with a huge head.this has a lot of carbonation.you can smell the malt , sugar and wheat.to me , this taste like a wheat beer and i do n't like wheat beer.i 'll try to be objective.this has a medium feel thats not bad .  m : a hare thin for the style , a bit hi for the carb .
pours an opaque black color , with a thick , deep tan head .  mouthfeel- medium body . decent co2 level .

appearance beautiful dark brown and thick with a large , tan , foamy head that went down slowly and covered the inside of my glass .  still can not get the new belgium offerings in the state of michigan - too bad in my opinion . a friend brought a sampler twelve pack for me to try as i 've only had the fat tire and ranger ipa . of the four in the sampler i believe this is my favorite . it is a good session beer that is not particularly strong or bitter at all .

pours a medium/dark brown from bottle but is somehow nearly jet black in glass . gorgeous light tan head forms and lasts until bottom of glass : pillowy , fine bubbles .  m - too light for my liking , and sometimes even border-line watery . at least there 's a strong carbonation , and it 's nice to kind of toss around on the tongue to search for the other flavors . still , fairly average .
a - very dark , with lots of foam that stuck around s - not extremely pleasing , sharp with soft undertones .  the mouthfeel is light .

a - a yellow/pink hazy fluid with a two finger big head that slowly retracts into a good layer . exceptional . no visible carbonation .  wow , just not pleasant at all . the sweetness sometimes bordered on cloying . the vinegar tastes were not so strong as to be basalmic or repugnant , but it was getting there . at least they were a bit more rounded . i regretted ordering this after the first sip , but i did n't want to kill myself while drinking the rest of it , so i guess that 's a plus . we need more good sours to come to texas so i do n't have to subject myself to this as one of our few options !

the second the can is slightly cracked open , this beer fills the room with aromatic hops - amazing . citrus , spice and a bit of pine . great hop aroma . the hops are all there in the flavor too . i really want to like this beer .  mouthfeel is a bit watery , but so is the original mad hatter in my opinion so that is to be expected .
looks gorgeous . nice white head .  first sip reveals a lighter body than expected but no watery texture just a little thin , the carbonation is very fine and spacious , again not what i expected .

wow , head-o-rama , big 1.5 finger rocky monster tan ( with oxblood hints ) head with incredible retention . about as good as it gets .  mouthfeel was a bit thin , but it would help in sessioning it .

pours a bold thick black with a tall dark brown head that slowly fades to a subtle stippling of the surface . retains a good stick to sidewall of the glass ( even and thin ) .  lack of head on the initial pour but this beer is definitely carbonated .
looks incredible . s : smokey , peat aroma with bittersweet chocolate and a touch of hop .  the mouthfeel is a little thin .

pours black with a nice one-finger peanut butter colored head that leaves light foam on the beer as it settles . impressive for a beer that presumably has head-killing peanut oils in it .  mouthfeel was unexceptional , and light to medium bodied .

end result is a cloudy ( milky , really ) golden , delicious looking , uncapped mess smell is really amazing . spicy and such , love it . taste , however , is one of the bigger disappointments i have had with beer ( not to the level of sa triple bock , but still disappointing ) .  mf - the carbonation is n't very high , giving some it some body .
poured into a stemless red wine glass . beautiful . simply beautiful .  m - thin to medium . lots of carbonation . feels crisp .
the beer is fantastically dark in appearance , almost as black as the background on this hallowed website .  the body is a bit heavy for the style .

this brew poured a syrupy black , with a very attractive tan head , smooth and silky .  a very unique apperance . the taste is very hoppy and refreshing . has a bit of a bite to it . i am not a big fan of ipa 's but i would drink this again .
12 oz into a pint a - pours very dark brown/amber colors to just about black . strong mocha colored head formation .  m : a bit dry and thin , which is surprising .

s : i think the first thing i said as i inhaled this wonderful aroma was `` oh my god ! '' chocolate and caramel malt that is nice and toasty . amazing . very nice . m/d : full body that is low on the carbonation side .  texture is pretty well-balanced , but leans a little more on the watery side .

poured a clear copper color , with a big , fluffy white head that left rings of lace on the sides of the glass .  when combined with the relatively light body for style , orval is almost dry , and is thus very drinkable .

s - juicy pineapple , citric hops . love the nose on this one . t - this is a tasty brew . notes : i 've loved this for a while because of the label , and the contents inside really lived up to the hype .  the flavor is nice and chocolatey , but the body is nowhere to be found . i think it suffers from the lack of body overall .
beautiful orange opaque body and thick slightly yellow active head pineapple and belgian yeast aroma .  i think a little carbonation would do this slightly heavy beer good .
bottle poured into a standard pint glass black cherry in color with a huge , chocolate brown head of foam .  medium , silky body , maybe a tad overcarbed .
looks fantastic . good retention and lacing all over the glass .  the body is a bit watery , but very nice and flavorful on the whole .

let me start this off by saying i love everything rogue . i think this bottle may be a bit old , but with what i drank i ca n't possibly see why everyone rates it so well appearance : so black i could n't see even a hint of light through it when i held it next to a 60w bulb . the head betrayed it ... too foamy , too lacey , not thick like you 'd expect from such a dark stout .  saison du buff appearance- very hazy golden , lively white head that dissipates quickly.4 smell- hops - green buds to the max 5 taste- wow . delicious . sweet and citrusy but with huge hop and wheat finish.complex balanced . spicy nutmeg 5 mouf- easy 3 drinkable - oh so drinkability 4
translucent light burnt orange color , wisping head of fairly large bubble size .  a little to watery for a porter .

a-pours a pitch black color two and a half fingers of thick , stout-like head that leaves thick , sticky lacing behind .  i 'm conflicted on the body . it is light and that prevents the nice mouthfeel that should be evident in the best of this style . having said that this is a lighter stout that does n't feel too heavy on a hot summer day and would be enjoyable to drink outside .
looks and smells nice , with a medium amber pour and very floral juicy apricot , hoppy aroma .  very light ( perhaps too light ) in the mouth , with strong carbonation .

pours with a nice inch of foam , which leaves rings of lace all around the glass .  sampled this at the brewery ( portsmouth ) at the end of the tour which is short but wonderfully informative ( thanks byron ) . it didnt hurt that i was a few pints deep from the restaurant already . its been 2 weeks and its almost gone and i have to say its great for a stout . it pours thick and has little head retention so presentation isnt off the charts but taste makes up for it .

s - great aroma full of complexity . absent is the usual metallic aroma in most bocks/doppelbocks , which is worth the 5 in my book . t - not nearly as complex as the nose , but thoroughly enjoyable . molasses/dark bread semi-sweet flavor hits early on and segues into toasted/slightly roasted malt .  m : surprisingly light body with lots of carbonation .

' s - smells fantastic ! lots of diacetyl butter & vegetal tree notes , as well as some roasted grains . there is a cloying sweetness to it , so if it 's not an artificial sweetner , then perhaps it was pasturized and microfiltered before the syrup was added , or at some point before full attenuation was reached .  fat tire beer is great . it is a very drinkable ale that is available almost anywhere here in boise . appearance - nice semi-dark amber color , smells like something you want to drink right away . taste - ahh the taste is great on this ale . the new belgium brewing company really outdoes themselves with this ale .

appearance : bright yellow body with a billowy snow white head that slowly collapsed in on itself in valleys and craters . thick tide marks showed the progression of my enjoyment .  creamy , chewy , yet somewhat thin bodied and surprisingly effervescent .
lovely roasty caramel notes alongside peaches , cherries , and a small dose of cocoa .  m : kind of light in body , i do n't know if it 's the can , but needs more heft , overall resiny and creamy .

pours black with a small tan head .  this beats out negro modelo , pacifico and bohemia as the best mexican brew made ... the only exception possibly being indio or nochebuena , which i havent had the good fortune to try yet ... anyways victoria is a very hard brew to find as well ... basically only sold in southern mexico.. however the hops are very very present in victoria ... probably the best summer quencher you could find especially in parts south of the border ... lime or no lime victoria is tops ... cheers !

s - wonderful saffron notes on the nose . for those who have never had saffron in food , the aroma is incredibly hard to describe ... earthy , floral , and something else entirely of its own . t - really good flavors here , not quite as potent as the nose . m - good dubbel , the abv isnt that noticeable on the nose , which is good considering it is 9 % .  light body , with low carbonation , ho-hum .

this beer has , bar-none , the best aroma in any other beer i tasted ... it 's a beautiful combination of citrus fruits and the malted wheat . unfortunately the excellent aroma does n't translate as hoped to the taste of the beer , which nevertheless is pretty good but a bit on the spicy end and leaving a very citrus fruit-like aftertaste .  m - very effervescent , but i guess not much more than most saison 's . a bit thin and watery , especially on the back end .

smells just about perfect for the style - lots lf sweetbreads and undeniable belgian esters . drinks all too well , thanks to each sip being charmed along by that wonderful smell and finish .  the consistency seems about right , but the carbonation seems a little much . it feels quite spritzy .

this has to be one of the best smelling beers i 've ever had . luscious bready malt and flowery hops odors wafted up without having to stick my nose near the creamy head . it was amazing . the nose was so big , it was almost a let down when finally tasted . all in all , a really fine beer and a great surprise .  m : overly-carbonated mouthfeel , almost stings the the mouth .

smells like a bag of hops , which i personally love .  full flavor , nice beer taste with bittersweet aftertaste , leaving only the faintest hint of hops . good bock , typical of these end-of-season beers with a richness that comes from fully ripe barley . enjoyable alone , not timid with food .

on tap green flash brewing co. mira mesa , ca hazy , golden , and glowing yellow with a thin , light , airy white head . gorgeous .  carbonation runs a bit rampant , but it 's this brew 's only real flaw in my mind .
a - clear amber , and with a hard pour i got an easy 4 fingers of off white head . retention is decent and a thick cap remains . very nice looking .  the body is a bit thin .

whistler export lager pours a clear light gold with a beautiful fluffy head that lingers into a nice lacing .  maple , chocolate , soy sauce , hersheys syrup , rancid hersheys syrup and other forgotten descriptors were used over these 2 samplings . perhaps marinade is the best destiny for this brew . what if we blended gubna and satb ? could that save both beers ?

stange at hopleaf . appearance : darkness is what it says on the bottle , and darkness is what is inside . it pours a midnight blackcolor with just a hint of slightly off-black molasses in the very tip of the glass . darkness indeed . a creamy dark tan coffee head mellows in its creaminess , then recedes , reforming with every swirl and leaving some unexpected lace on the glass .  m - very , very thick . perhaps a little too thick for me .
pours a beautiful dark reddish copper color with a monster head , so-so lacing , excellent head retention . great looking brew .  medium to thin body with smooth mouthfeel .
solid offwhite head , 2.5cm , leaving superb lacing all over the glass as i drink it down .  the mouthfeel is just a little too light and watery .
pure white head . very pretty pour .  mouthfeel is a bit watery .

ebony is the color on the pour , my idea of how all beer should look . the size of the head is medium frothy in texture and light chocolate in color as it erodes a fine covering of lace is formed to conceal the glass .  m : about average in the mouth .
awesome and absurdly complex -- very intrigued . i could smell this all day .  a bit chalky . hints of grapefruit and bold coffee flavor .
the smell was great , but got lost in the flavor .  less co2 would have provided a silkier mouthfeel .
a : opaque black , decent tan head , good lacing .  body is a touch too thin .

when its poured into the glass the beer is very dark brillant amber color with a huge 5 finger light tan head that lasts several minutes . the lacing is great . as that huge head falls it coats the whole glass , like a film falling all the way to the body .  mouthfeel is slick , with lower than average carbonation .
great retention . amazing lacing .  m - light bodied and crisp . at least they got this part right . d - simple , watery , and low quality .

intriguing nose : grape must , huge funk , lightly sweetened tropical fruit . a nice clean citric element , barnyard funk , and grassy graininess . great balance for a gueuze . `` thick '' for a gueuze ( low carbonation ) . very dry finish . delicate and delicious , especially on the nose . i just wish there was n't that lightly watered-down feel/taste on the front of the palate .  the mouthfeel is a tad thin and falla short in this department .
pretty nice lacing . good looking beer .  m : fizzy but medium-bodied d : high alcohol flavor gets to me , and leaves a taste in your mouth in the end , overall not too impressed .
this punkin ale pours a mixed fall season leaves . the head is a light tan .  mouthfeel is on the light side , with a little more acidic carbonation than i 'd like in this sort of beer .
beautiful pumpkin perfume with good spicing .  m -- it is a little bland in the mouth .

appearance : deep red with a foamy , pink head . nice , almost champagne level of carbonation initially , which decreased fairly quickly .  beer follows germany 's purity laws . a : solid black , thin head s : plum , chocolate , fig ; very sweet and delicate smell t : coffee , roasted grains , sweet ; hops are subdued ; light abv makes this easy to drink a pretty good , decent beer .

stunning appearance . simply flawless .  i drank this 22oz beer out of one of the new fandangled sam adams pint glasses . the first taste i thought `` oh great another ginger ale . '' then as i tasted it more i focused on the saison character and citrus notes . pretty nice . not as good as 6-6-6 though . when it warms up to room temperature it gets a buttery nose and a quite intense ginger flavor . i assume this ginger will mellow as it ages .

the smoke smell hits you and does n't quit . this brew is like liquid barbecue and had me craving some pulled pork and ribs . along with the smokiness , some spice flavours can be detected along with a bit of nuttiness . i really dug this brew and hope to find it again real soon . one of my favourite rouge ales .  - in the mouth it feels thin , and quite carbonated .

the trees are great . what a nice touch ! aroma carries lots of bourbony booze and fusel-boosted yeast mutations . like a stinky old man , you have to respect the work that went into its culmination , regardless of how gritty his current situation might be .  mouthfeel is thinnish , but with plenty of flavor . i found that the fizzy carbonation dissapated a bit to quickly and left the last half a bit flat , but that was my only complaint .
rich ruby red , dark mahogany colour with a well formed off white head .  man oh man , the fiesta of flavor wo n't die down in its rented oral event space , my mouth .

pours out to a sparkingly clear rich amber , forming a voluminous creamy head with superior retention and very nice lacing . great looking beer .  m- a little thin and watery with little carbonation .

s : the aroma is an excellent blend of floral hops , fruity citrus and caramelized malts . t : the taste starts out sweet with strong flavors of citrus and caramel .  the feel is just too thin ; it does not make for a bad mouthfeel , but it is far from the potential heights of enhancement that i envisage .
bottle : poured a pitch-black color ale with a dark brown color head with great retention and some very good lacing .  the mouthfeel is lighter than i expected .

a - beautiful rocky tan head of two fingers . muddy , amber body . after the addition of the yeast into the glass there are swirls of brown in the head creating a nice visual effect and the head stays thick throughout , leaving mild , spotty lacing throughout . a beautiful beer .  essentially , this is imported bad malt liquor . cidery malt , with an overwhelming fusel alcohol presence . a strong lager can be done well , or , as this demonstrates , very , very badly .

s - smells really good - like a chocolate orange ! d - i just do n't like the flavor very much , even though the smell is quite nice . one of my least favorite haymarket offerings , although i can see others really liking this .  medium to thin body disappoints a little . high carbonation , slick mouthfeel . overall decent wee heavy , a tad thin on the body , but definitely one i wish i had more of .
750ml a - pours a deep golden with orange highlights and a 2 finger white head that leaves sticky lacing .  m : a little too much carbonation for my taste .
it has a rosey copper color with a goodly oatmeal color head and great lacing .  mothfeel is slightly light .

it had a citrus-fruit , rose-floral hop profile that was nicely balanced by a golden malt and slight honey bouquet that filled my nose with fresh spring time happiness . this really made my tongue excited to experience this elixir . it is good and quite fresh , but not quite as enlightening as i thought it would be after smelling it .  a bit thin on the feel though , would have throught it would have been a bit more robust .

really sweet tasting and inviting . t : it is a very bitter coffee stout .  when left to sit on the tongue , the carbonation was almost non-existant ( due to it being on cask ) i 'm guessing i 'd like this better bottled , or on draft and i 'd definitely like to try it again .
s- smells nice . notes of sherry , dark fruit , bourbon , vanilla , and oak . o- a very unique and tasty beer .  m : feels thin especially for a stout .

bornem dubbel 12 oz bottle soft pour in a tulip glass unknown bottling ( fl 30cd 08:55 ) , sanctified 12/06 poured a hazy ruddy brown with a huge faint brown fully lasting rocky pillowy fluffy head with excellent lacing .  an incredibly easy-drinking beer , great as a thirst-quencher but could use a bit more body .

) of dense hilly off-white head , as stiff as meringue on top . sunk to a modest layer with a huge plateau in the middle , so stiff that cracks formed when it started to break apart . yikes . substantial chunky lace .  lots of bitter orange , banana , even cinnamon in the taste , with smooth but underwhelming mouthfeel .

the smell is great . lots of banana and clove . one of the better tripels i 've had the pleasure of smelling . the taste does n't translate quite as beautifully , but it is still good . very good mix between sweet , dry , and bitter . overall a very good , drinkable tripel .  the mouthfeel is somewhat disappointing . i like gueuze to be effervescent , or at least moderately carbonated , but the carbonation i find here is quite low .

nice 2 inch carbinated white head smell - apples , floral , wheat and yeast . smells very nice taste - starts of with a bite of apple , you get the wheat and some coriander taste also .  reviewed 6/1/2006 ( 22oz bottle ) : pours a yellow-reddish clear colored body , with a big head , off-white yellowish in color . some good lacing . has a nice sweet aroma , some hops , malts , northwest beer aroma . a bitter taste , some malts , slight acidic aftertaste .

a healthy golden color , with a fluffy head on top . the nose is very underpowered .  the only hint of carbonation i could find was a few bubbles on my tongue . sipping and taking huge swigs it tasted good . my first lambic and after this , i can imagine i will try to seek out more .

smell : wonderful sour lemons with a hint of floral hops as well . i 'm a bit disappointed since the smell really impressed me . the mouthfeel also fizzles out . overall : great promising initially , but disappointing in several aspects .  m : the body is medium and so is the carbonation .
i really feel that there are very few beers that have the great appearance that `` lager '' , as we call it in philly , does .  mouthfeel overall is thin , slightly malty and citrusy .
appearance : pours with 1 1/2 fingers of nearly pure white head .  mouthfeel : medium to light body .

the appearance is outstanding , with beautiful lacing when served in a maredsous glass .  below average carbonation with a smell of sweet roasted malts . tastes of smoked , roasted malts , with chocolate/coffee overtones . very balanced and very tasty this one good beer . drink and enjoy !
