excellent glowing gold-orange color , minor chill haze .  the mouth feel is light and has slightly higher carbonation which makes it a very refreshing beer .

nose is strong with citrus . dough and yeast as well . overall it gets better over time , but at first a bit much .  definite hop rom a with a fruity grapefruit smell . taste was quite hoppy in a good way . i 'd heard a lot of hype on this beer , and overall i 'd say it was n't a letdown but i do n't see myself craving this anytime soon .

bottle enjoy before month notched-sep served in a pint glass fantastic appearance . glowing orangey-amber with a two-plus finger tall head of bubbly , light tan foam .  crispy , mouth watering . tastes good & is n't watery or light . medium to heavy body .
s : incredible smelling brew , almost entirely composed of sweet malts .  creamy mouthfeel , although a bit thin .

amazing fruit nose . taste : surprisingly simple after such a complex nose . initially , some ever-so-slightly bready malts and some black pepper and pine resin . eminently quaffable .  mouthfeel is a little lighter than what i had expected , verging on watery .

i poured it into a basic tulip and almost had a beer-gasm . it looked amazing ! i mean it looked like the other two big irish dry 's but still , beautiful .  m - medium with light carbonation , seems a little flat .

) dollop of whipped cream-like head ! it just will not go away , and the belgian lace is top-shelf ! the bier itself is a dark-golden , orangey color , with some cloudiness ( a smidge of yeast may have crept into the goblet ... ) .  lots of hops in the taste , more than expected actually , along with roasted malts , coffee , and hints of bitter chocolate , and carmel . lingering bitterness on the palate . recomended .
a : lightly hazy copperish hue , effervescent and tightly creamy off-white head with good retentiongently carbonatedlooking great !  it tastes a bit thin and tinny .

a : pours black with almost no translucenty even when held to the light . lacing is good and sticks all the way down the glass . a really good looking stout .  mouthfeel and drinkability : light bodied with surprisingly low carbonation , it fades almost as quickly as it comes into play .

poured into a tapered goblet a very dark amber with a thick , light brown head .  m-pretty smooth with a slight creaminess to the carbonation . seems a bit on the light side for an oatmeal imperial stout .

appearance is good , dark golden color . nice head , but dissipates quickly . looks great !  i know plenty of girls who live for it though m= high carbonation which in my opinion made it a little more drinkable d= hard to do more than one without something in between .

bottle : poured a deep brown color ale with a huge medium brown color head with good retention and lacing .  all light beers have deficiences . this one at least has a nice hop bite , very rare for a macro beer . no sweetness .

smell was not as overpowering as i was expecting . very hoppy , but not particularly floral or citrusy . just what you might expect from sierra , very hoppy and fresh , always a good bet at a party .  the body is softer than you would expect . the light body leads me down this path , but the abv could hinder drinking a lot of this beer .

poured a very alluring golden / light bronze color , crystal clear with a few very fine co2 bubbles consistently rising from the depths . head settled down into an ever-present but wispy thin layer , nicely lacing the glass the entire way down .  finish leaves a mass produced adjuncty lager flavor which is slightly unpleasant and makes you want to drink another sip to get rid of it .

custom six pack from ross deli in lakewood a & s : sweet malts , smoky and a bit of caramel , but pretty darn weak smelling . dark , murky red-brown colored beer . thick , foamy tan head that dissolves slowly . o : not a huge fan of this beer , thought that the two other english browns id rated were much better ( majestic nut brown mbc , and samuel smiths ) .  for a winter brew , the mouthfeel is a bit thin and light .
clear gold with a white head that leaves incredible lacing .  mouthfeel : meduim carbonation is shown in a bit of thickness in the mouth that dissipates quickly and leaves the mouth watering .

burger , claremont , ca app- this was a golden amber orange with a finger of head . fell to a generous pond layer of head .  seems a bit thin , shame , because i really like this brew . the carbonation is good just seems that it is watery .

the hop aroma is very overwhelming and not over bearing . overall : this beer is well hopped and smelled great . good balance of ingredients , but the hops produce a lingering bitterness that wo n't go away .  nose has a metallic hop quality , but overall is fairly faint . palate has a sour , spent grain flavor that is n't simply not very good - it 's actually has a bad taste . what are they thinking ? and no , the bottle is not defective . finish is unpleasantly bitter . has an unwelcome sulfur component as well . could n't finish this one . i hope the kitchen drain enjoys it more than i do .

smell - like chocolate . something must be going on w/ me but this beer actually smells kind of like sweet cocoa to me .  slightly more carbonation would aid the drinkability imo , but otherwise this is a very enjoyable and unique ipa - glad to have tried it !

deep orange color with a thick foamy head with tons of lacing . the brew is more opaque than clear . the highlights are its fantastic looks and excellent mouth feel .  mouthfeel : medium body with a medium to high amount of carbonation .

pours a translucent brown with very creamy head that retains well , laces nicely , and is by far the best feature of this ale .  i got this beer orginally thinking it was a japanese lagar . this beer is a very light sweet tasteing beer wich is a nice change to the bitterness of my useal sout . the aperiance is a trnncelucent gold color with a decent head and is very drinkable do to the sweetness with just a hint of bitter hop all in all a very good beer
nice nitro head that is tan . i think anyone who gives this a 1 on appearance when they pour is being way too partial , this shit looks good .  m - maybe my problem is the carbonation .

pours a beautiful deep brown , nearly black , with a nice light tan head that retains perfectly all the way towards the bottom . no guinness cascading effect here , but just as pretty a picture .  the beer is a little under-carbonated for my liking and is also a little more body than i would like .

color and clarity much resembles cranberry cocktail juice . smells of red wine , raspberries , white cherries , faint woodsy barrels , funk , and sourness . the taste is much like the smell . tastes similar to a red dessert wine with raspberries and cherries .  m : a little flat in the mouth , sticky and slick in a disquieting way .

this was a beautiful bottle with a very nice label . the bottle was closed with a cork and when opening it there was no sign of life coming out of the bottle , the beer was flat .  carbonation is sizzling , a bit too much in my opinion as it has the pop rock fizzy jones . i can see how this would be too sweet to some but i think the carbonation really sizzles away the lingering residual sweetness . upper 3 's if it was n't for the lackluster appearance and pop rock mouthfeel .
aroma is rich and malty with very floral hop presence . flavor doesnt match up to the great aroma for me .  carbonation is moderate , but i think the body is a tad light for my liking .
the aroma is spicy with a large amount of scents melding together into a potpourri of smells .  m - a little slick for my liking .
12 oz bottle into duvel tulip a - black body with light brown two finger head great retention and lacing on this .  m- lighter bodied than i would have liked .

jet black body with a cascading tan head . laces the glass like a good belgium beer .  a - nice golden yellow , very bright and clear s - malted corn smell with a light aroma t - great taste ( again to style ) with clean flavor , a sweeter corn taste and very fresh and crisp m - just average here , although the carbonation adds to the crispness of this beer d - very drinkable for this style .

22oz into a tulip . pours a crystal clear gorgeous new copper penny , minor head required an encouraging pour , minor lacing .  mouthfeel is light does n't really laste , but conversely its very drinkable for a stout .

smells very strong and appealing ! roasted coffee is present , but it seems to be hiding in the background of chocolate and cream .  mouthfeel : plenty of carbonation and definitely thick , but not as smooth and creamy as i 've had in other oatmeal stouts . nothing special .
s : lots and lots and lots of pineapple in the nose . smells quite nice . t : sweet pineapple up front followed by grapefruit notes .  the body is medium-light with moderately high carbonation .
the head is massive , and recedes slowly into thick lacing that sticks to the sides of the glass the whole way down .  main complaint is that the mouthfeel is a bit thin .

urthel hop-it 12 oz bottle served in jever pils glass . pours gold with a thick , soapy white head of two inches that holds forever and leaves lots of lace . very sticky foam .  mouthfeel is competent . worse than corona .
this stuff pours out thick & black . looks more like an imp . stout to me . nice tan head .  perhaps a little more watery than i expected from a `` cream '' stout .

pours out to a sparkingly clear light bronze , forming a rocky and soapy white head with amazing retention and wonderful sheets of snow white lace .  a very thin initially light ale taste quickly rounds out with a nice hop bite . high carbonation inhibits the taste at first making it very foamy .

nose is wonderful - lemongrass , floral and yeast phenols . nothing funky or farmhouse about it , a 'clean ' smelling saison . light crackery malt , but the sorachi ace hops are the main show here , it seems a perfect fit for the beer . delicious . lemony hop flavor with some wheatgrass and clean pilsner malt .  though i found the body of this beer to be quite thin , it may have just been the effects of the cask , but overall this brew was quite quaffable and the alcohol was n't noticeable until after i finished a pint .

one of the best-smelling beers ever ... a very enticing citrus-like aroma . the flavor stays fairly consistent throughout the cycle , but it is n't really a beer or ale flavor -- more like a citrus tea with spice and floral notes .  m - nothing typically outstanding in the mouthfeel , but it is more than made up for in taste .

on my glass it left an almost spider web lacing , sadly the most interesting part of the beer . color is a lite leather color with hints of red .  s : roasted malts , coffee , chocolate with a citrus backer m/t : light to medium body on the tongue , not a huge feeling beer . d : the lighter body of this beer makes blackout stout a pretty drinkable beer , however the strong malt and semi bitter aftertaste can catch up with you .

ripe citrus aromas with a light woody spiciness .  mouthfeel was the only place where i was disappointed . too thin for my taste . but for what it was lacking in mouthfeel it made up in drinkability .
pours as black as an beer i have ever seen . a big head up front dissipates to a fluffy 1/2 finger head .  light carbonation .

amazing aroma ; about as strong as i 've ever gotten from a beer . hops do come on strong , but it 's just part of a long and evolving mouthful of flavor .  old foghorn has a lighter body than i would have hoped , but it is excellently carbonated .

a - like a clear , reddish tea . nice head , reduces to disk . lots of sticky lacing .  m : smooth , not as robust as i would like in a ris , a little thin , pretty average . d : the lessened mouthfeel adds to the drinkability , making this probably the most drinkable ris that i 've ever had .

on tap at the houston flying saucer . dark ruby body that , in the relatively low-lit bar , could be mistaken for black with an off-white , moderately sized , and creamy head .  the mouth feel is somewhat watery and is the only flaw in this beer .

poured a hazy deep golden colour with a monstrous white fluffy head that had big soapy bubbles in some spots , and was very dense in other spots .  order a `` pint '' in scotland pub , they will give you a pint of tennents lager . sweeter than other lagers . cool , refreshing . i love this beer . if you 're looking for that nostalgic scottish pub feel , mmmm .

strong and incrediblely inviting fruit and floral aroma , definitely lemon stands out . smells fresh and sweet . top notch ipa , very easy to drink . absolutely impressed with this ipa .  more sweet than sour ; it has a predominant taste of cherry m - does n't linger as much as other , imo , more complex sours/lambics .
pretty great for the style .  it 's a great balance . nothing overpowers - not any of the flavors or the alcohol , or the carbonation . the drinkability is the main factor as with all my beers .
a beautiful , brilliantly clear amber with a big sticky white head .  m : very light with little to no viscosity . tap was much better , but most likely force carbonated .
very good retentioin smell - extremely fruity hops . apricot and citrus prevail .  m : light body , medium carbonation , starts crisp but thickens and becomes creamier toward the finish .

s - lots of hops up front - bursting with grapefruit , tangerine , peach and tropical fruit . some light caramel notes add a touch of sweetness but definitely a hop forward dipa . fresh and juicy . t - citrusy bitter hops are the dominant flavour . grapefruit really comes through but the other citrus and tropical fruit flavours that were evident in the nose are non-existent in the palate .  the smell is bold pizza sauce , which basically included oregano , garlic , bad tomatoes , and bready crusts . i just get bready yeast and very grainy corn adjunct that is short and stinging .

rich mocha aroma with lots of black malt in there as well . rich , potent , bitter flavor . not to be a whiner , but it 's too damn bitter . it was n't that cold , but i 'm going to let it warm up and bit and see if it mellows because it 's pretty harsh right now ... ok , well it 's almost an hour later and it has mellowed quite nicely .  mouthfeel is a bit thin .

appearance- pours a hazy dark reddish brown with a beautiful one finger super creamy off-white head . a perfect half finger cap and collar remain the entire beer along with thick sheets of coated lacing .  standard bottle poured into a pint glass . the aroma was of sour peaches , smelled wonderful . it tasted sour than i expected but the more i drank the more i liked it . it was super easy to drink and is one of those beers that you crave on a hot summer day .
poured a very dark with sparkles of red and a long lasting head with substantial lacing .  it 's so much smoother and has much body to it , compared to all the other crap macro out there .

hazy , but with little-to-no particulate . s huge bouquet . i could smell the sweet wheatiness of the aroma as the glass was set down at arms length from me . once i brought it to a proper distance , the nose was full of beautiful banana , honeysuckle , orange pulp , washed lemons and agave .  medium carbonation and body . nose is the normal malty/hoppy-ness of a porter , starts malty and hoppy and finishes with a nice mostly malty bite . very fresh - brewed 12/13/03 . the abv is 4.5 % .
smell is fantastic . yeast and dark malts abound .  m : thick and moist - rather surprising , more carbonated than i would like and no body .
very sweet , but excellent . t : oats , and chocolate .  m - medium bodied with a bit too much carbonation .

11.2 oz bottle poured into pint glass a : this has to be the pretties beer of all time ... .pitch black beer with a fingers worth of off white creamy head . the beautiful cascade as it 's being poured is wonderful to watch ... the head settles to a 1/2 a finger layer and stays there ... lacing , hell the foam sticks to the sides of the glass all the way down .  mouthfeel is on the thin side , and there is perhaps a little too much carbonation .

a- pours a very dark ruby almost black in color . nice off white with good retention and nice lacing .  winter warmers are one of my favorite types of beer . however , i 'm a rheinheitsgebot type of guy . i taste nutmeg and maybe ginger in this beer . that 's outside the boundaries for me , even if the flavors were managed through some odd hop/malt/yeast combination . i had to dump it down the drain after a couple of tastes .

malts prominent , figs , bananas and yeast - no sense of alcohol . classic ( of course ) dubbel taste . i think i may subconsciously rate trappist brews a little higher than i would otherwise simply because the thought of monks brewing beer is just so cool .  it maybe was a little bit thin in the mouthfeel , but this was a good beer overall .

nose starts the taste buds watering right off the bat with floral hoppy notes and hints of vanilla .  t- roasted malt flavor with some hints of burnt malts , sweet chocolate during and in aftertaste , coffee in aftertaste , nutty flavor , ice cream shake like finish , gets sweeter as it warms m- smooth , at times the body felt solid then other times it felt rather thin .

a-pours a muddled , ruddy orange with some slight flashes of rusty brown.the head on this beer was unbelievable.very belgian.three full fingers of super dense , barely off-white foam that left good sheets of lacing and stiff , half inch , meringue-like chunks on the inside of the glass for the duration .  only quibble is that it seems a little thin , does n't have a lot of oomph or gravitas to it , just the flavor .

the aroma quickly made up for the poor start , with a wonderful spice note . cinnamon , nutmeg , and allspice as expected but they were well complimented by a sweeter vanilla like scent . simply heavenly . the taste was a bit more average . yea , its a pumpkin ale , so it should have lots of pumpkin and lots of spices , but thats all you get . overall this is an absolutely awesome pumpkin beer .  this had an average head color was dark brown.aroma was of pine , raisin.sweet caramel.the taste was of raisins , malt , and prunes.the mouthfeel or palate was average.finished slightly bitter and dry.good , smooth , complex beer.has a biting , dry finish.i like the finish .

the smell , however , is very nice : funky , musty , wet-straw and barnyard , grape skins , pale malt . wonderful and complex aroma ! the taste is solid ... mouth-puckeringly sour , but also also balanced with a decent sweetness .  the some rum notes come through as well alongside a slight boozy aspect . a slight toffee flavour is present throughout . alongside a slight alcoholic warming component . overall , the flavour leaves a bit to be desired , but this is still worth checking out . an interesting take on a scotch ale from a belgian brewer .

the aroma is surprisingly refreshing and sweet with fresh raspberry puree in the forefront floating on a nice body of delicate malts . very nice .  medium-bodied and moderately carbonated , the flavors throw back to the aroma , with a pronounced hoppiness that is balanced well by a base of biscuity grain .

an excellent bouquet . very roasty and nutty flavors on the front , with more espresso flavors on the finish .  f - more than almost any other beer i 've tried , this one leaves a stickiness in my mouth , and makes me quite thirsty .
nose is wonderfully realised , and pleasantly odd .  mouthfeel was medium with a sugary sweetness that made me wonder if it is possible to develop diabetes from a single can of beer .
clear amberish color , amazing looking head . this beer has great visual appeal .  very good beer , albeit a bit on the thin side .

smell is robust and complex with dark and sweet chocolate , caramel , some nuttiness , and a hint of hops in the background . good stuff .  the first swallow is sharply bitter , much starker than an american ipa . this is woody and tangy more than the citric fruitiness we yanks have come to expect from a beer labeled ipa , unfairly . with a solid malt undertow and a nicely balanced bitterness , i feel this is a very under-rated offering . ( # 2688 , 2/6/2007 )

pours an extremely pale golden , crystal clear , with a spongy pure white head that stays and laces very nicely , considering the pale color .  the drink is on the light side of medium bodied but is somewhat overly carbonated .

pours a gorgeous hazed copper with a fluffy and very lively three finger , pearl head with intense lace . a very beautiful beer .  mouthfeel is a little thin for the style but really , it 's the best brew in the smokies .

poured this into a pint glass , pours an awesome yellow with some serious suspension in the glass , hold it up to sunlight to see what i mean , this is about the best thing i enjoyed about this beer .  feel is bright and slightly thin - refreshing , but could be a little fuller .

a -- pours a near black that only shows color when held directly to the light . full two fingers of light brown head that recedes slowly leaving a layer on top of the beer and thick lacing down the pint glass . awesome .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin and dry for my taste , but it is also very drinkable .
the smell is pretty good , like a mocha chocolate cake .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with low carbonation and kind of watery .

s - picked out the black ipa character of this quickly . roasty and hoppy . leans more to the hoppy end of the scale with good fruit and specifically grapefruit while retaining that roasted element . very odd and a bit of a letdown .  this was one of my first craft beers that was not oberon , blue moon , etc . smell i do not really remember too much because i had just started getting into craft beers . taste was great for a new craft beer fan , pretty light not too strong or overpowering but tasted great . i could drink these all night and love it .
pours a thick black with a duvel-esque dark tan head which lasts for ages and settles down to a permanent half-finger at the top of the glass .  mouthfeel is a little thin and watery .

color is black and more black . large creamy brown head that took forever to recede . beautiful sticky lace all the way to the end .  i love cherry juice . this is cherry juice ( 25 % ) and a gueze lambic . the general characteristics are of cherry juice . sweet but not cloying like some other fruit beers . comes across as mostly juice . best as a summer or desert drink . might even work over ice for the heretical among you .
a- ruby color , very creamy looking , slow settling carbonation . a beaut .  mouthfeel - when i think scottish ale , i think big mouthfeel . this beer lacks that mouthfeel .

pours an effervescent amber/orange with 3 fingers of fluffy tan head . insane lacing & head retention s : citric & floral hops show up early , but muted t : floral & piney hops , plus biscuitty malt up front .  the flavor left lying on the taste buds lasted an average amount of time , and was bold and flavorful.. mouthfeel was creamy and a tad oily in texture , and medium to full in body with a flat carbonation .
huge head showing great persistence and lacing .  m : light chalkiness is on the finish while medium carbonation and viscosity are the main .

roasted and crushed nuts make up the body with that nice roasty toasty edge . flavorful and easily sessioned brew .  a tad thin on the tongue ( possibly desired for style ) but all in all a good changeup .

( bb date 9-04 ) pours a nice cloudy peach or light orange color ( almost blond ) . superb appearance !  personaly , i 'd like the mouthfeel a bit fuller , but perhaps i 'm spoiled by the big pilsner which initiated the hoffmann series .

pours a pitch black colour with thick tan head . lots of lacing around the glass and nice head retention smells of black licorice and not too much else .  stella artois pours a pale yellow with a fluffy white head from a green twelve ounce bottle . aroma is standard euro lager skunky hop profile . the taste also reflects the same skunky hop profile . not particularly good to my taste . there 's cheaper and better alternatives to this . not recommended .

12 oz bottle into my oversized snifter ( no freshness dating on bottle ) a - deep golden amber , mostly clear , with a one finger thick white soapy head that has good retention and great lacing down the glass considering the abv .  how they got the enhanced mouthfeel is beyond me .

the head is cream in color , has tight bubbles , looks very creamy , and is about an inch thick . the lace is amazing . s - light hop smell .  the mouthfeel is decent , but not what i expected , which was a heavier feeling .

pours a dark brown/black color with a creamy tan head that left sheets of lacing down the glass . very nice !  the body is lush and thick , though unfortunately it 's marred by a fairly high level of carbonation .

great color . light lacing following a virtually non-existent head .  extremely fine carbonation that lends both sharpenss then smoothness ( beyond a somewhat soft malt character ) . seems a bit watery at times .
served in a brandy snifter , this beer pours black as night with a moderate tan head and aromas of rich roasted barley and floral hops eminating from the glass .  mouthfeel could be thicker .

on tap at st. james infirmary this is a really interesting beer . ruby red body , very different and alluring .  mouthfeel- light-medium body , medium carbonation , smooth , but does n't have much to offer on the palate .

decent one finger head has great retention and leaves decent lace down the glass s sweet grains with some booze and some petrol t not much better then the smell , pretty bad you know this beer has one purpose and that is getting drunk without spending money m/d i 've never drank petrol but i would guess it would feel something like this . looks great but it makes you gag as you swallow and that 's a trait i do n't like in my beer  mouthfeel is light with low carbonation .

aroma : very yeasty . fruity , banana . banana bread . taste : brown sugar , cloves & spicy , yeasty flavours . it reminds me of guava ( a tropical fruit ) juice .  this is a decent beer with a subtle nutty flavor to it . i typically enjoy drinking these in large quantities usually at the local bar while playing foozfall and darts . the beer emits a subtle aroma of malt , that is followed up quickly with a fairly well balanced taste . it has excellent drinkability . the only problem , and this is slight , is that it tastes a bit watered down sometimes .

awesome smell , can definately smell all of the hops ! overall , this beer is ok , but did n't quite live up to the hype for me .  3.0 m : medium body , which is lighter than i was expecting and much lighter than i had hoped . good carbonation . mouthfeel was lacking , but did n't effect my overall impression too much .
750ml bottle , pours a deep rose , hazy copper orange in the light . big rocky white head .  m : fairly smooth , either needs to be a little more carbonated or a little thicker .

pours a big head that retains very well , and with al= wonderful lacing .  lots of malty and caramel characteristics as an imperial brown ale . slight hint of like a scotch ale almost , but without the over-alcoholy taste . would definitely drink it again at that price and would even bring it to a party with average beer drinkers .
dark rich color , sweet , would like to see this with some age .  mouthfeel : smooth but a little watery or thin . nice carbonation .
poured into a champagne flute , it looks awesome . pale rose with a light pink frothy head .  thin to medium feel . this is my favorite saranac by far .

bottle # 266/350 and poured into a lost abbey tulip . appearance is black , even when held up to light , not super thick pouring . had a nice , moderately dark tan head of foam that sat well at a centimetre after pouring at a touch more .  while being the first irish red beer i 've had , it was very good . the reddish amber color and the malty flavor all made my pallate explode with joy . the overall experience of this beer was very good for me , while i have heard other people say that this is n't the best one out there , i enjoy it from time to time , and will continue to do so .

despite my shaky hands , this is still a sight to behold , packing amazing retention and shimmering color . enticing to say the least .  5 it 's a bit thin and the carbonation works to emphasize that .

strong notes of sourness and grapes . while the initial nose is sharp , there is a certain depth to this aroma ... perhaps derived from the oak mustiness . all in all , quite nice , and something i 'd be willing to share with a friend ... .  m - very bubbly , a little too bubbly , for my liking .

yet , a strong floral-hop aroma filled the room again raising expectations . the flavor was mild , without the abundant hop aroma promised ; a velvety and kinda watery sub-par pale ale ... a good cookout beer where taste is not too important .  very deep hop aromas , with huge citrus hop scents over a very nice deep maltiness . excellent flavor , with a huge malt forward and a great hop back that lasts on the tongue , with great citrus hop flavors . there is a fair bit of hop roughness , though .
smell is quite nice , big fruity farmhouse esters .  mouthfeel is a bit thin , slightly astringent , but somehow also smooth .

a : pours a nice looking dark red color with a cream colored head that stays for a pretty long time .  the taste is very pleasant with a citrusy sweetness and a little bit of tartness that almost reminds me of a cider this beer is extremely drinkable an i could imagine reaching for it over and over again . i 'll definitely be picking this beer up again sometime in the summer , it 's very refreshing .

pours a thick black with a small mocha head .  500 ml bottle from riga , it is rimi supermarket beer pours golden with rocky and fizzy head with rather good rention , some lacing . aroma is sweet grainy malty , feels rather sharp and is dominated by alcohol . taste is extremely sweet malty with alcohol and warming aftertaste . i could not manage more than a few sips from this beer .

it poured wonderfully , though it took a few minutes with the monstrous foamy head it produced . nice orange/amber color to it , a little murky .  feels a tad heavy with a micro-carbonation that thickens this one up quite a bit .

lively , clean and complex .  i typically love belgian ales , limes , and unique beer - this one definitely falls into all categories . the smell was mildly astringent . the taste reminded me of the smell of the detergent my gradeschool janitor used on the floor . someone else mentioned anbesol and that would also seem quite accurate . i 'm disappointed , as a lime-kissed belgian blonde ale sounds fantastic . this one does n't quite do it .

beer is a reddish amber color with lots of sediment s- very pungent ... could smell it as soon as i popped it open . smells very sweet with malts and fruit , and funky . almost like a much more appetizing medicinal smell t- bit of a let down in the flavor .  it is nicely carbonated ; the bubbles last till the end . the first sip is overwhelmed with carbonation and a tangy citrus under tone : almost like that first time or soda when the bubbles hit you , but this dose not last . the over all taste is a bit watery leaving a slight tangy-hopp after taste . it is a very easy beer to drink . the beer is a great beer to replace the useless monarchy of the current king of beers . for people who dont care what beer they drink and morally just go to bud , this is a great beer to get them hooked on .
18 february 2006 , best before june 06 light brown colour with a dense foamy pink head . great thick lacing and head retention .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , a bit drying on the back end .
the smell is absolutel phnomenal vanilla tons of caramel bourbon light oak and a hug boozy sweetness .  a little rough from overcarbonation .

poured a darkest coffee black with a large , fluffy , frothy brown head that slowly settled into a thin bubbly , sudsy lacing , small amount of ringed laced sticking , very impressive .  m - thinner than expected .

really incredible aroma . wow , where to begin .  i suppose an islay whiskey drinker might like the novelty of this beer . as a fan of wood aged beer and not of islay whiskey however , i would call this the worst thing i have ever tasted . i was the token beer geek in the group and as such i was the only one to finish the 3 or so ounces of beer in my glass . comments were : `` must be an aquired taste '' , `` aweful '' , `` that 's the worst thing i have ever tasted '' , and dumping the beer down the sink in descending of order preference . well , that being said , i am glad i tried it . it 's important to temper one 's taste for beer with the occasional dog brew .

pours out a nice black with a one finger tan head , ,looks creamy.smells just ok , a licorice smell { im not big on licorice } .wow bitter taste as i first sip.has a smoky taste , light on the licorice , bitter lasting taste.has a nice mouthfeel not too thick , not too thin.just an ok beer , no freshness date so i dont know how old this is.i had high hopes for this beer and was let down .  slightly darker copper appreance . nice strong stench that fills your nostrils . it has a very unique strong taste at first but leaves a nice smooth after taste . i have never had it on tap but bottled is just as good i assume . highly suggested if you have not tried and are a big bock fan ...
pours a nice dark amber , the smell is heavily bready .  body seemed a tad thin .
the aroma was absolutely unreal and wonderfully pungent .  m : medium-light body . carbonation is medium-light .
pours a gorgeous glowing rust color .  m : medium bodied mouthfeel , seems a bit thin and not a lot of carbonation o : a well-done , not over-the-top stout .

pitch black with a finger sized tan head . overall the flavor comes out too burnt , and the coffee is very dull .  the mouthfeel is better than its parent beer , probably just swimming in maltodextrin boosting .
beautiful murky copper , not much lacing .  m : medium to light bodied .

poured back as night , with 2 fingers of mocha head . great head retention & lacing s : roasted malt & some coffee t : big-time chocolate sweetness mingles with dryness & coffee up front .  m - almost medium bodied , i wish there was more creaminess and more body , definitely the most disappointing part of this beer .

appearance : pours pure golden-amber and perfectly transparent . beautiful carbonation and a huge head that leaves clouds of lacing along the side of the glass .  m - a little like bodied for a stout , but still light and creamy .
beautiful cascading effect to the head retention .  m - not too carbonated , especially given the foaminess of the head .
pours a deep burgundy color with a large sticky light tan head , a beautiful looking beer .  body is light and yet seems to be a bit too light .
it 's really amazing . the flavor is much milder than the aroma .  the feel is a little thin , but still enjoyable and easy to drink .

nitro-can $ 6.49 4-pack sam 's downers grove murphy 's stout poured the perfect looking pint out of the nitro-can . darkest of brown body bordering on black with mahogany highlights when held to the light . delicious looking cascade on the pour that formed a 2 finger head that acted like meringue and never went away . left big sticky lacing with each drink .  mouthfeel is light and fizzy , and drinkability is low due to the poor flavors .

very appealing looking beer in the glass ... aromas are grassy , floral , yeast like , spicy , and with a bit of a mineral hop smell .  my one complaint is that i feel the body is slightly lacking for an oatmeal stout , especially one that 's on cask .

smells awesome . i smell an abudance of roasted grains ... must have put copious amounts of chocolate , roast , black , and dark crystal malts .  it smells and tastes so nice that the thin body is even more disappointing .

beer poured a very nice clear dark amber with an exceptional creamy head , and left amazing lace on the side of the glass . the carbonation on this was very low , making it real smooth and mild up front .  it was medium in body with moderate carbonation .

a : totally black body , head is light brown creamy with good retention . lacing is great .  sometimes a beer has kind of a vomit taste . not full on vomit , just kind of . this was one of those times . it was from an hours-old growler . i 've had a couple of other beers with that prominent flavor note , and once it was with a beer that did not normally have a vomit taste . is it me ? or is it some particular thing that has gone wrong with the batch ? i do n't know . but with so many yet to try , i do n't want to try this one again to find out .
big head on this one , left behind some very pretty and surprisingly complex lacing .  mouthfeel slacks off a little .
a great stout appearance . deep , dark , indeed black body with a thick , frothy medium brown head .  mouthfeel is a little thin for an oatmeal stout ( or ris as stated in the style here ) .

a- pours a orange brown hue with a nice off white almost tannish head that has great retention .  i have n't yet had 100 different beers , so this takes the title of oddest beer to ever cross my palate . this beer tastes like bananna-flavored lemonade . just esters , hops , and yeastiness . ( i tried one without yeast , then one with yeast since the back label says you should dump the yeast in . ) i did n't notice anything about moutfeel one way or the other , so i give it a score of average . as for drinkability , this is a highly-flavorful light beer that a person could have quite a few of in a drinking session .
2011 bomber . excellent creamy head , tan color . body is a very dark brown .  mouthfeel is ok , syrupy but as expected for such a liquor .
probably the most stunning looking beer i 've ever seen .  this beer 's a little thin in body and the flavors are n't the strongest on the tastebuds but all in all this is a very good beer .

great score for appearance .  little bit chalky like most widmer beers ... - overall it 's a fantastic stronger version of drifter . just a bit thick and carbonated heavily for my taste in a double ipa .

pours a rich , nearly opaque body with a tall finely-bubbled creamy head that leaves crazy amounts of lacing on the sides of the glass .  m : here is where is is lacking a bit for me . it a bit light , and over carbonated . if the mouthfeel was smoothed out a bit.. creamier , this would rank much higher in my estimation .

there was a big fruity yeast aroma balanced by dry roasted malts , and perhaps a slight sweetish note from the honey .  hops do the bite the tongue quite sharply , but not as intensely as i was hoping , and as a previous reviewer stated , the flavors are not there to match . body is shockingly thin/light for a supposed double/imperial ipa , ditto with the abv . more intensity in hops , a better body , maybe some more balance with malt could bring improvements .

this was a great stout , but it could have been so much better . the appearance was exactly as a stout should be , which is black as midnight . i held it up to an 100w light and i could barely see some reddish hints at the bottom of the glass . flavor was blasts of chocolate , coffee but very smooth and little to no carbonation to it .  mouthfeel : pretty full-bodied as far as ipas go . sharp and crisp too , with the alcohol peeling itself off your tongue afterwards .

the nose is dominated by the hop floral aroma with sweet malt at the back , crisp and clean to the senses , start is sweet with a nice malt profile , top is middling in feel . finish is delectable in its acidity and the hops pronounced in their spiciness with a bitter-sweet aftertaste that lingers on long after the beer is gone , had a few of these , yummy .  wish i had taken better notes in my beer journal t - funky , spicy ; in essence all over my tongue . love the complexity m - not the beer 's strong suit . another instance of judging on style vs. judging categorically d - considering its complexity , this is a very drinkable beer

anchor- bock a- deep red , huge thick frothy head . heavy lacing down the glass . overall- a great looking beer that is quite easy to drink .  taste is good , nice malts , good alpha - maybe too much . bubble is sharp but small and not foamy .
poured out a heavily clouded bright yellow with about a finger of dense off-white foam .  body is a little light for a stout .

aroma is an intense acidic and vinous blend of plums , grapes , chocolate , oak , red wine , bourbon and after someone rudely suggested triple block i began to imagine soy . while i enjoyed this blend and contrast of bold flavors in the aroma , i though the taste was a sloppy mess . i guess i 'm interested in how this ages , but i would n't be surprised if this became really awesome or really terrible .  this beer was an amber color with a thick white head that dissipated quickly . a nice fruity/spicy taste , with some warmth in the aftertaste . it was a little too fizzy for me , but still a very smooth and drinkable beer
appearance : richly ruby hued with a adorning crown of sticky off white lace .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and a little watery .

very nice .  palate is slight corn and slight malt with a slight bitter hops and the carbonation . odouls is a slight of everything brew , no yummy malt , no well bittered hops bite , just a lot of gas ( carbonation ) and if you ask me , its a slightly boring brew .

very nice ! drinkable and worth a try but the flavor never matched the beautiful aroma .  low carbonation dominates , with earthy and mellow malt tones . a bit flat , but it works for the esb . i do not find the normal citrusy american hops , maybe they have reworked the beer .

pours a five+ finger white head that fades to a lumpy layer leaving a good lace . nice crystal clear amber color .  i get a whiff of something like sparkling mineral water , a hint a citrus , and light grains . the grapefruit is only slightly more prominent on the palate . has flavors of light , nondescript grains , with a few drops of watery fruit punch , with nothing really popping or asserting its presence . i do n't detect much in the way of ginger ( which the label says it was brewed with ) . easily my least favorite of the shiner lineup .
this badd boy pours a big thick creamy looking head with very good lacing for a stout .  it has a mouthfeel of cough syrup . the one saving grace is this still had some carbonation left in it .

smells so good . chocolate and a touch of hops hit the mouth right away , then some serious coffee comes in .  my complaint is the really light body , something this dark could easily have a bit more weight to it without being overpowering . strong carbonation , mixed with the light body , almost gives a cola feel .
lots of lace rings with good retention . one of the better looking browns imo .  body is on the thin side of medium .

in 10 years time , american water will probably be this hoppy . it displays the hop -- bitter on the back of the tongue , sweetly aromatic ( like bubble gum incense ) -- without being an asshole about it .  it feels a touch too thin and watery .

fred pours smooth , retains head for hours , and is amber and hazy in appearance . definately can see bubbles from ample carbonation .  i work at a distributer that sells this beer so i had to try it . at first open i thought that the high alcohol smell would make for a bad beer . after a couple sips , it was actually pretty good . i would compare it to miller high life ... .except that you get smashed after two or three beers . since beer is for the purpose of getting drunk ... this is the right one . if it taste good and serves it 's purpose , why not take this one . since i do work at a distributor that sells high end beers , if anyone ask for a good beer that will serve its purpose , i will highly recomend camo & gt ;
nice amber and deep orange color - a nice looking brew . smells all malts .  light bodied with a bland feel on the palate and touch of carbonation tingle .

aroma is chocolately and full of caramel . nuttiness makes up the background . sweet maltiness is inviting and also provides some nice hop aomas .  a thicker then water feel , but not much . o- very much on the lighter side for a hefeweizen .

that thick cap remains the whole way and leaves lots of nice looking lacing down the glass . beautiful look and colour . this is as good as it gets here .  the ultimate cross-over lager to bigger and better beers . still , it was the first `` national '' beer i can remember that decided that a brisk hop aroma was not a bad thing as the macro brewers had seemingly ordained . the body varies somewhat between light to medium-perhaps based on the brewery from which it was contracted ?
pours a lightly cloudy golden orange color with a large , three fingers of soapy white head and some impressive retention .  moderate carbonation , medium-light body , this part of odouls is decent .
pours a nice cloudy gold , as you 'd expect .  the body was medium light and just a bit on the thin side .

a - very deep amber in color . beautiful beige head with good retention and very small , fine bubbles .  mouthfeel is n't as stellar as the taste . there is a distinct lack of carbonation that i like but the beer finishes very dry which does n't work to well . good thing this one tastes so good because the flavor of this almost full bodied beer distracts from the lackluster feel .

12 oz bottle poured into a pilsner glass . a - a slightly aggressive pour made the tan head rise to two-and-a-half fingers and stay well retained for quite a while . dense bubbles coat the glass in a ring of foam . totally clear amber beer .  yielded a monstrous thick white head.a very cloudy yellowish-orange.very inviting aroma with hints of spiceskind of smells like unibroue 's la fin du monde.a very crisp mouthfeel almost harsh like seltzer.very citrus flavor with a slight bitter finish that lingers in the back of the throat.a bit but not much lace.high drinkability with this one.very crisp , clean , and refreshing .

big thanks to shogokawada for this extra ... pour a beautiful maple color ... with a nice head that seems like an ice cream float ... bobbles around the top of the beer nicely ... looks awesome ! smells ... like a bud .  this is a little lighter in feel and really does n't give that nice buzz that railbender 's 6.8 % leaves you with .

a nice film stays and decent lacing down the glass . pretty nice looking .  did not like this beer at all . i have had many worse , but i found no compelling reason to finish this one off . the look is pretty nice , but the aroma is overpowering with a over malty smell . the same goes with the taste ... was it sparged too hot ? i 'm not sure but it tastes like that too me . it does go down nicely considering the taste . i did n't finish off the beer and do n't see why you should either , it 's just way to malty for a pilsner for me .
appearance- pours a very nice deep chocolatey brown with a solid 2-3 finger head . plenty of lacing makes its way down the glass the whole way .  m : carbonation and weight are really just average .
an extremely addictive sweet smell of ripe fruits arise from the glass .  the pint i had had no head , and very little if any carbonation .
i expect a deep amber or orange or copper when it comes to pumpkin ales . i love the aroma of this beer . it actually smells like pumpkin pie .  m - the feel is rather watery with a coarse texture .

pours a light copper color with a two finger head into my bruery tulip , great lacing while the head sticks around .  the mouthfeel on this seems somewhat like it 's mostly carbonation , which disappoints somewhat , but it 's full and silky .

looked like a nice rich ipa . really amazing smelling beer . nicely balanced , soft pine ... not as sticky as i had expected . candy , banana , bubblegum ... all blended with a citric undertone . the hops are so over the top , my palette hurts . d - i 'll be honest ... it 's a bit over the top for me . the way that this beer is praised and put side-by-side with much better balanced beers really made me expect another sublimely balanced hoppy ipa . the smell is there , but the rest is just kind of like a sn pale ale on steroids ( and i quite like snpa as it is ) .  the body and mouthfeel are decent , at least .
quite enticing . t : malty notes up front with a little bit of hoppy bitterness to follow .  kind of like chocolate flavored sparkling water . ok here .
a : clear reddish brown color with a solid one-finger off white head that left rings of sticky lacing .  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied and kind of watery .
the sweet aroma draws me in .  the body of this brew is a little skinny , but the flavor profile makes this one a nice drinker .

great skunky aroma . the good kind .  mouthfeel : a bit thin for a bottle-conditioned weiss beer ( at least i 'm assuming it 's bottle-conditioned ) . still , there 's a enough great things about this beer to offset the rather pedestrian mouthfeel .
ink black with the hugest tan head sets up a pretty picture .  m - mouthfeel is light and thin , though not terribly so .
a - giant orange-tinged foam with great retention and glass-coating lace .  fresh mouthfeel , but not much taste at first , clear chocolate and a bit of coffee in the aftertaste though .

carbonation is swirling in the midst of a pale yellow body and it builds a huge , billowing white head that leaves chunky lacing . belgian strong pale appearance ?  mouthfeel : overcarbonated . if this was poured and left out for say an hour at a controlled temp it would be amazing .
absolutely fantastic . t : exactly as above with some freshly shaved lemon/orange zest .  m : carbonation is light , and the feel is a bit thin , especially considering the roasted malts in here .

s - fresh fruit ( big purple ripe grapes on the vine ) and cut grass waft over to my nose from arm 's length while i poured this one . let 's see what it smells like up close . german chocolate cake , cocoa , coconut , and chocolate breakfast cereal . there are hints of port , and hershey 's kisses . there is a nice , but odd , purple grapey flavor in the finish . d - a bit too sugary and under-hopped imo . the nose is subtly complex , but the flavor is too cloying . this is good stuff .  what this beer lacks in a thinner mouthfeel actually makes up for it in drinkability .

a : clear medium-amber body with a big 3 '' head of rocky white foam . good retention and tons of fine spiderwebs of lace . lovely .  m : tingly , very prickly carbonation d : i could only drink one glass of this , but it is delicious !

pours a burnished orange , couple fingers of head , good retention , lovely lace .  12 oz bottle into a dfh signature glass wow what a mess this beer was . while it looked fairly innocuous in the glass what was hiding in its depths was anything but ... butterscotch . lots and lots of butterscotch . this is where diacetyl men and diacetyl women meet up to have little bastard diacetyl babies . if saranac would change the label to saranac butterscotch porter they would probably have an award winner on their hands because this sure as hell meets that description . in a word ... terrible .

fantastic aroma -- very full and pungent . tons of roasty malts & oatmeal sweetness right up front . taste follows the nose . strong malts balanced nicely by bitter chocolate & faint hops . a touch watery on the finish , but still quite good .  somewhat thin but easy to drink .

complex , pale , clean and inviting . taste brings on a rummy booziness to add to its complexity which is more warming than i would have anticipated with this being at what many in its style consider a modest 8 % . quite vinous , with taste bringing on an equal balance of red and white grape .  mouthfeel is a little dry once you kill one or two of these bad boys , but the taste and smell definitely makes up for it .

smell is very nice and sweet , like fresh raspberries . taste is not too bad , reminds me more of wine than beer , but still pretty good . mouthfeel also leans more towards a wine than a beer , slight sourness followed by a sweetness .  thinner and lighter bodied than i expected , but it does n't detract from the enjoyment of this beer .

aroma is saison splendor , classic . a nice blend of citrus and floral notes . the barnyard is in the far distance .  it smells like rotten fruit ( bananas , apples , and grapes ) . it tastes like cotton candy ice cream mixed with bittersweet oaky busch light . in the words of samir nahinanajad : `` this ... is a f -- k '' update : the last 2/3 of this went down the drain . this is the second beer i 've ever done this with ... i do n't waste beer .

a - bottle conditioning manifests itself as a frothy fist-full of head . nice wide range of foam density that leaves creamy peaks . great lacing with chunks of froth clinging to the sides of the glass .  i found this beer to be incredibly fragrant and smooth , with a fairly strong hazelnut flavour . not particularly heavy or bold , and would probably not be easy to drink more than one because of the powerful almost coffee like flavour . the hazelnut flavour and aroma is n't quite overpowering , but it 's close .
it pours a light orange-yellow color with a heaping 5 finger duvel-style head . there is lots and lots of lacing left here .  the body is typical for the style .

this beer was poured from a 12 oz bottle into a tumbler , revealing a gorgeous orange amber color , with a 1/4 '' head that lasts a few minutes . a ; very subdued surprizingly .  tingly mouthfeel brought in the flavor of more hoppy fruit-sweet malt mix .
very surprising for a mrzen , but also very pleasing . there 's also a deep , rich caramel aroma .  finishes a little dry . mouth feel is almost champagne like and very effervescent .

looks pretty much perfect for a stout .  its possibly the second smokiest beer i 've smelled behind the alaskan smoked porter . the flavors are very well integrated . it drinks a little light for a porter but with the flavor profile its ok . this beer is pretty superb , i 'm very impressed , its an excellent smoked beer .

dark oak colour with ruby highlights and a majestic tan coloured head that laced profusely .  i have enjoyed several growlers of this beer . it pours dark , with a nice head and good carbonation at first , but it goes flat if you do n't finish the growler in 1 night . probably normal , but too bad since i ca n't buy it in smaller containers . taste is smooth , with roasted chocolate flavor , and very drinkable . not so drinkable that i can pound away the whole growler in one sitting , but very enjoyable as a refreshing beverage in warmer weather .
a : pours a deep black with no visible light .  mouthfeel is a bit lacking .

i was interested in trying brown shugga ; i ca n't help feel a little let down a- clear redish brown , one finger tan head s- the best part of the beer was the anticipation of the brown shugga flavor , it had a smell , not too over powering , but sweet .  m : sweet , citrus , malty .

overall an excellent style and a lovely beer .  appearance : brown nutty color smell : nothing notable , somewhat sweet taste : delicious sweet barley and hoppy flavor moutfeel : medium carbonation , not full bodied drinkability : good enough to enjoy as a regular

this beer has very good head retention and excellent lacing as well . in other words , this beer looks damn good .  the fizzy yellow stuff of the great white north , as far as i 'm concerned . that 's right , corn . prominent in the aroma and taste , along with some traces of malt and hops . i was quite thirsty after a bout with us customs , and this failed to satisfy . difficult to finish .

a - super clear golden color with a thick white head that has excellent retention s - floral with sweet malt , touch of honey , no hop t - bready malts with a smooth hop balance , flavor is accented with the lavender floral taste which is present long into the finish m - medium-light body with moderate carbonation d - overall this is an interested recipe and well-executed by sam adams .  m not very much mouthfeel .

the beer is very clear straw color with a creamy white head that has great retention and lacing . i 'm conflicted on this because i hate such a light colored beer but has a great head .  appearance : dark orangish yellow , good head that recedes too quickly but has good white lacing . smell : reminds me of a homebrew with a bacterial infection . taste : i do n't know but get it off my tongue ! somebody grab a water hose ! who buys this garbage ? ! drinkability : if you tried to force this on prisoners , they 'd complain to the warden .

nose has hints of melon , sweet pineapple , a real nice touch . citrus smell .  m : the mouthfeel was the only disappointment , as i was expecting something a little bit more evervescent given the light color - in my mind a light ipa needs to be more carbonated than a dark ipa .

there was a huge amount of creamy/fluffy , long-lasting head .  what a name ! good thing this one lives up to that mouthful . a cloudy ( unfiltered ) straw gold extra special bitter with orange hues . developed a creamy , glass-crawling white head with good retention that left some nice lacing . strong , hoppy aroma with a medium-heavy body . malty bread , apricots , butterscotch , citrus notes . yum . a great example of their extreme series , bold and complex .

beautiful ruby-brown with a lingering head .  great brew to enjoy on warm or hot days . apricot aroma eclipses any malt or hops on the nose . taste is predomanantly apricot/peach , with just a slight bite of hops in the finish . the clean malt helps to balance out the apricot . a great , simple , summer session beer for hot days .
extremely solid appearance .  the flavor is there , it 's just a little thin .

its good , but something you ca n't just crush nor is a tripel . no floral hops at all ... the feel is ok , easy to take few drinks , then its just to much .  if this brew has a weakness it is in the mouthfeel , it is light for an oatmeal stout .

let me just say this beer is one of the greatest smelling beers i 've ever had . just wonderful . now the taste starts off well .  mouthfeel smooth and milk-like . i would prefer the carbonation be toned down a bit for a silkier , less astringent effect .
the bitterness of the beer is not balanced with anything . the nose on the beer is amazing and choc full of hops .  mouthfeel light body with a bit of carbonation .

the body is n't nearly as black as i remember , more light a dark brown , with amber tones by the edge of the glass . 1/2 '' creme colored head holds on for a long time , some muddy brown colored curtains from the head falling back into the body . the lacing is very impressive , it coats everywhere with a thick creme curtain .  mouthfeel is near average , a bit more body and flavor concentration would be welcome .

nose is sweet fruits and alcohol , with something heavier but hard to identify coming through . so far so good .  mouthfeel is light , but some weight from the yeast sediment , but the carbonation is weak .

this beer looks and smells great . its a very dark brown thats nearly black in color , a cream-like tan head . after that , the rest of the beer is pretty bland .  surprising hoppiness is only accentuated by the high carbonation level .
poured into a delerium snifter . deep red in color , phenomenal head that stays like a film over the top of the glass .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin with low carbonation .
on-tap at the irish pub a - light orange color with a bright white silky head , very smooth with tons of lacing .  mouthfeel is a bit syrupy for me , but this beer far outweighs any cider around .

very strawberry aroma , enough real strawberry with the actual fruit bits , that the beer is disguised . good fruity dessert aftertaste.i am not running after fruit beers , but this was the most natural of the many presented this summer in ontario .  mouthfeel - light smoothness , carbonation is a tad low . average weight .

brilliant orange/copper color with loads of tiny bubbles that create a bit of haze . solid white foam that lingers and then settles into beautiful ring present all the way down to the last sip . just a wonderful looking beer .  my first scotch ale and it made me feel pretty good on an empty stomach . the great dane makes some great beers , but they make everything too thin .

nose is quite organic , with a lot of herbal characters , green grape skin , hint of honey , very finely balanced though . phenomenally well balance , tart and sweet and bitter are all there , very natural , funky herbal smell . hang is there , a bit tart , but otherwise very nicely balanced . mouthfeel is full , thick and sticky - very nice , and there is not a hint of the 8 % alc/vol . a shit-fucked good beer in fact . i like this so much i love it .  m - medium bodied with extremely lively carbonation that is a bit too brisk and prickly .

welll for a am macro this baby showed head retention and lacing that could teach a good euro pils/lager a thing or two . i was impressed by how good this beer looked right out of the fridge .  very light body . smooth from the over active carbonation . i 'm not a big fan of light beer .

trying to pour this it is an intensely head forming beer it is a clear dark brown colored ale i observe . an impervious black colored beer in the glass with a dark brown head .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with little carbonation .

poured from a 22 oz bottle into a tulip . this beer pours beautifully . dark amber , very clear . probably it 's best feature . the appearance is beautiful , but nothing else really impresses .  there 's just something off with the taste that did not work m : crisp and light d : drainpour .

a- this one pours out a very nice looking copper colored body with a small white head that quickly fades to a mere skim .  mouthfeel is creamy , and would be even better if half of the carbonation was n't so harsh , with sharp edged bubbles .

black with burnt edges , and a very generous creamy white head that puffed up to about a finger in length . lacing is just what i look for in my stouts , coating the sides beautifully . a glass of eye candy !  for real , closest mass-produced craft beer to snpa . coppery , high crystal malt appearance with nice head and typical bottled carbonation . grassy . flavor is a bit bitter at first followed by some mild hoppy/flowery/cascady flavors . bite at finish . not too much but bitter enough to say this is a pale ale . fine everyday drinking pale ale but nothing exceptional or cheeky . b+

a- pours an absolutely beautiful golden color with amber hues . a hefty 3 finger head forms as a big fluffy mound that dissipates very slowly , leaving thicck sheets of sticky lacing down the glass .  feel is moderately light with a fair amount of carbonation .

truly a gorgeous looking beer , and i ca n't find a fault with it .  oy gevalt ! pours an interesting reddish brown slightly hazy body with a finger of beige-white head . head lingers and it laces the glass well . aroma is nice and sweet . tastes very hoppy with dates dark fruit notes . a bit of a bite in the aftertaste , that is not pleasant !

got a pitcher at the tap room , into a pint glass this beer is pretty much the exact same as the nitro can version . the only difference is that maybe the mouthfeel was a bit more chewy and thicker , and the darker malts were , well , maltier .  mouthfeel is watery with a crisp finish .

the aroma is quite flowery with hints of corriander , orange peel and other citrus smells .  aroma is orange and lemon wedges , sweet and sugary . taste is nicely balanced , lemon zest and pepper for a little kick of spice , but not quite a hefe in the traditional sense . slight bitterness at the end from the hops . nothing to write home about but a very sessionable ale . a solid american wheat ale , a good choice to have while watching some baseball in the summer or at a fourth of july party .
a very fruity apple nose to the beer , smells like an apple cider rather than a beer .  flavors are big , and the mouthfeel is incredibly full and well rounded .

smells of centennial and cascade . perhaps the hop aromas would be more overpowering in a fresher example , but i enjoy this beer very much .  mouthfeel - very smooth with easy-going carbonation . a healthy body , really lifts up the flavors .

this cork was one pain in the ass to get out . poured dark black , with brown edges , and an averaged sized off white head . aromas of smoke , roastiness , chocolate , caramel , and coffee .  lush and extremely creamy on the palate . super fine carbonation structure ; uncious and smooth , velvety even . the booze becomes a bit burdening , as is expected with the high abv .

the smell on this one was amazing ! i could smell it right away as i began to pour . lots of hops on the nose , and sweetly so . a little bit of fruit in there ( apricots ? well balanced . great carbonation level and nice weight for the style .  m : right about perfect for the style ( or nearly any style ) .
s - awesome stuff ! excellent stuff here . i like a little carbonation in my wild ales , but otherwise this was pretty nice .  excellent mouthfeel , i enjoyed this one a lot .

aroma has citrus , nice light malt , lots of breadiness -- - more than i 've ever smelled in a beer -- - and some hops . bursting with rich malt and light fruitiness . just enough hops to keep it from being cloying -- - leave it to a german-style brewer to avoid the over-hopping which characterizes so many american microbrews . quite drinkable .  as in the nose , some alcohol in the finish m : incredibly smooth , creamy mouthfeel . full bodied with just enough carbonation d : great , easy drinking imperial stout .

the aroma is citrusy . i get orange , lemon , and even lime . that being said , i am not a big pilsner fan .  silky smooth mouthfeel with only mild carbonation makes this one lean a little to the full side as far as body goes . full bodied or not , i could go for a few more of these .
smells phenomenal . the nose is awesome tastes heavily of bourbon with a touch of hops but not very bitter .  absolutely a wonderful mouthfeel perfectly carbonated hiding its abv very well .

s : notes of red wine , lots of brown sugar , pleasing smell . t : aged malt , bit of a harsh husky quality to the flavour .  mouthfeel is great . very smooth and silky thanks to the oatmeal with just the right amount of carbonation .
s : sweet chocolate really dominates with a slight bit of dark malt .  mouthfeel is thick and creamy chewy . mouthfeel of manufacturer 's cream .

smells of fall spices , yeast spiciness , and a earthy flavor . some sweetness on the nose as well . taste was a little disspointed as i figured the beer would have more caramel flavors , and a little more yam .  the taste is mellow chocolate on the front as it glides down with its thick silky mouth feel . almost a fudge aftertaste .

the smell is wonderful . very concentrated malts along with nice balancing hops .  it is quite pleasing to the pallet and has an amazing mouthfeel , i also had no problem finishing up such a large bottle because of its wonderful drinkability .

the smell is full of intense grassy/corn based malt character . lots of dried grain on the smell as well . alcohol smell is pretty present , lots of starchy rice layers . slighthly funky yeast character . nice alcohol warmth and rounded lager yeast punch at the end .  m : medium-light bodied , remarkably smooth and creamy . d : very enjoyable and satisfying .

the aroma is overwhelmed by chocolate and coffee with the oatmeal , a bit of bread or biscuits balancing it out . the taste is very nice although not quite as powerful as the aroma lead you to believe . it is full of coffee grinds , chocolate , and a pleasing background of hops . overall this is a fine oatmeal stout .  the mouthfeel is absoutely perfect for this style ... thick , creamy and subdued ... as i mentioned before ... the consistency of a nitro , yet this brew still maintains is flavour .
an in your face blast of freshly roasted coffee beans that just were devoured by there enemy the grinder .  mouthfeel is large , with almost a creamy texture .

smell- this year 's example ( 2008 ) is exceptionally fragrant and appealing ... the coriander and orange peel is *way* upfront , and could be considered too much so , i 'm sure . i love it , on the basis of its sheer perfection . sweet , tigerlily-like aromas fill the air . taste- the spices explode across the tongue instantly , unraveling and unveiling a very deep and delicious array of layers that incorporate what seems to be rosehips , among other flowery elements . it 's the most uneventful aspect of this tasting .  almost a perfect mouthfeel , both for the style and for a beer in general .

head fizzled quickly but smelled great . smell even though thin and too boozy was big time freshly baked gingerbread , pumpkin spice and nutmeg .  nice mouthfeel and great body to it along with quite a flavor punch to your taste buds .

s : you can really smell the hops as this beer is poured . other scents i got from it were of flowers and citrus . d : this is a pretty damn good beer , i would definitely drink it again .  i like the unique green apple and middle eastern-style rose candy flavors , and it has a nice , full mouthfeel for such an easy drinking brew , with lots of dark yeast floating at the bottom .

hint of boozy fusel barrel juice , vanilla , charred wood , roasted grain and a blackberry brandy fruitiness . hard to balance near perfection like this in a bigger beer .  mouthfeel is great . alot going on in the mouth . full bodied and crazy carbonation .

the other thing that you notice straight away is the beautiful fruity aroma that climbs out of the glass as you are pouring . i will straight away say that i am not a fan of belgian pale ales .  mouthfeel is excellent , best i have ever had from an ipa , i know this is coming from the oatmeal , but this is serving as inspiration for me to make a good oatmeal ipa at home now , too bad this is n't around longer as it was a great beer .

it smells like coffee , i have never had a beer that smells prety much 100 % liek coffee like this before . i am not a coffee drinker but i enjoy most coffee beers , this one smells like it could be cold , carbonated , alcoholic coffee .  mouthfeel is buttery - so smooth with just a tinge of carbonation .
smell : citrus and floral with just a hint of malt .  m : medium-bodied , low carbonation results in a creamy and silky smooth mouthfeel .

sexual chocolate was not any good , barrel aging it certainly did not improve it much , if any ... a super dark black pour that is lacking most carbonation ... the aroma gets this off to a nice start that makes me think i finally found a good foothills beer . the aroma is a touch to light but shows complexity that you 'd think would be tough with some a chocolate dominated base , light bourbon , a touch of canilla , a chocolate all come through really balanced ; the taste not so much .  has a great mouthfeel .

the best part about the beer is the huge pine scent . blindfold a person make them take a big whiff and you could convince them they in a british columbia pine forest .  mouthfeel - it has a nice blanketing feel , a moderate heaviness that coats without being a filler . full body matches the flavor perfectly .

great aroma of vanilla and chocolate , and hints of coffee , but i 'm not getting hazelnut , nor any hops .  it is incredibly smooth and creamy in the mouth , certainly one of the creamiest feels i 've ever had .

the nose is musty and funkey from the lambic and banana sweet . it is after all a banana lambic . the flavor is full of banana initially , moving to a rind-like flavor , almost a banana peel , on the finish . the somewhat cloying sweetness on the initial sip is a bit overwhelming .  mouthfeel is full bodied with minimal carbonation .

s - best smelling ipa i have had . sweet floral . it is definitely good , but has room for improvement .  buttery , syrupy mouthfeel , like butterscotch and cream . this one is truly a treat ; it has seemed to age really , really well , with a wonderful balance of flavors and a vinous profile that is not overpowering or overwhelming .

s - fresh raspberry , real raspberry like what you get in those small plastic containers in the produce section of your local supermarket . it even has that mildly plant-like scent . its like i mashed a raspberry in my hand and then smelled my hand .  fuller body , decent carbonation , sticky , silky smooth , and creamy on the tongue . i 've heard some people say this needs some time , but this is fantastic right now .
the smell was spectacular ! plums , cherries , lots of alcohol and some distant malts .  m : damn near perfect . smooth , silky , easy .

the smell is great ! two sniffs ... mouth open ... the whole deal is well worth it . i was hoping the taste would have been as great as the smell . the taste is good at best .  body is quite full with a nice creamy texture , no apparent alcohol and good carbonation . very good overall and easily drinkable which makes this one the best in this series .

poured into a bateman 's ( good honest ales ) pint sleeve glass . aroma was very hoppy , yeast and peppery/ginger smells also prevail as you sniff the brew . i have had this beer at beer fests in its cask form and do n't remember the aromas being so strong , being bottle conditioned obviously aides the beer some way in the smell stakes . the beer has a spritzy , lively feel to it , a fresh almost young ( green ) taste . typical english bitter flavours , but fairly well pronounced for such a carbonated beer .  m : thick and chewy d : the massive flavors make this one a sipper , but unfortunately , due to the liqour like alcohol burn , this one is n't very drinkable ... .yet.. as the one i had is already aged 1 year , i 'm guessing this thing needs a good 3-5 years to really smooth out .

aroma is just about the best lambic / gueuze aroma you can imagine . its amazing , funky , mildly acetic , good brightness , mild leather , good overall . a very good beer though .  once she warmed a little , i got an amazing mouthfeel of chocolate milky smoothness . very creamy , with some hop sweetness with a touch of vanilla .

a - a very clensed ruby-brown that pour a thin vanilla head that disipates quickly s - great a plethora of spice , fruits , and toasted earthy hints t - great light and complex with a good balance m - for the toasted malt and hop nature the brew carries it has no pretentious overwelmingness ... .aka well balanced d - will drink anytime i get the chance to .  the feel is super tannic and sticks to your mouth .
the smell is delightful . this is sweet biscuity malts , chocolate , molasses , and caramel .  m/d : a medium to full body that is velvety smooth . very rich and creamy .
nice banana smell , some wheat , clove and caramel . smelled great , but taste was marred a bit by a strong boozy finish at times .  this beer feels thicker than it is .

this is a wonderfully complex aroma that lends itself more towards a sour than a saison . nonetheless , it 's fantastic . t : the under-ripe tones of the fruit are prevalent moreso in the flavor than in the nose and man is it full of it .  mouthfeel : medium to bodied with an air of hops , alcohol and what i can only assume is the effect of the oak cask all mix with the hoppy bitterness to create an amazing mouthfeel .

this was a very decent ipa- it looked great with a reddish brown tint and a very aromatic aroma from the generous hops . very refreshing , but if drinking in a session , your tastebuds will take a while to recover .  yet this red ale has an absolutely amazing full , creamy mouthfeel , wholly unexpected for this style , which leaves me duly impressed , it is a textural pleasure to drink this ale , a damn palatal masterpiece , worth the price alone .

while the nose is fairly one-dimensional , it smells damn good ! t - heavily roasted in the flavor and very dry cocoa with dirt and bitter chocolate .  mouthfeel : creamy and round and full like no other , like a caress of silk towards the palate . the carbonation is , as expected , low but it should n't be in any other way considering the smoooth outcome !
s : ahh , coffee . still nice , but a let down coming off the nose .  thick smooth mouthfeel and mildly carbonated . the creamy smoothness is more apparent and delightful now .

kind of a sweet and spicy scent to it , reminscent almost of white pepper the taste follows the aroma , with an obviously high hop profile , i almost expected it to be legit spicy ( like jalapeno chip spicy ) , but it was n't .  mouthfeel : wonderful . feels like champagne and the sourness makes my mouth water .
smells of sweet fruit - mainly pineapple .  mouthfeel was silky with a nice interaction of hops and malt on the tongue . finish was super smooth , going down like a champ .

this is nice actually . the nose has a genuinely rich and sophisticated bouquet . 4.5 t : keeping with the theme we get peach , red apple and some alcohol .  m - incredible . the creamiest beer i have ever had .

the strongest thing about this brew is it 's intense , spicey , dry-malt , car-freshner scent . very nice lacing out of this deep brown beer , good foamy white head . very bubbly . unique , but not a good high-quantity beer .  mouthfeel is spot on . thick and syrupy with just enough carbonation .
smell is just amazing . i 've never really grasped `` floral '' hops until this . the malt is there , and it 's somewhat balanced even .  feels lovely in the mouth .
smell is very strong and floral , very nice .  m : so creamy and thick .
roasted coffee and a bit of oak in the aroma . lots of good caramel and roasted malts here .  felt smooth and creamy in the mouth .
pretty interesting aromas ; i 'm drooling ... t-wow , not following the nose at all .  mouthfeel is creamy smooth and full bodied .
the smell is by far the best thing about this beer .  velvety-smooth texture with full body . the hops stand out at this young age .

aroma is awesome ! candy apple , semi-sweet chocolate , pear , light banana scent and some boozy characteristics to name a few . very complex smell . reminds me of a barelywine or a tripel . excellent ! the big aroma i inhale each time i sip is nice . there is a slight warming from the alcohol presence .  a really creamy smooth mouthfeel that feels almost cask like .
s - full roasted malts , mild smoke , chocolate and dried fruit .  mouthfeel the mouthfeel on-cask is unbelievable . it is so smooth and pleasantly foamy it literally makes your mouth water .
this beer is a good balance of citrus and evergreen and is very aromatic .  mouthfeel : incredibly mellow and smooth . a perfect feeling beer , truly .
aroma is delicious , a mix of light , creamy coffee , chocolate malts and bananas coated in fudge . expertly crafted like most ng 's .  m- big , creamy , great carbonation , spot-on .
