t : the taste does not follow in light of the awesome nose . bitter almost to the point of a bad sour , a little hint of fruit , and a slightly roasty finish .  superb mouth feel , a full sensory experience . the after taste is delicious , tongue coating , coffee , full bodied .
nose is exceptional . this could seduce any non-beer drinker into having a sip . so , so seductive nose .  mouthfeel fantastic . one bottle went to the head .

aroma is quite rich , very spicy with tons of cinnamon , cardomom , thyme , sage , ginger , nuts , caramel , tobacco , chocolate and a mild alcohol touch . quite complex and appealing .  m - mouthfeel is perfect . silky smooth bubbles and full bodied texture .

perfect blend of bready malts , lager yeast traits and subtle flowery hops on the nose . i love this aroma . it 's got some poundcake aromas as well without seeming overly sweet .  on the palate it is very supple and silky , with beautiful integration of aggressive ruby red grapefruit flesh flavors with dry impressions of honey . it is cascading , dry and very grapefruit-infused tonic ( a quality i usually despise in beer ) . a beautiful sequence of spice , honey and grapefruit in a very dry , mouthmelting texture package .

aroma : dry hopped with centennial and crystal hops ca n't beat this , great floral earthy hop aroma nice mellow caramel malt tone good stuff . drinkability : the aroma alone leaves me wanting more and more beer , awesome stuff not expecting anything here but boy i 'm i glad i found this gem of a balanced hoppy ale .  exceptionally smooth mouthfeel , a buttery diacetyl eases it along .

aroma is very deep , with fig , overripe plum , green apple , caramelized orange peel , ginger , phenols , and a touch of saccharine cola . rummy raisins , orange peel , ginger , and licorice . alcohol and carbonation are a bit too apparent and so this beer is not particularly drinkable , but it is a nice warming winter treat to share .  m : i love how smooth this beer feels in my mouth .

a very pleasant sipper , mildly complex and delightfully balanced , however maybe a little past it 's prime as its lost the robustness and complexity of the regular wee heavy .  creamy , a textural marvel really ... .likely the creamiest and most velvety beer i 've had .
overall a great smelling stout . t- coffee is definitely in the taste , but not in the quantity i expected .  mouthfeel- silky smooth , even though it was more tart than i usually liked in my beer .

nice rich and malty nose ! smells big and robust . smells smoky and dry with chocolate malts and sweet toffee . fantastic nose on this one !  mouthfeel is full and creamy with a sharp smooth . very crisp with a dry finish . excellent beer .

s-rich , dark fruit with plums being the predominant smell , some sweet , deep caramel and some traces of alcohol .  the incredible thing here is the smoothness -- this beer goes down so easily , and the flavor is so well-integrated . medium-light carbonation massages the tongue amidst a creamy medium body . it 's very lightly fizzy . absolutely incredible drinkability .
simply lovely . clean pour , good carbonation , light foamy top .  the mouthfeel is beyond silky it is down right syrupy !

it 's very thick , but you can see each individual bubble that makes it up , kinda neat . tastewise , it is indeed the noble hop bomb as promised . grassy hops , some flowery finish .  just enough carbonation to balance the syrupy nature of the beer .

otherwise , very enjoyable . drinkability : a dessert beer .  where this beer really excels is in the mouthfeel , which is everything you can hope for from a cask . its smooth and full , with a wonderfully deep texture that shows baird know how to make a great cask .

a- pitch black , non-transparent , thin tan color head that faded quickly s- fresh coffee , dark chocolate , sugary , creamy , vanilla t- cocoa powder , burnt malts , old coffee , bitter , hint of sweetness m- medium/heavy body , medium carbonation , smooth , slight burn of alcohol d- not worth trying the appearance and auroma of this beer makes you anxious to try it , but all that excitement ends once you taste it .  smooth and hoppy with that cask-pureed-banana mouthfeel .
the smell was fruity , spicy hops with not much malt . this was a very nice and very hoppy double ipa .  wow.. good powerful stuff . super smooth in the mouth , and almost creamy in feel .
beautiful head and wonderful aroma . that is the good news .  very silky smooth , awesome all around .

spiced nose , big time . pumpkin notes , all spice , cinnamon , caramel , toasted grain , great nose . flavour is clean and toasty , the pumpkin is clearly there at all times , and is accompanied by light cinnamon and all spice , big on the bread , huge in fact . it 's a big beer , so it 's naturally a bit thicker than normal , but i think it could have been improved with more carbonation ( god forbid thinking how snazzy this would be on a nitro tap ... ) . the drinkability is also a skosh above average , one of the better pumpkin beers i 've had , and probably my favourite one with these spices since the long-dead harry magill 's spiced stout from bell 's . this is a good bomber to split with a friend come september and october though . very evocative of fall , and a very effective pairing of the spices , pumpkin , and bread .  m- very smooth with an easy carbonation on the medium to full body .

thiah has amazing finish and aroma , rivals some of the best i 've had for grand cru . nice lacing .  i do n't normally give 5s in a category , but old viscosity and ten fidy will always get an exceptional rating for mouthfeel .

the beer has a nice sweet hoppy aroma to it , and the taste is that of oranges , hops , black pepper , and some lemon .  here is where the beer shines , on the palate it is pure velvet . the texture is lush and liquor like without any heavy alcohol notes . really fine finish that comes off with some hints of bitter tannins .

the intoxicating aroma is just decadent of rich , warm bourbon notes with woody , vanilla undertones . there 's also some light , fruity/citrusy hop accenuated notes with the faintest of oxidative notes which adds to the overall complexity . the flavor starts off rather dissapointing with only a fraction of the richness implied from the nose . the flavor eventually gains momentum with some nice cracker toastiness from the continental malts combined with the hop bitterness and lingering bourbon notes eventually combine to make this a rather enjoyable experience . the finish is dry & minerally with a slightly thin edged alcohol warmth .  medium to low carbonation . really smooth for 10 % abv .

s - insane . rum , wood , hops , hops . this is really different . tarted very hoppy and shifted to the rum sweetness . just find a few people to share it with because it is definitely overpowering .  perfect . o : while this was a tasty beer , i have such high regard for the brewery that anything that does n't blow me away really disappoints me .

smell was simply magnificent . rich complex hops with fruit and a earthy oaken tone i usually associate with english ales . simply outstanding taste was very good .  mouthfeel is very comforting - like a fall evening in a cabin in the woods . incredible . this has a little bit of everything ... a collaboration of brewers yields a collaboration of ingredients in an exercise of beautiful chemistry .

the smell of this beer is amazing . i 'm sitting about 2 feet away from this beer and the smell is so strong and sweet i cant help but give it a 5 .  mouthfeel is rich and creamy and with huge grapefruit flavors , followed by pine and then resin . beautifully balanced .

lacing is well below average s : the nose offers up an explosion of the listed smells . for whats in the nose , i like it t : the palate is right in line with the nose . nothing pumpkin-like really stands out as spices reign . i find the combination of nutmeg , malts , cinnamon and sugar very pleasing . however , i might add that the flavors are walking the fine line between manageable and overpowering . i like the taste but in moderation , glad i just bought one m : kinda heavy and silk like , maybe a few sheets of silk in smoothness d : more pumpkin would be nice . one of the better pumpkin brews and full of bold spiciness .  m & gt ; lovely . perfect .

s : intense floral and herbaceous hop aromatics . some orange juice may also be detected as the beer begins to warm , if searched for diligently enough .  carbonation is extremely pleasant and elegant on the tongue .
great sweet , woodt smokey smell . nice coffe chocalate and molassas taste and a all round nice and easy to drink stout !  mouthfeel is big , heavy , chewy , and viscous . very nice .

if you like hershey 's `` choklat '' syrup then you will be a big fan of this beer . it is way to syrupy in my view . it is very sweet and tastes nothing like beer at all .  great balance , just a little lacking in potency still . the palate is great in balance and freshness .

a-nice cloudy gold with a thick cream colored head s-this smells great . it smells of banana and some funk . good strength t-comes in with a malty and faint taste of banana and some funk . m-light creamy carbonation with a watery finish o-the appearance and smell got me so excited but i was let down by the taste .  mouthfeel : lighter then most riss . less oily and thick . really nicely balanced bitterness and fruitiness .
the smell is very nelson , pungent and fruity at the same time , almost a touch sour . very nice , great use of a great hops .  mouthfeel - very smooth , pretty darn heavy too .

s. toffee , caramel , butterscotch , sweet deliciousness - looking forward to a taste . t. dissappointing after the smell . a very sessionable , very british beer .  the mouthfeel is excellent and about as creamy as i 've ever had in a porter .

some of the most delicate barleywine smell i 've encountered . not impressed at all with this beer except for the fantastic smell .  mouthfeel of pure velvet and again , this radical brew is reminiscent of amantillado .

the aroma is amazing ... . it immediately reminds me of johnnie 's diner in mcconnellsburg pa ... 1st day of deer season ... 4:00 am.. very strong coffee ... and now what i know as whiskey . the nose is pretty phenomenal ... tons of coffee beans.. lite cocoa ... and there is a decent whiskey note that really does n't jive as what i think of as `` bourbon '' ... almost an irish whiskey nose .  the mouthfeel is incredibly smooth and the finish is clean .

aroma is off the charts , it does resemble oatmeal rasin cookies very well . protein oaty aroma , spices , raisins , more dark fruit , plums , a light touch of boozy warmth , with just a light whiff of cinnamon .  leaves your lips a little sticky . this beer is the perfect belgian tripel .

it has a beautiful aroma , chocolate , black , and earthy . the malts that make that great aroma create a bit too much astringency , and even with the high alcohol , the mouthfeel is a bit heavy for me .  s : coffee , chocolate t : roasted coffee , toffee , chocolate m : wonderful , full mouth feel , but not a heavy beer d : why not drink a beer that tastes like a meal , but is n't heavy on calories ?

s : sweet chocolate , and awesome roasted coffee . the coffee is just amazing without being too bitter smelling . i wish there was a tad more of the cream in here , but still pretty damn good . m : fairly light mouth feel considering the style and the abv .  great body and smoooth . highly drinkable .
smells very hoppy but does n't taste as strong as the aroma would lead you to believe . has a sweet smell along with the grains .  viscous , perfect . rough .

the smell on this one is absolutely unreal ! simply stunning . to my dismay , however , the hops really come through on this one [ in the flavour ] . this is still a very tasty stout , but the over the top dessert aromas get you ready for something that does n't quite show up . overall , well crafted , a good stout and definitely unique , my personal qualms aside .  the mouthfeel is exceptional . the oatmeal really gives this beer a great body .
excellent . o - very nice and not very sour if that sort of thing deters you .  spot on creaminess .

aroma always greets you with a big time flowery hop kick . i mean , this pale ale has an incredible floral hop scent to it . fresh , clean , & crisp in the mouth the mild biscuity malt background is dominated by - yes - more floral hops . medium to light bodied & finishes cleanly . unique & well-crafted , one of my favorite pale ale 's .  mouthfeel is great , thick and syrupy .

it 's a beauty to behold : frothy white head that could withstand a hail storm , and a brownish-orange body like you might find on a chimay . i 'm getting pineapple and grapefruit right off the bat , but there 's some spice in there too , and booze , and some definite funk too . the taste is good , but not quite as good as what the smell promised . there 's bitterness and tartness , like you get from grapefruit , and a little funk .  mouthfeel is full and round .

still a very nice flavor without being too sweet or too spicy ... the right balance of pumpkin and spices to make it very enjoyable . m - the mouthfeel was a little lite/thin , but still smooth and nicely carbonated .  mouthfeel - absolutely exquisite . very silky and velvety . exceptional .

smell : strong dark fruit hops , grapefruit , and hints of pine . a little bit bitter , and not as smooth as i was looking for , but very good .  this beer feels exactly like it appears pretty damn close to a stout shake !

you can smell the whiskey/bourbon immediately . the beer starts off like a typical rye then finishes like a shot of bourbon .  a beer i have been looking forward to trying since it came out , poured into an impy pint glass a deep mahogany brown with a slight chill haze to it a pillowy one finger almond colored head atop with good retention.complexity the word to describe not only the nose but flavors of this beer , at first i picked up juicy fruity malt aromas like orange with brown sugar sweetness the hops are subdued but do provide some floral character.i would say malt tilted but hops are there on the palate the whiskey barrel aging shows itself with some real vanilla/oak sweetness along with a chocolate covered nut quality the rye is actually somewhat irrelevent just a very slight lactic-like bite.the complexity of this beer gives high marks sure iam a hophead and was expecting maybe more of a hop profile but its a damn good beer , the creamy mouthfeel is to die for.a `` nice '' beer here it is well crafted .

the aroma was absolutely amazing and so unique . super herbal , spicy and floral with notes of ginger and orange zest . as the beer warmed , the ginger became progressively stronger .  sensual body slides against the tongue , with the perfect amount of carbonation satisfying any beer-drinker 's palate .

s - freshly baked chocolate brownies , milk/dark chocolate , dark fruits . the chocolate notes were unlike anything i 've had recently , in a good way .  overall , pretty damn good , beautiful mouthfeel and fairly drinkable .

i 'm going to have to take the minority view here , because i think this smells pretty damned good . it smells like something i would want to eat for dessert . buckeyenation thinks it tastes better than it smells , and i 'm going the opposite direction - i think it smells better than it tastes . for me , interesting to sniff , and the 7 % alcohol is no factor , but somewhat dull flavor makes for merely average drinkability  it 's definitely mellowed a bit , but still has a nice hop edge , and is wonderfully warm and spicy.the aroma is mostly of slightly toasted malts..the mouth feel is big and smooth .

smell : amazing , pils malt and continental hops , in perfect harmony . no esters , fusels , diacetyl or other flaws .  while the flavour did n't do much for me , the mouthfeel is simply awesome . soft and pillowy , its all you could hope for in a beer , and works well with everything else going on here .
- the smell is fantastic ... grains , slightly sweet oats ... roasted nuttiness ... . quite nice .  the spices sit on the tongue and create a festive atmosphere in the mouth .

4.5 s : definitely delivers on the hops . lots of indistinguishable citrus and herbal hoppiness . lots of crystal malt sweetness with some roasty and toasty components .  this amazing and smooth stout is aged in a burbon barrel for a year . it is amazingly smooth , warming you up instantly .

nose is super fresh mix of bright , orangey , citrus hops . sweet sugary caramel and again just a huge huge attack of bright citrus fruit hops . fantastic nose . body is medium to full bodied leaning a lot more to the full body . hops are pure citrus peel with a huge attack of fresh flowers . little to no malt taste as the hops are soooo overpoweringing . good beer , i would n't mind having it again .  this is the best mouthfeel i have experienced in a brew in a very long time .

smell - a very nice freshly ground coffee bean type smell . the coffee aroma seems a bit heavier than the cocoa , but that is quite alright . taste - the taste is not quite as robust as the aroma .  perfect for the style .

the smell is quite wonderful with aromatic pineapple and grapefruit plus a low malt presence in the back . i had a couple of enjoyable glasses .  m : light-bodied , crisp and clean . very easy to drink . seamless .

the aromas are stellar . its like a fruit salad : smells of fresh tangerine , green apple , and apricot .  bottle into pint glass a massive cream colored loose head forces a short pour , moderate recession speed leaves scattered patchy lacing to a thin pillowy layer , brew is a hazy brown amber 4 s grassy , florals , milder citrus biscuit apricot & caramel notes 3.5 t lots of flavor , bitter hop edge up front , a caramel malt spine takes a back seat and lets the hops shine in a quality way , lots of complexity and a unique balance in an american ipa 4 m excellent mouth feel , medium body is very rounded and carbonation is great as well , soft & smooth drinking , abv is transparent 5 o a very good ipa , try it . rare for me in the hop levels where i still consider the malts as adding so substantially to my enjoyment , very good balance with a great mouth feel and good drinkability 4.5

not what i was expecting for the # 1 pumpkin beer on ba . weyerbacher imperial pumkin is far superior in taste and aroma .  first i notice the taste of bananas , pears , and pineapple followed by a spices and hops at the end m : perfect carbonation , very full beer d : tastes best as it warms and goes down relatively easy

nose : sticky sweet smelling with lots of dried fruits ( figs , dates , raisins , apricots ) and some orchid-like floral notes . notes : wow , you know - some beers can surprise you . bummer .  m : medium body . the mouthfeel in particular is excellent for the style , and this is surprisingly polished . who knows if this is what it actually tasted like in the 60s - this is a very good american lager right now .
smell is fantastic - coffee , chocolate , gentle hops .  mouthfeel makes the beer great . chewy and soft and oh so smooth . brewed with oatmeal ? must be to get this mouthfeel .

s - definitely one of the unique barrel-aged aromas i 've encountered . based on the other reviews , i 'm guessing some of the solvent and incongruous citrus hop character has faded over the past eight months . plenty of oak , earthy , and char . d - this was very good , and reaffirms my belief that half pints has the most `` american '' portfolio of any brewery in canada .  very smooth and it represents itself very well ine mouth . delicate but throughout . nice .

smells oranges and woody . touch of earthy spiciness . tangerine and dried fruits , like a trail mix . tastes wonderful .  slightly oil mouth feel ( the hop oils ) but with a great crystal like cleanness that just blows me away . exceptional .

brilliant nose . smoky pork , milk chocolate , sweet oatmeal , vanilla , coffee with heavy cream and even some toasted wheat . perfect . the flavor doesnt quite live up to the nose , but exhibits many of the same characteristics .  mouthfeel : fantastic , you know you 've got a meal in your glass !

smell : wonderful . floral , fragrent hops . wonderfully balanced , but slightly subdued hop flavors of flowers , pine , herbs , and grassy notes that dance subtly with the malt and leaves a slight bitterness on the end . i truly loved the flavor , but anyone expecting the hop punch that the nose would lead you to expect could be greatly disapponted or very pleasantly surprise , as my wife was who is not the biggest hop fan . overall a very good beer , but more along the lines of a dry hopped pale ale or esb than an ipa , but i 'll take another anyday .  m this beer has an almost pillowy thick mouth feel . just the right amount of alcohol and carbonation .

overall , a nice sweet scent , with light hints of fruitness , and just the right amount of spices . perfect for a winter warmer . hints of ginger and nutmeg are most pleasant . the beer has the perfect level of sweet maltiness , enhanced by the spices . m : perfect . medium body , with enough carbonation , but not too much . o : winter warmers are far from my favorite style , but great lakes makes a wonderful one .  great mouthfeel . thick , luscious , decadent , and somewhat chewy . very nice .
smells almost fruity like pineapple .  m - a nice full body complements the hop kick on this brew d - very smooth despite the noticeable alcohol .
s - wonderful , and a little different than some hefes .  i love the full mouthfeel on the speedway stout .
s- very pine forward , not much citrus here . o- i drank this about an hour after a pliny , and it stood up well .  m : incredibly smooth and creamy .

aroma is very sweet and citrusy , also lots of hops . overall , i would say this is a very good ipa , goes down very well on a hot summer day .  mouthfeel is great . like many good ipas , it has that coating feel that stays in your mouth , without the sharp bitterness that some ipas leave , and its flavor lingers a very long time .
pours a really nice straw yellow with a hint of orange . aroma is awesome . mango , pineapple and floral hops create an awesome tropical scent .  m : feels wonderfully smooth in the mouth .

it 's really hoppy , which i enjoy , but the hoppy taste feels forced as if it were a product of an extract rather than brewing .  streaming carbonation . still gorgeous as the light syrup , full body fills the mouth and the carbonation leaves the palate clean . this 500ml of a delicious , meaty , full , german beer is about as satisfying as i 've encountered .

smells outstanding ! highly sweet smelling . overall , a great dipa . best smelling beer i 've ever experienced . definitely recommend this one !  lively mouthfeel that dances the labamba on your tongue .

s : smells pretty good . tons of burnt malt , and bread , and a some sweet smells as well ... t : a bit of a let down , but still solid , just a typical weak irish dry taste ... m : smooth , but way to thin ... d : a good beer , worth a try , and its a nice break from czech pils in prague ...  the mouthfeel on this is fantastic ; full , smooth , and perfectly carbonated ( i.e . not too much ) .

incredible aroma and my favorite aspect of this beer . it 's quite spectacular . a full , inviting , rich , and unique aroma . very nice . medium to thick mouthfeel .  top notch as far as mouthfeel goes .

the nose is great ( and `` tickly '' ) ... apple sweetness to apple tartness with faint coriander on top of other spices . there is a ton going on in this aroma , and it 's all stellar -- i just do n't happen to have the exotic fruit knowledge to help describe what all is there . a very unique and complex beer , but not all of it works well together .  it 's very flavorful and has a perfect mouthfeel going on .
very nice aroma , looked forward to the tastes and then , wham , tastes of sour and tart cherries with some caramel .  taste : mouth feel is perfectly constructed to be both elusive and comfortable .

s- smoked meats , beef jerky .  m - perfection ... everything a nitro induced beer should be ... smooth ... creamy ... lush ... light to medium bodied ... just the lightest carbonation ... could easily go down in one gulp ... d - this beer was made for a nitro-tap ... it adds so much to this otherwise slightly above average brew ... insanely quaffable ... i could drink this all night long ... the abv of just above 5 % also aids to the drinkability ...

unique - smells funky and chocolately at the same time . i also smell a little woodiness and booze .  just the right level of sweetness , combined with a silky mouthfeel make this beer superbly drinkable .

s : the beer really shines here . strong smell of dates and figs which i 've never picked up on from unaged bottles . a very sweet malty smell as well with vanilla and caramel notes with just a tiny hint of citrus . to bring out new complexity to both the flavor and smell while also probably destroying the head retention .  m : luxurious and creamy , the carbonation is spot on .

the aroma was wonderful -- carmel , hop , and almost something akin to brandy ! not as hoppy on the finish as i would prefer , but an excellent beer anyway . the alcohol in this one is quite sneaky .  m - velvety smooth with just enough carbonation to give it an absolute perfect body and weight for the style .

smell was very pleasant . typical belgian aromas of clove , dried fruits , alcohol spice and yeasty aromas .  this is a full bodied brew with a smooth , creamy feel to the mouth . it has a modest and enjoyable level of carbonation . very good feel about this brew and well made across the board .

coffee char and roastiness come through in taste and smell , and this baltic porter from cugar city was round both the first and second time i visited the growlers .  just has a silky smoothness that feels great going down .

smell was the best part of the beer . this had a nice malty fruit front with small bits of smokey roasted barley notes . this really smelled like a stereotypical barleywine mixed with an old ale with some roasted hints . taste was good but had lots more smokey bitterness than dark fruit malts .  m - perfect carbonation .
smell : some wonderful character here . a tasty beverage that smells amazing !  perfect ! d : very easy drinking here .
i 'm impressed . taste = good malt flavor , a little bland in other departments .  the mouthfeel is amazing . this beer completely coats my mouth and it 's unbeliavably creamy and smooth .

s : this is definitely the best part , and makes me think this will be a promising beer over time . huge coffee roast , barley , chocolate , some resiny hops and sweet alcohol as well . too sweet right now , i think the carbo issue will help this cause it has potential to be great . m : smooth but no carbonation and chewy .  mouthfeel is full and soft .

smells like fresh fig newtons dipped in chocolate . very appealing nose for sure ! a bit of a chalky , yet silky finish . intense and hearty . i 'm full .  right off you notice the mouthfeel is perfect . medium bodied , well carbonated , crisp ... top notch .
the aroma surges out of the bottle - bitter orange hops , mostly .  the mouthfeel is super smooth and creamy . unexpected , but could n't be better .

a really good smelling wit . in general , this was a good beer .  awesome mouthfeel , smooth yet still some substance that goes down easy . highly drinkable , may be my new go to beer for relaxing during the summer .
it has the richest creme beulee i have ever encountered , maybe even more than the real thing . outstanding !  mouthfeel is silky , creamy , like a milkshake .
s - nice piney hops with lemon and grapefruit citrus . t - looked and smelled better than the taste .  mouthfeel is exceptionally smooth .

nose is fantastic , with scotch , smoke , leather , dark fruit , and port wine . there 's an amazing nose on this , but that 's where the greatness ends . this is a $ 12 mistake you do n't want to make .  great mouthfeel in particular .

appearance vibrant orange and clear body ; decent sized head that settles fast smell wonderful nose-juicy citrus hops as well as some nice dry malt taste & body taste does n't quite follow the delicious smell . the bittering hops seem to be outweighing the flavor hops , and the body is a bit on the weak side .  in fact , the mouthfeel is perfect and this is easily one of the more drinkable ipa 's i 've had in a while .

if there was beer soap this would be what it smelled like and it 's beautiful . taste is floral hops with a slight pine backing that intensifies as time passes on the tongue , there 's a bread crust like character hanging around in the middle .  m- amazingly smooth texture , the light carbonation yields a velvety smoothness .

smell was heavenly , super sweet , slightly burnt caramel , raison , cherry , plum , hard to fully describe . taste was almost as good as the smell , but was a bit overly sweet , not as balanced as the nose was , became a bit cloying even . a sipper for sure , damn glad i got to try this , hopefully some of the other vintages are even better .  the body is really the main draw here . the oatmeal lends a silky texture that is just sublime and fits the palate perfectly . this also renders the beer very easy to drink , ensuring that a solo drinker can handle the entire large bottle .

what an oud bruin should look like , which gets it at least 4 points in my book . aroma : the real winner here . that sour cherryness that we all long for from this style is here . mixes with leather and sex sweat . wood and vanilla round out a spectacular bouquet for the nostrils . taste : light . uses same ingredients of carolus but stops short of greatness . the best way to look at it is an easy way to drink alot of bruin without taste overload or a stomach ache . good in its own way but not great for the style .  the mouthfeel is very nice .

aroma is the best thing about this beer , the smell of roasted malt reminds me of dark chocolate . smell is again of dark chocolate , maybe just a little weaker this time .  rich , creamy , thick , luscious mouthfeel !
has a very nice strong hop aroma associated with it . fresh hops accumulate on your tounge with high intensity .  m - perfect finish , pairs great with sushi .
s - a slight hoppy , and almost liquory fragrance ( probably due to its 8 % alc by vol ) .  m - medium bodied , fantastic carbonation with a chewy feel to it that lingers .
an abundance of floral hops hits the nose hard . two hearted is one of the best smelling beers in all the land .  the mouthfeel is full for the style with a nice creamy texture .

a : pours a black opaque with rich reddish brown fizzy head b : smells of licorice and blueberry as soon as i opened the bottle t : lightly bitter , blueberry comes in the aftertaste , definitely not a `` fruity '' beer . m : rich and smooth over the tongue d : good stout  absolutely loved it .

smells like a very sweet beer , smells like a lot of fruit .  taste and mouthfeel absolutely amazing . this is one smooth , smooth beer that goes down great . best mouthfeel of any beer i 've ever had .

scent of raspberries , maraschino cherries , molasses , chocolate , earth , and a hint of alcohol . a monster of a scent , while not overpowering , there is a massive amount of strength to this beer .  the 8 % does n't show at all , insanely smooth and creamy , very slick mouthfeel . excellent .

nose really nice . some alcohol , definately some hops ... not really clear what i 'm smelling though .  mouthfeel is the huge winner . when the head is still around , you get the big , soft , almost downy foam you associate with a bubble bath . body has a presence but a definite silky , almost velvetiness feel to it that lightens the load at the same time .

to me , this is damn alluring . t // heavy dark malt shouts at you .  m- this is the best part of this beer , the high carbonation and medium body seem perfect with the hop oiliness seeming to just rush past the tongue with a slight lingering in a refreshing `` drink more of me '' way d- the hops are a little strong but this is certainly enjoyable enough to go back to for a few more , just would n't make it my regular beer of choice

s- oh boy this smells like heaven . big time sour funky oak , wild flowers and honey . t- well this is a complex brew and the layers of flavors are daunting . oak out front with the tannins and sour . fruit and funk with a earthy herbal quality . some medicinal and bandaid like touches after a while . things really settled down in the carb department as the beer warms . d- this is a serious brew and the flavor and bugs will take its toll on you .  the mouth feel is exceptional , but unlike the others this is n't drinkable .

s : roasty coffee , plums , chocolate , and licorice ( an apparent staple in the bell 's stout lineup ) . d : it is n't too strong or thick but it is n't very drinkable .  and the mouthfeel ? very , very smooth ! !

s- lots of complexity with raisins , smoke , chocolate , brown sugar and walnuts . awesome ! there is also some toffee like sweetness around the edges . earthy bitterness in the finish hint at hops and keep this from being cloying . a good flavor to be sure , but not quite as complex as the smell . as it warms a black cherry presence begins to show up in the mix as well .  m - just perfect . the carbonation dances on my tongue bringing out the flavors .

this beer smells wonderful but the taste seems like a mess .  i nice velvet that does n't coat like a barley wine but carries the carbonation on the palate . for some old and english an exceptional feel .

the aroma is chock full of dark fruits , with figs , raisins and plums weaving a rich blanket .  smooth , full body with restrained carbonation , which accentuates the richness and decadence of the flavours .

smell ... did someone just mow the lawn ! needs more malt but it 's still very pleasant . i wish there was some more after swallow flavors as well but the hops are crazy up front .  m : full-bodied with light carbonation . super smooth with an intensely thick and creamy texture .

so cloudy and dirty looking . sour and musty , so intense ! very nice ! unfortunately , the smell is the only thing i found good about this one ... . really , really do not like the flavors at all ... .  mouthfeel has a perfect sheen on it , and only at the end when the big alcohol presence is felt is there a tingling on the tongue .

s- smells good and right on with the style ... yeasty grass notes , some biscuit and sweet fruity esters .  mouthfeel- nice feel here . the beer is full bodied with nice light carbonation and feels oily and smooth . drinkability- really nice beer that is extremely easy drinking and pretty damned tasty .

the aroma is wicked , with a healthy blend of banana bread , vanilla , booze , and a nice roasted malt/toffee sweetness .  palate is really quite incredible- prickly at first , but subsides to become incredible smooth and unassuming .

aroma was heavenly ; candied sugary malt and grain , with some dark fruits and yeasty notes . wow . taste was very complex and enjoyable ; fermented grain , dark fruits , molasses , wood notes , warming alcohol , mild yet solid hops .  the rich roasted malt flavor is fantastic followed with toffee , caramel and maybe even a bit of roasted coffee ( though only a little bit ) m/d - mouthfeel is fantastic , quite rich .
s- strong aromas of peach as soon as i put my nose up to it .  its viscous , yet has a tingly mouthfeel . nearly ideal for my tastes .
the aroma is delightfully cocoa-forward , nutty as hell , and really heady with caramel , like a flan .  mouthfeel is amazingly thick and chewy .
heady and i like it .  crisp mouth feel with low carbonation . the smoothest beer i 've ever had - it was amazing .

the smell is wonderful : sweet malts , citrus , cloves , spices , coriander , some orange . the smell is exceedingly enticing and quintessentially belgian . unfortunately it goes down hill from there . the beer is sweet , a bit syrupy , moderately carbonated , a little on the dry side , and malty . it just does n't taste nearly as good as other belgian blondes .  again , it 's very creamy making the mouthfeel outstanding , especially for the style .
juicy , tangerine laced citrusy centennial hop nose upfront , followed by smooth medium lovibond caramel malt and subtle toasty malt .  the delicate carbonation makes for a very lucious mouthfeel .
the smell is absolutely amazing . smells of sweet fruit.. almost like a fruit roll up.. oddly enough .  m- full body with moderate carbonation and a nice wet finish .

very spicy ; grains of paradise , coriander , brett funk , biscuit , and orange peel . i 'd definitely go another session of this brew .  m smooth , thick and creamy with fairly low carbonation . almost like a nitro stout . amazing mouth-feel .
after that wonderful aroma , and my experience with 90 minute ipa , it was just a letdown .  drinkability : incredible mouthfeel and easy to drink .

smells strawberry fruity and bourbon oaky during the pour . to the nose , rich strawberry vanilla , licorice , playful oak , bourbon char , sweet caramel , cherry , clean alcohol , pineapple , lavender , and more . wow , just amazing , i hope the flavor is a match . beneath alot of tannin , i get some raisin and some basil ( may sound awful , but it actually fits pretty well ) .  mouth feel - i scored it a perfect , and it is well done .

aroma is very nice and fruity , hints of apple and peach or pear , some vanilla . a very good brew , worthy of the praise others have given it . i liked the blue better , but this one is still very very good .  m : super full body from lots of carbonation that makes it really creamy and thick in the mouth d : nobody on earth could say this is `` drinkable '' !

the aroma was comprised of sweet malt , citrus , caramel , citrus hop , and marijuana . the hop profile going on here was very sweet forward rather than bittering .  m - this is what i want in a dipa . solid medium body with spot on carbonation , creating a huge , super creamy , slick mouthfeel .

the aroma was nice on this beer with a really strong fresh ground coffee smell on top of the dark roasted malts . this one smelled great and tasted ok. not one of my favorites from great divide .  m : the feel is exactly what i look for in these kinds of beers .

scores actually remain the same -- -- 7-28-05 =4.2 rating cloudy deep coper colored ... .great nose ... awesome tropical fruits..sweet papaya ... mango..perhaps some very sweet ripe oranges ... mouthfeel is medium ... buttery and slick ... .tastes a little buttery too ... also the sweet tropical fruit flavors are evident as well ... . i expected a little more pure citrus out of the centennial hops but i call them as i taste them..very solid ipa with hop `` flavor '' and not just pure bitterness..i 'm sure east coast ipa lovers will like this one a lot .  the carbonation is excellent . d : i ca n't put away many of any double ipa , and it 's the same for this one - it 's clearly high quality but the sour aspects keeps me from wanting more .
the smell is clean raspberry , not much funk .  the mouthfeel was thick , rich , frothy and supple . this was unquestionably the most impressive aspect of the beer .

raspberry puree overwhelmes the senses with the ever so slight hint of wheat . pure notes of fresh raspberries rule the day with this brew as they obviously should .  m - thought this beer was very smooth and carbonated to perfection , definetely got the mouthfeel down pat .
huge sweet chocolatey roasty and awesome . the taste was the same , with a lot of sweetness and chocolate .  exceptionaly smooth mouthfeel - creaminess was rare like a milkshake .

smell is a sweet sensation of honey and spice , the honey really takes the cake here and reminds me a bit of dogfish head 's own midas touch . taste is sweet , the honey is also the most prevalent characteristic , the aftertaste though seems a bit sharp and astringent , the alcohol seems stronger than it should be at 8 % and is n't hidden very well . another interesting beer coming from dfh , they certainly like to experiment with these ancient recipes and i 'll certainly give them a go , but i probably wo n't go for this one again .  a smooth creamy finish . best i have ever had outside of a cask drawn stout .

s : strong , roasted barley predominant , toasted nuts as well t : syrupy , quite a bit of alcohol in the flavour as well -- a bit too much for my liking m : thick and rich d : while enjoyable , this was slightly less appealing .  mouthfeel- thick and rich like a good imperial stout should be . great carbonation and texture .

sadly not as good as the smell , but still excellent . malty and sweet , that is balanced by the roastedness rather than the hops .  strong big bubbles , surprising considering the small shape of the head , pretty full bodied as well , i like that . sweet and easy drinking proposing a lemon slice here and there that grows into a pungent tartness reminiscent of a straight lambic .
aroma was a very pleasant blend of malty dark fruit , peat and a hint of smokey wood .  m - perfect smoothness .
a whole bouquet of fresh cut wild flowers on a medium soft malted barley aroma . amazing . medium body .  palate is very chewy , heavy and absolutely great .

3/5 overall : i was extremely disappointed by the taste of this beer given the extremely pleasant aroma and delightful appearance . this one definitely did not live up to its hype for me .  i think that this is one of the best stouts made . great taste , great look , mouthfeel . this is one of the best imperial stouts , american or russian , ever made .
smell is strong with citrus and hops .  m : i felt the mouthfeel was perfect on this beer for a begian strong .

scent is roasted malts and dark chocolate . as it sits in the glass and warms a bit it opens up into a warmer milk chocolate/coco bean aroma .  perfect . o : i think this would have been an amazing beer if it contained just a bit more malt sweetness to balance out the bitterness and yeasty astringency .

appearance : out of the cask , the beer has a small khaki lid that crowns the dark brown liquid ; a modest amount of lacing is left behind smell : smells like a cup of richly roasted black coffee taste : up front , the coffee flavors dominate , with black bread and chocolate undertone ; after the swallow , however , the coffee adds a lot of acidity to the finish mouthfeel : medium body with moderate carbonation ; for an oatmeal stout , the body is rather thin and lacks the creamy quality i would expect from the style overall : this beer was made by adding coffee to the cask and it tastes rather like carbonated coffee , lacking the depth of flavor and mouthfeel that i would seek in the style ; although the ibus are low , the finish reminds of that old commercial where the drinker complains `` oh , this coffee sure tastes bitter .  first sip is amazingly creamy texture with minimal gentle rolling carbonation .

strong hop presence . beer practically floats off the tongue and hops grab onto the sides of cheeks and the flavor lingers there . excellent amount of lace .  m-mild carbonation and a full creamy mouthfeel without being cloying .

s - wow , smells just like a pumpkin pie , lots of pumpkin and spices , cinnamon , clove , allspice and some malt sweetness . as the beer warmed up the sweetness turned overbearing . o - just too sweet for my liking , but may be worth a buy for the smell alone .  perfect . incredibly balanced flavor and magnificent mouthfeel , it 's actually worth every penny of the high price .

s - the joy of fresh hop beers ! very aromatic , lots of cascade and centennial hops . this is a very floral beer . d - this could be a very sessionable beer , while it lasts anyhow .  mouthfeel is dead on and perfect . d : hah , it drinks easily , but if someone pounds this they should be slapped .
the aroma is awesome . it is near to maple syrup , with arid fresh floral character .  mouthfeel is fill bodied , heavy , and very smooth .
aromas were rich with a dark chocolate flavor and a slightly burnt coffee smell .  really good mouthfeel .

aroma is sweet coffee and caramel , and is wonderful . taste is slightly sweet up front , and the finish is coffee , oakiness , and complex .  m-very smooth and creamy , full bodied , good carbonation and a crisp grainy finish .

it really smells like you are opening up a bag of hops while homebrewing . awesome aroma . t : more of that hop kick , sweet malts , citrus , and a hint of spice . i wish they did n't filter out the yeast , but it 's still a very nice taste .  a great mouthfeel that is easily recognizable .

s : the smell is of quality coffee , cocoa nibs , wood notes and a layer of sweetness that would most likely be the maple syrup . as the beer warms the alcohol moves into the forefront .  the feel on this puppy is exceptional to say the least . full creamy and velvety smooth .
such a fun gift to give ! i loved the spiciness of it all .  with the nitro draught , the mouthfeel is exceptionally smooth and full .

smells beautifully hoppy . so tropical , with loads of fruit - pineapple , banana , passionfruit , touch of lemongrass and mint as well . just gorgeous . taste is a bit of a letdown . yeah the flaws are distinct here , just too much clean-up of the flavour , lacking early hopping . nice flavours , just not enough .  perfect mouthfeel in my opinion , feels silky smooth .
s- floral , nice malty bouquet , lemon , apricot , touch of lime .  finishes dey , sweet & warming mf : rich & chewy with minimal carbonation .

sweet and floral scent , lots of candied apples and berries . superb and easy to drink .  m : has both a crisp and creamy feel , medium carbonation , goes down very smooth . this is overall a very good beer , worthy of drinking a 6-pack easily in a sitting .
it 's a complex aroma that has a lot of things going on but they meld together pretty well .  the mouthfeel is just silky .
smell- an intersting mix of odd juniper bitterness and sweetness with hints of lingonberries . reminds me of a decent gin . mouthfeel- very syrupy .  incredible mouthfeel .
smell is very potent , butterscotch and sweet . very refreshing dark lager overall .  very creamy feel with medium carbonation and body .
aroma is big apricot , strong , a little grainy , smells good . this beer really pulls it off .  mouthfeel is light to medium bodied and super smooth with a solid hop character ad satisfying finish .

s- this beer had a sweet caramel aroma , with floral and fruitiness coming through the nose from the hops .  full bodied . the carbonation level and viscosity are virtually perfect . finishes intensely floral , warm and with fading notes of baker 's chocolate and anise .
the smell is dominated by coffee and is backed up by a sweet chocolate malt aroma . it smells a little bigger than it looks .  it definitely had clean taste and great body .
the beers aroma is tart pie cherries , dark chocolates and vanilla .  very full bodied and mouth feel complex and nice tastes all around very drinkable stout with nice hop balance

nice nose ! ! hops smell great . i want to swim in it ... taste - i 'm really digging the sweetness on the front and after about 2 seconds , the bitter , citrus hops kick in .  the body is outstanding , better than any abt from belgium i 've had , decadent creaminess and perfectly mouth-filling .
the scents come across a little less fruity than i would have expected .  mouthfeel is spectacularly smooth for a barleywine at this strength .
aroma is very nice - malt , dark ripe fruits , spices , a hint of honey and orange as described , also a bit of vanilla .  great stuff .

still not bad though , was just expecting more after the excellent smell . mouthfeel : medium-thick body , medium carbonation . still , not a bad beer , excellent nose , worth to try .  great feel ... smooth and creamy . loved it !

the smell was great . i got something that reminded me of maple . maybe my favorite smelling beer . the taste was very nutty and a little bit like log cabin syrup .  full and creamy in the mouth with a pleasant alcohol warmth on the way down . overall , it 's outstanding , but i would put it a notch below similar offerings from true trappist breweries .

moderately intense pine aroma with floral undertones predominate . some caramel malt is also present , but very subdued ( -0.5 ) dry middle and finish with lots of aromatic and bittering hops , particularly after the finish .  a little bitter but so much to turn me off , enough to make me want another sip to get some more ... the feel is super velvety , love it .

s : smells the part , clove dominated , christmas spiced bread with a hint of bubblegum and that banana bread undercurrent . t : clove heavy , very yeasty and bready .  a perfect , creamy and overall medium bodied mouthfeel .

smells great . but the bitterness and lack of balance just leaves this beer with low drinkability .  the body is where it really shines : smooth , full , everything great . carbonation levels are perfect , coming up shy of metallic but lightening up just enough .

the aroma is excellent , very german-hoppy and dank at first , though this develops into a fresher herbal character . the flavor is a bit thin for a pils , and i was expecting a lot more based on the aroma .  the mouthfeel is extremely thick and chewy .

smell : big roastiness jumps out with pleasant notes of dark chocolate/cocoa rounded out by some grassy hops . by far the beers best trait . taste : the roasted malt flavors dominate as indicated by the smell .  mouthfeel/drinkability- the mouthfeel on this brew is ace for the style , nice medium body with a good malt backbone and the perfect amount of carbonation to make the flavors really dance on your tongue .

lovely smoke aromas that reminds me of wood-grilled salmon . weizen flavors of banana and clove come through in the flavor , only to be swallowed up by more of that fishy smoke .  this is exactly right .
smell is extremely hoppy . citrus all the way with little malt coming through .  m - the mouthfeel is second to none . phenomenal body and mouthfeel , and perfect carbonation .
smells of sweet malts and bourbon barrels .  mouthfeel is full-bodied , yet soft and creamy .

s- smells hoppy , malty . truly amazing . t- it tastes like it smells , but alas it 's mild , and boozy . kills this beer for me . maybe one of the most amazing sensations of any beer i 've ever had was the smell .  and my favorite part about baltic porters ... the rich , creamy , velvety , smooth body . not too heavy , but just right .

looks great and the smell is absolutely divine . bitter chocolate , raisins , with a hint of nutmeg or cinnamon in the background . i 've always liked avery but they 've really gone all out on this one ! ok , granted , this is the most bizarre rating ive given but its friday evening and im feeling creative .  carbonation is right where it needs to be , medium/low and perfect . overall : if nothing else mattered , i would have a stockpile of this beer and start every day with one or two .

color with zero , nadda , zilch head or carbonation ... i know this is by design , but i still ca n't rate a beer high on appearance when it just pours completely flat and lifeless ... aroma is very tart upfront , sour acidity , lemons ... slight bit of sweet oak mixed in really makes this one smell like a tart juice . musty and funky but not overwhelmingly so ... really bizarre as the taste is directly affected by the complete absence of carbonation ... sour , but not overwhelming , like a tart ( flat ) lemonade ... there is some definite woodiness and a distinct grassy character that offsets the tart acidity . finishes very dry ... i just ca n't do it ... it 's flat , maybe they want that , i do n't , i 'm sorry ... it really negatively affects the beer , there is no life ... i really liked the smell and taste of this beer , however , the complete lack of carbonation really affected my enjoyment of this beer ... from the very get go with the still , lifeless pour , to the complete lack of decent mouthfeel , it 's just really hard to give this beer high ( er ) marks ...  smell : floral hops taste : combo of floral/pine hops . most excellent . drinkability : although the beer is pretty much perfect , the fact that it 's an ipa means limited drinkability . i love the beer , but the hops would limit how many i could drink .

the nose on this is incredible , but it does n't hold up in taste .  great velvety smooth mouthfeel . it reminded me of a boddington 's from a nitro-can - great mouthfeel , but otherwise unremarkable .
mmmmm , smells good . real good .  m : amazing feel .

picked up the second to last bottle from henningshead bomb a- pours a deep deep black , motor oil , deep brown head , heavy lacing on the edges s- smell pretty amazing , heavy like chocolate , tobacco , lots of oak , malts alll up in the bitch . t- very deep chocolate , marshmallow , burnt coffee , very robust , also a bit of bitterness from the hops at the very in . o- not my kind of imperial stout , but a very well crafted one , there are not random tangents and i can respect the brewery , being its my first .  lies heavy on the tongue . again , thick and creamy with moderate carbonation . much better than the experience i had from the bottle , but as i mentioned i do n't think the bottled version i tasted was quite right .
but the aroma ... .i am in love . sugar-coated melon , apple-cinnamon , cloves , light pepper .  excellent mouthfeel .

superb aroma , tons of chocolate , roasted malt , french-roast coffee ... if this baby had a bit more head to it this might be further accentuated ... which would be delightful . taste is more of the same ... but lighter , and less rich than expected .  usually mouthfeel is an after thought but with this beer the mouthfeel stands out as being wonderful . it catches my attention even moreso than some of the flavors . it feels nice and coats my mouth with a very nice feeling . this beer feels exceptionally good in the mouth .
smells really good ! !  m - full bodied and creamy texture on the palate .

clear blue waters , white washed sandy beach , this aroma offers a delightfully intriguing tropical aroma . freshly sliced pineapples , mango . very drinkable , deliciously well made .  m/d - this is probably one of the best mouthfeels i 've ever had with a growler .
aroma of caramel and vanilla , as well as some tea leaves and a nice earthiness .  entry is silky smooth with just a touch of carbonation showing on the back of the tongue .
s - very nice scent , not too grainy .  t- wonderfully light malt sweetness boasting just enough complexity to keep things interesting . m- perfect .

this is easily one of the best smelling brews i 've encountered in this genere . i love it . again , the combination of sweetness and bitter and tart hops creates an unusual , lasting aftertaste . the beautiful hops would be compramised -- and the food itself would be rendered bland .  m - thick , full bodied and creamy mouthfeel with a slick , oily texture and super soft , almnost non-existent , carbonation . plenty of bitterness on the palate that lasts well into the finish and lingers for quite a while . this one has an exceptional mouthfeel and a complex flavor profile that makes this a truly great example of the style .

the dark caramel malts are obvious in the aroma . phenols of cloves round out the scent . some aromas have a quality of weight , this is heavy .  very smooth and lightly carbonated . leaves a nice coating in the mouth . this beer is excellent .

aroma - heavy on the citrus - grapefruit stands out . actually -dissappointing after the pleasant aroma . mouthfeel - a little watery for an ipa overall not a bad beer , but not a superior ipa at all .  m= mmm perfection d= high . feels and tastes like an imperial ipa .
the aroma has an exceptional and strong smell of fat , soft , sweet barley .  perfect balance and the mouthfeel is amazing . i want to chug it at times .

pours a clear golden amber with a big frothy white head hat sticks to the sides and leaves a soapy cap . aroma is great with lots of juicy citrus , oranges and pineapples come to mind . the aroma promised great things but the flavor was just too light and watery .  absolutely the thickest stout i have had , makes the mouthfeel of expedition stout seem like light beer . this one is just big and chewy with an extremely mild carbonation . it is n't as sweet as i was expecting but i think it comes off as pretty sweet because of the thick mouthfeel .

the scent is really where i love this one , it 's a unique sort of pecan-malt mixture with only a dash of citrus and a lot of sweetness .  m : creamy , perfectly carbonated , and oily slick that is incredible . this helps this beer a lot .

tons of ripe banana , yeast breadiness , apple , clove , cinnamon , orange , lemon , and bubblegum . though not overpowering , it is distracting and far outdoes all of the other flavors . drinkability : i love the style , but wish the alcohol was as well hidden in the flavor as it is in the aroma . i will gladly drink it , though albeit slowly and responsibly .  outstanding beer . the texture was incredible . find some now for yourself .

aroma is incredible . earthy , malty with honey and caramel notes . smells great , but kind of falls short from there .  the taste is big caramel/biscuit malt , some sweet maple sap , and a strong , but smooth , enveloping booziness . the carbonation is quite low , the body thick , viscous , oily , and creamy - a surprising sledgehammer of pleasure to the palate .

great aroma . brown sugar , molasses , caramel , honey and roast tones all hit the nose . even though i tend to like hoppier browns and porters , i like this one quite a bit .  afterwards , it leaves a rich and creamy yet dry feeling in your mouth .
great aroma of baking bread with flowery hops on top .  mouthfeel was superb . very prickly and slightly thin but just perfect .

aroma is ... ..wow ... .very nice roasted , malty aroma . one of the best aromas for style i have experienced ! as far as vienna 's go , a very good beer , one i will be purchasing more of when wisconsin amber is out of stock : - )  the mouthfeel is very nice -- medium-bodied and quite chewy .

s- lots of banana in the bottle . after the pour , it gives off some lemon and ginger . rye is unmistakeable , yet not overwhelming . with warmth it almost gets some trippel-like qualities . lighter clove and black pepper in the finish . o- this is a really solid beer and very drinkable .  the mouth is exactly what a porter should be .

the aroma is cider-like with brown sugar and a yeasty spiciness . grapes ( fresh ) and cherries weave in and out . caramel/ginger bread cookie with warmth . there are other less defined fruits i there too , but it 's quite complex and hard to pick them out , but i get raisin , soft baking apples , plum and a sort of androgenous berry flavor .  very nice creamy full bodied moutfeel .

the aroma is probably the strong point of this beer -- a nice roasty , coffee-like scent , with a mild chocolatey undertone . as with the aroma , there 's a slight chocolatey undercurrent which really helps this beer out .  mouthfeel is just amazing . although it has a nice carbonation level the mouthfeel is liquid velvet , just coats the mouth and does n't let go .

unique and fabulous . the flavor is complex as pine tree bark , evergreen branches , nutmeg , clove , roasted malt , coffee and alcohol create a very different flavor .  m - the mouth feel is huge and rich , oily and very sticky . noticeable warming on the aftertaste .

s : again , top notch and very promising . huge , juicy hop aromas of orange zest and grapefruit pith . noticeable lemon and pine scented hops really round out the hop bill . stunning . sweet malts , pale malts and straw suggestions . you can tell this beer is going to be bitter . the huge hops on the nose follow through on the tongue .  a - deep golden , orange color with one finger , bubbly head ; faded to nice a covering cap with enormous amounts of lacing s - aromatic hops , then malt and bread , then pine t - bitter in front followed by brief pineapple then huge piney , bitterness at end m - velvety smooth ; medium carbonation with fine , foamy bubbles d - drinkability for me is low here ; not sure if this is from the bitterness or the lack of much fruit or anything beyond pine oil ; just not my favorite palate for a big ipa

extremely fragrant beer hops leap out and grab your nose from across the room lots of pine and citrus .  m - smooth and extremely creamy . a great ipa to savor and swirl around in your mouth . the fairly low carbonation level works well .

smells very delicious . loads of roasty coffee bitterness on the palate . amazing smell and great appearance save this beer from a pretty average score .  m - slick , smooth and very , very refreshing .

behold his venom and vengeance , both sweet and tempting , enticing you , his spellbound victim , within his wings '' . the appearance is a beautifull shade of ruby red with astonishing clarity . pours with a healthy dose of white foam that 's short lived and disappointing . the sweetness is unmistakable and addicting . starts off very sweet but ends slitely hot and dry . overall this was a decent beer which had a considerable amount of age on it .  overall , a great mouthfeel ; lots of action from the carbonation , a good full coat that gets scrubbed by the finish .

the smell was a very strong citrus that popped out of the glass as i was pouring . it was just great to my nose . the citrus bitterness was pretty apparent on the tongue .  mouthfeel - very nice feel , smooth and creamy with the perfect amount of carbonation . the bottle conditioning really left a nice feel .

the aroma was awesome - it smelled just like fresh hops !  mouthfeel and drinkability are fantastic . at nearly 3 dollars a bottle , this is a bit pricey for `` everyday '' beer , but that is exactly what this should be - an everyday beer and a staple in every fridge .
rather dry aftertaste.15 months later , another bottle at smokeless joe , and the smell even better .  m - very wet and distributing .

s - strong roasted flavors : caramel , toffee , chocolate & espresso all blend together . tart , sweet , and fruity blueberries start to come through as this beer warms , adding a nice complexity to the scent . t - starts with a kick of tart blueberry and some dark chocolate and roasted malt notes . d - an interesting & worthwhile combination between roasted malt and tart blueberry that is worth a try , but its not something i would crave nor purchase often .  there 's some hints of vinegar in the background that , surprisingly , seems to fit right in with everything ealse going on in this beer.. mouthfeel/drinkabilty ; the mouthfeel on this one maybe the fullest , and mostly velvety of any beer that i 've ever had . between the raspberries , chocolate , nuts and very full mouthfeel , this is like drinking a chocolate raspberry cake with a some walnuts or pecans sprinkled on top .

s : absolutely astounding cocoa smell . that 's amazing . the best cocoa smell i 've had in a beer to date . that is absolutely excellent . tiny dry espresso finish . o : this is hands down the best `` chocolate beer '' i 've ever had . absolutely amazing . would recommend to anyone .  mouthfeel is , on the contrary , excellent . extremely creamy and smooth , with good carbonation .

s- alot of pumpkin spice and a ton of nutmeg . smells like a sweet pumpkin spice candle from yankee candle . t- as soon as you put this in your mouth it 's sweet but then the pumpkin spice takes over and your tastebuds just scream out as if to say `` what the hell is that ? a bit overpowering . feels good .  thick , chewy and velvety smooth .

s - the aroma is outstanding - fresh , juicy raspberries all over the place . d - overall , a very nice fruit beer - maybe the best non-sour one i 've had .  mouthfeel was exceptional , as it is with many cask beers .
smell is very malty with a toasted grain and biscuit scent and very fruity .  m : thick , full mouthfeel says a lot about the prodigious malting of this beer .

fresh american hop cone aroma ; chinook and cascade like grapefruit and citrus/floral . huge citrusy cascade and fruity chinook flavor wash over concealing the sweetness . finishes somewhat dry , but more slick than anything . fairly well put-together , but a little over board on showcasing hops without a balancing amount of malt .  m : velvety , soft , thick , luscious chewy mouthfeel .

s : there is the typical horse blanket brett aroma but this beer has a very sweet and fruity aroma with some coriander and hop also . t : the brett flavor hits right up front with an acerbic quality .  very smooth , creamy texture . carbonation assists the creamy texture with tiny bubbles mixing well with the full-bodied beer .
average head retention & lacing s : intense toasted malt & caramel t : caramel & toasted malt up front .  almost perfect . it just does n't have any edges , it 's just meant to be drunk .

caged and corked , popped the cork with a loud pop ! brett tartness hit my nose immediately and got me excited about this beer . it pours a bright yellow color- pretty cloudy . smell- tart cherries , a nice funky waft of brett , maybe some white wine notes , perhaps champagne . this beer is pretty unique . i do n't feel like it sits well in the wit category , and it is n't 100 % about the brett either .  for all the bitterness , this beer maintains a silky smooth mouthfeel .

s - very nice piney smell some malt hints but mostly the flowery hops are present . attractive but a bit dry in the nose .  light carbonation and very velvety . smooth and decadent finish . creamy and appetizing .

soapy , fragrant aroma . wonderful aroma for this style . great looking and smelling american hefe , but ... a bit boring in taste/mouthfeel .  very nice wheat aroma with a hint of citrus , poured a nice golden and cloudy appearance , very nice head that was more fizzy looking than creamy , head quickly went down to a nice thin creamy cap , very little lacing , lightly sweet with a slightly fruity taste , touch of banana , slightly malty with very little bitterness , very pleasing in taste , medium body that is slightly oily , very smooth , a nice light to medium carbonation , overall a very nice brew !
aroma is very nice . incredibly yeasty , backed by a whirlwind of spices . i love it .  the mouthfeel here is awesome . medium-full body , very chewy , even tannic almost .

excellent lacing left behind . s - big citrus aroma with lots of grapefruit and just a little tangerine .  m - terrific ! smooth , velvety creaminess , mild carbonation , and tons of residual stickiness . d - high abv , and gets a little too sweet after awhile , but bonus points for the incredible texture and ridiculously low retail price ( under $ 5 !
aroma is actually quite interesting . an odd and interesting blend of vanilla , grape , oak , alcohol and caramel .  big , thick , full , creamy , exquisite feel .

ultra dry , petroly tasting geuze sampled at the delerium caf on 8-18-08 . plenty of funky horse hair aromas , gasoline , grapefruit , dust , etc ... flatish body is forgiven as the wildness of it all more than makes up for it .  mouthfeel : this is a perfect 5 for sure .

big thanks to amphion1065 for this insanely interesting brew . pours a clear gold with a billowing 3 finger white head that fills my great divide tulip perfectly . this beer has by far the strangest ( but inviting ) smell i 've ever experienced . smells like chunks of peppercorn being mashed up in some orange juice and flower pedals . it 's hard to get passed the peppercorns at first , but so much is hidden behind it . ok , maybe this style is n't for me .  m : got to give perfect marks for mouthfeel on this one . perfect amount of carbonation , just enough to bring out the taste .
the aroma was very promising . a bit of fruitiness anchored by sweet malt , some spices ( perhaps cinnamon ) and yeast .  mouthfeel - nice and creamy full mouthfeel .

smells of brandy , vanilla , dark fruits , milk chocolatejust a great aroma , and makes you just want to enjoy the smell and not even take a sip , but .  very bourbon heavy . this is very rich and creamy . if any beer could have `` milkshake like '' qualities , this would be the one .

s - really nice aroma with the obvious smoked meat aroma .  if i could give mouthfeel a 6.0 , i would . ridiculously smooth , soft , creamy , mousselike . beyond exceptional -- sublime . as others have mentioned , a bottle of oat will be the perfect beer for the snowy , house-bound nights that are sure to come .

the smell is fresh , hoppy and wonderful , citrus and spruce balanced by a moderate , doughy malt backbone . no , its not off , just weak . strange because the smell and the early flavors a bit more balanced than the finish .  mouthfeel is ridiculous . smooth , creamy with outstanding perfect carbonation which is very fine . pretty dry and exactly what i want in a saison .
s : hearty coffee aroma , notes of toffee , chocolate , roasted nuts . quite a delicious smell . t : coffee bitterness quite apparent as is a nutty flavor .  creamy and luscious mouthfeel .

s- killer hop aroma , equal parts dry pellets and juicy citrus . reminds me of what a tangerine orchard would smell like at the first blossom of the year , with a bit of piney , grassy bite . t- definitely driven by the hops , but these hops create some complex flavors .  m - light to medium body and fullish zingy carboination that is perfect for this style .
s : sweet yet refreshing , heavy on the wheat notes , slightly spiced . smells exactly as it tastes .  m - really thick and awesome . viscous , decadent , velvety . practically perfect .

it is a very nice rich and deep golden color and you wo n't find a beer that smells any better .  m-extremely smooth and thick , full bodied , perfect level of carbonation , slightly slick on the back of the throat and coats it as it goes down d-this has a great complexity that is blended just right , nothing overpowers anything , it just messes in a great way .

wonderful . all the advertised aromas are there : coffee , chocolate , bourbon , vanilla . this is very well balanced . alcohol is also present here . m : medium carbonation , a bit oily , perfect for the style . o : a very good stout .  the feel of this beer is ideal . silky and creamy with a soft medium body and a mild carbonation .

smelt of strong sour apples , fresh lemons , soap , cloves or coriander . overall , a saison that looks and smells wonderful , but attacks the palate and tastebuds too aggressively to achieve a perfect balance .  smuttynose nails the mouthfeel - excellent carbonation tickles the tongue intensely and then settles into an impressively full and malty body , actually seeming fuller than it is ( a neat trick , really ) , some alchohol-type warmth and a nice soft malty remainder bringing up the tail .

smell is sweet , very floral hops , alkohol . taste , hm what say about taste , sweet sticky , thick , very alkoholic , tons of hop aroma . mothfeel , again very sweet , very sticky , like liqueur , not bad but very intense .  smooth and silky mouthfeel , with plenty of weight in the body . carbonation is easy going , allowing the flavor some time to sink in .

s : has a very pleasant smell to it . this is an awesome smell to a beer . very pleasant . t : it has a sweet taste to it thats similar to how it smells , but just a hint of bitterness and hops , but in the end it feels a little empty .  flavor is exceedingly smooth , and it subtley builds to a very full yet not overwhelming coffee-ness . mouthfeel is quite smooth and viscous , like delicious motor oil .

s : here we go complexity here . woody , chocolate , alcohol , charcoal , with hints of a toffee and caramel sweetness . wow and this beer is n't even warmed up . t : lets see here it starts out sugary sweet with an alcohol kick surfacing in the middle with a drying burnt chocolate finish . m : very rich lush thick feeling in the mouth .  m- low carbonation and amazingly creamy d - i 've always thought that drinking guiness was like drinking a loaf of bread -- a can makes a good dinner and this is still the same
oranges . lots of aroma here .  mouthfeel - i love the shake like feel of guinness .

the smell was very nice , with caramelised cereals , and candy sweet / herbal hops . i did n't think it sounded very nice , but turned out to smell fantastic . taste was roasted malt , booze , and hops and in that order .  m - incredibly creamy mouthfeel .
classic belgian aroma , yeast and earth .  do n't get me wrong , i love the mouthfeel and i think that it is appropriate to the style/what they were going for .
big waft of grapefruit , with some piny scents there too . t- the grapefruit influence is huge .  excellant mouthfeel once again .

ca n't describe the individual components but overall it 's very , very pleasant . the palate has no idea which direction to head on this one . overall , this is really funky good .  mouthfeel is outstanding , nice and silky , one of the best beers i 've had in this category .
the hop aroma was also quite complex . the bitterness was readily apparant , but it was quite smooth , without any nasty bite .  mouthfeel is perfect for the style .
very nice looking lambic . the smell is amazing . sweet raspberries and funk .  taste & mouthfeel : smoothness is sublime as it rolls off the tongue , thick medium body .

the smell is very hoppy ; nice strong floral scent . overall this is a pretty good ipa , a bit different , and i think that hurts this one .  mouthfeel is outstanding . it 's perfectly carbonated , slightly dry , and you can actually taste the beer before you even swallow it .
it 's got a very nice citrusy aroma but the flavor does n't hold up to other dipas i 've had .  mouthfeel is amazing , very smooth ( like keith stone ) , creamy , just enough carbonation .
s. smell is really good . citrus hops , combined with new belgium 's biscuity malt smell .  wonderfully smooth mouthfeel -- the best part of drinking this beer .

sweet and bready smelling . actually smells just like a warm bob evans biscuit slathered in honey ! sweetness still lingers on the tongue , but the fruity and floral hops are felt in the nose and throat . i prefer my american pale ales more dry and bitter , but this is a tasty little drink with no real conflict from the mountains of west by god virginia .  m : excellent . perfect balance of carbonation and of body weight .
the smell was amazing . the taste was a 5 , but had an aftertaste of a 2 .  amazing . overall - this is a fantastic ipa .

smells pretty good .  the mouthfeel is incredible . old dubh is supposed to mean old oil i guess , but this beer is nowhere near as thick as oil or even syrupy . it 's creamy smooth , medium in body , and has a perfect level of medium carbonation .

s - amazing fresh , piny , citrus hop smell . t - delicious citrus hops right up front . o - very good apa .  the taste leads with a bracing bitterness into a rounder green pine hops that is cut with malt before fading into a pleasant lingering aftertaste . really an exceptional beer for those who like hops .

s - huge coffee , roast , dark chocolate . i do n't get a ton from this one , but i enjoy the nice coffee notes and roast . not nearly as good as the nose .  mouthfeel is almost perfect - smooth but with a light , fluffy carbonation that is close to flawless .
wonderful bouqet of smells . the bottle lists all of the spices and you can smell just about every single one of them .  taste- great even keel for this beer . very good beer .
smell is nice .  m-exceedingly smooth with a full , luxuriant body .

i was so excited to drink it after smelling it , so i was so disappointed when ... t : ... the taste was overwhelmingly bitter . the only reason it has a good grade at all is because it looks and smells really good .  mf/d : i love the mouth feel of this stout . the body has a rich fullness to it and feels slick on the tongue .

on cask @ the blind tiger ... 1/19/09 pours a cloudy , hazy , bubble-less blond color . wow the smell is exploding with citrus and pine . excellent cask beer , would love to try this on tap or the bottle .  mouth feel is awesome , just smooth creamy and dense , great weight and probably perfect carbonation , exactly what i would want in an ipa .

a decidedly american take on a belgian strong dark ale , as foresty hops hit the nose first . whiffs of raisin and fig-laden booze follow suit , with caramelized toffee and toasted chocolate malts . enticing , to say the least ... hoppy taste , too .  m- crisp and of medium viscosity . i love how crisp it is without being overly carbonated .

the barley aroma is really strong here . i am a little dissapointed after such a great aroma . there is a faint aftertaste of honeydew melon.. subtle caramel overtones come outwith a little warming .  the mouthfeel is awesome . lots of carbonation and a crisp relatively dry finish .
most appealing is the smell . mouthfeel is a bit weak .  m : incredibly smooth and one of the fastest pints around . smooth , crisp , with exceptional body and feel .

aroma- has a huge pumpkin aroma from the beginning and light spices in the background . what i like most about the aroma of this one is that the pumpkin was so huge ! flavor- has nice spice and then finally pumpkin but very light with both of them . very sweet also and malty . not sure its in my top 5 of pumpkin brews ( except for the aroma ) . its still very good for the style !  taste : smooth yet crackles with some of the finest carbonation yet to fill my mouth .

the nose is undeniably intoxicating - the best of two great worlds - rye and stout . lightly carbonated - this might be the best aspect of the beer - really allows the decent flavors to stand out and take the fore . enjoyable , and a unique twist on a stout , but not the best option - rye has been done better .  i feel this beer really shines in its feel . it 's highly carbonated , but still feels rich and syrupy .

the smell is very powerful , with almost wine-like overtones , defininitely some raisin notes . that is where i ceased to be very impressed .  m - thick , full bodied with medium to low carbonation which lends to a very smooth beer .

s - wonderful balance of hops and malts in the aroma and easy to distinguish between the two . the malts are very sweet but not too caramelized or toasted and the hops come in with a nice earthly note which complements the malts nicely .  caramel , ripe fruit , alcohol , brown sugar create an amazing complexity on the palate . long , balanced finish . an outstanding brew .
