aroma is seriously hoppy and evergreen with a firm undertone of grapefruit and just a whisper of sweetness . it pours a clear amber with a thick , fluffy , persistent off-white head and leaves some respectable lacing . flavor is decidedly hoppy , very much like drinking a pine tree , with a grapefruit undertone and minimal bitterness - quite tasty . smooth texture is a little on the thick side and nice and rough on the edges , leaving a hoppy and persistent tingle .  by the smallest margin , i prefer the flavor bottled version , as there 's a more assertive resiny pine presence , but this is damned tasty , and the mouthfeel is simply incredible . long lingering embrace of hops in the finish , as the tangy citrus kicks up the bitterness a notch .
the aroma is intoxicating ... i just walked into a fucking flower shop ! very sweet aroma , but not overpowering .  mouthfeel is spot on : wonderful carbonation combined with a luscious consistency .
smell was of fragrant apple peel . earthy .  great flavors , good complexity , an intriguing depth and an outstanding mouthfeel .

nose is big , rich and sweet smelling . all about sticky stringy caramel chews , green hop leaves , some high notes of alcohol ( maybe an oloroso sherry ) , a little herbaceous quality and some candied orange .  t/m : the taste is a citrus , grapefruit hop dominance , but the mouthfeel is as creamy as a glass of milk . a very interesting brew that works out very well .

smell : spicy notes throughout , clean and forceful . modest alcohol scent .  very thick in the mouth . has pretty good carbonation but the thickness is awesome . really believe this to be one of the best o-fest beers because of the mouthfeel .
the aroma is so good , funky barnyard / horse saddle , & whatnot . good thing it comes in small bottles .  perfect mouth for a good sipping beer .
powerful notes of banana and clove with subtle spices . d - this one delivered the right smell but not the right taste .  body is very good and carbonation perfect .
this is a dark copper ale with immediate aromas of citrus hops , carmel and grain . very strange indeed .  m : very silky and smooth . carbonation almost unnoticeable . great texture .

the aroma is exceptional , full of floral hops , fresh orange , almonds , and honey . beautiful . the flavour is actually not quite as good as the aroma . quite drinkable .  t : malts , booze , citrus , and hop bitterness m : perfect , just the right carbonation overall , this is just darn brilliant !

poured deep maroon color with decent carbonation leaving a small dirty white head.nose of booze , caramel , oak and more booze and whiskey . it is a strong ale . secondly , dont bash other reviews .  mouthfeel was excellent . medium to thick bodied with a perfect amount of carbonation and creaminess .

really nice . taste- malt-forward and full , a bite that feels like more of a fusel alcohol attack gets in the way of the palate .  taste follows well , it 's bitter in a way as if there is some significant hopping which is odd as legend 's ipa is not well hopped.. mouthfeel is awesome . smooth and silky without being syrupy or thick .

the aroma was wonderful with plenty of cascade hops that gave a dank hop smell with a lovely floral presence . nice work av !  it felt perfect . one of the few beers that i enjoy holding above my tongue just for the feeling .

very complex with changes as it warms . very drinkable and very enjoyable . i 'll try this one with some good strong cheese the next time i find it .  rich and creamy . thick to the point where im expecting lumps , but no lumps appear . huge , as a good ris should be .

smell is amazing . taste - spicy , malty start which leads to a hint of banana followed by a nice clean dry finish .  d : such a balanced beer and the mouthfeel is really exceptional and was possibly the favorite part of the beer .

smells incredible , and drinks very easy . tame on the sourness .  given the above par flavors and great mouthfeel i have to say this beer was one of the most sessionable beers i tried in the country .

aroma ; brown sugar and molasses , alcohol . some nice bready notes , and a hint of pipe tobacco taste ; initial is like a lightly chocolated cherry cordial and what i can only describe as muscovado sugar .  consumed in a hotel room in amsterdam appearance : served in a small water glass at slightly cooler than room temperature , dark as night with a light creamy tan head ... looks much like an espresso , something ive been more or less living off of for the last 2.5 weeks on the road smell : peat malts , dark belgian chocolate , light notes of the scotch barrels taste : rich dark malts , peat , earthy , dark chocolate , char , scotch , dark fruit , very smooth but forceful mouthfeel : silky smooth , medium-full chocolatey body drinkability : sipper , but nice

and i have n't had a doppelbock in ages . there 's more to it than that , it 's complex and i wish i could get more detailed but the 5 for smell says a lot . tastes good .  thick chewy mouthfeel with fine carbonation .

s : beautiful-grassy funky notes with pineapple and a bit of spice . t : quite good , but a bit of a letdown after that wonderful first whiff on the nose . bready malts and bitter , grassy hops dominate .  thereis also a carmelized sugary feel along with what i percieve to be some molasses notes . the body of this brew is super dense , but at the same time has almost an airy , creamy feeling to it which i can only describe as magnificient . no barleywine that i have ever tasted has such as mouthfeel as this one .
i have to say it , this beer smells fucking awesome . smooth , creamy , the ending is a little rough .  the finish on this beer was so exceptionally smooth .

smells beautifully chocolatey , rich and dark and sweet with a good belt of roasty espresso as well . tasty , aromatic big porter . taste is not quite as good , sadly .  the verdict : truly luscious body with a coy palate . fantastic beer .
pretty nice . there 's a bit of a roasted aspect , but not much .  mouthfeel was amazingly smoothe going down .
this smells wonderfully complex . a little bit of a good cigar smell in there too .  the mouthfeel is nice , very creamy and lucious , substanial but light at the same time . exceptional indeed .

n : nice aroma dominated by fruity hops . t : lemony flavors and fruity hops .  -- awesome mouthfeel- a smooth milk-like creaminess . so light and fluffy and full . there is barely any carbonation to disturb the whole experience . thank goodness , my tongue is so happy .
the aromas are the best trait of this beer . t : buttery , caramel malt , even blend of alcohol , hops , and malt notes . bitter finish , but nice and clean .  silky in the mouth .

smell is quite spicy , with lots of pepper and coriander , but also has a nice sweetness to it . i think this concept , essentially a saison with wit spices , comes through in an interesting and very pleasant way in terms of aroma . complex and very appealing . taste is not quite as sweet as the smell , or perhaps it 's the very vibrant carbonation that keeps it moving and does n't allow the sweetness to linger .  the mouthfeel is one if the best i 've ever had .
smell is great , not too harsh .  mouthfeel is exceptional . thich but very smooth with a crisp , semi-dry , bitter finish .
aroma is fantastic ! ... sweet , malty , almost rumlike .  mouthfeel is coating but not syrupy . outstanding in this area .
smells pretty darn delicious . t- this stuff tastes pretty insane .  m- creamy and smooth .

12 oz bottle . big time chocolate and roast with hops in the background to keep you going . chocolate and roast with supporting bitterness . i like this beer a lot , but best characteristics faded as the beer warmed .  mouthfeel is full and round .
the moment you open the bottle you smell cherries . the beer tastes of cherries , and a malt sweetness .  the mouth feel of this beer is really incredible .

s -- huge , wonderful citrus smell . rivals any other single ipa nose i 've had . all hail west coast ipa brewers ! this has made me want to get another pliny very soon try it again because i had to have missed something if russian river can make and ipa like this .  full , super creamy body .

aroma is a huge assault of leafy , citrusy hops in the nose and alcohol .  full bodied , slightly thick , flavorful , and all around a very enjoyable beer that i wish i could get more readily ... just what i hoped it 'd be , and easily one of my favorites .

a : monk 's elixir , delivered to me in a chalice at falling rock after gabf , is a dark , almost black brown with glimmering amber and ruby highlights . the nose is packed with cloves , banana , toffee , grapefruit , candi sugar , bananas , and pineapple . the spicy , tangy profile leans heavily towards candi sugar byproducts . t : the taste is a medium-bodied , malty and sour .  medium-ish body .

incredible aroma . this beer achieves a fantastic and lasting floral hop aroma , but the bitterness was much less than i expected after smelling it . a great beer , but may disappoint those who like really bitter , resiny ipa 's . one of the best aroma 's i have ever seen come out of a bottle .  mouth is also as good as it gets for heavy stouts . also with very crisp carbonation . its quite amazing in flavor and mouthfeel , but as far as `` drinkability '' is concerned , its very boozey and powerful .
i loved the smell . the taste was molasses , alcohol and dark fruit ( prunes mostly ) .  very smooth body and almost creamy carbonation .

the aroma is intensely rich . notes of caramel and burnt/smokiness dominate with light fruit notes including plum , raisin , coconut . the rich aroma was the greatest aspect . i would recommend seving it cool , not cold .  huge full mouthfeel .

smells terrific . the taste did n't quite live up to the promising nose , but it was still quite tasty . hoppy and bitter throughout , a good finish of herbal hops and tea , with an ephemeral malt and caramel flavour at the beginning . not nearly as complex as the nose indicates , but still highly drinkable .  m- this gets a 5 because it had a perfect level of carbonation and a really nice mouthfeel .

funky sour fruit odor is essential and simple . some sweet peach candy and chocolate fudge hints in the nose . bizarre and enthralling . flavor presents brett hints first , then a nutty chocolate snickers blast .  extremely creamy mouthfeel !
it has an absolutely terrific raspberry aroma . it reminds me of a raspberry pastry .  m : perfection here , this is a great beer for chewing .

a very , very , very aromatic beer ! fruity , yeasty , sweet aroma . yet the simplicity is not a bad thing . in fact , it 's quite an enjoyable thing , because it 's so well-refined .  very nice m-medium body and oh so smooth !

s : lots of vanilla and caramel , notes of coffee and dark chocolate . t : very boozy initially , but does blow off , though the whole beer has an ethyl undercurrent . lots of malt character with a nice complex finish with some vanilla which i like .  m : slightly sticky and slick mf but overall a super creamy light bodied brew that is just so delicate on the palate . i imagine this brew is amazing off of a cask .

incredible nostrils punching pineapple and cedar aroma . pure spruce.. incredible . as if it werent enough , that funky yeast reminds me why i love beer ( one needs that every once in a while , eh ? firm and mellow bitterness at the same time.. incredibly tasty and aromatic , lots of different range of flavours that youd never think match together , but you needed japans advanced beer science to come ahead with that .  mouthfeel : terrific . full bodied , smooth , and creamy .

smell is exceptional , the hops are there but there is something else too ! whatever it is , it smells glorious !  hops hit you right off then the different fruit flavors mixing with that pine resin and the smooth thick mouthfeel lets you know that your drinking a nice beer here .
aroma : intensely sour wood aromatics some malt sweetness .  nice , full mouthfeel .

s - super strong hop aroma , the citra hops really shine here . d - a bit sweet , but it tastes so damn good , i do n't really mind it . o - a very nice ipa , a little sweet , but it is a winner in my book .  m : smooth and syrupy - exceptionally smooth in imo d : strong sweet flavors and alcohol , but still smooth and delicious .

the slight pumpkin pie smell is subtle but nice . the taste is nice , a strong cinnamon uprfront will lent into a nice caramel malt smoothness in the end , a hint of pine fall hops in the back .  m : full bodied , silky , slick and oily but has a surprisingly clean finish .
the nose is all pepper . love it . the pepper is not as evident on the palate , more chocolate .  very thick feeling , creamy , velvety .

mmmm smell the hops from here . aroma is piney and caramel malts with an earthy undertone . i have had my fair share of the cold nose and am very impressed . this brewery is continually impressing me . devil dog is great . huckleberry cream is one of my favorite all time fruit beers ( traditionally i do n't appreciate fruit beers ) .  it 's smooth taste is characterized by a perfect blend of hops and a great mouthfeel .

the aroma is outstanding . very floral and fruity . this may be one of my favorite smelling belgians in this category .  slightly thick and a bit syrupy going down but not cloying in flavor . the carbonation is on the soft side making it rich and smooth .

s-wow this smells ridiculous ! in a great way ! very funky with a mix flavors that i just ca n't put my finger on . i 'm getting a bit of a chocolate scent , i 'm pretty sure its not brewed with any chocolate malts , but i 'm getting the scent . t-it comes in with a great floral sour , funkiness .  mouth is a caress of carbonation , perfectly so .

smell : strong aroma of roasted malt with a hint of dark fruit . drinkability : the aroma is probably my favorite part of this beer , it really got me excited to taste it .  m- super creamy and lush but not so chewy as to be a stout .

sweet , roasty chocolate goodness . is this stuff available as an air freshener ? `` alcoholic chocolate milk for adults '' . really good !  m : full bodied and silky . have n't had a beer with a mouthfeel this good in a really long time .

smell : the fruitiest hops i 've ever smelled . smells like summer fruit : peaches , pineapples , berries . no wheat malt to speak of which makes me sad , hence the 4.5 .  m- very creamy and smooth with a bit of a carbonated bite at the finish . d- a very enjoyable take on the style .
the aroma was great though .  feels amazing . wet and quenching .

plenty of hops . the nose is stronger than the final result . orange , earthy and a bit on the raw side . finishes on the sweet end for my taste but overall its excellent .  beautiful . d : great in so many ways , but just a little too hot on the finish to be truly drinkable .

smells really very lovely . huge citric hop whiff with lots of tangy lemon , orange , pineapple , sherbet and passionfruit . lovely , as i said .  quite a full and velvety body . it had excellent body too , and the alcohol was fairly well hidden .

s - semi sweet chocolate , roasty , toasty malt aroma that seems light , fresh and not as heavy as other ris . it smells better than it sounds . d - aroma seemed light but i really enjoyed it .  with the perfect amount of carbonation .

note : 2010 batch review adapted from notes taken 2/5/11 appearance : very black with a tan head - looks great smell : super complex - burnt , roasted malts , chocolate , coffee , wood , alcohol , and a nose full of bourbon - epic taste : rich , burnt malts exploding with bourbon - roasted malts , chocolate , coffee , oily hops , wood , complex bitterness ... but mostly bourbon - this would get a higher score , but it is rather unbalanced - needs more malts in the body mouthfeel : moderate body and somewhat effervescent - could be a bit heavier overall : best to split this 750 with a friend i had this back in 2009 and it completely blew my mind .  love the feel to this brew .

up front the appearance and aroma was very good . it pours a nice copper/amber color with a bubbly head . it was a bit strange , the beer looked great , smelled great , but the taste was not that great .  full-bodied for the style with a super creamy , rich and fluffy mouthfeel .

d - this one starts out very promising with an excellent , bright and peppery aroma of hops and spices . the flavor profile , unfortunately fails miserably in its attempt to live up to the promise of the aroma .  the flavors and mouthfeel are amazingly well-integrated , and it feels like drinking velvet .

the smell immediately calls to mind chocolate and coffee , which also comes through in the taste . with the first sip there is a heavy bitterness , which quickly fades , slipping into subtle but vibrant overtones of both espresso and more chocolate . this beer , my first porter , was an unexpected surprise -- a pleasant experience -- and i look forward to taste-testing others .  m : perfection . this is the smoothest ipa i 've had to date .

the aroma is fruity and full of esters , as well as wheaty and zesty , a very good smelling hefe .  m - the feel is full and rich like an amazing glass of red wine . this has such a rich velvety texture ; amazing .

the nose is rather odd and unusual , with notes of pear , sticky wet flowers , prickly pear cactus/nopales , maybe some stone fruit like peaches , honey and of course one would say you can smell the agave nectar . no woodiness to speak of here .  m : incredibly thick , i love a stout as thick as this .

s : musky , tart , and sweet cherries up front . funky yeast . i good beer to sip on . this is a good fruit beer . i was hoping for something a little more like a funky fruit lambic . though it is still good for what it is .  m - it was very soft and velvety .

aromas were a fantastic mix of fruit contexts and hops . i smelled grapes to an almost wine-level alcohol punch .  m : exceedingly velvety smooth and easy to drink , which is amazing given the 11 % abv .

it was delicious on all accounts . in the aroma there was sour-vinegar , light fruitiness , musk , lemon-orange-citrus zing , damp and fields . there is nothing like a good belgian beer when it comes to aroma .  great creamy smooth mouthfeel , perfect carbonation .

this smells fantastic . t- the taste starts out with some of the barnyard odor i picked up and some mildly acidic sourness . d- the beer was very good , but it costs too much . probably the best smelling beer ive ever come across .  mouthfeel is unbelievable ! ultra thick and creamy with a perfect amount of carbonation .

the nose strikes an admirable balance between roast and sweetness , the coffee definitely `` regular '' with milk and two spoons of sugar , you get carob , hazelnut , milk chocolate powder , caramel hard candies , cherry , blackberry to black raisin fruit scents , touch of burnt oats , without you noticing completely fills your nostrils . the hazelnut , brazil nut , macadamia nuts lend an attractive thread throughout . moderate corn and grain notes but never gets `` hoppy '' per se .  m : the carbonation is perfect for a barleywine .
s - malts , spices and some warmthy deliciousness welcomes your nose .  matching taste and awesome creamy mouthfeel .
really rich & strong , good stuff .  excellent mouthfeel from this bottle-conditioned brew .
smells of coffee heaven , with big dark roast notes . it 's a solid coffee stout .  solid mouthfeel , but there is a charming lightness to it , despite the style and the barrel aging .

s : a few hints of chocolate and smoke , fairly earthy , smells like an old bar , sort of , has some rum hints at it as well , pretty fair amount of booze , a few hints of caramel . the nose is good , but this just comes up a bit short in my book . wo n't seek out again .  it 's amazing . smooth , light , and a billion tiny bubbles that appear on your tongue .

the wild yeasts and barrels have created a wonderful smelling beer , probably the best smelling flanders oud bruin i have had to date ... slightly tangy to being with , but not nearly as tart as expected .  a little light for a german style but still tastes distinctly german . creamy mouthfeel and very , very smooth . medium bodied well carbonated making it quite drinkable .

as soon as i popped the top on this one the granny smith punched me in the nose ... it made me anxious to get started because i love apples and didnt expect that strong of an apple aroma ... very nice t -- another woah with a sucker punch to my tounge of granny smith apples but it wasnt completely sour like you expect grannies to be ... nice and balanced with good aftertones of sweet malts ... m -- kinda bubbly compared to other beers ive had lately and the bubbles stayed into the stomach..kinda made me burp more than the `` average ( if there is such a thing ) '' beer but didnt bother me at all ... did not coat my tongue either ... smoothish d -- i may drink two of these in a row but no more than that due to the bubbly aspect ... .i loved this beer though and will definetly get it again ... it was better than i could have expected ... another nice taste for me from unibroue..thanks guys  alcohol was very very well hidden and the warming effect in the mouth led to an excellent mouthfeel .
m/d this drinks and feels like a lighter ipa with some really interesting smells to it .  very full feeling in your mouth , thick and heavy but smooth .

s : the yeast gives off a sweet banana smell that mixed nicely with citrus and light malt aromas .  rich and chewy body , very full and creamy , and without the sharp slice of razor hops i was expecting . taste is initially slightly piquant , with pine needle freshness at the fore , but the body mellows and the palate is wonderfully long , balancing through some light fruit characters before the chewy , sweet and full finish , which is like caramelised sugar on the tongue . mouthfeel is as heavy , slick and glutinous as anything i 've yet had .

smell is amazing . i can smell it , just sitting there on the table .  a sweetness lingers in the back , but just enough to give the brew the right body the mouthfeel is one of the most unique ones out there . i have heard others mention an oily mouthfeel and this one is a perfect example of that oily hop mouthfeel ... one of the coolest things about beer that i have ever experienced !
smelled wonderful , lacked in complexity , and overall would n't seek out again .  the malts are incredibly thick and rich , the mouthfeel is just luscious .
smells like piney hops .  the mouthfeel was perfect for a dark lager .
great nose that did n't come through in the beer at all .  clean and soft on the palette , so amazing to earn a 5 . drinkable to have a few more .
very nice , though . o- enjoyable , would prob .  mouthfeel is thick and chewy . very impressed , much more so than other trappistes and clones i 've had the privelege to try .

if your a hophead like me the aromas are sublime deep resiny pine and grapefruit rind not much else just intense hoppy goodness , the flavors are not as intense but its still a hop driven palate no doubt very resiny like in the nose big pine elements with the citrus somewaht taking a backseat malt well its there but its in a dryer form and pretty well hidden.iam burping hops so thats a good thing a good brew from flying dog .  aside from the exceptional mouthfeel , nothing remarkable going on here .

smell is beautiful , but largly dominated by the chocolate/malts . however , the aroma was so nice ( and strong ) that my wife noted how good it smelled .  mouthfeel - medium-full bodied and extremely creamy . this beer feels like velvet in the mouth .

beer smells of peaches ! ( which is claims on the packaging ) tastes like peaches and pecans.. freaky but somewhat tasty . not sure if i would buy it again or not .  the body was medium light with a high carbonation and a super creamy mouthfeel .

s : excellent aromas of dark fruit , rum soaked raisins , heavily roasted malt , caramel , and boozy fudge . m : very roasty and dry . d : extremely boozy .  feels very smooth and clean , not overly bitter .

s - wonderful balance of toasted malts and earth-tone hops . not much past that . t - starts out promising but then develops a tinny/sour flavor rather quickly .  wonderful mouthfeel with a good thickness and carbonation to keep it from feeling syrupy .

smell - musty , cherryish , spices , sweet candy , fruity . taste - sweet finish , you can taste the spices and fruitiness of the beer . not as light feeling as most saisons . drinkability - not as drinkable as other saisons or fantome de noel , but still quite good .  mouthfeel : the feel is my favorite part about this beer . a bit over medium bodied , with very fine , light carbonation . incredibly creamy going down .
smell is alive with fruits , yeast .  m - this is where the beer really excels .

very aromatic with a long nose of resin and flowers . amazing aroma is both spicy and reminds me of fragrant orchids . while this is very rich , it is an interesting example of using big hops with a strong beer .  full-bodied , rich , and creamy mouthfeel . almost chewey . very good beer , but not nearly as interesting as barleywine should be .

malty , complex - what kind of beer is this ? brown and hops combine , excellent . t : expected a hoppy version of newcastle - but got burned sugars , malts , and complex flavors . excellent . spicy , nutty , need a few more to think about it.. m : smooth , cream - looks heavy , but does n't feel it . d : great . i will enjoy this more in the future .  mouthfeel is wonderfully chewy .
caramel and sweet malts balance the nose quite nicely . t : taste is pretty average for the style .  quite hoppy , but also with a fairly sweet maltiness , and a great , full mouthfeel .

the resemblance to the dessert creme brulee is almost frightening , especially at 10 % abv a- pours thick and rich , almost like black simple syrup s- absolutely wonderful ! vanilla , cream , and cinnamon are the dominant scents , but roasted malts definately make their presence known as well .  slippery and smooth . outstanding mouthfeel ! ! !
the smell was very very hoppy . really nothing else to smell except a bit of sweetness . very pleasant and very over the top .  nice creamy soft mouthfeel in this hop bomb .

the aroma was quite stunning , sweet maple blasts the nose with salty bacon on the back , its a bit smokey which i like as well . it smells like breakfast and seriously smells incredible . the flavor though , is interesting , salty bacon , smokey and salty , its weird having a beverage thats so salty .  m - perfect medium mouth feel .

the aroma is enticing , with dark chocolate coffee cake with a lactic sour barrel funkiness . unfortunately the smell was much better than taste and mouthfeel .  m : oatmeal stouts always have a creamy , full mouthfeel , and this one is no different .

this beer pours a hazy straw color with a decent white head . the smell is powerful and piney and citrusy .  the beer had a great mouthfeel , with a very hard water like texture and smooth carbonation .
the smell is fantastic . if you 've been wanting to try something with birch syrup , make this the one . very good .  mouthfeel is full and round .
really , the coffee notes in the nose are fantastic . t : taste is really hitting the spot !  super thick mouthfeel , absolutely velvety and palate-coating .
fruity nose with exotic enough including passion fruit and pineapple .  excellent mouthfeel .
aroma is wonderful - like a chilled chocolate syrup .  terrific mouthfeel .

smell is all big malt , tons of complexity . strong aromas of anise and smoke , maybe a little cinnamon and clove . outstanding . taste has a `` christmas '' edge that totally ruins things .  m - fantastic , crisp with a perfect level of carbonation overall , port city has made a delightful fall seasonal .
nose is incredibly smoky , mesquite wood .  smooth , luscious mouthfeel ; satiny . full bodied and soft .

very pleasant aroma makes me anxious for that first sip . d - the dryness in the mouthfeel definitely leaves me wanting more , and the great aroma makes me happy to keep bringing it back .  now the mouth feel is fantastic , swished it around and it was almost as if i was chewing on a piece of bubble gum .
though it smells absolutely fantastic , the taste is not all that great .  the mouthfeel is very thick .
smells very nice - caramel and burnt sugar .  mouthfeel : remarkably smooth . full body , velvety texture , low carbonation .

s_fairly strong smelling . a nice mix of roasted malt and caramel .  black cherries take on a sweet and sour lemon , with balsamic edge , which is both mouth-puckering and refreshing . carbonation comes out as creamy in the forefront , with a medium blast in the throat , all at the same moment . then returns to being creamy and rolls down the throat . pleasing .

s - wonderful aroma . like a belgian dubbel dessert in a glass . i also get just a touch of whatever fruit flavor is in red bull . interesting in a good way .  m/d : perfectly carbonated , smooth , and incredibly easy to drink . champagne-esque mouthfeel and drinkability .
definitely smells like a winter beer .  m : another incredible aspect .

4.5 s : really nice smell . this is a beautiful smell . 3.5 t : this would be pretty good if it was n't so alcoholic in nature .  milky smoothness about it , this beer is delicious ... fill my pint again and again . super thick mouthfeel sticks .

following a nice bit of smoke the beer poured a light copper to amber hue . ( i think the beer may of been a bit warm upon initial pour ) fruity , peach , roasted cherry and apple were the first things to come to the nose.. however this beer still maintained a bit of an earthy aroma .  what i like most : the wonderful mouthfeel .

i can smell coffee without even sticking my nose in the glass ! needless to say the aroma is coffee grounds and the burnt smell of malts with the air of something slightly sweet . the first sip is awesome . huge coffee flavor and roasty malts followed by warming alcohol .  body : pitch black ; practically no head , even with a straight hard pour from about a foot above ; sludgy thick - this stuff literally coats the side of your glass with a molasses-like look ; full bodied . - i was surprised , however , to find out that this is aged in oak , not bourbon , barrels -- i 've never tasted so much bourbon on a beer that did n't see some time in used bourbon barrels ; decent chocolate bitterness ; some cement-like minerality .

the aroma is amazing ... strong sour cherry with honey , oak and molasses . some foam would really help break up the sour and the complex . aging may do to same thing and maybe that 's the intent , but if so how about you write that on the effing label .  thick and creamy in the mouth , but rugged and challenging .

nose is amazing : breadiness , sweet cookies , roasted coffee and light citrus hops . lots of dried fruit . surprisingly hoppy - drying , bitter roasted malt rolles right into the citrus hop backbone . good , not great . overall , a really solid brew , although honestly a bit of a disappointment . next i got ta get my hands on that racer x ...  almsot has a thick taste of xmas . almost . great warming alcoholic palate with the just right sweetness mnake this a great after dinner drink or nightcap ; ) .

the aroma is rather outstanding , plum and prune , toffeeish malt , and a whiff of apples and funk . a very vinous beer , a little bit of an oily mouthfeel , and quite complex . not perfect by any means but certainly worth checking out  m - full bodied , rich and smooth . silky body works well with the smoke and spice .
aromas are quite sweet and hard candy like . but wow , this is a nice beer to smell . taste is quite hot and boozy .  an ideal body for the style imo .

smell = very strong hop scent , some of the typical sugary sweetness present that appears in most ipas . i like the smell a lot as it makes me think this will be a darn tasty brew .  m : soft , delicate , moderately carbonated medium body . so , so supple .

nice light wood , bourbon , and a really nice vanilla that is not sweet which just shows off the natural vanilla and bourbon ... the taste is n't as smooth or sweet , brings out some light coffee .  mouthfeel : excellent for this style .

the resiny , pine-like hop smell makes my nose pucker . sweet caramel malt lurks in the background , but hops are the star of the show . t. the taste is an utter letdown after the smell . the intense , resiny , pine-like smell is in reality very bitter with a muted hop flavor . the sweet caramel malt is weak at best , and the beer has an overall dishwater- like quality . d. what started out great turned out to be just average .  m : full acid , this one packs a punch . like the lactic version of la folie , i loved it .

aroma is massive . big pungent grapefruit and resinous pine sap . flavour is all hops all day . its almost alarming . maybe one of the most bitter beers ive ever drank . big , rough and burly . forget about balance . medium bodied with medium carbonation . i think only bigfoot beats this one on bitterness .  t : tastes strongly of malt , mild citrus , strong creamy oak/woody flavor m : so smooth with a perfectly carbonated body .

smell - the scent is perfect . it has the sweet aroma of a strong belgian brew with that hint of alcohol for a push .  it is amazingly comfortable to drink and has the perfect balance of carbonation .

it smells like a bar ; rather , the apple-and-hops smell always makes me think of a bar ( same thing occurred to me with ephemere ) .  mouthfeel is full bodied with low carbonation , super super smooth . this beer has one of the most fantastic bodies i 've ever had .
great brown malty smell , but undeniably sweet .  it has medium thickness , with a full body that invigorates your mouth and leaves it very dry .
the smell is of chocolate and coffee , a perfect mocha .  m - extraordinarily smooth , medium-full body .
s : smells really fantastic . awesome tartness of green apple , lemon , and sour cherry aromas .  mouthfeel : smooth , creamy , buttery , spicy , this beer has an incredible mouthfeel .

the smell is fantastic , you can smell some cedar in it . the beer does have some ipa notes to it , but its not a traditional english ipa , this beer definitely smells better than it tastes , not to say it 's bad , just not as good as it 's aroma .  m/d- full bodied and chewy , smooth , easy drinking for 8+ % abv .
the first smell is a beautiful roasted coffee aroma .  thick mouth feel , chewy with almost zero carbonation .

the smell is phenomenal with a mixture of grapes , prunes , banana , and bubblegum . then comes bubblegum and a hint of banana . i like .  this is definitely an intense beer , but it is well balanced for its stature mf : thick , creamy , chewy , velvety , low carb , perfect d : too boozy to have more than one but the flavor is exquisite and this sets the curve for bba stouts imo .
a fiery spicey fruit filled nose , sweet creamy notes with maybe a bit of malt .  m : excellent . very light and thirst quenching !
the smell is fantastic , with a slight bit of wheat malt hiding behind a large dose of fresh citrus hops .  velvety smooth texture has a good tingle to it .

this dundee offering pours a deep golden reddish color , the rich odor reached my nose before i even lifted it .  wonderfully thick and viscous in mouthfeel , slick with a subtly prickly carbonation teasing the tongue .
overall , lacking in appearance and complexity , but good aroma and blend .  mouthfeel is wonderfully smooth and viscous with some carbonation keeping it from appearing syrupy .

2000 vintage appearance : not as peachy as most of mr.van roy 's beers , this one is a little more like opalescent apple juice , the real stuff you can buy at the farmer 's market . smell : that unmistakable cantillon aroma , it smells just like at the brewery ... dank attic with cobwebs , a horse blanket , a wet cat , and this acidic twang that would normally repel the average beer drinker but that somehow strikes a note with me .  exceptionally smooth and silky with a terrific feeling on the tounge .

it 's all about that skunky smell . i enjoy it immensely and smell is actually most of what goes into taste , so i enjoyed this lager . it is very smooth and drinkable , much better than a beck 's , and you might as well buy the six packs without the fancy bottle .  m : the mouthful is excellent . the beer is so smooth and rich .
the aroma is powered by clove and hints od spice . the taste is very good , and follows the aroma of clove and spice ... and backed with a heavy abv .  piney and bitter up front . smooth as silk .

aroma is interesting , reminiscent of an english strong ale with complex hop character.. or a mellow american barleywine with a few years of age .  highly carbonated medium bodied . perfect for a cali-belgian ipa . very drinkable ipa .
grapefruit citrus and fresh hops blasted me . salivating like my great dane at this point . very enjoyable beer .  mouthfeel is thick , chewy and oily .
body and carbonation are perfect for style . finish is like flavor , clean , balanced , and of good length .  the best part of the beer is it 's amazing , thick chewy mouthfeel .
interesting ... smells more like a bpa .  mouthfeel is unbelievable on this !
the smell is rich with fermented fruit and leather .  mouthfeel & drinkability - mouthfeel is great due to the roundness complimented by the mouth pucking acidity .

s : under a decent amount of bourbon and barrel , molasses and toffee ... i get a faint but distinct aroma of my grandmas and mothers christmas cookies . bizarre . d : after the aroma i was expecting great things , and i 've rarely been let down by kuhnhenn ... but things just did n't quite add up .  the mouthfeel is full bodied with a frothy , creamy carbonation and incredibly smooth .

garden fresh - citric , grassy , piney , knock your ass over dank aroma . incredibly crisp , and insanely aromatic . this beer should win an award for just it 's smell alone . i 've seen ipa 's with way less impressive aroma profiles .  the mouthfeel is thick as a sumo wrestler 's thigh , and covers the tongue thoroughly .

above average head retention & lacing s : yeasty pepper , apricot , juicy fruit gum t : follows the nose , also over-ripe persimmons , a touch of brown bread , & green bananas up front . finishes spicy & fruitty & grainy with some gingerbread notes mf : medium bodied , low carbonation pretty good , but i found it a touch too spicy , the booze is well hidden in this one .  the mouthfeel is exceptional and velvety smooth .

alright , so the regular bender by surly is one outstanding beer , it 's tough to put your finger on just what it is , porter or brown ale , but there is belgian malts and its quite hoppy . when we finally got to try this at the blue nile , we just sat around smelling this beer for probably 5 minutes or so before we even tasted it . it was almost like putting your nose into a bag of fresh ground coffee , delicious .  a thick , chewy body rounds out the mouthfeel , and the full malt profile hides the alcohol while accentuating the flavors making this beer strong , but very drinkable .
it 's good , but not as impressive as the awe inspiring aroma led me to believe .  full bodied , very creamy/chewy mouth feel .

smell - great mix of malt , caramel , roast grains and buttery yeast notes . smells like the quintessential porter . flavor does not measure up to the promise of the aroma .  mouthfeel is exceptional , the carbonation just completely envelopes my mouth and throat .

nosewise this beer is an a+ . incredibly deep , dank hop aroma that smells less of grapefruit than gooey-ripe heirloom cherries ... just as rich as a rain-soaked hop farm on processing day . at first i did n't believe these were amarillos at work , and i 'm still not sure , but there 's a ton of citrus lurking in its thinly biting way .  the mouthfeel is full creamy and smooth , a pleasure to drink .
the smell hints a roasted malt and vanilla , but is overwhelmed by the bourbon .  the mouthfeel is perfect with a medium body and a rich , smooth texture .
smells like assorted fruit ... .but i also got a toffee/caramel smell ? but maybe that was just the fruit playing tricks on me .  incredibly smooth body , very soft carbonation , full bodied .

smells just like a really tasty pumpkin pie . it 's easy drinking and it smells great . easily the most drinkable pumpkin ale around , and generally not a bad example of the style .  incredibly smooth , perfectly carbonated , and just the right slick residue left behind . exceptional .

aroma is incredible . i 'm getting pineapple , mandarin , and grapefruit eloquently dancing around in my nose . taste ... definitely a west coast ipa ... hops are the star all the way . i might get a hint of malt , but the hops beat it into submission .  insanely big body and texture , with a creamy and sticky texture .

given the yeasty , leesy elements in the nose it remains appealingly fresh and endowed with ripe apricot , peach , pear fruit , juicy orange citrus and pressed flowers , also produces wheat germ , pretzel dough and sea salt notes , never showy but always persistent , has a long presence . strikes you as happy with itself and wanting to make you smile too .  it 's quite smooth and creamy in the mouth with a full body and a very fine-bubbled , natural carbonation from bottle-conditioning .

indicates great nose . lace . great nose ! very floral , piney and sweet smell of hops . more bitter than i like , but backed by hop oils , which i do like .  m- thick full body with some carbonation .

very strong but pleasant smell . taste features plenty of sweet malt to balance out a lot of spicy , citrus hops .  m - dry . great . you can play with this beer in your mouth , it 's amazing : take it on the tongue tip for a little and then throw down ... eh ?

smell is of huge chocolate up front , prunes , and cherries , along with notes of spices and mild astringency and roasted malt . the flavor mimics the aromas with the huge abundance of chocolate with notes of port wine and abrasive , graininess that may , or may not mellow with aging . the mouthfeel is medium-full bodied , lowly carbonated , with some astringency coming through and making this one less interesting . i 've got another bottle of this that i 'll be sitting on ... perhaps not until judgement day but for a few more years anyway .  mouthfeel is excellent , very crisp and medium carbonation perfectly matched to the malt 's feel .

smells quite awesome . i 'm pretty sure they used debittered malts in this beer at this point , since its dark but there is no evidence of roast in the nose .  the mouthfeel on this beer though is truly exceptional , it is extremely pillow and fluffy like in the mouth it feels great .

the smell is really interesting . you can really smell the spices .  simply outstanding . nice , full bodied beer that is n't too slick or syrupy , supported by a smooth and velvety carbonation that complements the body . drinks very well indeed .

the first pour stirs up fresh coffee beans and toasty-smoky malts . it is very inviting . later on , aromas of chocolate and dark fruits emerge .  feel : low carbonation , rich full body , ridiculously smooth and creamy , somewhat dry finish . drinkability : fantastic english-style stout .

theres also a bunch of grass and lemon peel , making this aroma incredibly dense , sticky nose . behind everything is an unsettling muskiness , like musty old crackers or bread . i get none of the bright hops from the nose here , though there is some bitter grapefruit . the aroma is just as fantastic as i remember , but that weird musk isnt .  absolutely perfect . d : thanks to jdv for this one .
appearance : a great light orange amber color smell : amazingly aromatic . pouring the beer brought out so much smell .  mouthfeel was thick and creamy like it should be .
smells delicious ! ! t - floral hops up front .  mouthfeel is amazing . super smooth . the mouthfeel is really the highlight of this one .

as soon as the thump is finished from the opening of the growler an aroma of pineapple cottoncandy fills the room . i 'm drooling ! citrus and piney . for a beer this bitter it is very smooth . recommended .  the feel is fantastic and is the first time in awhile that i 've been totally taken aback by a beer 's hop level .

i could smell the hops from this bad boy the second i popped the top and poured it into the glass . big heavy grapefruit , pineapple , pine , and spruce nose with grassy , hay-like undertones . this beer is already a winner . a hop lovers delight . if you ca n't handle hops , move along , nothing to see here .  m - full-bodied , smooth , thick , creamy , yummy d - so well-balanced and so tasty without ever being too much on the taste buds even though there is a lot going on .

jerky ! jerky ! pungent ; a thing of beauty t : tastes as if a brown ale forms the base of the smoking ; it is rather simple in flavor once you get past the jerky flavor ( did i say jerky ?  not overly bitter for the style , very impressed m - smoother than any brew i 've had in quite some time ... perfect subtle carbonation .

has the trademark belgian spiciness ( particularly coriander ) that all of my favorite beers have . t - the same spiciness as in the aroma ( coriander and pepper ) with hop bitterness .  mouthfeel : very smooth and pleasant , not aggressive or passive .

smells of dry dark chocolate , tart raisins with a fruity mellon zip .  m : a great after-taste , long and in almost perfect balance between sweet and bitter . the body is full and the carbonation is moderate with only really small bubbles .

the aroma is the highlight of this beer . fun and fruity with a bit of pine underneath . very drinkable and goes down easy .  smooth , creamy mouthfeel , and the first taste that hits you is that of a dark coffee .

smell was tremendously hoppy , very pine resin with sweet maltiness behind it , but way behind it . great taste , with a little pine up front , but in general , i thought floral/citrusy hops dominated the taste , whereas the cedar and pine doiminate the smell . great amber beer qualities , with a slight malt kick part way through the sip . a perfect session beer - mouthfeel is awesome , goes down smooth , easy and agreeable . the aroma was not as strong , and the mouthfeel/body lent more texture to the beer , but was n't bad in any way . just an interesting note .  mouthfeel is superb , soft bubbles over the tongue , and drinkability is good as well .

smell : very strong smell of grapefruit and a scent of lemon and flowers . mouthfeel : medium bodied , very nice amount of carbonation , slightly oily ... from the hops leaving a thing film in my mouth .  mouthfeel was damn near perfect , being right in the middle .

tulip tasted nov. 12th 2011 ( from notes ) a - very nice semi-translucent copper/brown , barely any white as snow head and minimal lacing s - wow , the smell is incredible , resin , fresh citrus fruits , fresh flowers , crisp water , fresh malt , the grapefruit is beautiful and a slightly sweet smelling yeast t - very fresh ! nice refreshing crisp water , very nice hops , citrus , grapefruit , nice malts , weed , pineapple , slightly toasty , flowers , earth and wood m - medium minus body , well balanced , even complexity , low acidity and medium finish d - best part about this beer is its simplicity . this is a beer for any craft lover . just well put together , refreshing and just plain well done final thought - if you like hops , fresh tasting beers , deschutes and only paying $ 5 a pop , get this ale !  the mouthfeel on this beer is amazingly silky .

the aroma was just amazing ... even my wife was impressed by the smell ( although she was n't as happy with the taste ) ... scents of sweet caramel , toasted nuts , even a little coffee and cocoa aroma in there . in my perfect winter ale , there would be a little more sweetness up front to balance the bitter , with a taste to match the aroma of this one . still , an enjoyable seasonal that i 'll definitely pick up again .  smooth and full bodied , creamy as anything i 've ever had .
s - slightly sugary ... awesome carbonation . big chocolate and bigger coffee ... caffeine buzz is coming ... some big chili too .  m : full bodied . love it .

great ! t : big , tart cherry flavours with a creamy , chocolate flavour rounding it out .  lol mouthfeel is soft and oh-so smooth , and drinkability is superb . plan on bringing in the 1/4 keg for a fill asap .

it has strong roasted coffee aroma that 's maybe a touch sweet . it smells delicious . it 's medium bodied with a quick , dry finish that gets slightly gritty afterwards .  brown with hints of read s- ambiguous fruits turning to alcohol as it warms up t- dried fruits ( raisins , apricot ) , some warming alcohol , pleasing amount of bitterness m- so smooth , carbonation is just right , very nice d- a pleasant warming sensation . mouthfeel and flavor keeps you coming back .

phenomenal nose -- not much different than sumpin ' sumpin ' with bountiful pineapple and mango fruitiness bursting forth .  big abv but not hot , well carbonated , the amazing mouthfeel , fantastic complexity and drinkability .

this may be the second fruit beer that i have ever liked . smell & gt ; bananas , hops and burnt sugar . excellent taste & gt ; bitter start , hop punch , smoothes out with a resiny hang ... but all the while there is an overlying ( and not overpowering ) layer of fresh baked banana bread . i think it 's grand . mouf & gt ; just okay drinkability & gt ; sure !  mouthfeel - it 's too bad about the flavor , because the mouthfeel here is superb imo .

has an absolutely big hop smell , like a huge ipa . a pleasantly hoppy version of the run-of-the-mill summer wheat beers you find . it was nice to try , but i do n't think i 'll be making a habit out of it .  the mouthfeel was full and creamy , even kind of silky on the swallow . these factors , coupled with its low abv make it a session candidate , especially when you include its fairly common availability .

smell-spicy citrus that overpowers , a great nose , no metallic flavor from the can taste-sharp spicy flavor , hops come up , settles with an alcoholic kick , the spicy flavor continues its agression mouthfeel-not that smooth , but flavor is certainly there .  as it comes up to room temp it really starts to get interesting , the hops appear a bit more at the front , the bitterness is nice , deep rich chocolate is rich and full . m- very mild carbonation , delivers nicely , smooth , good creaminess .

the nose has big pine , coffee , and alcohol , along with smoke , mollasses , bbq , and hickory . the taste is a bit like sucking on bbq sauce , lots of mollasses , brown sugar , chile pepper , smoke , alcohol , and a bit of fruit . i would n't consider this a very rinkable beer , but it is unique , and great on a cold winter night .  incredibly easy to drink . m- outstanding . perfect carbonation .

s : divine . fresh bread yeast , gentle spice ( coriander , mace , white pepper ) , pear , apricot , apple , wet moss . t : nice . elusive spices , strong farmy yeast , lots of pear and biscuit . a hint of mild cherry is in there too , and a lot more barnyard than was in the nose . it has a very strong hard-mineral-water finish . still , it 's not as full-bodied as some in this style , or as the nose might suggest . if it goes up in price anytime soon it probably wo n't be worth it for me , but for now this is a good go-to belgian-style amber from this side of the pond .  the mouthfeel is simply fantastic . chewy and thick , with carbonation that feels perfectly natural .

aroma - tons of coffee , bitter chocolate , and roasted malts appearance - dark with a brown head that quickly dissipates to a collar taste - first impression is all coffee and bitter notes . all i 'm getting is burnt coffee and bitter with hints of alcohol .  perfect amount of alc , spice and carbonation , and an easy to drink body .

wonderful . t : bready grapefruit , is pretty good , but too light .  extremely creamy mouthfeel that is silky as can be on the tongue and going down , despite the big hop presence which does give it a slight bittering dryness in the finish , also keeping the brew from being too full .

def looks exactly like a white ale . s-smell was dominated by citrus notes along with additional floral notes . t-like the smell this beer has a lot of citrus flavor running through it but its not overpowering at all . the spiciness helps balance out the sweetness so you arent overwhelmed by either .  mouth feel is perfect , not cloying like other stouts of this variety . lingering taste of coffee . highly recommended .

... the aroma is shockingly great , tons of raspberries with chocolate , reminds me a little of kre . combination works perfectly , but a little on the sweeter side ... the taste is so bad , did n't see this coming . the taste kills this , not worth trying as it does n't live up or stay true to a great aroma .  the mouthfeel was incredible , very chewy and delicious .

appearance is a solidly dense orange-amber hue , one finger of soapy white bubbles sustains , moderate lacing smell is big caramel/sweet bread malts battling with equally large citrus hops , hints of pine resin and light fruit , delicious ! taste is mostly pine and citrus ( orange/lemon ) hops initially , nice balance of sweetbread and caramel malts soon after , tones of toffee , brown sugar , floral , and grapefruit , finishes more sweet than bitter mouthfeel is medium-bodied , thick resiny texture , moderate to high carbonation level drinkability is moderate , this is a solid single ipa with a very admirable malt/hop balance , the flavor tends to slip away a bit too quickly , but at 6 % you can make sure your drinking of it is more constant , very sessionable  super awesome feel .
this is the best smelling sam yet . this is a very sweet beer .  wonderfully velvetty mouthfeel .

not to disparage this beer , i love the smell , i love soy sauce ... taste ... the more intense `` soy '' flavors poked through to me instantly , a bit intense ... not surprising considering the higher alcohol content ... .the finish is coffeelike , delicious . overall , the men at spaten really know what they 're doing , and this dopplebock reaffirms my high opinions of their creations ... i 've never met a spaten i didnt like .  mouthfeel ; very smoothe and velvety .
the smell is all hazelnuts : sweet and earthy .  m : very smooth -- the beer goes down so easy , yet it 's very full flavored .

scent is really great . t : slight caramel up front with a big earthy almost metallic hop punch in the aftertaste .  the body was quite full , and the feel was excellent , mouth-coating and smooth . a bit of a cottony/fluffy character and crisp carbonation kept a full body feeling light and almost weightless .

smell is intense , an insane amount of sour fruit and funkiness , cherries , oak , vanilla , lots of tannic goodness , strawberries , good balance of sweet and sour , very fruity , this is solid stuff . this is pretty solid , but the crazy sour fruit character in the taste is a little too much .  m - smooth and crisp .

poured with a huge , thick , foamy , frothy , fluffy , white head that lasts a long time and lots of lace .  feeling very blah about that palate . not a bad texture actually ; quite full , lively without feeling overcarbonated .

opaque black with a multi toned browna and orange head . tastes as if hershey just released a new chocolate bar that has been infused with some strong ass coffee . oily slick , and prickly . of all the coffee stouts ive rated over the last few weeks , this is the best . still not a fan of the coffee .  m - thick . oh god , is it thick ! carbonation is surprisingly high . it is a little bit refreshing , but it also leaves a residue in your mouth .

beautiful in a glass .  there are alot of polish lagers showing up around here in the buffalo area an its kinda cool to see.this beer poured from the can ( a trashy looking can at that ) a deep clear bronze/russet with a large tight one finger head that settled into a creamy top.pretty clean lager aromas slightly toasted with light caramel and honey notes , wow pretty sweet on the palate almost sugary in the finish overtop mild toastiness with a faint drying earthy note underneath the big sweet finish.pretty creamy mouthfeel but the sugary sweetness is a bit much for me to drink maybe even a whole can .

appearance : orange golden and slightly hazy . the head is white and pillowy huge , but drops somewhat quickly . even still , a solid white cap remains and is constantly being replenished .  it has a nice medium thick body , which was pleasant and unexpected given the semi-blandness .

received this 750ml bottle in a trade and i pour it into my lost abbey tulip to review . not quite what i 'd call a gusher , but i 'd certainly recommend opening it over the sink nonetheless . huge tan colored pillowey head rests atop this dark brown beer that has carbonation bubbles rising constantly keeping the retention at an inch or greater . thick , lasting lace lines the inside of the tulip .  the mouthfeel is pleasant , and probably this beer 's best attribute .
1/3 inch light brown head , big bubbles retain and nice lacing .  mouthfeel is light-medium , sticky with low carbonation .

it 's got a distinct raspberry aroma - not a sugary-sweet lindemans framboise aroma , but more the `` impression '' of raspberries in the glass .  mouthfeel - medium body ( for the style ) . nice level of carbonation . it really gets to dancing over the toungue .

label claims 85 ibu . appearance : this was a hazy , glowing copper beer . i poured it very carefully down the side of the glass and still got a think , dense head over two fingers tall . it left tons of thick foam on the side of the glass as it dissipated . after drinking , the glass was covering in lace , solid sheets in most places .  m : a vibrant carbonation on a sweet body .

really amazing . very nice red-mahogany colour with a small , foamy , light tan head . it does n't seem as complex as the aroma and is just a little harsh . i still like it . medium-full body with moderate carbonation . right on . a great beer . lots going on and really , really tasty .  mouthfeel - slight crispness . sweet body with a strange finish . sweetness on the lips , and a dry astringency on the tongue .
pours a viscous dark brown with 1 and half fingers of head .  mouthfeel is solid . a little resiny .

a - dark brown with copper edges s - plums , cherry , and red grape smells with light malty character . some acidic aroma as well t - malty and smooth with some munich/vienna malt present , not as exciting as the aroma presents m - minor puckering feel , with low carbonation o - an amazing example of a belgian dark strong ale .  the medicinal character vanishes at higher temperatures and all that remains is a faint coffee bitterness m - carbonation is a bit high , thick , and pretty refreshing .

carbonation heads topside at a regular pace , and lacing left behind is superb . great looking bier !  sweet tasting , but has a great solid malty mouthfeel . nice beer , but a little too sweet for me .

this is one of the boulevard beers i have not had before , but tank 7 is one of my favorite saisons , so i am really excited to try this . smell- tart peaches , cloves , some definite barnyard funk , pepper notes , lemon zest . overall , this is a beautiful saison , but still not as good as cellar door in my opinion .  m : fine .
s : very hoppy . very `` west coastish .  unbalanced . mouthfeel is thick and syrupy , matches the taste well , appropriate carbonation .

22 oz bomber from newbie bif : http : //lumen.phpwebhosting.com/newbiebif.html pours a cloudy gold beer with a puffy white head , basically perfect looks for the style .  the beer is fairly thick with a good carbonation .

pours a pale bronze with a nice 1/8 '' of creamy tan head . tons of creamy lacing and sticking . super faint , almost non existant aroma .  the mouthfeel is on the lighter side of medium bodied with lively carbonation . it is nice to see leinie 's not going overboard with the carbonation like they usually do .

pours a cloudy orangish-amber color with a very small white foam head . the smell is a ton of hops and very sweet ! the booziness just gets worse and worse as the beer warms up .  nice and creamy on the palate . very soft and pleasing brew : notes of dough , bread , oatmeal cookies and just a hint of toffee sweetness .

the nose on this one is pretty big . very nutty with molasses and cocoa . the taste is a little bit of a letdown after the smell . sweet and nutty up-front , but then the flavor just seems to disappear .  mouthfeel is good as the carbonation isnt to strong .
sweet & malty chocolate smell . very inviting . the taste is very satisfying .  mouthfeel was very smooth and slippery , with a decent amount of carbonation .
a rich copper color with a nice tan head thats creamy and long lasting with nice lacing makes this look like a great english ale .  mouthfeel is smooth and surprisingly not grainy .
the smell is a rich milk chocolate and molasses malt with some hints of a citrus hop aroma .  taste & mouthfeel : the upfront crispness holds a refreshing quality in the palate .

the nose is huge and full of fresh cascades . it 's like i just opened a bag of leaf hops to dry hop a beer . it 's an excellent ipa , but i think i 'd like a bit more malt flavor and body to back up the raging hops .  the brew is full bodied and seems more like a milkshake , rather than a beer .

the smell is what draws me to this beer , it is an awesome aroma that i love . there is a collage of aromas imparted from this beer , everything from dark malt roastiness to earthy spices to an underlying smoke component . delectable indeed .  mouthfeel is not bad light crisp nice carbonation lightly tingles the throat .

very interesting smell - quite vinous with a good amount of red wine / vinegar in the nose . there 's a bitter aftertaste and unfortunately it smells much better than the overall taste .  m - perfectly fine , like drinking naturally carbonated spring water .
this brew pours a picture perfect presentation . the head is very tight with lots of ultra white foam and a golden clear body .  m -- mf is fine , carbonated and smooth .

extremely complex aroma that is very pleasant but in your face and does n't fade at all throughout the session . awesome . appearance : pours with no head whatsoever .  mouthfeel/overall : light bodied with quite a bit of fine , abundant carbonation . pretty smooth going down .

pours a terrific reddish-brow hue with a half inch head that would have sat atop if allowed it .  in the mouth it 's full bodied and dextrinous with a gently caress of the tongue due to its fine-bubbled , moderate carbonation .
black with a stunning tan head leaving excellent lacing .  light to medium bodied with creamy carbonation , off-dry .

pour into a la moneuse tulip yields a head that virtually fills the glass , and falls slowly , leaving dense lacing in its wake . head color is creamed coffee . beer is dark brown , ruby when backlit .  good body for a lager ; high carbonation .
the nose is very sweet ... spot on for the style in my opinion . i do n't think i would get this again , but its worth a try .  m : mouthfeel is crisp and carbonated ; refreshing .

poured this beer into a glass and formed a short lived medium tan head over a very deep brown ( almost black ) opaque body . some light lacing remained through to the bottom .  goes down very easily -- very enjoyable . d : it 's very smooth and goes down easy .

a huge , rocky , tan head that boasts some pretty good retention . a great looking beer .  goes beyond anything recognized as beer , anywhere ... no , it 's closer to port , and should be consumed as such . thick on the tongue at first , then mild , still with a sweet , treacly coating that trickles down the throat .

great 2 finger thick head that sticks around for a while .  the flavor again is pure butter . where 's the saison yeast or spice ? this reminds me of pechish woods . this is a complete miss for me . it was very solid and had plenty of funk and brett .

sweet and creamy milk chocolate malted shake with cinnamon , vanilla , and essences of coffee . amazing smell that i cant get enough of ! has an interesting french vanilla creamer aroma to it . ( t ) - ample roasted malts that are lightly bittering that is followed by dusty cocoa and sweet creamy vanilla on the finish . ( d ) - a unique stout with the addition of being brewed with vanilla beans .  m - crisp , without feeling over carbonated , with a nice light body that seems to fit what they are going for .
a-poured a reddish amber with thick , pink head and left very nice lacing on the way down .  i am not impressed mouthfeel is good . carbonation is just right .

quite nice ! the taste is quite a bit different .  finishes with some booze hotness , a bit juicy , with herbal & metallic hops mf : medium bodied , moderate carbonation & some juicyness drinks easy enough , this is a little too weird for me .

a gentle pour produces a thick , custard colored head , the consistency of the foam is creamy and milky . lacing is gorgeous , very delicate bubbles slide across the glass . the body color is the same as the brown bottle glass .  m : nice & light texture for a summer beer .

for smell , this was great . ca n't pinpoint the smell , but maybe fruit and pine . i was pleasantly surprised . drinkability ... you could drink these all night .  a definite crispness initiates the mouthfeel but soft , relatively low-level carbonation provides for a slick finish .

big , sweet aromas of dark malt , rum raisins , coffee , and chocolate . taste is very much in line with the nose , but i honestly feel that it 's a bit messy , like the flavors are n't quite syncing up with each other . the raisin character does come out quite a bit , but other then that it 's all muddled .  m : extremely thick and malty .
very nice smell . t- bitter coffee and chocolate . this beer is strong and biting .  mouthfeel - fairly light with a good dose of carbonation .
the smell was amazing , very malty with hints of chocolate and coffee .  m : moderate body with medium to hi carbonation .

i had this beer poured from a 2009 bottle into a pint glass ... a : the beer pours a nice orange and golden color with a small 1 finger white head , decent lacing ... s : the aroma on this beer is nice , it has some slightly fruity notes , but a strong spicy yeast smell as well , i seem to get something sugary or cinnamony , but cant pick it out well ... t : the taste is like the aroma but not a full flavored .  taste was much of the same ... kind of porter-ish with chocolate and roasted malt flavors but then the vanilla hits you and that 's all you 're left with . maybe im just not in favor of vanilla in beers but thats how i feel .

some nice bubblegum aromas and a tangy smell are evident .  body is the high point probably , some malt thickness is evident , but it makes its way around the mouth nicely with good medium carbonation to match .
looked pretty good .  mouthfeel is actually pretty good on this one.finishes on the sweet side .
a : beauty . head has excellent retention and plenty of lace as i drink it .  i 'd say the best thing about this the feel , it 's real silky and full bodied .

well crap , about an oz poured into the glass and my glass is filled to the brim with head . pours from the glass as a somewhat light brown color , i 'd say about 10-20 % lighter than most stouts . wow the head is so thick that the beer pools at the top when poured in before it goes below the head .  nothing special to be honest m : rich , refreshing . has a good mix of carbonation d : easy to drink but not something i will pick up again .

s- spicy . brewing spices . molasses .  i am not sure what this beer is supposed to be , an artisanal brown ale or a dubbel ? flavor is not what expected , no sourness of a oud bruin and no rich caramel maltiness of a dubbel . quite bitter for a belgian beer with a metallic aftertaste . this beer is either mislabeled or does n't travel well or both .

it had an aroma of malt , caramel and raisins with a hint of the alcohol .  the auroma seemed to disapate as the drink warmed in my glass and left a thin head . i 've had this beer in previous years and really liked the smoothness and drinkability . i was a little surprised at the level of hop bitterness that met my mouth , as i have had the impression , in the past , that this beer leaned more towards a english esb .

poured into a samuel smith pub glass . appearance : clear and golden orange with bubbles popping up . a foamy white head developed up to about 2 1/2 fingers , at which point i had to start pouring . medium retention and some lots of lace .  m : somewhat thick with low carbonation .

popped the 16 ounce can and poured this honey-colored nectar with an orange glow into my dfh becker and raised an unimpressive head that sacrificed its structure to support its offspring ... really nice lacing . the aroma that wafted up from the glass was awesome ... it 's as if i 'm peeling a ripe , juicy red grapefruit . and the good news is that it pretty much transfers to the taste . in fact , i 've had few ipas better than this one ( one or two ) , but i 've got a pliny waiting in the wings which , if its reputation holds serve , all the ipas on my favorite list will drop a rung .  mouthfeel is thick , creamy , and smooth .

aroma ? spicy . citrus zest , coriander , soccer-mom-fresh orange wedges , grains of paradise . earthy , too , with a hint of funk and herbal hops . i could smell this one all day long ... the flavor is as rich as the aroma suggested . seven is inviting , but deceptively simple in its profile , with orange peel and grapefruit leading the way . vegetal & musty mid-palate with traces of white pepper . bottom line : delicious . i would gladly have this one again .  mouthfeel : thick , medium-high viscosity . medium carbonation .

aroma consists of coffee , vanilla beans , chocolate , and toasted/burnt malts . amazing nose , but the flavor and feel of it just does n't add up .  mouthfeel is medium to light bodied , low to medium carbonation , very drinkable but no spicing really hurts this .

mmmm the nose is delectable . sweet roasted grains with a squeeze of fresh grapefruit hops . an awesome smell that i 'd put among the top in this style . the taste is a slight let down from the glorious nose . the malts fade to the back and a slightly over bittered hop takes over .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with plenty of carbonation leaving a nice tingle . it 's probably the best aspect of this beer .

pours out a nice porter brown that lets through little light ; the head is very slow to form , but once it gets going , it froths up to a thick , creamy outta-control tan . it hangs around for ages , leaving a complete wall of rocky lacing in its wake .  m : very light bodied and crisp .

appearance : poured a nice light tan head that lasted the whole way down . plenty of lacing too . the appearance is great , but it smells/tastes like someone was smoking when it was brewed .  m - it has a full mouthfeel .
mmm ... smells good . excellent toasty , bready notes with some earthy , floral hop aromas .  this one has a nice 'edgy ' carbonation with light-medium body for mouthfeel .
golden ale with a white fluffy head . the lacing on this brew is awesome .  nice thick mouthfeel , though .
smells yeasty with big orange blossom nose .  medium bodied creamy mouthfeel .
i love the appearance , but the laced head does disappear before you 're done .  the mouthfeel is very decent , and a high point to the beer .

luckily , it smells absolutely heavenly . extremely sweet , heavy citrus notes , lemon and orange being most prominent . quite a bit like a blue moon , with the same type of odd , overwhelming sweetness that comes just a bit too close to being cloying .  slightly heavy body , bubbly , good mouthfeel .

s - this is where it really excels . aroma of piney hops , caramel malt , and some fruit . m - very good for an amber ale .  somewhat thick and sweet on the mouth , with lingering cherry flavors . i 've had a lot of lambics but not a lot of krieks , but i can tell you doubtlessly that this is a very sweet beer that lacks many lambic characteristics .

cracking the can i got an awesomely sweet aroma . yum . excellent lacing on the glass . sweet and hoppy on the nose .  smell : sweet cherries ... .sour berries , red wine and oddly ( to me ) vinegar taste : ( only took 4-5 sips ) short and simply put ... .very sour and nasty tasting . a few sips and i knew i would not be able to finish this brew . this is the first flemish sour i ever had and it will most likely be my last . kicked : perhaps a desired then aquired taste for certain sour ale drinkers ... .and this is probably very good brew in it 's category/style but it 's just not my style ... .take this review w/ a grain of salt .

11.2 oz bottle ( best before 01/08/08 ) served at 50 degrees f and served in a tulip glass . gushing pour ( despite a very gentle decant ) reveals a golden-yellow body with the slightest of yeasty haze . giant , towering , rocky , unstable cloud-white head dominates above .  m : this is where it 's most reminiscent of its style : sticky hop resin , lingering alcohol heat , bitterness hanging on the tongue .
a - two full inches of deep brown , cola like head . it has stamina enough to maintain itself as a frothy and humocky layer on top of a very dark brown body .  mouthfeel is crisp and very dry .
aroma is great , hops and malt married in a happy union .  mouthfeel is medium with good carbonation .

pours a light golden with a large white head that sticks around the entire time the beer sits in the glass . excellant retention .  smell is mostly sweet cherry pit and a woody pine tree brett type funk . sweetness is strong in the nose . straightforward dry brett is also dominant . i 'm still getting this pine tree or bark flavor following through from the nose . it 's just an odd woody flavor . lots of other off flavors in this one too .
the beer looks fantastic , with a nice cloudy leather color and a thick head .  m - medium bodied ale that goes down smooth and finishes surprisingly wet .
smells great . lots of hops and citrus .  nevertheless , i really enjoyed how the body seems to evolve from rather watery at first into a creamier blend as it warms .

if it quacks like a duck ... the sinebrychoff porter looks like a big beer , smells and tastes like a big beer , it is a big beer . it has an exceptionally complex mix of smells ; dark chocolate , raisin and bread crust esters , dominated by caramel and roast barley . a beer geek 's beer , for sure , and it helps if youre a big roast malt fan . i am , and i found this to be an excellent beer , just not one for the masses .  i thought this was supposed to be an ipa ? mouthfeel is smooth , not much to say there .

the aroma of coffee , cream , chocolate and soft and roasted malt .  medium bodied brew , has a nice rich malty backbone . just a tad to tart & sour to make this one a real session drinker not to mention the 7.5 % abv saludos to bross242 for the sample .

upon opening it smelled of lovely green apples ( the cork still smells like apple candy ) and it poured out a golden yellow with a nice white head .  the mouthfeel is rich ( typical of surly brews ) .

s : a mix of cherry and oak . t : tart ! d : very refreshing overall . a daring and fun offering at coopersmith 's .  the feel is creamy and fizzy , actually the best part of the beer . sits on the tongue ; solid .

12 oz bottle , poured into a sam adams pp pours a nice jet black with a great 1inch fluffy , off-white head that sticks around for a while .  medium body , well carbonated . crisp and very refreshing .
pours a jet black color with a thick and dense cap of light brown foam . good looker .  mouthfeel : medium bodied with moderate carbonation . it dries a bit in the finish .
reviewed 8/25/2007 ( bottle ) : pours a dark brown clear color . cake foamy head , good lacing , stiff , reddish white .  m : nice feel . feels good .
this beer has great color , a great smell , but is way too watery and thin for my liking from a stout .  body is decent , light but not too thin .

smells yummy . caramel malt , candied fruit , spice ( clove and coriander ) , faint floral hops .  mouthfeel is on the good side of medium and has a slightly creamy consistency . i expect much better from ommegang .

perfect pour into a hennepin tulip with golden orange slightly hazy hues and about a foot of antique white head that sticks to the glass like it was glued there . head cap was jupiter sized and went nowhere for about half an hour .  light-bodied , highly effervescent .
pleasing copper color under a firm head has a malty smell that does n't appear in the taste .  mouthfeel : thin to medium bodied , with a nice mouth tingle .
hops are definitely the main event here with aromas of pineapple . citus hops follow . this is the best part of the beer .  creamy , soft medium body and very light , prickly carbonation .

s : fruity fresh blueberry mingling with light flowery hops . there some malts in there too but they are tough to discern through the blueberries .  bottle into nonic a : cola brown , fairly thin looking body , good carbonation but low retention s : crisp cracker with a hint of carob , maybe a bit of green apple , heaving co2 t : almost pear-like quality , a bit of toastiness but not much , somewhat chalky/malted milk-like in the finish m : very bright , effervescent , final finish is quite dry but clean , good . i did enjoy the mouthfeel and clean finish .

let it warm , but if you do , you 'll be rewarded with a bouquet of malt and roast notes that are simply fascinating . chocolate , earth , brown sugar and nuts , a hint of tobacco and dark fruit , alcohol and a fine subdued hop bitterness are all blended extremely well here . the flavor does n't quite live up to the hype spread by the nose , but it 's very good . big boozy malt envelopes the palate and teases you with complex bitter roast coffee and sugar notes .  pretty good feel actually .

spotty lacing left behind . sweet , spicy aroma that 's bursting with a ton of pumpkin and autumnal spice . medium bodied with a blast of alcohol , pumpkin pure and rich spices . stronger than expected with lots of boozy sweetness and heat .  m : crisp , light body and medium head .

production code 23cf a : pours a slightly hazy light golden color with a massive foamy head that takes up half the pint glass . great sustain with thick lacing all over the glass .  mouthful : creamy smooth feel that improves when the beer warms the alcohol is more noticeable in this beer than in most dogfish head beers , nice and dry at the end .
