pretty fresh as i understand . this beer has a distinctive nose , one which sets off many alarms and triggers that i struggle with.. rich molasses malts , piney hop exclamations , and an earthy booze.. earthy booze in the sense of whiskey-soaked hay bales and the sweat of the drunk farmer who lays unconscious atop them . overall , the scent reminds me alot of west coast style american barleywines.. kind of like an aged bigfoot . chalky , hoppy , extremely malty elbows to the nuts one after another.. a soft voice that carries a message of hate . essential cherry , bourbon and oak emerge slightly in a warmed finish . global warmer 's potent flavor will certainly appeal to fans of big barleywines , strong old ales and things of the like .  mouthfeel is spot on , not complaints .

i tried this one once before and i am pretty sure that bottle had gone south already so this one looks and smells a lot better right off the bat . serving : bottle poured into a konings hoeven snifter appearance : looks like murky iced tea , very little white head smell : smells like honey with slight cherry , and burns a little in the nostrils taste : sour cherries , tea mouthfeel : medium-thin body , the sour makes you want to pucker when it hits the back of the cheeks , drying finish , almost non-existant carbonation drinkability : i could n't see drinking more than one of these .  m- medium in body and fairly light in carbonation .

pours a deep brown , with that big creamy cream head , impossibly slow to fall . lace is extremely thick , leaving stain of a similar quality that create a second wall on the glass . eerily attractive from the nitrogen but must give it some credit .  m/d : slick , creamy , decent mouthfeel .

aroma on this is delicious ! big malted milk ball smell , with plenty of chocolate , molasses , and just a nip of grassy hops . ( yes , i said nip ) thin mouthfeel with just a touch of carbonation .  this cream ale is quite creamy , with low carbonation and a medium body .
pours hay golden , slightly hazy , with a nice and big alabaster head ; great head retention and excellent lacing !  mouthfeel : medium body with tingly carbonation and a dry finish .

a - beautiful looking pour of a beautiful looking beer .  alcohol present in the smell , along with butter , raisin and a hop finish . lots of flavors on this , but a little out of control for me . an initial grassy flavor of butter that does n't blend well with the raisin , pineapple , alcohol , brown sugar and hops . some seemed to like it , so chalk it up to personal taste i guess , but i did n't feel like the flavors in this one were in order . too much alcohol and too much buttery sweetness .

it has a very pleasing and forward aroma of floral hops , but with a deeper unique fruity sweetness to give it a complex nose , which is quite rare . this leads into a surprisingly malty palate with a mildly citrusy hop highlight on the middle of the tongue .  flavors of whole wheat bread , slight must and some hops in the finish . warming , decent body and mildy creamy .
exceedingly clear golden colored beer with a good sized white head . this has a paler color that i would have expected .  mouth is bright and light as the style suggests .
pours pitch black with health viscosity . huge deep mocha head forms and holds for quite a bit .  m- quite smooth nicely carbonated .

s- wow , loads of citrusy hops and caramel malt ... at first the hops dominate this beer and smells a lot like weed , as it warms the caramel malt brings forth which i did n't like as much .  m & d : very creamy and smooth making it rather palatable in spite of the the varnish remover notes . the carbonation is light but tenacious and adds to the texture . honestly , if the alcohol was n't quite so noticeable in this it would really kick ass .

this brew appears a clear copper to light orange color with a finger of silky white head . the cap holds fairly well and as it recedes leaves some patches of leggy lace and a line of lacing with every sip .  this is the fifth hefeweizen i 've tried . of the five this ranks fifth best . something about these dundee beers that initially offers a metallic taste when cold . perhaps i 'd call this a beer that is better than dull but in need of some more flavor . at this moment , my hefe-universe is franzikaner and weihenstapher taking the lead , with sierra nevada a distant third , followed by paulaner . dundee sits behind paulaner .

i 'm really looking forward to trying this one from brewery that 's so good at lagers . smell : runs the gamut from bready to toffee to chocolate to candied raisins . i could smell this all day . taste : much emptier than i expected . dunkel lager , sure . but i would n't go as far as doppelbock for this one .  too heavy on the black licorice flavor , unfortunately , because the medium body is nicely carbonated with a crisp , drying finish .

could age a bit , but with it being fresh it 's still some outstanding stuff .  m - smooth , creamy , medium-full body with perhaps a touch of grain to it . pleasant carbonation , and well-hidden alcohol .

s : can clearly smell the blackberry and i love it . t : can taste both hoppy-ness and blackberry in the aftertaste , blackberry is not overused either , very good .  mouthfeel is full bodied , pretty smooth , and slightly carbonated .

aroma is very unique . unlike one i 've ever smelled before . fantastic aroma . very fragrant and sweet , yet no where near cloying . absolutely amazing aroma , and great taste .  smell suggested some yeast , alcohol , some raisin or malt scent . tasted malty , with a stong presence or molases or brown sugar ( i suspect this came from the belgian candi sugar ) , followed by either raisins , prunes , or fig newton filling . slightest bitter edge on the end ( hops perhaps ? ) . overall , a good beer , especially for the novelty of it . however , i could n't drink more than one , especially as the 8 % abv .

straight copper , pillowy eggshell shaded head that fades kinda quickly , smells like fresh hop flowers . i love it . there 's citrus in there as well and some sweetish malts when the head dies down a bit . it 's mighty tasty , just not as potent as the aroma . nice and crisp , light to more a medium body .  good mouthfeel .
s - pine and grass . smell is inviting , but taste is lacking .  mouthfeel : nicely crisp and refreshing .
this beer looks magnificent ! a pillow of white foam caps a cloudy golden beer .  mouthfeel is slick with modest carbonation .

purchased @ : hilander cost : $ 7.50 head : 1 '' slowling disapating lace : medium formations color : ruby copper aroma : sweet lager mouthfeel : light / foamy palate : slick / resinous taste : bitter brass , too much going on for me and the overall impression wasnt all that great either comments : just because you can put a bunch of spices into whatever it is youre brewing doesnt mean its a good idea conditions : mowing/working on car- n with friends- n sipping- n get my buzz on-n  m : smooth and creamy with a semi-dry finish .

let me just cut to the most exceptional aspect of this beer ... it 's smell is the sweetest , stickiest , hoppiest deliciousness ever . a lot more , and we might be something more than friends ... as an aside , i am thinking that if i could get this silly fresh , the taste score would come closer to the smell score .  medium bodied and tingly from the carbonation , yet relatively smooth .

s- very interesting complexities here that are not traditional in a lot of stouts i 've had . tiny roast also , but this lends itself towards a more smokey , meaty , sweet stout . this is incredibly different than the nose ! not much smoke or meat in the flavor .  m - oily and dry ; medium body with moderate carbonation o - this is my first encounter with a belgian ipa .

a : light reddish gold hue with a very poor head and retention for a dipa s : deliciously sweet hoppiness with notes of peaches and pears . t : i 'm definitely getting the strong fruit flavor , like a peach , which is present throughout the finish .  this brew poured a large head of fie to large sized off white bubbles that soon disappeared . it had a nice transparent amber color with no carbonation evident . now the real interesting part of this review is the brew 's flavor . it is smooth with a complex flavor of many interesting notes . there 's nut , malt , spice , caramel , and butter in the flavor .
loved the smell ! i took a whiff and my nose was treated to a cornucopia of scents . enjoyable , but not up to par with the smell .  light body and light zesty carbonation .
the rolling cascade is just fantastic . a fair head that lasts and lacing that lasts as well . dark brown , almost black in color .  m : seemed very nice , smooth and creamy .
i rate this one so highly mainly because of the head . leaving beautiful lacing down the glass that sticks like honey .  the mouthfeel is good . it is a low bodied beer with good carbonation .
loads of malt , loads of hops . loads of interesting flavors . theres an odd sour tartness that does n't do me well .  t & m- creamy mouthfeel , mild carbonation .

s ) great peach nectar aroma tops a toasted bread base with a hint of hops . nice level on the fruit . t ) the peach is a bit heavy in the taste , giving a bit of a syrup element that 's a bit overdone . d ) flavorful , festive , not a bad beer and i 'm glad i got the 6'er .  the body does have a medium thickness as the bottle suggests and that is nice . the carbonation is a bit heavy but has a pleasantly sharp bite without being fizzy .
oak aromas are huge in the nose , definitely overtake the hops . as it stands , the flatness makes it forgettable .  very nice mellow carbonation and drying mouthfeel .

this looks sublime - just what an apa should look like . slightly hazy body , with a beautiful burnished golden colouring . thick , creamy head of off-white , peppered with small pancake bubbles . lacing is heavy and sticky . just beautiful , and exactly what a pale ale should be .  mouthfeel - about right for the style ... the style being a flavored american wheat beer and not a witbier , as listed of course .
aroma is great . light alcohol .  body and texture are good for the style , but beyond that i really dont have anything nice to say about this beer .

rose petals , sweet boysenberry fruit , starfruit , very juicy , sweet and enticing . the aroma doens't follow through as good too the taste .  m : smooth and slightly creamy . carbonation was subdued .

fantastic pour as usual , per rogue . bottle conditioned , unpasteurised , tons of sediment and a creamy , tan colored head .  alcohol is too hot as well m : pretty good for a big barleywine . moderate carbonation d : this was almost drinkable .

awesome nose . mango , grapefruit , floral hops , bit of apricot and more awesome tropical fruit . awesomely hopped , extremely well put together hop forward flavor profile .  so this year i was happy to find that they were binging together several things that i particularly like : rye malts , saison yeasts and dry hopping . the funky yeasts , hop bitterness , and spicy sweetness compete rather than contribute to a balanced whole . then there is the metallic aftertaste that sometimes accompanies a higher-alcohol beer .
this is a good tasting one . the smell is very fruity as it should .  mouthfeel is medium bodied and lightly carbonated .
very complex , very earthy . outstanding .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with a nice carbonation tingle .
the beer looks alright , smells terrific , but the taste is not something i would seek out again .  mouthfeel : thick for the style . almost seems chewy or nutty in the mouth .

regardless of how you may feel about lambics there is no denying that this thing smells great . taste is of course heavily characterized by raspberry and similar berry fruit but sweet malt and baked doughy bread yeast ads a familiar twist .  mouthfeel : pretty well spot-on for a wheat beer - full and a tad creamy , without being heavy . medium carbonation is refreshing .

smell : a nose smelling of cherries ( sweet ) , orange blossom honey , dark caramel , a light earthiness , a trace of rustic bread dunked in brandy , and tired , old wooden barrels ready to be halved and converted into tomato planters . i 've been informed it was aged in apple brand barrels , but i 'm getting more of an off-brand grand marnier kick .  mouthfeel : high carbonation level . body is good .
nice . t : strong hops up front , basically continuing from the smell .  medium mouthfeel .

near yellow head dissappears in seconds . pretty beer . huge aromatics on this one . complex and very sweet . noticable alcohol fumes , brandy soaked cherries , licorice , raisins , pineapple ( ? ) .  md thick mouthfeel and strong carbonation .

big time hop aroma , as was expected , grapefruit is the main player here followed up by subtle pineyness . overall a great imperial ipa , the great balance between the malts and the hops make it enjoyable for all , even if your not a `` hop-head '' .  mouthfeel is quite light with high carbonation .

first thing is the absolute massive duvel-esque head that forms with even the softest pour . it 's really quite beautiful floating atop the cloudy peach body of this brew and though it does dissipate in time , it still leaves a huge dimple filled marshmallow island and sporadic lacing everywhere and for the duration of the session .  m : smooth with just the right amount of bitterness .

pours a golden orange color with a massive off-white head that possesses amazing retention and leaves a good amount of lacing around the glass as well .  the mouthfeel is medium to full with good carbonation .

a : pretty deep amber in color , good transparency with a quarter inch head that doesnt leave much lace or retain all of that well s : tons of citrus notes that are primarily grapfruit with hints of lemon , followed by loads of piny bitterness and some hints of caramel sweetness t : damn this is piny , but in a very good way . the grapefruit too is very dominant . the hops are quite powerful and hide the alcohol that is clearly present m : a nice lingering bitterness and a decent amount of body without being too heavy .  very smooth mouthfeel , surprisingly , and its complete lack of off nodes make it quite drinkable .

aromas are great . smoked salmon smell that i noticed as soon as the swingtop was opened . the smoke flavors are very nice , and not overpowering .  honey . malt . sugar . and some hop bite . it really helps clean the palate . a good brew for a hot day and a barbecue .

yellow labelled bottle conditioned beer , picture of a b-52 inside an orange circle within the yellow label . poured carefully into my 'old speckled hen ' vase shaped pint glass ( my current favourite pint tasting glass ) . cracking looking beer , light amber with a creamy off-white head sat on top .  tastes like mocha syrup , very very sweet , then finishes with some alcohol burn . slick , low carbonation .

i took a quick spin through some of the other reviews and have to agree : a wonderful smoky wood fire smell with hints of bacon . a very intriguing beer and one i 'd like to try again , and/or other examples of this unique style .  md thick mouthfeel and moderate carbonation .
very nice . t- holy hell , this is hot . really boozy and not too complex .  mouthfeel : medium bodied and smooth , with a surprisingly smooth finish topped off with warming alcohol .

a-when poured has a very clear amber color with some nice ruby hue . it has a 3/4 finger off white head that goes to a decent froth ring . it is a really nice looking beer .  feel is a bit beefy though comparetively speaking with whats offered in taste ; the full crisp feel more then makes up for some of the faultering taste .
s : strawberries , bubblegum and molasses , raisins take over as it warms up . a unique nose for sure even in the style .  m : light body with a surprisingly good amount of carbonation .

the appearance of this beer was quite stunning . there was almost no head on mine after pouring it into my glass .  m : somewhere between light and medium bodied with a moderate amount of carbonation .
for an ipa , the aroma is subtle with hops . this is a hearty and enjoyable ipa .  m - light to medium body with medium carbonation .

a bright , sweet grapefruit / citrus scent smacks you in the face when you take a whiff . the beer tastes great but i do n't think the citrus taste is as strong as the smell . i will end up buying this one again . good stuff !  mouthfeel : fine .
wonderful aroma of spices , mostly cinnamon and nutmeg , with a touch of clove .  medium mouthfeel .
smells of chocolate , toffee , cherries , and maybe a hint of coffee . overall this is a complex and genuinely good beer .  m - medium bodied ale that goes down smooth and finishes nice and wet .
excellent aroma , just the right amount of tangy bitter orange and a slight honey backdrop .  m. smooth with appropriate carbonation .

the aroma is of roses , coriander , leather , earth , and bretta with a nice tart sourness .  it is a quality brew from the perspective that it carries a nice light bodied quality with lovely crisp carbonation .

this is the first beer in a long long time that i can remember smelling so good from all the way across the room from my pint glass , the nose really carries that far ! heady scents of pineapple / mango , pine resin , and roasted malts as if from a porter mingle together in a combo that really makes me salivate for some reason . tastes of all the things promised by the nose and also some interesting interplay between a sweet caramel malt tone that plays hide and seek with a roasted more bitter malt , finish is relatively straightforward bittering ... overall a fantastically well-executed bipa .  creamy texture medium plus bodied with lowish carbonation .
looks like the froth on a good cappucino ! full marks for appearance !  mouthfeel juicey and full and pleasant .

s - phenomenal yeasty aroma of banana and other fruits . a little spice as well .  t & m : smooth at first but the hops hit the tongue and are definitely noted on the after-taste . nice mouthful , beer really stays with you after sip .
s = smelt of stewed fruits like plums and figs . d = drinkable but there are better bocks out there .  medium body and moderate carbonation .

a - dark amber color with amazing chunky dirty brown three-finger head . the head stayed nice and thick and left excellent lacing .  m-smooth and creamy with a medium body . it is slightly syrupy with just enough carbonation to hold a firm finish with just a touch of crispness d-this is actually easy drinking , the flavors are pretty light but everything works together and it has a soft smooth texture on the palate making it quite inviting . solid drink , nothing great but definitely a solid drink if it is there .

smells absolutely divine : complex sweet and tropical fruitiness , with a nice spiciness and gentle yeastiness . exceptionally refreshing .  v=un-g035xuny appearance : transparent light amber , minimal head , minimal lacing smell : bready malts , caramel malts , lemon rind , hint of pumpernickel + fig taste : medium/thin body , toffee , caramel , doughy bread , cranberry , stainless steel sweetness , english breakfast tea , orange + lemon citrus layering , grassiness on finish , baked turkey residual , crisp + slightly metallic mouthfeel , mild carbonation pairings : bratwurst brew + pairing : brew lets the flavors of food shine , keeps palate crisp

corked and caged , with black foil covering , and a hangtag noting this is the 2004 holiday stout . poured into an imperial pint glass , formed 1 1/2 '' of dark brown head over the opaque dark brown/black brew .  the carbonation and mouthfeel is pretty good .

from 10/16/10 notes : a : awesome huge light brown foamy head of at least a finger throughout the drink . black color , great lacing .  well-balanced mouthfeel , as you might expect at the taphouse . good amount of carbonation and , since not on nitro , pretty good overall .
i kept smelling it until i could n't smell it anymore , it was that good . tastes robustly of grains and alcohol .  it is light bodied and very smooth . it 's lightly bitter and fresh tasting .

one of six stouts we shared last night at the vine street pub during stout month . aromas of cocoa powder , mint and roasted malt . medium bodied , balanced and delicious . dark chocolate , thin mint cookies and roasted malt .  the body is nice but i 'm still not crazy about this beer .
big head with soapy bubbles , with lace .  m. medium to full bodied with decent carbonation . coats the mouth decent , definitely all that sweet malt .
aroma is of port , dark fruit , sherry and hints of alcohol .  mouthfeel is fuller and creamier than anything i 've had before .

pours a dark but still translucent mahogany color topped with a substantial creamy head .  i give it points for appearance and mouthfeel , and on a hot summer day i suppose i could put down a couple around the barbecue .

overflowing with tart cherry aroma , matched by a flavor of the same .  the foam does not hold nor does it leave behind much lacing . very interesting , but way too powerful as opposed to subtle , which in my opinion leads to greater exploration of the beer . my throat was very dry after just a few sips which probably has to do with the alcohol content of this beer .
aroma is strong floral notes with a lot of good ol american hops .  very smooth with a medium amount of carbonation .
it smells of citrus zest and ginger but has a lot of complexity to it .  m : light and crisp . what i 'd expect from the style .

appearance : gorgeous dark colour with mahogony hi-lites . head pours like a rootbeer float , lasts quite some time and has excellent lacing .  medium body , drier than the initial aroma leads me to expect .

perfect tan head leaves a merengue-like film on the side of my tasting glass ( from the 1st ever gitchee gumi fest , heh heh ) and makes me think of dessert . sure , why not . velvety-smooth with soft carbonation on the first sip , but with a nice hop bite and significant bitterness braced-up against the malt complexity . notes of green apple in the aromatics , along with complex phenols and warming alcohol . probably great with cigars .  mouthfeel is very smooth , good .

the aroma is unreal on this brown ale . big time hazelnut aroma like fresh toasted hazelnuts . pretty much the best smelling beer ever . the flavor drops off for me a bit as it 's extremely dry and get a hint of astringent flavors . worth the 4.99 a bomber and would really open up with some roasted pork or a steak sandwich .  very nice for a wit .
pours a dark , dark brown with reddish highlights . combined with the the textbook lacing , i must say this beer looks perfect .  m- nicely carbonated and smooth to boot !

s- there is a wonderful blended citrus aroma . not only is the expected orange zest there , but i also smell some lime and maybe some lemon as well .  the mouthfeel was good , above average for the style .

pours a dark brown with a creamy brown head . nice lace . beautiful in a glass .  took a little swig at first , assessing the carbonation . very bubbly , which i like . felt really smooth in my mouth .

pours a lovely caramel color with a fine long lasting head . it 's a beautiful thing .  it was slightly thick with some carbonation , and had a bitter aftertaste . it had good body , but it had strong alcohol flavor that made it tough to drink .
large white head with sticky lace and great retention .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , crisp with just the right about of carbonation .

355ml bottle poured into pint glass may27 2010 a a glowing peachy amber with plenty of bubbles feeding a big ass off white head that had excellent retention slowly falling to an island holding its own to the bitter end ( pun intended ) leaving multiple rings of lace well down the glass , not much i would change in this department s some citrus with mild pine balanced out with a healthy amount of sweet malts t even more malt while tasting but nothing overwhelming , some caramel and orange rind go with the flow m no reasons to complain here not too thin well carbonated and a lingering aftertaste d i 'm feeling this beer for sure , a 4.25 option may have come in handy for this brew , well rounded and strong in all areas all that being said this beer is way to expensive here in alberta at 22 $ for 6 i ca n't see myself drinking this too often .  the mouthfeel is nice and thick and is the highlight .

s : grapefruit , aromatic , juicy hops up front . lots of tropical flavors going on . also some alcohol present on the finish . t : the front is fruity with notes of grapefruit , orange , and tangerine . warming sensation on the finish . overall , another very solid offering from half acre .  on the nose , this was about 50 % skunked -- i 've had worse , but i 've only had it once from the bottle without at least some funk . as for the taste , i 'm not old enough to be a grumpy nostalgic , but i distinctly remembering this beer having way more hop flavor . in prague it 's sublime , 3 years ago here it was damn good , now it 's nothing to write home about . for 60 cents more a 12 pack than bud ( i hate cambridge ) , i 'll drink it , but it 's a pity to remember what this beer once was .
t/s : lots of flavors - they just did n't mix well ! lots of fruity esthers and sweetness on the bottom , molasses and roasted malts on the top .  nicely carbonated , at least .

there are lots of competing flavors in this one : smells range from raisins/dates to caramel and winter spices , although there is strong fruit smell to it ( bananas ) and some sweet candy . really fun to parse out . taste - good , but a little disappointing after some wonderful olfactory notes . a little too bitter at the start , and very , very sweet on the tongue .  a full , creamy mouthfeel with moderate carbonation is the highlight of this beer .
i really liked how this brew smelled .  m- thick with low carbonation .
smells awesome- definite notes of banana and yeast ; in a word , i would describe it as inviting and delicious .  m : syrupy . thick and decent carb .
poured a pitch black with a great creamy , beige head . the ribbon , no streams of lacing around the glass were amazing . the lacing simply did not move and did not fade .  soft mouthfeel .

s - ohhh man . wheat , lemon , marshmallows ? very , very inviting . t - tastes like a witbier should . light , very pleasing , but not quite as complex or tasteful as the aroma had me thinking .  the first sip delivers some hints of malt that are immediately shoved aside by the hops . some smooth , creamy textures ease up the hop flavors . pretty empty in the malt flavor department . just a hint more of malt and maybe a little more diversity from the hops . a lot good things happening in this beer , but not enough to get me to drink it again .
glass : sam adams signature glass a : awesome pillow-like head , about 3-fingers . sticky , soap-like lacing .  m : medium to full in body with a moderate carbonation .

looked great , a light brown color with great head and lacing that retained well throughout .  the mouthfeel is fine , drinkability is ok , the aftertaste is n't excessively long or unpleasant , but it 's just not that tasty .

ommegang abbey a : pours a very dark amber with a lively & enormous brown-orange head that displays magnificent retention . looks as if someone dropped a mini throw-pillow on top of it . gorgeous .  mouthfeel is very full .
a - black brew with a large mocha brown head . strong lacing in thick clumps .  the carbonation is moderate low and there is a smooth mouthfeel .
a bit of heat here too but nicely balanced overall . the aroma was amazing and the taste was really complex .  medium bodied and high carbonation .
the smell is unbelievable . chocolate , roasted grain , caramel , and oak .  mouthfeel is astringent and tingly , with good body and a dry finish .

a : pours a hazy amber with golden highlights . low-medium carbonation and two fingers of fluffy white head that dissipates slowly give way to some excellent lacing .  feel is well carbonated with a firm body .
very pleasant . very wine like .  nice clean mouthfeel , with just the right amount of carbonation .
nice aroma from the roasted malts .  m : nice and smooth , very mellow .

s : beautiful yeast , tropical fruit , bubblegum , a hint of hops , a hint of booze . intense and beautiful . m : good amount of body without being syrupy .  mouthfeel is nice had good body and goes down smooth .

12 oz bottle poured into a wine goblet - 06 | july | 2007 - cellar temp appearance : pours a transparent golden/yellow/orange with a thick 2 '' head that is off-white . thick , foamy head with tons of lace . excellent .  m - asahi super dry is dry but i would n't call it super dry . quite a surprise with how carbonated this one is .

smell is typical pumpkin ale - pumpkin pie spice with a nice sweetness . i prefer a pumpkin pie-y flavor to my pumpkin ale , so while this is very good , the lower sweetness does n't make it as good as a weyerbacher or schlafly .  nice and round . good soft carbonation .

the aroma came through in a major way after a seemingly unimpressive pour , delivering a plethora of rich barleywine-like notes , including toffee malts , brown sugar , raisin , fig , red wine , sherry , and resinous , spicy hops . coffee and raisin cake lead into a world-class strong ale finish , with a burst of booze , a quick flash of fruit , and a kiss of piny hoppiness to seal the deal . overall , ithaca 's ten is an enticing , complex beast of a beer . very happy to have this as my 700th review , and i 'm sure the other bottle stashed away in my cellar will only improve .  mouthfeel : crisp on the tongue throughout . light in body . clean aftertaste .
strong citrus and piney hop aroma . pretty good , bitterness is not overwhelming .  very little carbonation .
it 's a gorgeous looking beer , with sheets of sticky lacing that clings all the way down .  smooth body is a bit under medium . super crisp , snappy , a bit drying .

the beer pours a deep brown to almost black with some ruby highlights , the head modest and somewhat creamy , the color a light tan and as it dissipates a nice clinging sheet of lace forms on the glass .  mouthfeel is rather smooth , viscous maybe .
looked like thick chocolate in the pour . simply amazing looking .  mouthfeel on the other hand is pretty good . medium to full bodied with a nice level of carbonation .

one of saranac 's best best beers . this beer puts just the right hints in to make it very drinkable .  i like the body and mouthfeel , but the distinct alcohol burn and slight metallic aftertaste distract from the nice simcoe hop flavor .

the aroma is very nice ! it has a wonderful fresh hop scent along with monster malt aroma .  hops pretty much out of the equation until hints of them at the finish . other notes- the tastes are complex and appropriate for the style . you really can see what the brewers were going for . this beer tastes like christmas in a bottle . unfortunately , for me the various spices and other flavors were a bit much and did n't combine as well as they could have . i would have liked to see a more malt dominant profile with the spices and whatnot more in the background .

this brew poured a medium tan head with fine-small bubbles into my glass . the body was brown in color .  m : at least the mouthfeel is nice . this is a full bodied beer with low to moderate carbonation .

s : the aroma is fantastic . sweet caramel malt character , and significant raisin character . really interesting , and enjoyable . the aroma was fantastic , and the mouthfeel was very good , but in the end i just ca n't keep tipping this one back .  it had a lite to medium body what was smooth and refreshing .

s - sweet syrup with floral/cirtus hop . overall , looks great , smells great , i just do n't think i got the flavor they were going for .  thick in the mouth , it might be nice to have a few ounces of this on a cold night .

a real beauty to look at , bright orange with a british judge wig for a head . nose is of pure grapefruit . damn enjoyable . two weeks later another buddy shares his growler that was filled that morning .  md body and strong carbonation .
s : really nice funky nose . really nice .  m : just fine - refreshing with a mild carbonation .
s - vanilla right away with milk chocolate and caramel .  mouthfeel was solid .
looks exactly how a good pils should look . poured with an impressive white , foamy , frothy , thick head that lasts a while and good lacing .  mouthfeel is smooth and medium bodied carbonation .

the archetypal ipa . dreamy nose , so well done . alive , ripe and in your face . one of the better ipa 's i 've had the pleasure of smelling . taste is quite a feat as well , lemony and citric , a bounty of fruity hop qualities cover the tongue . finishes full and sweet , which at times is overwhelming , but usually very enjoyable . a very well crafted ipa , a very fine example of the modern style .  mouthfeel is creamy and full , very satisfying , but a little slick upfront and a little warming in the finish .

nice appearance . the dark copper-brown body is black until closer inspection and the head is sandy and healthy . it lasts nicely and leaves behind a fine lace .  the beer was recently purchase from belmont station so i know it 's not too old mouthfeel : medium body and medium to low carbonation overall : just and ok beer .
a - a massive pillowy head with no intent to subside sit over a very cloudy deep brown brew .  creamy feel . drying . nice . for some reason , this tastes like cheap mac and cheese .

the smell here is amazing , smells like a latte almost , roasted coffee and sweets mixed with roasted malts and oatmeal , the good sweets are definitely from the oatmeal . taste is almost the same , roasted malts and coffee , a bit of hops bitterness , a bit of sweets but then there is some weird watery taste that throws it all off but does not ruin the taste .  mouthfeel : refreshing .

smell- has a wonderful malty aroma with a very pleasant malt sweetness . the aroma is subtle but pleasing . taste- hoppier up front than the aroma would suggest .  and this is with some decent aging on it so the hops have had some time to calm down.. medium light bodied with lightish carbonation , this has a good mouthfeel .
pretty good ipa . very nice aroma , but the mouthfeel and maltiness could use more backbone .  good carbonation .

s - absolutely superb aroma . lactic acidity , funky brett , oak , red wine vinegar , hint of vanilla , a bit of sweet caramel malts - all of which are working in perfect balance . one of the beers that smells so good you feel guilty drinking it .  quite sweet with a fairly agreeable flavor until the finish which has a phenolic , chemical edge to it . the body has a nice fullness to it as well as a nice soft , chocolate tasting , roast grain flavor to it . this is newly arrived in arizona , so i do n't understand why this is so bad ; and to be honest the flavors of this beer seem pretty fresh , it is just that there are also some significantly off components to this beer as well .

loads of coffee , chocolate , vanilla . a really sweet smelling beer . behind the breakfast stout quality resides the rum barreling . its quite complex . lots of licorice and faint hops . t- very different . i have not had anything aged in rum barrels before . its a lighter , very sweet and acidic type of alcohol presence .  mouthfeel : the beer does have a pleasant body that is thick and chewy without making it a sipper beer . there is a definitely slick feeling to the beer which i would guess is from copious amounts of oat in the grist .
overall , good appearance , aroma , and blend .  m : tingly on the top and smooth and light going down .

appearance- with a color equivalent to a rich , fine cognac , the beer pours beautifully ... clear with a billowing , foamy head that fills as much of this glass as the beer itself . after many minutes , the clingy lacing drops off and settles to an uneven translucent map .  medium mouthfeel .

huge , insane , and inexplicably enjoyable . it sounds terrible , and yet i ca n't stop inhaling .  a friend of mine here in greensboro thinks this beer is the one all be all and shared a bottle with me sunday night.poured into a standard pint glass a deep clear amber/bronze with a half finger slight off white head atop , great clarity and hue to the beer.whoo man the aromas are borderline harsh , just wicked resin with a bit of caramel base but the hop onslaught is wicked in not such a good way.the 168 ibu 's is just overkill on the palate , its dry as all get out and bitter to the hilt , wicked pine resin and alcohol make you wan na grab a glass of water and chug it.iam a full on hophead but this is overkill to the umteenth degree , sorry brian i told ya i liked it but man that stuff is harsh .

the smell is what hop heads live for . it 's full of citris , piney and spicey hops . not much malt , just smooth high end hop flavors dancing throughout your nose . taste starts out wiht some caramel and hop notes , then turns into a blindingly bitter hop blast .  smooth and light bodied .

smell is very interesting , in a good way . very complex with sour notes and also a very typical belgian yeast aroma , not something i 'm used to in this style .  medium carbonation . smooth mouthfeel .
this smells absolutely amazing . t : pine resin and bready malts hit first .  mouthfeel is very creamy , almost like drinking foam . very pleasant .
amber color with an off white head . good head retention . smells bitter .  mouthfeel is nice . medium-bodied , but not mouth coating .

nose- potent - full on bourbon with rich roasted coffee and dark fruits . taste- bourbon is quite strong initially then warms up with oatmeal , vanilla and cofee flavours .  m - medium body with a nice hearty chew . light carbonation .

a- the head on this beer stood a full two inches over the rim of my pint glass , wow ! beautiful rocky , frothy tan head with some really extensive lacing that travels the whole length of the glass .  nicely balanced carbonation .

aroma is extremely sweet and nice smelling . extremely nice smelling - the cinnamon is very pleasing . it tastes pretty much how it smells - although sweeter , which is not a good thing .  the feel is light , sharp and very crispy , especially to start out .
s - sweet , warrior hops , candi sugar . this might not sound too extravagant , but believe me the scent is worthy of a 5.0 rating !  the spicing is nice on the medium body .

a : glowing amber in color with some brownish hues . lovely coat of creamy lacing at first , which fades to sticky rings further down the glass . one of the best looking beers i 've seen .  i did not enjoy this beer . purchased in bomber form , the beer poured nicely , but my hopes began to wane when i sniffed it . too much chocolate . the chocolate nose reminded me of chocolate syrup for lattes , which is never as good as hershey 's syrup -- which is n't very good . the taste was more offensive -- like someone dumped a bunch of flavoring into what could have been a good beer . well , someone did . although i did not like the strength of the chocolate , it was the synthetic characteristic that i could n't get past .
the beer has the look of true quality . really nice thick head .  full bodied with admirable carbonation .
poured clear gold with a huge , rocky white head that stuck around for a while .  the mouthfeel is really smooth but it reminds me too much of a banana beer i had a couple weeks ago .
smells excellent . pours black with mild head . looks good .  it 's crisp and sharp , not bold and complex . it looks good and feels good in your mouth .

nice strong hop aroma . after about five minutes i really started picking up the caramel malts . incredible aroma . top notch . the aroma on this beer is rediculous . could use a little less carbonation and a some more hops in the taste .  mouthfeel is solid ; ample carbonation , slightly dry on the finish , not overly resinous .

dynamite aroma . big hops , fresh , citrusy and spicy . some sweet malt in the background . some sweet malt and caramel in the middle , finishing with that spicy , pungent grapefruit aftertaste that i love sierra for . rich , full and a creamy lemon tanginess . excellent drinkability .  a very minimal white head is apparent with smile delicate lacing along the side of the glass . i 'm going to forgo my normal formulaic review to say very little else other than this beer is liquid pepper with a hint of ipa . it is very peppery and very smokey . i fear i may need to drink another beer to just put out the fire from this beer ! i ca n't say i like the taste of this beer . there is very little to taste other than just the pepper . i taste very little of my beloved ipa . i ca n't really find a reason or a purpose for this beer other than maybe a pepper or texas themed party . i 've had many other beers with hints of pepper and that 's all beer needs .

smell - ok this is the best thing . tons of hops smell , citric or pine smell . i think it is simeco hops . overall - this is the signature beer of jack 's abby .  palate was medium bodied , creamy , soft and lively carbonation , with light astringency . neither a beer nor a lambic really , just a monster of its own .

this beer poured a beautiful , crystal clear cherry brown with little clumps of off white head the left behind a few spots of lace .  had very fine carbonation . thick creamy mouthfeel , which was good .

this beer starts out nice . the mid-palate gets a little worse and then the finish is just plain poor .  decent body ... it 's a carbonation supported medium body which makes it clean and crisp like crunchy fall leaves . i like the mouthfeel , just not too much else .
it pours an amazing color . it is a peachy orange with the slightest hint of rose .  altogether a full taste though and with good and high carbonisation alltogether good mouthfeel .
i love it . taste : a mellow sweetness with a strong note of alchohol in the end .  good carbonation .
the nose makes it sexy , absolutely full of raisins and malts .  the mouthfeel is medium-full and creamy .
i was greeted with a massive rocky tan head , on a black pour looked like a dollop of ice cream on that baby .  the mouth feel is medium bodied with decent coating and weight .

wow , so much citrus in the nose . i do n't even have to get my nose close to the glass to smell aromas of grapefruit , tangerine , and orange . aroma is still fantastic . very hoppy and tropical .  m : the body is medium with medium to high carbonation .
smell : very good . as always i could be completely wrong but i smell banana , orange and maybe some lemon .  medium bodied , moderate carbonation .

poured a deep brown color with foamy brown head that faded somewhat quickly and left good lacing .  i bought a bottle of this as part of a mix a 6 from food & friends on 20th & spruce in philadelphia . i must have purchased a bad bottle , it was from batch # 9462 . the smell was there , it had an awesome coffee aroma to it that i was very excited for . until i tasted it . it tasted like a sour . i love sours , but not when i 'm expecting a coffee stout .

one finger of stark white head recedes leaving just a touch of soapy lace . the aroma is very fruity and sweet . lots of oranges and lemons . the flavor is quite a bit muted compared to the nose . all these flavors are very tame and fall rather flat .  medium mouthfeel .

s : lots of cherries , raisins and grapes and brandy . smelled a lot like fine tawny port . almost no smell of alcohol , despite being a pretty hefty 8 % abv . lots of complex , fruit esters make this beer a really sweet-smelling beer .  m- fairly thick with a good level of carbonation to keep it from getting syrupy . the alcohol is n't too noticeable , but the mouthfeel and overall heaviness of the beer limit its drinkability .

incredible aroma , sweet and very intense . t- the taste matches the aroma quite a bit . very sweet with a bitter dark chocolate finish . m- creamy and smooth , the malt flavors stick around in the back of the throat for a while , so it has a very long finish , which i prefer in a beer . d- very nice , a great sipper for any occasion , i would suggest this more as a dessert beer , but it could be paired with some great food as well .  m & d - the bottle says snappy and crisp . that 's right .

12 oz bottle from a goblet at 50 f appearance : very impressive . gorgeous dark brown with a subtle red hue if held to light . if poured fairly vigorously , a terrific head will develop . the carbonation is just enough to promote lacing without disturbing the beautiful islands of foam .  m : surprisingly pleasing . the citrus character refreshes the mouth and lasts until swallowed .
smell is out of this world . caramel & dark malts , scotch , peat , alcohol , hardwood , this is one of the best smelling beers i 've yet had .  mouthfeel was full bodied with medium carbonation .
a : vigorous pour gave me lots of haze on the yellow-orange body and a marshmallow fluff head .  notably full mouthfeel as well , but overall pretty bog standard ris offering .
an immense amount of light tan head that laces , a solid wall .  light body and medium carbonation , feels quite nice .

excellent aroma . t - malty ! it has an good flavor and a fantastic aroma though .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel was appealing to me in that it was malty but the slightly bitter hops kept your mouth dry and encouraged you to drink more of the beverage . a solid mouthfeel that acted upon the whole mouth interior .

no apparent freshness date a : clear , dark orange with a thick , meringue-like head that leaves thick lacing . a very attractive beer .  m- the carbonation actually mellows out nicely in this medium bodied beer . it 's creamy on the palate and i actually like the fact that a yeasty aspect develops as it warms up .

had a dark red hue that i could just barely see through s : smell was ridiculously awesome ! exactly what i think of as a peanut butter and jelly . she absolutely loved it and is begging for more already .  mouthfeel was nice and creamy . goes down smooth .

a amber body , one finger head poured into clear glass right from the tap . very pleasing , inviting appearance .  mouthfeel is smooth and maybe a little creamy , and i can see drinkability being decent with this beer . appearance : 3.5 smell : 3.0 taste : 3.0 mouthfeel : 4.0 drinkability : 3.0

s - caramel , molasses , brown sugar , cinnamon . very wintery . t - very bland next to the smell . this started off very promising , but this taste is just not doing it for me .  despite the finish , the mouthfeel is excellent . d : avoid .

two fingers of latte fall to a very thick quilt of the same . stubborn lacing . good looker .  it 's pretty good in the mouth , never really any sense of harshness and the head made every taste a little cremey like , so it was good .

nice appearance , but the smell totally grabbed my attention . one of the hoppiest , citrus , floral , spicy powerful aromas ever . the taste is also very hoppy with a finish that was almost too bitter for me .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and sharp on the tongue but is a bit creamier and smooth feeling on top , which helps this go down .
smells great though .  mouthfeel : the body is on the thick side of medium with mild , tingly carbonation and a finish that has just a touch of dryness to it .
this is a really good looking beer .  the mouthfeel was good balance body and bitterness .
a nice hazy honey-straw color with tons of fluffy off-white head and great lacing . unfortunately , this is the best thing about the beer .  m - medium coating with a tingle over entire tongue .

huge 4 finger or more head rises and hangs around for a very long time before falling to a thick cap .  the flavor does have raspberry hints but not what you would get from say an authentic framboise . this seemed like an amber ale with raspberry syrup added to it . the alcohol was noticeable which was strange for a 5.6 % brew . this was not bad but there was also nothing really good about this beer other than the appearance .

smells like a goddamn chocolate dipped banana . if i closed my eyes and you put this underneath my nose i would n't think it was beer , at first -- that 's how much it smells like a chocolate dipped banana . as it warms you can pick out some sweet and spicy yeast and just a hint of peppery wheatmalt , but the banana still runs the show . tastes very much like it smells .  medium bodied with a super creamy mouthfeel .

as soon as i cracked it open i smelled the hops . i could smell the oily resin of hops as i poured it . s - as state before this beer has an intense nose . sweet malty and alcoholic esters are immediately present as well as some nice oily and piney hops . very intense . extra sweet grapefruit citrus character .  m : thick and slightly syrupy . proper for the style .

the head soared up like most hefe 's but did n't quite have that big puffy marshmallowness i 'm used to seeing . s : first off you get that wheat tang kickin in high gear , but soon starts smelling of cloves , spices , and an unmistakable smell of banana bread . t : initially you get hit with a subtle sweetness , moves onto the spicy cloves taste just like aroma then transfers to the wheat tang with a bit of a metallic in the finish as well .  m : medium light body . well balanced carbonation . very smooth .
pours a nice deep orange/red . some floaties/carbonation . nice thick head with great lacing .  m : highly carbonated , crisp , refreshing , finishes the littlest bit dry .

a- nice head that sticks to the glass and slowly settles down with time to a thin layer of foam . this is really what beer should look like in my book .  a : pours copper colored with a bit of white head that disappears quickly and leaves just a halo and lacing s : big pumpkin smell , but it has too much of a buttery , biscuity taste , like a pie crust .

it smells like coffee , roasted nuts , and chocolate , giving the nose a great preparation for the taste . my first sip was a little over carbonated , but the second was perfect .  m : good mouthfeel on a reasonably full body .

s - this is really the standout aspect for me . smells of delicious citrus , grapefruit and tangerine , with nice hints of peach and maybe even mango ? really an excellent example of the style , though it does border on the hoppiness of a dipa ( which is a very good thing ) . i do n't really notice the malt backbone , though i would n't call it unbalanced , m - excellent . smooth with plenty of carbonation and a refreshingly bitter finish .  the body on this one is good , with a nice heft from the unfiltered body .

very nice russett with an enormous head that lingers .  the beer was way way harsh on the palate . you can taste a slight cherry taste ( from the lindemans kriek blended in ) as well as regular ommegang ale , which is nice , but the alcohol is n't hidden at all and the significant malt and yeast ca n't cover up the boozey flavors . the label says it 's ready for immediate consumption without aging , but i do n't agree . i was disappointed , especially considering how much i love ommegang , hennepin and rare vos .

pours a briliantly clear russet color with a massive fluffy off-white head that stays around 2 '' . beautiful bold rings of clingy lace all the way down . overall a great looking beer and then it goes down hill very steeply and quickly .  mouthfeel is pretty light bodied with nice dry , crisp and refreshing qualities . a session beer for sure .

the raspberry brings out chocolate in the aroma which i did n't notice much of in the old heathen .  hey , that happens from time to time ... ; ^ ) it has a good medium mouthfeel and the carbonation is on the light side of medium . bottom line : it 's worth a try but it 's not something that exactly grabs your attention .
appearance : pours a beautiful dark reddish amber with a finger of fluffy off white head . there is a decent amount of retention and some very nice lacing . pretty beer .  light carbonation .
a beautiful dark copper tone , with perfect head in my opinion .  m : a lot of co2 ( trippel ) pretty creamy

a : bright orange color , translucent , very appealing s : imagine shoving some hops up your nose , very floral , spicy smell t : initially very citrusy and spicy .  m- the mouthfeel is medium bodied with a good amount of carbonation .
a nice very dark opaque brown color with a finger widths of head .  m/d - medium bodied and very smooth/creamy . great feel to the beer , just not a great taste .

it 's a really good looking beer ; sediment noticeable .  big citric show . t & m- medium body , creamy smooth . maltiness rolls out a light maltiness middle to end . d- just for shits and giggles i tried this brew again ... sorry , game over . i love stone brewing but they went too far with the god damn hops ... and you know what hops i am talking about .

up to a bright light it 's a clear stunning red . great looking beer , perfect five .  mouthfeel is light bodied , with quite possibly a finish that is crisper than any other brew this ba had experienced . very intriguing .
awesome looking beer that compliments the season .  as the malt bill is substantial , this beer has a nice heavy body . the carbonation is moderate , and overall it has a nice feel .

absolutely love the smell . taste- lots of chocolate with a little coffee and roasted malts .  taste : smooth with a crisp malt and fullish mouth feel , herbal and almost tobacco like hop bitterness and flavour erupt in the mouth with a light juniper berry flavour . notes : not a bad brew at all though hops seem to over take the brew with an earthened hop flavour that may not be agreeable with some beer drinkers .
pours a deep dark brown brew .  the mouthfeel is good , almost crisp , but slightly heavy even for an imperial ipa the drikability is decent , but not great .
overall , this smells great , but is rather flavorless .  m - smooth , thick and a little refreshing .

clear , copper hue with visible carbonation topped by a thick off-white layer of foam that receded within a minute or two . fantastic smell of floral hops ( maybe some distant grapefruit ) and an underlying biscuit aroma .  m : thin-bodied and well carbonated ; crisp and dry .

pours an enchanting multi-colored , lively celebration of bubbles and foam . taste : cocoa powder , bitter chocolate , touch of alcohol ( sucked from inside a liqueured chocolate novelty ) .  first sip has the strong body you 'd expect from an english stout , but the positive impressions begin to dissolve when the taste coalesces into a bland , mild muddiness that lasts throughout the pint . unless you look for a beer on the basis of mouthfeel and consistency alone , there is little to be found in this blandsville brew .

very aromatic of flowers , honey , and bread with a tease of germanic hop ( ? ! overall very nice .  the mouthfeel is full bodied with moderate carbonation , and a smooth texture . overall , this is an average beer at best .

huge fluffy light tan head sets the tone for this one . pretty much black as night with really faded red hues on the edges , but only when held to the light .  tastes too spicy which throws this brew out of balance the mouth feel was great prickly carbonation lifting the sweetness , but not the spice , while creating a light mouth feel .

aroma is rich and smoky with coffee and molasses undertones . flavor is not as strong as other stouts i have tried but still pleasing - smoky with coffee undertones and a hint of molasses .  bobbb has a nice smoothness to it , courtesy of the wheat , and surprisingly has a decent amount of carbonation given the appearance .

the nose is fantastically sweet/malty . vanilla ad caramelize sugar immediately jump out at my nose , eventually making room for subtle bourbon and oak scents to show themselves and add a layer of complexity .  full bodied , it is incredibly sweet and unidimensional ; it is candy sweetness , then candy sweetness , and more sugar .
smells great . ( 5/5 ) ( t ) - amazing taste .  m - good , full body that goes down smoothly d - interesting beer for me .
a : this was a medium chestnut brown . it poured with a thick , clumpy , creamy , and sticky head .  m : creamy , smooth , a little syrupy maybe .
smell is primarily roasted malt with a huge whiff of dark fruit like raisins , hints of chocolate and some light spicing .  m : one of the thickest and most syrupy barleywines i 've tried .

s : strong pine aroma followed by the sweet tropical scent of guava . t & m : surprisingly dry with a heavy floral taste . d : overall , a good beer , but not half acre 's best , though i should probably blame that on short 's since i 've never been enamored with anything from that brewery .  pretty good on the mouthfeel .
pours a hazy golden yellow with lots of sudsy white head with great retention .  there is a really creamy feel and very small amount of carbonation .
s - 4.5 smells of barley wine . hmmm ... i love barley wine . t - 3.5 tastes like a spiced tripel first hit is belgian .  m - medium to full body beer . pretty thick .
a : jet black , large mocha colored head , reduced quickly . average lacing . this is the darkest porter i have seen .  mouthfeel : substantial , good on the tongue .

one inhale reveals one of the best smelling beers i 've ever encountered . it literally smells like pumpkin pie . delicious . taste is very pumpkiny and very spicy ... lots of nutmeg , cinnamon and brown sugar . just a little boozy burn on the tale to close the taste out . made for a pleasant autumnal sipper .  the mouthfeel was good , the body medium/full and the carbonation average .
nice and fragrant . i can smell some hops and malty character .  m - one of the better qualities of this brew . it was crisp and sharp .
cloudy with visible particulates and plenty of carbonation . spicy aroma .  m - medium body , slightly creamy with light carbonation .

the aroma has a distict pumpkin scent , with nutmeg and perhaps clove .  the mouthfeel is this beer 's only saving grace ( if i had to come up with one ) . very creamy and smooth with mild carbonation .

it smells like someone took grape nuts and threw some dark cherries in it . it is n't like the other fruit beers i have smelled , it has a bran scent with some lightly fruity cherries .  feel is actually pretty good , with some pleasant carbonation and texture .

s : juicy citrus hops that make me weak in the knees !  cold 22 oz bottle served in a straight-sided glass . the flavor is as promised by the nose , but the anise flavor is definitely more natural and less artificial/sweet/candyish . there 's also a definite funkiness to the licorice , which between the oak and the belgian yeast is no surprise . maybe if i really loved licorice this could be an ok thing , but sadly i 'm not a big fan .

this is a very pleasant smelling brew . taste is a bit of malt and spiciness from the hopping but not as strong as the scent .  not the usual cali ipa hop blast . m- went down smooth , crisp and refreshing . prob . this beer 's strongest asset , highly drinkable .

smell : raspberry puree dominates the aroma . addtionally , the flavor is not as endearing as the smell was . mouthfeel : medium to thin body , with lively carbonation and sensible raspberry flavor . the aroma was great , and perhaps misleading .  i really do enjoy the mouthfeel of guinness nitro . maybe one day my palette will become too sophisticated for nitro smoothness . i drank 8 pints without retching .

the aroma is where this beer begins to really score well . prune , wheat , black pepper and cloves dominate the nose . taste : carmel complements the cloves that were so dominate in the aroma . this beer 's relation to schneider weisse is pretty evident .  medium-light body ; crisp and more than semi-dry on the finish .
smell is a fantastic dark roasted and wood soaked dream . overall i really did enjoy this .  md thick body and moderate slightly creamy carbonation .

tons of lacing ... aroma is awesome , smells like crown , tons of sweet alcohol , wood , lots of vanilla ... the taste is still pretty sweet , oak and vanilla , but not as strong , after such a great aroma , a slight let down ... feel is silky smoth , light warmness just smoothness . worth seeking out .  taste is very bland , but the mouthfeel is surprisingly smooth . the best part of the beer actually .

s : astoundingly complex . bourbon , oak , lots of vanilla , chocolate , caramelized sugar , raisin , apple cinnamon and coconut . wow . t : the roasted sugar and chocolate appears first closely followed by vanilla and oak .  mouthfeel is heavy malt on the tongue . finishes crisp with a lingering hoppy bitterness and sweet malt on the lips .

sharp , citric cranberry aromas dominate nose . sweet , floral , slightly herbal and woody .  the mouthfeel is nice and creamy , but still there is that tannic wood in the background cutting against it . not very drinkable at all , like a beautiful cabernet that someone has oaked all to hell .

i poured it into an english pint glass and had to admire the visual effect of the beer . it was black with a hint of ruby color , and a much lighter head that was about 1/8 of an inch .  fairly pleasantly full mouthfeel actually with not a great deal of sizzle from the carbonation .

carefull with this one as it takes a gentle pour to get the desired look . big tan head that peaks in a mountain shape , sea foam texture , loose bubbles .  this was not a bad beer at all , merely average . it did have a good mouth feel but i was only able to drink one of them .
pours nicely - slightly opaque with ruby hilights and a good dense head .  m - thick with a slight carbonation tingle , goes down fairly smooth .
very rich . nice .  mouthfeel is nice - thick and creamy .

some malty sweetness , hints of a caramel malt - very nice . taste does n't deliver the complexity that the nose suggests , although this could be because the bottle is a few months old .  low to medium carbonation with a medium mouthfeel helps make this beer sort of drinkable for the style , i guess .

s : a wonderful blend of dark malty aromas and strong , lightly acidic , medium roasted coffee . the coffee smell is soft but dominates the aroma . if you are a coffee beer lover , this is where it 's at for coffee beer aroma .  my 1st flanders oud bruin that is obviously meant to be a sour beer . i love belgian brews and ommegang is my all time favorite brewery , but i guess i am just not cut out for ouds .

s- huge burst of orange , lemons , and grapefruits explodes from the receding head the citrus hop notes are big on this one . back notes of clingy caramel malts . t- leads with lightly flavored citrus sweetness of tangerines and orange rind , mid plate rolls through with little distinguishable notes . finishes with a really nice balance of lingering perfect sweet malts and kindly bitter citrus and herbal hops .  mouthfeel- medium body . good carbonation level .

very nice lacing smell : floral hoppy and reminescent of what made me start taking more notice of red ales earlier this year . very pleasing nose , this is as much a part of the experience as the taste where this beer is concerned mouth : very nice medium body , about what i expect from a well made red or amber ale . really drinkable and one that i will probably start getting growlers for myself when i visit .  the mouthfeel is decent , as the carbonation and spice tingles your tongue . pretty average witbier .

sinebrychoff- porter a- black , plain and simple , jet black . looks like a rootbeer float sorta .  dark malts had a stronger presence and the hops have only partially faded enough to be in perfect balance . carbonation is lively , i could tell immediately from the loud hiss as i opened the bottle .
this thing is really cool . 10oz pour color- cherry red this thing is bright red as it goes .  mouthfeel was creamy and light , with very high carbonation and very light feel .

, the unmistakable scent of wisconsin belgian red , i dont know if i should mark this down for not really having any stout characteristics in the nose , but should i really care ? wbr is one of the most heavenly scents on the planet , tart door county cherries t-again the base of this mainly consists of the wisconsin belgian red which is awesome in it 's own right , there is tart cherry skin , it 's slightly medicinal , maybe some chocolate and malt , but barely any to notice m-pretty darn light for a stout , almost watery honestly , has quite a bit of carbonation as well o-it 's pretty tasty , but not much going on in terms of being an actual stout , was happy i got to give it a try , but i will just have a wisconsin belgian red in the future  not what i 'd expect from an ipa m : feels crisp , not slimy .

s- i think this smells fantastic . blueberry , and more blueberry .  exciting . o : i think i prefer this slightly to duchesse du bourgogne , but only slightly - both are unnecessarily sweet and lacking in genuine complexity .
wonderful smell nutty and banana ... but its not sweet and its very light .  mouthfeel : the body is on the thicker side with tingly carbonation and a dry finish .
pours dark ! this has the best head retention of any ris i 've ever seen .  buttery aftertaste and mouthfeel is a big plus , but the way the alcohol overwhelms the flavor is mildly disappointing .
the taste was n't as great as the aroma but was still very enjoyable . it was n't too sweet , but had an incredible vanilla , creamy flavor to it .  m = thick and malty d = glad to be sharing it .
s - great hop aroma , it smells awesome ! t - good bitter taste .  m - creamy , full , minimal carbonation , which would make sense as this is naturally carbonated .

smell of bourbon , oak , chocolate , coffee and booze . taste of intense booze , corn mash bourbon , caramelized sugars , vanilla , oak barrel aging , and booze .  the smooth feel of the liquid and its medium-hevay mouthfeel bring hope , as does a dark chocolate aftertaste .

on the palate , the beer is nearly as outrageous , with the flavor profile showcasing plenty of chocolate , vanilla and coffee , with a fairly long , hoppy , dry finish . nevertheless , this moderately sweet stout is quite impressive . mouthfeel is fairly full , with long , dry , bitter finish . nevertheless , this is a very impressive stout from rogue .  mouthfeel is light with a good amount of carbonation .
the aromas are rich . inviting warm fresh baked bread malt .  m - good carb , medium body d - for this style i feel it 's a little on the weak side , that being said it still is a pretty tasty brew .

poured a deep chesnut brown with a half finger off white head that is quick to vanish leaving no lace bhind.a nice mix of roasted chesnut , dark fruit , and leafy hop in the nose , everything seems to meld well together.there are some good malt accented flavors but it seems to be missing something , roasted nuts along with some raisin flavors start out well , but it seems to have an abrubt ending , not as chewey as i would like either.its not a bad bock beer , it just needs something in the finish to make it complete .  m - good mouthfeel . again , the abv content is well hidden in the mouthfeel .

the nose is very nice , and it 's noticeable as soon as it 's poured .  a cheap porter is like a bad shortcut : seems like a good idea at first , until suddenly you find yourself in a swamp of murky flavors and wish youd taken the trouble of keeping to a more sure-footed path . the mouthfeel is plump and has good roll , and lace makes a solid appearance . the best thing i can think of to do with this beer is take the label off and tell your friends you brewed it yourself .

s : mmmm . beautiful malts help accentuate the herbal , piney , resinous hop profiles . the nose reminds me of a really good red ale , not really so much a pale , but i ai n't a hater . allowance for the hops to shine , provide the bitterness and balance i anticipated in the nose . there 's a woodiness and oaky profiling that nearly dominate the entire palate experience .  medium/light mouthfeel .

poured into a tulip glass from a 750 ml corked bottle . the beer is a dark brown , with a substantial , active , light brown head that leaves noticeable lacing . beautiful beer !  mouthfeel is very thick and chewy , like drinking syrup .

lots of oranges and reds mixed in with a dusky brown color , the head is absolutely gorgeous and tinted orange . the lace is fantastic and three-dimensional in most place .  mouthfeel : light in bodied . clean aftertaste .

after the appealing appearance , we get the mesmerizing aroma . fragrant with dark smoky malts from over a foot away : i ca n't wait to taste this one !  mouthfeel is thickish and syrupy with decent carb .

a soft pale brown head clings to the glass nicely , but the nose explodes with caramel and malt before you can even get your lips to the rim . sweet and creamy , the flavors roll over the palate and open up tremendously as the glass warms , with huge notes of caramel , along with banana , almond , raisin and a light bitter bite in the back of the tongue .  surprisingly , mouthfeel is quite lush and the carbonation pretty on for a beer that probably co2 injected .

bottle poured into a tall tulip glass a : hard pour produces a beautiful deep burnt orange & blood red sunset color , with 3-finger rocky , dirty white head . lots of lacing left behind .  the carbonation is low and there is a somewhat smooth mouthfeel to the beer .
clove , banana , yeast . all together it was a great mild scent of fresh banana nut loaf . it is very good .  the feel of this beer is very pleasant and should be applauded .

glowing hazy apricot straw in color . strong weisse beer smell , a little bit of spicy malty fruit . i love the aroma , but the lack of carbonation kelled the appearance and mouthfeel .  mouthfeel : smooth , medium-bodied mouthfeel . also a little zing from the carbonation .
pours with a five finger off-white head leaving a good lace . nice crystal clear amber color .  the mouthfeel is creamy and slick , the drinkability is just not there .
color is hazy golden with a ton of fluffy , pillowy foam that sticks to the glass .  milkshake-like texture . it was smooth . so smooth that it lacked character .
smells awesome . slight sulfur , tastes kind of like flowers . i think it smells better than it tastes .  mouthfeel is nice , full , creamy , and not too carbonated . its pretty good .

the smell is hops ! it was like i took a piece of dried hops and rubbed it in my hand then smelled it .  classic winter warmer m - medium body with medium carbonation d - ok. easy to drink but only kind of enjoyable
intriguing . taste : hmmm , it kind of tastes like seltzer water in a way that only michelob ultra has before .  mouthfeel , on the other hand , i would actually say is good .

huge fruity hops scent hits you in the face . lots of grapefruit and other citrus scents . taste- ummm , mind ale this is not . mouthfeel- damn this one had the great flavor , but it was really watery . not to the point of being bad , but it would have been so much better , maybe even a `` 5 '' taste better if it had just a bit more backbone . drinkability- even with the watery aspect , it 's still a very good beer that i would definitely buy again in the future .  the mouthfeel was also really quite nice , a moderate body that is not at all cloying like the imperials can often be .

giant tan , rocky and creamy head that was fully lasting . the lacing was phenomenal .  m : medium-full and well carbonated d : this beer nicely fits the characteristics appropriate for abbey beers , but is lacking in intensity ( as compared with other classic examples ) .
pours an intense pitch perfect black with an incredible chocolate head that is a sight on the initial pour , though is less and less for future pours .  mouthfeel is medium with good carbonation .

the alcohol is present but smells calm and enjoyable . taste and mouthfeel : the taste is oddly dull . for such a great smelling beer i 'm let down .  `` sampled '' this beer at the saratoga brewery ... .they have an odd practice of selling you the glass and then pouring you 2 `` sample beers '' - clever ! the flavour is more of the same - very light on the palette , and extremely refreshing for a 6 % beer .

just incredibly nice overall .  the body is full . the taste is truly well balanced , to the point of being bland . it does have some hop like aftertaste which is very surprizing and adds a small bit of character to which this brew is in need of .

wonderful punget hoppy aroma . the aroma almost dares you and invites you at the same time . taste is much like the elder . hops are more agressive and the alchohol is more noticable in the finish .  mouthfeel was fine .

the aroma is a sweet orange and grapefruit thats candied from the fruity yeast and sugary malt aromas . makes me think of a northwestern ipa and a belgian dark ale in aroma .  the feel is good . slightly heavy but not too bad . has some carbonation present .

smell - 5.0 amazing aromatics - pine needles and citrus fruits ( orange , lemon , grapefruit , all of them ! excellent . drinkability - 4.0 a brilliant , light summer drink , but powerful enough to drink in the colder months too .  mouthfeel is good and creamy . very oily and probably lots of dry hopping on this one .

the aroma ingratiates itself immediately after popping the bottle cap , and it 's wonderful : sweet , roasty , with maple syrup and nut flavors . in fact , a little more blossoming flavor would be welcome here , as the end result is squeaky clean , even a bit watery . a very pleasing beer and one of the best american browns to have wide availability .  again , mouthfeel is smooth and rich , a real revelation , actually , but i would n't want to drink more than a thimbleful of this in a sitting .

smell is super hoppy , citrus galore , very pungent and fresh , some sweet caramel .  m - full-bodied and refreshingly crisp in carbonation d - i 'll drink the 6-pack over a few nights , but i 'm rather disappointed in the brew .

s : amazing scent of dark fruits and molasses , with a chocolate and bourbon finish that smacks of a fine dessert . t : rich chocolate cake and bourbon filled dark chocolate .  a-light brown body with an off white head s-citrusy , grapefruit t-firm malt front , hoppy but not overwhelming m-light-medium mouthfeel d-not very assertive for this style but all styles have a range and this is on the weak end of the assertive flavor scale
the smell was overwhelmingly minty .  mouth feel is smooth and clean , with a low carbonation level . overall , poor appearance , but good aroma , feel , and body .

aromas are really fruity ; raspberry , light cherry , sour funk start things off . the tastes are equally as impressive as the nose . a balanced light pale sweet malt flavor coupled with a great deal of tart berry fruitiness .  cereal . this is an old school ipa , so i was not expecting a hop bomb . some hop bitterness . smooth and refreshing .

pours black into a pint glass out of a nitro can , with a beautiful , pillowy , off-white head , with great retention and leaving prodigious lacing .  the mouthfeel works for me . it has a nice thickness to it with a fairly substantial amount of felt carbonation .

a=frothy foam and rich dark brown color ... very inviting .  the taste unfortunately got skewed right away as the butteriness of this brew superceded any and all other flavors . the feel was medium/full and creamy .
s - great aroma . smells very fresh . t - disappointing taking from the nose .  body is right , but finish is somewhat boozy .

aroma : nice caramel maltiness , oaky aroma with some peppery/spicy yeasty notes . this has a lovely , woody aroma . very complex aroma , gets almost perfumey as it warms . raisiny maltiness with a subtle vanilla flavor that is very pleasing . the flavor also gains perfumey notes as it warms , very nice flavor , very complex like the aroma . mouthfeel : some alcohol warmth , creamy mouthfeel . overall : excellent beer , one of the best i 've had in a while . very complex , wish i had a few more bottles of this stuff ! ! very easy drinking with a good oaked/vanilla character in the nose and flavor that remains throughout and makes it a pleasure to drink .  m : feels refreshing , average carbonation .

pretty complex and pretty hoppy . carbonation is about right ... has a creamy feel but also some citrus notes that lend a little acidity ... booze is pretty hidden for 9.6 % overall i love the nose on this ... and the taste is pretty unique if not particularly memorable .  the feel was very creamy .

smell : spicy , spruce and pumpernickel , some peppermint and a cattyness that i 've detected before in some english brews , but that was from the hops , and i 'm not even sure this beer had hops at all . intriguing ! taste : mid carbonation , which may not be totally true to style but a thumbs up from me , the spruce beer and herbal taste comes clean .  consumed 12/03/07 at crown city brewing , pasadena . creamy nitro texture . then , unexpected black coffee bitterness appears on tongue long after beer is gone .
insane lacing & very good head retention s : slight iron & chocolate notes t : a little iron up front , then some roasted malts .  mouthfeel - nice round feel , good carbonation .
golden yellow color with a perfect small bubble head . lots of lacing .  mouth feel : the mouthfeel is quite smooth and full for the style .
the aroma is deep , unique and crazy . the oak aging certainly plays front and center .  mouthfeel is light body and there is lots of nice carbonation .

the nose on this beer is huge ! it almost smells like welch 's juice . the wheat is present only on the finish by scratching the back of my tongue .  m - kind of a lingering bitter finish . fairly full bodied with moderate carbonation .
smell is of dark roasted malts . chocolate and coffee lead the pack .  mouthfeel : lower than average carbonation , good for a stout . body is very good .
the beer pours inky black with an absurdly large head . really amazing .  m- there is a creamy medium-full mouthfeel with a mellow alcohol heat and soft fizz in the finish .

the appearance of this beer is simply spectacular . the head is firm , thick , long-lasting , and glowing-white . it sits atop a cloudy , milky , yellow liquid .  in the mouth , it was rather solid , having a nice creamy feel with lively carbonation .

12oz bottle into tulip glass appearance : light amber colored , slightly hazy , finger and half of cream colored head . lots of carbonation off the bottom aroma : spicy aroma , little bit of banana and orange .  the mouthfeel is pretty solid . medium bodied , decent carbonation , moderately sticky .

tall frothy tan head that does not want to go anywhere . large chunks of lace stick to the glass . color is a deep dark brown that is almost black .  the body is light and it goes down with an easy dryness .
smells awesome . it was a great smelling beer .  m - lightly carbonated . creamy all in the mouth , and finishes wet .
aroma very nice . very big on raspberries .  m - medium-full body , lower carbonation , a slightly grainy texture , with light residual stickiness .
app - opaque color , pours a big tan head that is creamy and long lasting .  the feel is actually nice , with a moderate thickness and a moderate carbonation .
