appearance - jet black with about two fingers worth of thick creamy tan foam .  the beer is smooth and clean . chewy malts and a lot of spice with an aftertaste i 'm not to fond of .

reddish brown . it looks like a bit of a beer that has made the cellar for a few years too . the finish is heavy in this style of ripe red wine which gives it a blood flavor , slightly sweet but it is not the level of beer that quickly reveals itself still disgusting .  it has a rich , creamy mouthfeel , but not a lot of taste .

22oz in my piraat snifter i thought this was one of the best pumpkin beers that i have ever tasted . it poured golden to copper and had a huge nose of nutmeg and spice . i did not find it terribly sweet but like a pumpkin cookie . i think it hides the 9 % abv very well not hot at all .  very soft bottle-conditioned carbonation gives a sliky mouthfeel .

smell is an amalgam of a whole bunch of things . sweet pale malts , grassy aromas , nice sweet citrusy orange notes , and a bit of apricot in the background . taste is not as impressive as the smell . heavier on the grassy hops , the apricot and citrus are there , but not as prominent .  fairly thick in your mouth , but again does n't get to a level where it is a bad thing .
the aroma on this beer is amazing . i smelled strawberry pop-tarts and graham crackers more than anything .  medium-full body with a smooth low-mid carbonation .

this is the best nose i have ever gotten from a beer . all the hop varieties they speak of are there . the sweet malt backbone was an afterthought . hop juice in a glass .  mouthfeel is thin to medium bodied with a gentle carbonation tingle .

tasted at the brewery itself , it gives off a a great blueberry aroma . if you have a lady friend in your life that does not like beer , have her give this one a shot .  mouthfeel : clean and refreshing . just barely medium body .

poured black with a huge two finger light tan head . fantastic head retention with tons of sticky lacing coating the glass after the head diminished some . a beautiful beer . incredible aromas from this beer .  medium carbonation feel .

slightly hazed deep honey amber with an inch-high head that lingers very long and leaves dimples and oily rings around the insides of the glass . aroma of brown sugar , ripe fruit , cinnamon and grapefruit . flavor initially of honey malt , some alcohol vapor , grapefruit pith , some grassiness , touch of mint , and some woody notes , almost a hint of smoke .  pretty creamy mouthfeel with low carbonation the drinkability is below average in my opinion .
pours a solid black that does n't let any light through .  good mouthfeel , almost sticky for the style .
the nose was a very promising sweet malt aroma with some peat smoke on the bottom .  mouthfeel was good , with a lighter body and decent carbonation .
s - an rich inviting mix of dark fruit , bready maltiness & light spices . t - a molasses sweetness tends to dominate the taste .  medium body and carb .
thanks for the opportunity ... poured into an imperial pint glass , formed a 1/2 '' thick tan head above the clear brown brew .  medium-high carbonation .
i poured it into a pint glass and was very much impressed with the red orange color along with a 1 finger or so bright white head .  m : medium body , smooth carbonation , dry finish but off a bit .
a great smelling beer . a bit too sweet for me .  m : great carbonation that rolls and pops along the tongue , light bodied for an ipa but still finds a nice balance between smooth and textured .
this might all be fake aroma but it is still pretty good .  nice mouthfeel though !
s : smell is very good . sweet for an ipa .  there 's a hop mouthfeel , like a ghost of hops , but no real bitterness or flavor .
a - copper colored with a nice lacey white head . looks great .  healthy carbonation lends a slightly acidity to the mouthfeel .
smell of very nice hops .  mouthfeel was smooth , of medium body and carbonation .

smell ... like sticking your head into a basket of fresh peaches . incredible . hint of sourness , but it 's all about the fresh peaches here . carbonation is appropriately high , lifting the beer off the tongue and keeping it from being cloying .  good carbonation and `` easy to drink '' .

the best smell ever . t & # 8211 ; very dry and bitter , like cuban coffee . m & # 8211 ; it is big , salty , astringent , and exceptionally dynamic . challenging but good . d - obviously not one to bust out for a day at the beach , but it is real good so it is real drinkable .  mouthfeel is good and full with a coated feel , which in this case only spreads the unpleasant taste .

smell : juicy citrus and a big helping of biscuit malt . deliciously fresh and delicate . little bit of resin and bread crust . nice level of balance . taste : grapefruit and orange flesh . nice sweetness coupled with an almost straight bitterness . the fresh hop nature is assertive .  d - good carbonation .

s - the aroma is amazingly complex and inviting . its base is the super-hoppy , grapefruit smell of a classic west coast ipa . on top of that is the spicy wood aroma of a fine cigar box and a whiff of alcohol . the flavor and aroma are among the most complex and interesting i 've ever had .  medium-light body with moderate carbonation .

smell is amazing . holy crap ! smell was better . the good qualities of uber and soft combine nicely , but the bad qualities of each are just too much . complex but flawed .  `` rum is the power , rum is the key . rum is the thing that will set us all free . '' rum , by alestorm color fade of tawny , to sepia to deep hazelnut . black cherry . rum opens up a bit more as it sits . tastes like dark fruit , especially black cherry . again , woody . not much rum , maybe a little rum spice . i was expecting more rum . captain morgan , himself a scot , would be ashamed .

s roasted malts . strong oak characteristics dominate . complexity is not as deminsional as its smell . kind of boozey with an odd burn .  some chocolate malt throught he middle , but mostly this is just a big hop bomb of an imperial ... or what i like to call an ipa/stout . i can appreciate that some people like hoppy beers , but when i pay $ 18 for an imperial stout and all i get is a dark ipa it irks ne ... whatever . perhaps with age this could become a solid brew , but right now this is just a hopped up mess and has next to none of the flavors youd expect in an imperial stout .

wonderfully malty aroma is blended with sweet fruitiness and mild alcohol notes .  taste - some nice stoutish flavor , but the insecticide was too much mouthfeel was nice for an impy stout but my focus was drown away overall - somehow i finished this .

thick , slick , and hot the way a young barley wine should be . amazing overall , though i feel i am tasting too much barrel and not enough beer .  it does posses a nice mouthfeel , as stated , crisp , but not overwhelming .

s wonderful expression of soft , bready malts and fresh rich ginger without the bite . m light , dry , and refreshing . good carbonation , and notable substance . pangaeas aroma is incredible , and the concept insprirational . unfortunately the flavor profile looses the potency promised by the nose , but it remains a delicious summer swigger all the same .  medium-light bodied , creamy , and well carbonated .

alcohol , plum , roasted malts , and sweet yeast aromas . good meld of aromas and flavors though the roasted and hop flavors are a little high so it may benefit from some aging .  mouthfeel is medium with good carbonation .
whoa , very atypical aroma , with raspberry and strawberry scents as well as coriander and licorice .  nice mouthfeel ... medium-full and very satisfying .
s = cinnamon and peppery scents of peaty malts , with a fresh yeast kick thrown in , dark ripe fruits , pretty good smells .  good mouthfeel though ; again , fine bubbles and good carbonation .

s - lots of sweet malt and caramel with a hint of toasted grain . the malt character is excellent , especially in the aroma . the flavor is a bit weaker , but still nice .  mouthfeel - i do like the texture . this beer has a nice body , and the carbonation leaves a little zing on the tongue at the finish .

excellent balance of nuttiness , malt sweetness , spice , yeast , and a hint of alcohol thrown in .  the sweetness punches you in the mouth , maybe a bit too brute . the hops come out much stronger in the taste . i would say the body is light to moderate , with a smooth feel and strong finish . it is not the best tripel i have had , but it certainly is not the worst . the crafting of the beer is a bit sloppy in that i think the sweetness is too strong and the 10 % is not hidden as well as it could be .

the aroma was intense . toasted oats and a distinct powdery yeastiness came through strong . although the aroma of this beer was really terrific , both the taste and the mouthfeel were disappointing .  mouthfeel : this was great .
rich amber in colour with a decent head .  m - medium body and moderate carbonation .

nose is exceptional . deep dark chocolate , a touch of cream , and hints of ground coffee . wow ... this really does smell wonderful . surprisingly bitter tasting and kind of harsh .  medium body feel with a clean feel and finish .
nice glowing crystal clear amber with a massive sticky white head that melts to very heavy lacing .  mouthfeel is full . finish is dry .

smell - lots of fruity esters , some orange , and candy sugar . a slight yeasty smell and a bit of alcohol . however there really is n't as much depth beneath it as would be expected from the smell . some esters , raisins , a little coriander , a good bit of bitterness from hops at the end .  the palate is medium and wet , probably the best part of the beer .

cleared a bit , some head retention & lacing s : apple peels , straw , pears & general orchard smells , plus juicy fruit gum t : bartlett pear , a touch of green banana , & juicy fruit along with grapefruit & grassyness up front . finishes a bit tart , grassy & lemony , with a kiss of warming booze the last 3 ozes or so mf : light/medium bodied , medium carbonation , really good balance for the style drank really easy for the style , an approachable , yet fairly complex take on the style that is session worthy , when many others are just too damn potent .  the feel is light to moderate with plenty of fizzy carbonation . nice crisp lager .

color is a really interesting - bordering on brown and red , it feels like an optical allusion , changing colors as you look at it trying to decide the color .  surprisingly a soft and creamy mouthfeel .
pours a hazy orange with a nice fluffy white head that leaves lacing down the glass .  m= sooo fizzy and light .

love the nose . minty , fragrant , orangey , definitely sweet , a little lime . lots of stuff and it all works together perfectly . the mouthfeel is slightly prickly . good take on a saision .  it 's a struggle for me to judge this beer as obviously a lot of craft went into it 's production , and yet i have to acknowledge that it makes me want to vomit . i will qualify all of this by saying that i hate eggs because i can not bare the sulphurous stink that i experience when they are cooked in any form . it get 's easier with each swallow but to me this tastes like someone is pouring a skunky heineken down my throat just after i 've had a swig of a very nice brew .
this beer pours a incredibly brilliant , deep , true red .  good mouthfeel .
beautiful pour of hefe-weizen like cloudy golden color .  m - good carbonation , fairly large amount of bubbles .
perfect scent , just as a wit should be .  m/f - nicely carbonated and creamy . medium body . pretty nice m/f .

the beer poured into the glass pitch black like motor oil with a tan and frothy head which rose tall and fell slowly to coat the glass in a tan foam .  m : highly astringent - to the point of physical puckering and spine tingling . medium body , which is nice , and the carbonation is decent for the style .

the aroma is sweet and juicy with a big whiff of clementine oranges , lemon zest , and rock candy . quite drinkable , but sadly , the aroma wrote a check that the taste could n't cash .  mouthfeel is exactly what i would want from a porter .

the smell is huge fresh hoppy goodness , big citrus , juniper and mango . the flavor is suprisingly balanced after the big one dimensional smell . very solid ipa .  mouthfeel - nice and crisp on the mouth . good carbonation .

the cold totally wrecked the smell and flavor of the beer . smell : this is truly where this beer shines . this beer is a spicy bomb of cinnamon , nutmeg , and all spice . this combines with a tart cherry and apple pie fruityness . taste : this delivers almost perfectly on the smell . is this wine or beer ? the beer has a well balanced sweet and tart combonation that compliments the spice bill . the smell wakes up to perfection . i think the flavor suffered when mulled .  best flavor description i can garner is tonic water with added salty . crisp but full in body .
poured into tulip . lots of head that stays around , becomes rocky .  medium bodied and relatively smooth .

the smell is amazing , a floral , citrusy aroma - that smells like hops ... if you 've ever had a handful of hop pellets - that 's what it smells like .  the mouthfeel was good . it was perfectly carbonated , mouthcoathig , and you can feel the head with the swallow ( innuendo ? ) .
white pillowy head with great retention and lacing .  creamy mouthfeel , soft and lazy on the tongue . the best part of the beer .
scant lacing at the top of the glass s : wow , that 's a pretty potent bourbon smell .  mouthfeel is full and round .
pours a very dark brown with a gorgeous red tint around the edges . very pretty .  carbonation and feel were quite nice , but the taste just seemed to be lacking .

from a wheat beer i would expect a little more in terms of head volume but the consistency is creamy and displays good retention and lacing . smell : deliciously spot on ; huge notes of banana nut bread ooze from the glass . drinkability : i think this beer is perfectly delicious on any occasion and has all the makings of a repeat offender .  strange brew this one . very fine carbonation makes it way up from the bottom of the glass . taste is hard to describe , initial thoughts were that it was like a combination of beer and white grape juice . in fact , that thought still persists so that 's how i 'll describe it .
smells incredible , smells a lot of grapes , not so much grapefruit but grapes and citrus .  m - smooth , thin , extremely refreshing .
copper , slightly hazy , with a dense off-white head .  mf : nicely coarse until the finish - exactly the opposite balance in texture of what it ought to be .

amazing amounts of that belgian yeasty aroma . the aroma is perfect . t : this is the only place that may be able to have some improvement . d : excellent . easy to drink and enjoyable to the last drop .  the mouthfeel is smooth .

in any event , there 's suave orange , tangerine , lemon citrus spray , a biscuit and scone breadiness , well blended banana , pineapple , peach , nectarine , yellow apple , cherry fruit scents , no clearly dominant force , no real chocolate but the coriander , cumin spice sweet enough to cover , clean with nary a trace of funk . if you can acclimate to the level of carbonation you 'll find that it is a fairly dry beer with good outline and length . ambitious beer .  nice mouthfeel is slightly thick and fitting . moderate carbonation also fits with the taste of the beer and style ideal .
a picture of perfection .  they get knocked on appearance 'cause it 's too carbonated but that very same extra carbonation helps greatly with the mouthfeel .

paid $ 6.99 for the mixed brewmaster 6-pack ... the beer pours a clear amber colored base , with a light off colored white head , 1/4 '' head retention for the full hour consumed and a nice cascading effect with the lacing , this one looks perfect , like a guinness .  m : well carbonated with small bubbles that mostly blend together as soon as they hit your mouth .

s : smells beautiful . sweet chocolate and cocoa slightly toasted . very enjoyable porter .  it formed thick coagulated mats of dense foam and left incredible lacing on the inside of the glass . medium-light body ( but creamy smooth ) and moderately carbonated .

a : pours a pitch black color with a two-plus head which is tan in color . great retention . very impressed with the carbonation level after 2 years of cellaring .  mouthfeel is very good , full and interesting as it explores . its growl is far worse than its bite .

spicey yeast aroma is great . cloudy yellow with substantial lace . good belgium strong and good break from so many other chocolate and coffee ales .  mouthfeel : lighter body with medium carbonation and a crisp , refreshing finish .
s- has a very pleasant citrus/orange smell with a hint of malts .  mouthfeel : very clean and crips , slightly bitter that lies with the high carbonation , light body .

a- conservative pour creates a massive head , i 'm talking like 3 fingers of beer and 4 fingers of head . the beer is an incredible coppery honey bronze color .  mouthfeel is slightly thick and slick with a little hint of carbonation tingle .

2004 vintage appearance : the bottle is definitely the best thing about this beer . as far as the beer itself , it 's a dirty brown color with almost no light getting through .  aroma was pale malt and a weird kind of `` synthetic funk '' . it literally tasted like sugar water . there is a great carbonation in this beer which made it drinkable , but none of the great flavors of a true saison are present .

i can smell this from a full two feet away . yes , the hops are there with loads of juicy citrus , earth and leaves with a good spicy kick at the back end . what impresses me the most , though , is the major malt-presence in this nose . sweet , bready and buiscuity all together , this shows a real balance that 3f 's sometimes eschews in favor of beating you up . tropical fruit comes up next . sorry , but this is n't a double/imperial ipa because it is completely unique . the lactose demands a seperate category . you invent the style , you get the highest score !  nice medium full body ( the only thing i really liked about this one ) .
smell was good blend of hops of fruity sweetness .  m : the body is medium with a medium to high carbonation .
very nice ! t : dominant taste of toasted black malt paired with unsweetened chocolate and coffee .  m. medium creamy .

a sweet , citrusy , floral aroma . leaves nearly no lacing on the inside of the glass . overall : a very interesting brew , especially considering the recipe .  the first sip reveals a light crisp body with mild rolling carbonation .

s- the aroma of this beer reminds me of my grandmothers strawberry preserves . citrus and peppery coriander tickle my nose providing a supreme resting spot for strawberries . this beer would pair wonderfully with dessert .  aroma is dominated by belgian yeast , citrus peels and coriander . the hops give salvation an earthy , herbal profile and it meshes well with the big yeast backing . tastes notes are honey , apricot , overripe banana , coriander , belgian yeast and light candi sugar . probably too much candi sugar . overall a good beer but still far from the best examples .

luscious , lingering tan head with plenty of lace . you can get lost in the smell of this beer . the initial abv sting soon passes , followed by lots of malt , then a barrage of fruity , hoppy and even smokey elements .  on tap at rackhouse , i had high hopes considering this was made with wet hops and colorado peaches but i was let down because they were so subtle . smells like a touch of yeast and nit a single hop to be found . flavor had a very , very light peach note but i prefer more . i honestly could not taste the hops at all . this was not a good saison unfortunately nor was it a good introduction to denver beer co .

smell : chocolate , roasted grains , some notes of barley , a sprinkling of vanilla , and peek or two of coffee . this is a yummy smelling brown ale .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied . moderate carbonation .
this beer poured a beautiful clear amber color with a thick head .  mouthfeel is certainly damaged by the high level of carbonation .
pour is a beautiful jet black , but that seems to be the best quality of the beer .  mouthfeel : thin ... has a flat soda feel to it at times .
looks really nice .  carbonation is very weak and it makes the body feel thin and watery .
a - pours a deep black with brown twinges on the edges . the head is big and brown , yet my only gripe is the length of time it stays around .  mouthfeel is very thin almost watery .

rogue 's 2002 x-mas offering pours a wonderful chestnut orange with a tan head . poured into a tulip glass i could sniff this all night long .  the mouthfeel is too thin , though heavy and oily , and somewhat under-carbonated .

a- pours a sunset orangey red hue with a nice , 2 finger frothy head which leaves a ton of lacing on the way down .  taste-very thin and watery . overall-10.1 % abv and very watery , very light flavor profile .

pours a jet black , with a thin tan head .  on tap at rb ... this pours a super dark gold straw but its still very clear ... the head is totally dead , nothing at all there ... the taste is also super light , ca n't taste anything but light skunk . its not bad per se just boring , why drink this ? overall , an easy session beer but nothing special .

it 's got a great big head , a slightly hazy honey colored body , lots of activity , a little sticky lacing .  m & t - flat , no life to this at all and thin were my first impressions . really no carbonation and slick and oily in feel .
lovely cascading black body out of the cask . forms a mousse-like head that never really fades .  m & d : light , almost watery mouthfeel .

canned 3.11.11 ... poured into goblet a- pours very dark brownish amber color with mahogany corners . very large tan crema head , light , fluffy , stable ... incredible lacing s- very sweet burnt sugar and the obvious coffee aroma is present , but a bit dull and approaching stale .  mouthfeel : here 's were things go wrong ; this beer is very , very watery . it so hoppy and yet it sort of feels like you are drinking water .

a - pours with a nice large off-white foam that features good retention and splotchy lace . the body is a hazed golden color .  especially the mouthfeel which hurts the overall picture . the mouth is weird it gives the impression that the carbonation is n't really there which in turn makes the flavors get lost and just ooze to quickly over the palate .

pours a rich black color with a gorgeous white and creamy , foamy head that just sits on top and waits , and waits and remains clinging to the bottom of the pint glass even when it is gone . plenty of lacing sticks around as well , and the foamy head is present at every sip .  mouthfeel is the biggest fault here . it is light , fizzy , and lacks enough body to support the bitterness which means this brown ale is not the one thing every brown sould be , smooooth .

new from saranac and from time to time , they do a great job . appearance - pours a medium amber with a nice frothy head .  however , this is very thin , making this taste rather stale . this beer is light in body , moderately carbonated and a little watery to boot .

pitch black and cant see through it . hugh amount of caramel colored head , thick and milkshakey , as it settled it went to just some large bubbles . bittersweet chocoloate , dark coffe . very good stout , highly enjoyable .  not much to it really , kinda thin .

gun smoke from the cork , then out pours a high viscosity black mass , could cause thermal break-down . large dark brown mass of a bubbly head emerges from the depths .  it was very light on the mouth and too watery .

it pours a ruby-tinged teak . a solid beige head sits on top and takes its sweet time fading . lots of webs of lace mark your progress as you drink .  feel : it honestly feels like a light fizzy water with a bit of prickly sensation , not all that enjoyable really . it has a nice flavor , but it does n't work well with the thickness or the level of carbonation and it really makes it almost undrinkable .
has a great clear brown color with hints of ruby red .  the palate is thin for the style .

the pour presented an opaque black body and a head that not only lasted standing tall , but laced the glass brilliantly as it dissipated . some sediment is visable , floating in the glass .  m : thin , watery mouthfeel .

a : deep amber color , transparent , thick foamy head . almost perfect for the style . d : this is n't bad for $ 4.99 a six-pack , and it 's a pretty decent amber , so i 'm giving it moderate ratings .  taste is rich and full , very malty , but the body is too thin for the style . not too bad , could use a little more body , though .
copper.. amber.. crystal clear appearance , wow amazing clarity , with more of a , fruity- aroma than a basic citrus .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel is weak . there 's simply no body here to speak of .

pours a light-rust , transparent brown with an amazing head ; at first tall and solid like a frozen mousse , then craterous and cavernous , finally settling down to a light skim of sudsy foam . excellent lacings and glass leavings .  body is very thin , very watery .

a : the head on this thing is crazy huge . it 's tan and creamy like the head of a rootbeer float poured directly over ice cream . the beer itself is black and very dark brown at the bottom of the glass . lacing is immense , and does not back down while drinking .  t : very bitter and hoppy , some citrus in the background m/d : too thin for my taste , lacks a bit of carbonation , and a bit of a soapy feel .
a : the nicest looking wheatwine that i have ever seen . looks brown until it is held up to the light .  the mouthfeel is thin , and a bit watery .
has a great huge thick fluff head that sits atop of a orange brew . incredible sticky lacing is left .  mouthfeel is thin and watery , although flavors are assertive but simple .
this beer pours perfect . i mean , the color , the head , the consistency , it is all perfect .  this beer has a higher level of carbonation with a thin and watery mouthfeel .
there was a huge amount of brown colored head .  the mouthfeel is thin , and somewhat watery .
amazing looking beer .  watery texture .

glassware - waimea brewing co. pint pours a very nice orange copper with slight tones of amber . the off-white head forms up nice and sticks graciously to the sides of my glass . one of the best appearances i 've seen in a while .  body is thin and watery .

poured this into a guinness extra stout pint glass , and perfectly it does so . mounds of dark tan colored head , and an opaque black colored body that allows some ruby red highlights on the edge of the glass .  there was way too much carbonation , making it burn my tongue . the beer is also thin .

this beer poured out a beautiful clear dark gold color . it was nicely carbonated with a big , fluffy head that clung well to the sides of my glass .  m- very light , almost no body . kinda watery , nothing lingers .

a - no red , bark as night . bitterness in the after taste and not just from the dark chocolate .  surprisingly watery mouthfeel , this is definitely a letdown for a beer that came out of the bottle looking like it was going to kick my ass . i really would like a mouthfeel that 's a little chewier in this beer .

appearance for the darker germans is always an amazing sight in a cold glass ... dark as night .  m : again , to watery , their was no meat to this beer . d : you could probably drink bunch of these , it 's watery enough .

brilliant appearance with the exception of head formation . due to brew pub pour this is hard to judge for me . clear as can be and a very attractive golden hue .  the feel was slippery and as short-lived as the head . with the strong artificial vanilla presence , the lack of bourbon and wood flavors , and the watery feel , michelob winter 's ale is more diet vanilla soda than bourbon barrel aged anything .

appearance , well the beer pours a deep deep black with a lovely tan head which dissapated to leave a ring around the glass .  smells like faint ale , like watered down anchor steam , and i think it tastes like that too . not good , not bad , but definitely a weaning product for your freinds or a session beer . not alot going on , but you could drink a lot of them and not feel overpowered .
cloudy golden hue , superb rocky and foamy head .  m- really thin for a stout with crazy high carbonation .

11/14/2010 : -- popped and poured - -- tasted non-blind over 90 minutes - nose : slightly smoked coffee chocolate malt nose ; expressive body : pours sludgy , with a long-lasting chocolate malt head ; pitch black ; medium-full bodied - actually , it 's considerably lighter on the palate than the motor oil viscosity i was expecting .  now , with that said , you do n't need to slam three of these at a time , like water . generally , i drink beer like water , so the more it taste like water or has just a spritz of taste , that better it is . so , sit back and enjoy this one ; it has the alcohol content to make you feel smooth in just three bottles - that leaves room for the food !
poured a deep opaque brown with a creamy light brown head . fantastic head retention with excellent lacing left behind .  the body is thin .

appearance : beautiful , clear , light amber beer with bubbles rising through the mug to the thin one finger hear . head is moderate in duration with light lacing .  m : water and light chemical dryness . it has no body and very little bite , from either hops or carbonation .

dark , translucent , copper-mahogany in appearance . the creamy , tight , one-finger head lasted the entire drink . talk about fantastic retention . the nose was very weak , even as the beer warmed . this non-offensive brown ale was quite sessionable .  mouthfeel is watery , and despite its meager alcohol content , this one really is n't that drinkable .

the look of this beer was very promising . i 've never had a double pilsner , so i did n't know what to expect , but this has a thin head that is frothy and beautifully stable ( although thin ) . it is perfectly golden and foggy .  m : rather light and fizzy , thin . bit too much carbonation .

poured into a pint glass a : 1/2 finger light tan head with not good retention .  beer is thin , almost watery , with almost no carbonation . depending on your comfort with a `` flat '' beer , this is either a flavor treat or a tactile disappointment .

pours a completely opaque black color , with a tenacious tan head that sticks to the side of the glass .  a medium is rocked by angry carbonation . said carbonation is quite vicious , ushering away in a hurry each sip . overall impression - some ok things going on but the carbonation and bitterness drag it down in general ( not to mention to style ) .

huge dark brown wonderful head with incredible small bubble retention . one of the nicest looking dark ris i have come across . black as fricking midnight . there was none .  thin bodied ! majorly dissapointing . body of the beer carries no flavor !

the beer is a deep black color with a thick tan head , which has receded to a thin film . attractive .  taste : thin honey taste with few other real flavor components . mouthfeel : am i drinking water ?

appearance - poured an opaque black with a frothy patchy quarter inch tan head that falls to patches but leaves patches along the cap .  citrusy and maybe some pineapple as well m : full bodied , harsh bitter mouthfeel that is not very enjoyable really d : not a horrible beer but nothing i would willingly buy again .

poured out of the 750ml caged and corked bottle into an orval chalice , gorgeous brew ... pours a bloodshot brown with creamy lingering lacework after the luxurious head , so appetizing .  same story with the taste , even more so , actually . tasted decidedly boring and flat . not much to cheer about , although i may have to try another if i see it as this is my favorite style of brew .

a - has a great ipa color too it , and a great 2 finger head that last a nice amount of time . also the head leaves a nice lacing on the glass as it dissipates .  mouthfeel is thin , watery , and not very pleasant .

poured into a great divide tulip . very dark , almost black until held up to light . backlighting reveals very clear , deep red . very thin tan head dissipates to a ring almost immediately .  m thin and watery with minimal carbonation .

a : pours a slightly murky amber with copper tones when held to the light . the first pour yields a fluffy off-white head that covers the top 1.5 '' of the glass . retention is substantial , so much that i actually notice the head sticking around and preventing me from dipping into the beer . as it recedes into a light cap on the brew , it leaves a sticky web of dense lacing down the sides of the glass .  tastes sweet and watered down , but agreeable . very slight hop on the finish . give me this over any anheuser-busch ( at least that ive tried ) any day of the week , if i have to drink a macro .

the colour is the epitome of a fine clear copper ale , big points for that , very nice to look at . a shame , considering the ale looks so damned good .  mouthfeel is very thin and watery on the palate .

a : pours with a ferociously rocky , barely off white head . excellent retention . very volatile appearance but also very rich and luscious looking . appearance is hazy with a completely opaque burnt sienna , twenty year old penny color .  mouthfeel is tingly from the bubbles , but thin and somewhat watery .
pours a deep deep mahogany amber brown . moderate dense head of creamy tan foam .  mouthfeel was very thin , unfortunate .

this porter looked beautiful in the pour ... dark brown , almost black . big , fluffy , off-white head that retained well . clouds of lace were left , scattered about the sides of the glass . nice eye-candy .  the mouth is much too thin and watery for this beer , and this ruins what otherwise may have been interesting .

sampled on 7-11-09 bottled on 6-15-09 9.5 % abv pours completely pitch black with a foamy , long-lasting tan head and huge spikes of lacing .  the carbonation was awful though ; it was pretty weak and dull in general and just did not keep it alive .
nice , frothy , creamy three finger head that persists . sheets of lacing ... gorgeous . this is salma hayek gorgeous ... aromas are somewhat sweet .  very watery and pop-like in the mouth .
drachenblut produces a vast amount of light tan head that sticks around for a good bit .  mouthfeel seems incredibly thin for a stout .

375ml bottle with best by date of 05/08/11 poured into a chimay goblet a - deep , hazy golden color , two-inch white head with awesome retention and lacing , really great looking beer s - very yeasty and bready aroma , notes of lemon citrus and white pepper , light boozy heat t - mildly sweet and spicy lemon and white pepper up front , midpalate is pretty yeasty with a sourdough bread component , more lemon and pepper on the finish with a surprisingly strong bitterness that really dries out the finish , decent amount of alcohol heat m - medium-bodied , moderate to slightly higher carbonation , well-balanced finish that is on the dry side , good amount of alcohol warming d - decent in terms of drinkability , but the alcohol is definitely more noticeable than many examples of the style i 've had , and there is a bitterness that i 've not encountered in most other tripels , overall , however , it 's not too harsh on the palate and there is a decent amount of complexity in the flavors that keep it interesting this beer 's entry into the top 100 made me realize i 'd never actually tried it .  mouthfeel : carbonation is too low , and the body is flabby and slick . it is n't too far off-style , overall , but it is burdened with off-flavors , too much diacetyl for my palate , and an unpleasant mouthfeel .

a - pours opaque black with dark brown on the edges . one finger head quickly dissipates to clumps of huge khaki bubbles with moderate lacing .  mouthfeel was overly light and effervescent for a serious stout , but results in a good summer quencher stout .

so lets start with saying i am not a huge porter fan ... we got the sampler at the stockton bj 's and we were really excited for the brown ... turns out we ordered the pitcher of the porter after the sampler ... . pours thick and heavy with med to large head .  mouthfeel , what mouthfeel ? watery .

the beer poured into the glass black with some slight brown translucency . the head was tan to brown , large , and in charge lacing , no coating the glass from top to bottom .  way too thick and syrupy , lowish carbonation , like drinking a sugar solution .
a- pours a deep brownish black with a phenomenal , light brown , 2 finger , fluffy head .  the mouthfeel is hurt by excessive carbonation and fizziness .

looks really great for an english brew due to the richness of the foam .  i really dont like the mouthfeel . too similar to soda - fizzy , and almost gives you the `` burning '' sensation in your mouth , like a cheap light beer .

later in the day , an owner of a different bottle shop told me this was the `` must find '' beer in dallas and was the best stout in all of texas . a : thick , viscous pour with almost midnight black color .  it steals the flavor as the mouth is filled with bubbles rather than beer . the aroma was fantastic for this beer , the foamy mouthfeel highly reduces the overallness of this beer .

a- looks pretty damn good . pours a full , golden colour with very noticeable yeast sediment .  downhill now . i may taste a little of the hazelnut here , but no chocolate or anything like that . watery and unpleasant . this wound up drain pour very quickly.. i usually love the sam smith stuff but i just did n't like this one at all .

appearance : the body has a very dark brown color with some lighter brown highlights . the head is tan in color and makes nice slippery lace that slowly slides down the glass as i drink .  very little carbonation , making it pretty watery .
the czar would not be one of those stout 's . i do n't give a shit .  mouthfeel is extremely watery with almost no carbonation .

appearance & gt ; black like coffee . great lacing . the ipa is so dark , you 'd never recognize it ... in fact , deschutes calls it a new style `` cda '' -- - cascadian dark ale .  not a bad tasting beer , though the carbonation is a bit low . body is n't inappropriate for the style , but something this thin added to the low carbonation ... it was a letdown .

pours lightly sedimented gold with a ludicrously large white foam head that eventually settles to an inch or so of height .  like allagash 's hugh malone , in the epic hopulent , you have a beer that 's so hollow and so devoid of body and character that the hoppiness of it starts working against you .

this beer pours a nearly opaque black color . the head is an inch and a half in height , and recedes slowly into nice lacing .  mouthfeel : light , thin , with an oddly drying and unpleasantly long-lasting finish .
a : slightly hazy golden color with a three finger head . great retention . lacing is also excellent .  very thin .
pours black as night , light coffee color head , medium lacing .  m - thin and watery , and a bit of a disappointment in this category .

just opaque black with a prodigious cinnamon-colored head that , instead of falling , forms swiss-cheese-like holes that undermine the head 's structural integrity until the whole thing slowly collapses like the ottoman empire . very nice lacing , too .  m - creamy , harsh from carbonation and the finish .

a : latitude 48 pours a deep amber color , very clear with 2-3 fingers of off-white head . great looking beer .  feel is remarkably thin , but lots of flavour - raisins , molasses , peaches , prunes , cake mix , rotten apples , burnt sugar .
poured a hazy copper , frothy 1 inch head that diminished to a nice 1/4 inch collar with great retention , puffs of broken lace around glass .  light bodied with a thin texture .

appearance : two fingers of beautiful cloudy white head . there is some seriously wonderful carbonation in this beer . the color is a very see through yellow that just wo n't stop fizzing . this was the most beautiful beer i have ever seen .  flavor is like a fizzy lager , but i 'll be objective for the style . this beer is close to water , and i might only have it on the hottest day to refresh myself . there needs to be a bit more balance as the grains are a little bit offputting in this beer . this beer is just too boring and plain and the little flavor it hasn is n't too great .
a : hazy copper pour with a wispy white head . lacing is great .  m - w a t e r y .

very dark . great heat . the occassionaly streak of beaten egg whites in the otherwise yellowish tan head on the first pour and streaks of chocolate milk foam on the second . nice and thing but not too large .  mouthfeel is very thin and the taste is a little bitter and super dry .

a : poured a tall tan head and has a clear brown color with bright garnet highlights . head remains strong and thick with great lacing .  looks deep brown , reddish around the fringes , small head that does n't last , vague smell of semi-toasted caramel malt , taste is pretty much exactly the same , slightly too thin a body for my liking , but other than that , it 's pretty good .

appearance : the bastard does look dirty ! an intense raisin-puree color with no light , topped by a two-finger caramel-colored head that lasts throughout . very dark and earthy looking , with magnificent lacing to boot .  mouthfeel is bud . ok so this is n't oe 800 but it is bad !
great and lasting head and pale golden beercollor .  mouthfeel gets too flat sometimes .

a - poured into the heart of a snifter this beer as dark a brown as i 've seen . the head is nearly overwhelming at three inches of thick foam .  mouthfeel : very thin , maybe one of the thinnest beers i have ever tasted .
an aggressive pour yields a huge three fingers of bright white head . solid retention with a thick cap .  stiff carbonation , tacky , very acidic .

pours pitch black with a two finger dark chocolate/coffee-colored head with excellent retention , only slowly fading into a lasting cap that coats the glass with chunky rings of soapy lacing .  finish is a great big wallop of diacetyl ... m- thin , undercarbonated d- i likely wo n't finish the bottle .

gobs of thick lacing all down the sies of my glass . scored it a 5 on appearance due to the excellent head rentention and awesome lacing .  it 's thin in the mouth ; a little watery and a little metallic . it 's lightly flavored . it 's a little resiny and it tastes like wheat .

appearance is black like coffee with a white creamy head .  a-thick tan head , dark brown/garnet body s-smoky and malty , biscuit t-smoky front , some toffee , light hop finish m-very thin d-the mouthfeel really throws me off .

no available here in kansas . appearance : this beer was a light , golden yellow . even with a careful pour , there was a decent amount of sediment that made it into the glass . this was mainly due to the absolutely huge amount of bubbles ( caused by the sediment ) that was rising up from below and feeding it . there was a ton of lace left behind , creating solid sheets of foam on the side of the glass .  carbonation is absent .

bright yellow gold liquid with a white head ( one of the prettiest beers i 've seen in some time , reminds me of a gold coin in the sun ) enchanting hoppy aroma .  very little carbonation like a guiness .

pours a copper caramel color with a perfect amount of off-white colored head across the top . huge amounts of lacings stick all over the glass .  my main complaint though , it 's filtered to death and not bottle conditioned ... .just tastes dead , which leads to a poor mouth feel as well .
very good retention . looks perfect .  mouthfeel : light-bodied with a pretty boring finish . kinda watery .
pours an opaque black with a creamy light brown head that retains well and laces the glass .  mouthfeel is very weak and watery , however , leaving me quite disappointed .
pours a dark golden color . off-white head is thick and frothy with alot of staying power . a pretty beer .  m-low carbonation with a dry finish . very watery .
hard pour crowns the beer with a rocky two fingered head that laces the glass as i drink . nice dark brown ale with a lightly off-white head .  mouthfeel : quite watery .
it 's straw yellow , displays effervescent bubbles , has a tight whieat head and great lacing . perfect !  m : really thin , and the major letdown for this beer .

a : pours a nice orange with golden streaks when held to a light . settles to a nice cap and left tons of lacing .  club soda feel at first that peters out to a watery fruit juice feel . one dimensional raspberry flavor , modeled after lindemans and st. louis sweetened lambic sodas .

pours a beautiful head that leaves nothing but a huge lacing behind that sticks oh so well . the head is tan and the color is dark black motor oil , hell yeah !  simply too light in body for the style .

festiveale pours and looks beautiful . it pours with a very good amount of head and retains very well . this brew looks very orangish hazy and i can see bits of unfiltered particles .  m : way too watery , thin bodied .

deep red brown color with a medium thick head and lasting lace .  mouthfeel : thin and watery . carbonation is also pretty low . drinkability : low alcohol and thin body make this beer easy to drink , but there are certainly better porters out there .
a : pours a hazy amber colour . 2 fingers of fluffy white head and great retention .  mouthfeel - thin and under-carbonated .
appearance : pretty much flawless . i love that pinkish orangey color .  the palate is thin .

a : looks great , just like a dark belgian ale should . dark brown with a bit of a misty look smell : smelled like figs and some earthy aromas taste : upon the first sip i almost recoiled , the taste was very similar to tomato puree .  mouth is lighter bodied with absolute zero carbonation .
appearance- pours a brilliant , very clear , orange body with a huge , foamy , light beige head on top . excellent head retention . excellent lacing .  disappointing body -- too light and thin .
appearance lots of frothy head the color of heavy cream .  this is a very thin beer , very watery .
poured into a pint glass with a nice thick frothy soft tan head with a dark colour . has a decent lacing and lasting head .  mouthfeel is super thin , like off-puttingly thin .

it was pitch black even against a light . i gave a hard pour so it had a massive light brown head . it slowly settled into a constant foam with some lacing .  the palate is thin and the aftertaste bitter and tinny but not very citrusy or piney .

the folks at harpoon have left little to the imagination with this brew . indeed , when the bottle says chocolate it really means chocolate . if you like your beer like commercial hip hop - which is to say with little subtlety and less craft , then this is the beer for you . the pour is great , the smell is striking and the taste is somewhere between a smore and zinc lozenge .  the body to is next to non existance ... so what this is the best water i have ever tried , and a easy guzzler , deserves a higher ranking then it has .

i was very impressed by the appearance .  hops , malt , yeast , nothing , but there 's lots of water in it . kind of a weird aftertaste and mouthfeel to it , i have no idea what it is , other than not pleasant for the most part . very cheap , hence , drinkable .

arrived with a half-finger of white head that slowly dissipated , leaving a chunky ring , and lots of rings of lacing down the glass .  m : light , in all aspects , but somehow sticky - from the carbonation , or the tart of sour lemon candy flavours . the traditional flavours are there , but it seems watered down , and the mouthfeel is kind of nasty .

wonderful effervescence on the pour , and a nice off-white head . the lacing was what really impressed me though . i have never seen that before and it was very cool .  the mouthfeel is rather thin and watery , seeming unsuited to the style . overall , the dark chocolate flavours are pleasant , and a welcome change from the cadbury 's dairy milk flavours of young 's which i am more familiar with , but it is not a particulalry good stout , lacking body .
deep , dark mahogany in a color , with a massive , craterous light brown head .  almost flat .
look : pours a clear golden-yellow color with a nice white head .  m : medium in body , but very flat .
pours perfect with a two finger thick head , and an ultra clear copper colored body .  the body is way too light and this beer could use a little higher mash temperature .

superior head retention & lacing s : fruitty , leafy hops , some pineyness & some caramel t : some grapefruit , leafy & piney hops , with a touch of fruittyness up front .  m heavy on the tongue . sweet mellows to a balance of sour and bitter aftertaste ; almost no carbonation .

bottle into tulip . peach colored body with 3 fingers of rose-tinted white head . the body is hazy and light , and the head is shimmering and rocky . the head retains very well , almost like a raspberry soda .  mouthfeel was pretty poor to the point where it felt like i was drinking water .
mountainous unrelenting head with blanketing patches of lacing . truly a beautiful brew .  m : watery , low carbonation , slick .
one good looking beer , lots of foam and some kick ass lacing .  m - watery and dry .

black pour with a small tan head .  taste and mouthfeel - at first i thought the sparkling name was a misnomer however after a few swallows you definitely notice the carbonation . drinkability - definitely a drinkable beer but rather unremarkable other than the carbonation .

okay , let 's get on to the beer : it cascades and forms a beautiful head like a picture perfect guinness . so far , so good .  m/d : a much lighter body than i was expecting . thin , watery , and almost under carbonated .

poured into an imperial pint glass this amber-colored pale ale displayed a thick white head that sustained itself for several minutes . the brilliant clarity and lace left down the sides of the glass enhance the appearance of this ale .  the mouthfeel suffers as that annoying metallic twinge magnifies the less than ample body .

like its brethren , it 's black as the pitch with a tan , foamy top . thus one 's head seems a little more explosive and eruptive , as acid-like bubbles ( think white wine and champagne ) violently force their way to the top . more white house applesauce than biltmore house cabernet sauvignon . i so appreciate these ba varieties of black hole , and i know that cognac version is a real treat . black hole is one versatile stout .  the mouthfeel is very unstout like .
this simply looks damn good .  the carbonation levels and mouthfeel are pretty poor , as it 's a bit watery and leaves nothing to remember it by as far as aftertaste goes .

perfect marks for appearance .  both of these co-mingle into the aftertaste m : light bodied with too much carbonation o : this is a great dessert beer that manages to mimmic apple pie with the spices and apples and is easy to drink , but as a stand-alone `` pale wheat ale , '' this one is way off the mark .
pours a pale amber with a crisp , airy white head that sticks nicely to the glass and leaves lots of fine lacing .  just too thin for style all around .
light bronze with a full , lasting foam .  the beer is straw yellow no retention tastes skunked thin mouthfeel but very drinkable did 22 cans in one night .
this is a really nice looking beer , great lacing and a head that never dies down .  mouthfeel carbonation is very low for the style almost feels flat on the tongue .

reviewed 1/13/2008 ( bottle ) : pours a humongous head , off-white in color , and creamy , with good lacing , very lasting .  almost no mouthfeel whatsoever . this beer needs more body to be truly drinkable . too damn thin .

pours to a creamy yet large bubbled , tan head that has some good staying power . the head leaves some beautiful lacing on the side of my glass too .  m : harsh , with very little carbonation to tone it down .

great creamy looking head with lots of nice bubbles that create crsipness to the mouthfeel . very amber in color .  i was very disappointed when drinking this beer , much much too thin , almost watery thin mouthfeel , really bad when it 's supposed to be a stout .
a-pours a dark brown , almost black liquid with a ton of tight creamy tan head .  the mouthfeel is just strange . fizzy simple beer , over carbonated , but not terribly unpleasant .

this , of course , is from the nitrogen it 's either kegged or bottled with . otherwise , apart from it 's appealing crispness , i 've never found anything about this beer to write home about .  m - i found it very thin and watery , very surprising for a porter .

beauty of a beer . deep orange-amber color with a really solid white head .  mouthfeel was a huge letdown . no carbonation ( not that it was expected ) , and quite thin . despite the thick appearance , mouthfeel is surprisingly thin which feels strange considering the bold flavors .
a : i love the way this beer looks . copper and amberish .  the carbonation is a tad low . i think the lack of carbonation in this beer causes a thin mouthfeel .

giant rocky chocolate-colored head that soon settles to a good-looking skim of brown bubbles that hangs around for awhile , providing good lacing .  mouthfeel : disappointing here . feels thin and kind of watery with agressive carbonation that does not serve the beer well .

appearance- pours a light orange yellowish with a decent one finger creamy head that never really recedes . a nice cap and collar remains leaving a fair amount of lacing .  poured into an imperial nonic a dull brass color with a thin quick to fade soapy-like head atop , aromas are very tame , i picked up some light toast , sweet biscuit , and very faint herbal hops.the feel of this beer was just a mess , sharp and thin the beer was made extremely hard to finish , the beer never mellowed.toasted grain flavors with a ever so light smack of leafy hop in the finish.just a bad beer i wasnt expecting a world beater but a decent quaffing epa , it wasnt that by any stretch , dont spend the money on this it is not worth it .
a : looks as good as any ris i have seen .  after a few sips , the burps from the fizzy carbonation began to set in .
poured ruby black with a tan head that left some lacing .  mouthfeel was super light and watery .

nice looking label , poured into a nonic . this beer looks beautiful in the glass , a bright clear copper/amber with a massive , dense light tan head . sticky , clumpy rings of lacing and great retention maintaining a consistent finger thick head .  the body is thin , verging on watery , and the flavor has very little stick-to-it-iveness as a result .

a large mass of foam settles to a perfect one finger white head that doesnt look like it will budge anytime soon atop with dark brown/orange brew .  mouthfeel - too much carbonation , it has a light feel but instantly foams up in the mouth .
blackstone porter pours a nearly opaque black with a nice light brown head .  m : very thin mouthfeel , there is equal presence in hard-water tap-water .
head is pure white and looks very creamy . one of the best looking beer i 've see .  m : mouth feel is mostly burning and harsh . oily consistency with almost zero carbonation .

this brew appears an amber orange color that is fairly clear displaying rising bubbles of carbonation that support a finger 's worth of creamy tan head .  m : watery , very high carbonation levels , almost unpleasantly active .

appearance : golden with heavy carbonation . nice head , soft and pure white .  mouthfeel : with the chili it felt fuller than it was . the beer definitely is a very light and almost watery . it has a light taste much like a corona or dos equis .

a : big tan head on this beer , 3-fingers worth . it sits on top of a somewhat cloudy beautiful orange beer , visible carbonation though the haze .  m : too light-bodied for me even in a wheat , the flavours dissipate too fast , thin finish .

this pours well , looks great in a wine glass . the lacy layered head is breathing clouds in swirl around the glass .  watery . mild . not much other than the head and lace . almost no character . what finish ? go elsewhere if possible .

okay sam adams let me see your porter ... appearance : a picture perfect pint . two finger head rose right to the top of the glass without me even trying . body is an opaque black/brown that turns to ruby red when held up to light .  thin and weak to the palate gives this beer a poor mouthfeel .
pours a crude oil black with a large mocha head , excellent lacing .  mouthfeel is syrupy , disappointing i guess as it was the only below average characteristic .
pours a golden/straw yellow with a neon greenish hue when held up to the light . lively bubble action feeds a foamy white head that shrinks to a coating but stays for a while .  m : thin and fizzy .
exceptional pour . hazy cedar with a perfect lacy head .  thin and lackadaisical inside of the mouth . totally weak and completely boring .

presentation : classic label and logo , with simple green and black colors , seems very fitting for a beer style that developed during the pre-prohibition era . appearance : very nice amber color , closer to orange . very active carbonation .  375ml bottle poured into tulip april1 2011 a hazy amber with loads of suspended particles and very few bubbles , short lived thin film leaves no lace as expected with this alc % s booze with a little fruity aspect and some earthy tones , fairly intense but lacking the bourbon barrel other then a little sweet oak t not far from the smell but the booze comes off a little harsh , maybe a little vanilla and toffee on top of what i smell m thick and flat with a booze burn that i could live without o not drinking that well fresh , it 's just a little harsh . i understand its 19.1 % but still it feels like i 'm drinking a straight liqueur both in feel and effect out of curiosity i plan on aging a few of these for a decade or so , i could see this doing fairly well if the booze was toned down .

a - poured into a weizen glass . huge billowing foam , good lacing . appearance is actually quite striking . it may also find favor with those who do n't think beer should look cloudy .  first sip reveals a thin watery body with mild carbonation .
the color is really nice ( caramel/orange color ) .  m - thin soda pop feel .

very brilliantly clear , deep red , with a thin off-white-to-tan head . overall , it is somewhat complex and interesting , though i have to say it bombs when looked at as an american amber ale .  not bad flavors , and not a bad combination , but it tastes way watered down and light , especially for a 6.5 % abv . mouthfeel : light ... too light drinkability : high conclusion : good ?
pours with a huge ( two fingers ) bright , white head . the color of this beer is a remarkably clear gold to light amber .  thin mouthfeel . does n't have the body to be even an average amber/ale .
the body is pale lager gold with a two finger thick mostly lasting and quite creamy looking head . beautiful lacing hangs on the inside of the glass like drifts of snow .  the palate is thin .

this beer pours a brilliant copper color into a mauadite tulip .  t-some thin bread-like malt flavor , followed by a pleasant sour-ish orange/pineapple/banana , which is on style . m-the mouthfeel is thin . thin malt , and not nearly carbonated enough for style .

poured from the bottle into a pint glass a - pours a very dark brown with a tint of amber . so dark that even when i hold it up to a lamp , no light gets through . very impressive light brown fluffy head which stays all the way down the glass . leaves behind great lacing , especially in the lower half of the glass .  thin , overcarbonated , and hot with fusel alcohols . scores : appearance 4/5 ; aroma 4.5/5 ; taste 3/5 ; mouthfeel 2 ; drinkability 2/5
a : pours pitch , motor-oil black with an enormous tall brown thick head ; it 's so very thick , almost like hard whipped cream .  mouthfeel is sharp and overcarbonated . much too thin , as well .

light orange with a big bspa head that leaves a good amount of lacing .  the texture is a disappointment , with a thin , light fizzyness that does n't match the rich malty flavors . overall , this beer was complex and enjoyable , but the weak body really deflated the flavors , leaving me wanting for something more substantial .
appearance- wonderful full white head , golden murky pour with very nice lacing .  m- the mouthfeel is very faintly carbonated and watery .
a- cloudy golden tan with a large cream colored head . head fades slowly and leaves some lace on the glass .  mouthfeel was that of a club soda or somehting .

the head is a pillow of dark cream , awesome head retention -- it does n't dissipate at all .  cloying sweet & way too thick for my taste . it tasted more like a thick tart wine than a beer - carbonation , where are you ?

330ml hand wrapped half champagne bottle served in a flute glass.enjoyed on oct11.identified on the package as an oud bruin .  aromas come through but are trumped by a tangy , thin , watery mouthfeel .

pours a nice ruby red with a full inch of fluffy head . the head is very slow to drop and leaves lots of lace behind .  otherwise it is little better than your standard euro pale lager - a little dry and watery . limp mouthfeel , drinkability would be quite good , but it just is n't that good a beer .
a soft pour yields a massive 2.5 finger sandy head . this could be the best looking stout that has ever been in my glass .  m : thin , watery , not very fulfilling .

pours a dark brown almost black hue with amber highlights round the edges . head dies down to a solid layer of foam on top , and leaves nice lacing behind . it 's basically the quintessence of a porter as far as looks are concerned .  mouthfeel was thin and watery and the flavor never did quite live up to the promise of the nose .
beautiful deep ruby red color , three finger thich rich creamy brown to beige head .  the body is thin and the carb a bit distractingly spritzy , even masking the flavor a bit .
appearance : clear orange-brown big head and lots of lacing .  mouthfeel is watered down . a little too much carbonation bite too .
very nice looking beer .  very thin body , low carbonation .

a : deep amber/mahogany , minimal head . nice lacing and plenty of carbonation bubbles oozing from her .  thin and wet bodied . while it looks like i enjoyed this somewhat more than the others that have reviewed it , its still kind of got that leinie 's thing going on .

poured out of a nitro can a black color with a hint of ruby hue ( much less than a guinness ) with a perfect creamy white head that leaves great lacing and has great retention . i love to watch these nitro cans , say what you will about them but they make for a perfect appearance in my opinion .  m-light and actually thin , needs more malt heft to have it fit to style , imho .
bubbly froathy coffee head on a dark brown body .  mouthfeel was thin and flat , although somewhat smooth .

very nice deep brown with some gold highlights , and a huge overflowing white head .  2.0 m : this is one of the oddest and unpleasant mouthfeels i 've had . far too much carbonation and a bone dry finish .
reviewed 8/9/2009 ( bottle ) : pours a somewhat opaque burnt orange colored body , with a big creamy off-white color head , lasting .  the body is thin .
poured out with a beautiful bubble cascde , tan head dark ruby red hues .  m - felt watery and thin .
appearance and drinkability wise this offering is stellar for an ipa . aroma and flavor ... well ... .  mouthfeel is fizzy skunk .

pure bliss ... .it 's that simple pours black with a carmel tone on the edge . darker creamer head then most which holds it 's self up . smells sweat with bourbon . you can taste the bourbon on your tounge as soon as it hits it .  pretty thin mouthfeel , super easy to drink , and cheap enough that it is n't associated with the hipster ironic drinking revival .

fiery burnt orange , a little hazy , topped with a good inch of ivory foam . looks terrific . smells hoppy , as i expected .  m : too astringent d : nice mixed beer , and more beer like than most mixed beers .

looks like a light version of guinness given the amazing falling carbonation . overall : beautiful appearance , not much else .  m - this is where this ale suffers . there is not nearly enough carbonation which makes this way too thin for any ale , let alone a wee heavy .

a : pours a lemony yellow with a billowing bright white head that took forever to slowly fade into a thick fuzzy film that left a solid sheet of lacing down the glass .  there was carbonation observed and the body was a pale yellow . the taste of this brew was fizzy and tingly which is not much to my liking when it comes to taste . even if i really , really liked this brew , i would still say that it is way overpriced .

golden champagne look in the goblet with lots of tiny bubbles and a very dense and lasting snow white head .  m : i 'm somewhat certain that the poor mouthfeel here really damages what could otherwise be an interesting beer.medium bodied with lightish carbonation , yet overall the mouthfeel falls falt and is a bit cumbersome .
a - pours a jet black color , impenetrable to light , with a dark tan half inch thick head .  m : very thin and watered down .
pours black with a big brown head .  body is only about medium or medium light with pretty much no carbonation ... making it feel watered down .
once it settled , it was slightly hazy golden orange with 1.5 fingers of deliciously foamy head .  thin watery mouth feel .
really nice ! very nice overall with an amazing appearance , unreal head retention , great flavor and very pleasant mouthfeel .  too much carbonation , body is lacking .

residing on top is the most amazing three fingers of dark khaki brown head that i think i 've ever seen . multiple gobs , splatters , and tendrils of lace were left to coat the glass .  the mouthfeel is thin and reedy , with some small moments of tacky pastiness .
good lace and excellent retention . great looking beer .  mouthfeel - surprisingly light given its relatively strong flavor . watery and tongue-stingingly carbonated .
a - i just ca n't knock the appearance of boddington 's . same creamy head that lasts forever and ever ... this was n't even a nitro-tap .  the body is quite thin ( below average ) .

i would normally hate to say anything bad about my favorite domestic beer company , but this scotch ale was simply a huge disappointment . it pours a beautiful dark amber , which would lead me to believe i was about to enjoy another wonderful sam adams ale , but that is not the case .  mouthfeel is flat and lifeless without carbonation .

the absolutely most fantastic head ever .  unfortunately , the texture is limp and lifeless , with little crispness or hop bite in the aftertaste . far too watery to be satisfying , and too impotent to be refreshing .

pours amber with a a 4 fingers+ fluffy sand colored head . great lacing & head retention s : a hint of caramel & malt t : sweet malt & herbal/piney hops ; finsihed prickly & semi-malty mf : light/medium bodied with pricklyness , not balanced drinks average , this is a different beer than bottled version ; i 'm so confused ?  m- incredibly thin body with higher than expected carbonation .

once settled , the hat is a solid inch thick , and amazingly tightly packed . it 's like a solid mass of bisque white shaving cream .  light carbonation and light bodied . flavor is sweet that wants to be a milk stout , some caramel and almost a watery finish .
pours a cloudy , orange/amber color . the head on this lasted the entire beer , and left a great amount of lace .  m- very watery !
pours a hazy pale golden orange color with pale tangerine edges and a frothy two finger soapy white head . good retention slowly fading into a lasting cap/ring .  m- watery . really thin .
pours a beautiful deep red color with a huge bubbly tan head that survived for the entire glass despite leaving lots of lace in its wake .  oily i guess , and kinda thin .

the beer pours a pitch-black color with garnet high lights , the head preposterous in size , spumescent in texture and a medium tan or light chocolate color if youre so inclined , the lace forms a thick and glutinous sheet to seal off the glass .  a : golden with a very thin head s : grainy , buttery almost , a sweet breakfast cereal t : watery , sweet with grainy flavors m : nonexistent , might as well be drinking water d : if you live in the twin cities and want a excellently drinkable barbecue or party beer that you can down gallons of this is the one .
thick and fluffy 3 '' + head lasts forever which was surprising for a higher alcohol beer . some decent lacing developed .  carbonation is too high by far .
appearance : yellow in color , amazing head with ok retention , fair lacing .  a little too much roughness . feel is tacky , raw and sweet .
medium brown crystal clear body with loads of ruby highlights . thick , off-white head that leaves a good amount of lacing .  very watery mouth-feel for the style .

a deep ruby red that borders on garnet , it is topped with a fluffy white 1 finger head that leaves sticky streaks of lacing , as well as some spots of foam , all over the sides of the glass . this looks absolutely gorgeous .  not enough carbonation made me give a poor grade for the mouthfeel ... .needs more bubbles , man !

the appearance immeditely tells you that you are drinking a schneider weisse ; it has a deep rich cloudy amber color . the head is huge , typical for a weisse beer , and is managed by pouring it with the bottle opening at the bottom of a weisse beer glass and gradually raising the bottle as the beer flows into the glass . the stark white head has good retention , but does whither by the end of the beer .  mouthfeel is a bit thin on this beer and i think it 's biggest downfall is it 's carbonation .
the beer pours jet black with a thick rusty tan head . the head thins but never disappears and leaves a bunch of lacing .  feel : fizzy , fizzy , fizzy . way too overcarbonated .

a : pours a pitch black with a dark brown head .  body is about medium or so and it majorly lacks carbonation making it feel thinner than it short and maybe a sense of being watered down . the lack of carbonation really hurts it .

a : pours bright cloudy yellow , with a frothy two finger white head . looks great .  mouthfeel is creamy and way too airy and carbonated which almost distracts the flavors out of your mouth before it hits your tongue .
a : pours an almost crystal-clear amber-copper with three fingers of frothy , foamy white head , good retention , and great lacing .  the body was medium/light and a little watery and oily .
color is almost black , some sharp ruby color shoots out of the glass as it is held to light . really great looking beer .  mouthfeel was terrible . very thin and unusually high in carbonation .
pours dark brown , almost opaque , though it shines a deep ruby when backlit . light tan , very creamy head lasts all the way down .  m : extremely syrupy and pretty flat .

poured from a 12 oz bottle into a pint glass , chilled , it pours a beautiful amber color with a nice , cream-colored , dense head that seems to `` stick '' around for a while ; nice retention .  ) t - tart , light raspberry up front but kind of bland and tasteless on the finish ... reminds me of a raspberry spritzer with less flavor m - thin , light , almost flat and a little watery d - it certainly is easy to drink , but it 's something that i would only want on occasion notes : i can appreciate that balancing a fruit beer has to be difficult , but it seems like a lot of them fall short .
] light black , beautiful healthy head .  m : thin , thin , thin .

i love this beer . it looks like i think a wit should look , tastes great .  this beer pours a pale yellow hue with decent carbonation it doesnt have much of any smell at all apart from feint grainish notes , the taste is average and the mouthfeel is totally thin with no body at all , but in saying that this is definately my most favourite indian beer to have with a beautiful indian curry but apart from that leave it well alone unless its the only thing that can cool your thirst at the local curry takeaway .

beer is yellow and clear . forms an impressive head that falls away to a monolayer and leaves lacing on the glass , nice . carbonation is moderate and steady . looks good . we went there one night and drink 2 $ of red stripes in 2 hours .  mf : too smooth and too wet .
pours a great clear gold color with a big fluffy/rocky white head .  mouthfeel is light bodied with a watery texture .
a : pitch black . seriously pitch black with zero light coming through .  mouthfeel is poor for an unfiltered beer .

the brew looks gorgeous when poured into the chalice i drank it in - almost a ruby color .  interestingly , this beer is way over carbonated to giving you quite a bite and drying the finish out too much . i do n't think it 's infected , but there 's something seriously wrong with the carbonation level .
beautiful pour from the nitro can with the cool cascading effect .  m-feels thin in my mouth , almost watery , especially when compared to my expectations based on the appearance .

almost copper in color , with a very nice off-white foamy head that does n't vanish like so many beers .  it is slightly sour and has traces of coffee caramel and chocolate mouthfeel : is horribly carbonated . the mouthfeel is so badly carbonated that you have to struggle with the carbonation bubbles wrecking the top of your mouth .

a - very attractive cloudy dark brown color with a substantial foamy off-white head and good lacing .  heavy carbonation from the bottle supports a thick , pillow head the color of sand . not light enough , not refreshing enough , not ... pilsner-y enough . mouthfeel : none of the characteristic scouring you 'd expect .
dark brown ( bordering on black ) with a very creamy tan head that lasts the duration .  m : light bodied and low carbonation . texture is water like and leaves a very off bitter after taste .
pretty good retention and lacing . lovely .  a bit overcarbonated on the feel , has a very harsh tingle to it . pretty thin and wet otherwise , not impressed .
arrived with a nice thick half inch layer of white foam that ends up a thin wispy cover that remains to the end of the glass and leaves lots of lacing .  m - over-carbonated , felt like hard cider .

pours an opaque black , thick brown head forms , great retention as it settles down to a solid later , massive lacing on the glass .  very watery in the mouth , but there are nice roasted notes , and i was quite shocked that there were some malty traces in there .

a : beautiful deep golden , best feature of this beer s : sweet lemon , grassy , citrusy t : i 've come to expect a certain taste from a pale ale , and this does n't measure up on draft at the home kegerator , pint glass  mouthfeel also thin .

nice shapely imperial pint , creamy off-white head that takes up the top 1/2 inch of the glass . below is a midnight black liquid through which no light passes .  m - overwhelmed by all this carbonation .

great color full bodied.lemony undertones , can hold up to almost any food.glad i finally tried it.all the glb beers i have had have bben great , still need to try the eliot ness , being its my fav type , the vienna style .  maybe corriander and orange peel m : flat flat flat d : not too bad , i kind of like the funkiness in this one .
extremely nice clear reddish/amber colour with a white head that disapear not too quickly .  carbonation is very light . it has almost a flat feel to it .
it 's a damn nice looking beer in the glass .  mouthfeel is thin and almost watery .

the beer arrived with an inch of very dense tan foam which left plenty of lacing on the glass as the beer progressed . the brew itself was a very deep amber - so dark i would n't have been surprised if you told me it was a brown ale .  watery body , i know swarz can be light but this is bmc-like . very light roasted flavor on the palate ... just weak in flavor and body .
this beer looks very lively with tons of bubbles rising to the top of the glass . this beer really has a great appearance .  mouthfeel is very thin and watery .

pours a bright , copper-ruby body that turns peach in the light . carbonation level is quite impressive , despite the poorly retained , peachy white head that recedes to a foamy collar .  the result is a thin , watery , and disappointing mouthfeel .

pours a deep dark black . a heavy tan head and very nice lacing follow this stout down the glass .  m - watery mouthfeel is really disappointing . o - good flavor and balance , but the mouthfeel really hurts this one .
a : pours a slightly translucent black with a substantial yellowish head and excellent lacing .  mouthfeel was very thin .
appearance -- pours a honey amber hue with two stiff fingers of lily-white head . lots of craggy lace . looks good !  m - thin-bodied with sharp , fizzy carbonation .
the color was spot on nice big brown color , but with nice clearity . a white head and decent lacing .  feel is disappointing . very thin and watery , light body and carbonation .

great clouds of clingy creme ! the dark brown and brandy booze looks ready to go ... smells of three heavy hitters ; coffee , cocoa , and caramel . overall a solid seasonal , one that makes me very excited for the colder seasons as those are just as good here in co as are the warm ones  soft mouthfeel , fizzy .
bottled january 20 , 2010 750ml into a founders snifter , pours a reddish pink with some orange highlights . plenty of cantillon signature funk .  m : prickly in the extreme . way too carbonated .

the pour is great , super lacing and a black hue with flashes of brown on the sides , the head is a khaki color . beautiful .  mouthfeel is thick and syrupy , which would be fine , except there is virtually no carbonation to give the back of your throat a break . in sum , if it were n't for the carbonation issue , this would be an extraordinary beer .
head is still complete intact ! beautiful color and quite dark for the style . looks magnificent !  the palate is thin but ok .
bright shiney new copper colored beer , almost neon .  m : that 's where the beer lacks . watery feel , really nothing extraordinary . carbonation level is a bit low for the style ( mid-low ) .

it 's not just the coffee-like aroma of some of the darker malts , but real quality coffee . appearence is nice , black , but not quite opaque body . the head is large and frothy and lasts .  mouthfeel is ruined by the overcarbonation , which seems to be an issue with this brewer . other than the ultra-fizzed body , this is an okay brown ale that does even better if the chill is taken off a bit .
big time froth , hung out for awhile . pours a way dark brown slash black .  m - typical shipyard fizziness . why do all of their offerings feel like i have pop rocks in my mouth ? average .
