a - pours a hazy dark yellow with a beautiful 1.5 finger head that stays around for a while s - you definitely wo n't mistake this for anything but a hefeweizen .  m-carbonation is present , but low , maybe lacking . body is flabby . signature creaminess is n't really here .

a- poured into an allagash tulip glass , this beer pours a clear copper color and boasts a sticky , off-white , two-finger head that leaves some great looking lacing in the form of web-like rings along the glass after each sip . the head settles to a patchy , foamy layer that sticks around for quite a while .  this beer is over carbonated and will make you burp like your grandfather used to .

the body of this beer might be the most visually pleasing beer i have ever seen . dark in appearance in low light , i recommend that you view it with a strong light behind it . i did that and it presents as a gorgeous , glowing red maple with hundreds of bubbles rising from the depths . really cool . notes : with a much more dramatic appearance and more body it is not the same as optimator but i think that there are a lot of similarities outside of those things .  again , the carbonation is very sharp on the tip of my tongue , which kills a lot of the missing flavor maybe ? i am not impressed by the flavor , but i 'd still take it over a macro .

really bizarre head , something i do n't think i 've ever seen from a beer . loads of lacing . appearance was outstanding , but the taste did n't live up to that high precedent .  almost flat and not very impressive m - carbonation is low and mouthfeel is thin and watery .
mini keg i bought at steve 's for 35.99 a-yellow golden orange , tons of foamy head .  m 2 light and fizzy , too fizzy .

dark orange with the perfect ipa color .  a - poured into a glass , gold in color , nice thick white head , good lacing s - grains , a little hops , not much really t - okay here it goes , metallic , sweet , light hops , grassy , not a lot of flavor , crisp m - thin , goes down like water , some carbonation , a little hoppy bite in the finish d - no doubt i could slam back a few of these fairly quickly , especially when it 's hot .

dark brown to black with ruby highlights , a full creamy tan head that lasts , decent carbonation , and decent lace rings .  soapy and bitter . no complexity , nothing to savor , nothing that entices the palate , nothing that slakes the thirst . huge let down .

a : poured with around 10 fingers of white head when combining the 4 pours it took to get an 11.2 oz bottle into my glass . billowy white head . almost looks black until held up to the light . then a nice deep ruby/rust color .  mouthfeel - very thin .

very good appearance , gorgeous clear chestnut brown color . head was a bit quick but is a nice tan hue .  serving type : bottle at the beach appearance : transparent yellow/goldish ... taken straight from the bottle most of the time smell : smells like my frat house taste : i do n't know ... mouthfeel : like seltzer water , but not as bad as some of the macro's drinkability : sure , i could drink this all day long , especially on a hot summer day at the beach - but would i enjoy it ?
black with ruby red highlights and a nice creamy brown head .  mouthfeel is light bodied with a mild effervescence and a thin and watery finish .

appearance : this brew pours with a marvelous eggshell colored head . lacings are plentiful and head retention is long . excellent first impression .  carbonation on this is tough to handle for me . very fizzy .

very strange ipa , that i 'm sorry to say , i just do n't like . it smells good by itself , looks good ( has great head actually ) , but the taste ... starts out with some malty goodness , then comes the hops , which ai n't that bad either .  the mouthfeel is rather disappointing for the style and really is what separates this from a quality belgian . quite watery and light to medium bodied .

this pours out equal parts beer and head , completely filling the very large draak tulip to its golden rim with eggshell white head , a big styrofoam brick that hangs out on top of a tawny orange-gold haze - visible yeast particulate and rising bubbles throughout .  thin and uninspiring . contained none of the characteristics typically found in a stout . this is more like a light bodied porter .
looks like a really great heff .  mouth : thin and veering toward over-carbonation . almost like cola .
pours black with 2 fingers of mocha colored head .  there 's no carbonation , which was really a letdown for me . the overall mouthfeel was thin and unimpressive .

poured into a duvel glass the golden straw color and extremely white fluffy head are beautiful . this is one of the most beautiful double ipa 's i 've ever had .  mouthfeel is pretty thin and watery .

poured into a piratt tulip . a : deep copper/amber color . really wonderful when held up to the light . creamy white head with less than 1/2 fingers .  m - overly carbonated , not very stout-like at all .

this is one of the best looking hefewiezens i have ever seen cloudy copper in color huge white head that stuck around for a while leaving nice lace on the way .  m : too much carbonation and very thin and watery .

22oz pours a very impressive black with a cascade of dark brown bubbles . awesome head . i found myself watching the head settle .  i was really not impressed with this one . i probably will not be buying this one again although i have had worse beers . and i can not seem to put any food that might taste good with it maybe bbq ?
a : black , light tan head , awesome retention & lacing .  it had a thin and watery mouthfeel and reminded me of a shandy ... or maybe just a lemon soda .
a & # 8211 ; nice , lacy , beautiful red color and eggshell head .  the body was very weak and insubstantial .
bottle : poured a deep burgundy brown color ale with a big foamy head with great retention and lacing .  mouthfeel is almost non-existent ; standard macro thin feel .

this is a beautiful looking beer , a real honey amber color . no head to speak of which is my only quibble with its appearance , this is an otherwise gorgeous looking beer .  when i walk in and see that all they have is watery lite/light beers i look for the darkest one . it has good flavor , but it 's so thin that you forget you 're drinking a beer . after a while the aftertaste begins to build up in your mouth and you wish you had some clorox to gargle . so this beer is n't great , but it 's better than drinking miller lite , bud light , or coors light all night .

looks very inviting , good head retention .  just typical of the style , upon further review ( 2nd bottle ) way too cloying mf : thinnish with lively carbonation drinks a bit slow , too much cornyness .

jet black pour with a creamy tan head that laced well . fantastic appearance , and one that would give any stout a run for its money . it looks like its from a nitro-tap , but it is n't , so bonus brownie points there !  reviewed 10/26/2007 ( tap @ dragonmead brewery , warren , mi ) : pours a clear pale amber colored body , with a pure white head , small bubbles . spices , deep woods . floral , light flavor . some spices , watery . somewhat alcoholy .
wonderful golden color with a pillowy white head that retreated and left a solid lacing .  super thin and carbonated for the style .

review from notes taken 5/22/10 poured from a bomber into a snifter it appears a perfectly clear orange color with a finger of fluffy head that retains well and sticks in patches about the glass .  the mouthfeel is too much to handle - one small sip allows for an explosion of fiz that takes up my entire mouth making it hard for me to really enjoy this .

stout reviews are starting to sound redundant to me ... so , i 'll just say that this is one exceptional stout . an exquisite example of an american stout .  ingredients : water , light barley malt , brewer barley , rye malt , sugar . lifeless feel with weak carbonation and cloying sweetness . sweet like soda , somewhat astringent .

pours a beautiful ruby color , with a substantial rocky head , that diapates slowy with tons of lacing ... . looks great in the glass , plus anything coming out of a 3 liter bottle wins points just for being cool .  m - very light , too light actually .

a : mildy darkish golden copper that is a bit haze with a few rising bubbles visible . it has a good size off-white head that turns rocky as it settles reasonably slowly and leaves pretty nice lacing .  watery texture and not very well balanced .

ours a deep orange-amber with a huge frothy head and lots of lace . tons of visible carbonation as well makes this look just about perfect .  first sip reveals an average to lite body with very fine fizzy carbonation that bubbles and then disappears quickly . the beer goes completely thin and watery on the swallow .

a - pitch black , the mild pour continued to inflate a large three-finger khaki head . a bit of cascading occurred before the head showed an incredible display of endurance . thick lace is left on the glass as well . brilliant .  this beer very thin in feel , the head contributes some thickness , but not enough .

pouring into a tulip from a 22 oz chilled bottle . pours a slightly ruby/honey color with a creamy , tightly-packed eggshell colored 1/2 finger thick head .  mouthfeel is a disappointment , with a nearly flat , slick character . [ note : upon opening the can i noticed nothing that would indicate problems with carbonation . aside from the weak mouthfeel , this is a solid take on the style that first got me into craft beer several years ago ( altbier , that is , not `` american amber ale '' as denoted on this website ) .

lots of chunky lace on the glass . with some strain , i can detect a faint haze . otherwise , this is a lovely copper-amber color . gorgeous . as expected , a beautiful ( if mild ) fresh hop aroma .  mouthfeel is quite thin , which is evident from the first sip .
excellent retention and lacing .  the palate is thin .

a : looks magnificent in a glass , burnt yellow-orange , with a big puffy , white head with oustanding lacing as the beer is drunk .  refreshing , might be better enjoyed on a sunny day m : do n't like the feel , light and watery , the carbonation bites at the inside of my mouth d : easy to drink , although most light bodied beers are .
this beer looks amazing . it pours a glowing dark red with an eggshell colored rocky head that leaves gobs of lace on the glass .  m : light , lacking body .
the beer pours a dark dar dark black color with a dark brown head . it 's a nice looking stout .  mouthfeel is thin week and lackluster .
appearance- pours a brilliant deep red , nearly amber color with a big light beige head that billows and lingers .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and watery .
this beer looks truly incredible . truly beautiful .  mouthfeel : extremely thin - what were you expecting from ab ?
started off a beautiful dark amber , almost black unless light hit it .  mouthfeel is thin and very watery cool can .

pours a unpenetrating dark oily black but seems light ... tan head with exceptional lacing ... thick head present throughout ... smells very simply of chocolate , caramel , and alcohol ... very nice ... whoa , explosion of flavor ... the dry hopping gives this a nice finish ... robust dark chocolate and coffee flavors dominate with a strong and full flavored finish ... damn , this one 's good ... i thought the high alcohol would give this one a slight burn , but it does n't ... very rich and refreshing ... very bold , lightly thick , and refreshing ... again , the hop finish gives this imperial stout an amazing touch ... no stale aftertaste which i sometimes get with stouts ... overall , you 'll love this one ...  thin harsh mouthfeel .

a : copper-amber with a exceptional head , continual lacing even after it subsides .  mouthfeel , as i mentioned , is way too light , turning this beer into a fizzy bitter water .

lots of carbonation which created a nice shimmer in the pale gold beer .  everything suggested about complexity and structure within the nose and the appearance is met with a waters , formless and thin feeling beer . some wheat prevails , and some smoothness of texture , but there is not half as much of the pillowy champagne carbonation that i would have wanted .

a - the tall pour leaves a beautiful looking beer in the glass , one of the things leinie 's is known best for . the tall , foamy head with the medium-packed , sparkly bubbles is a deep bone color and resembles egg-crate foam . superb retention and three stages of collar lace on the glass .  the mouthfeel is flat , slick and oily . it tastes like the beer has been watered down .
super carbonated , tons of bubbles w long lasting white head . very sticky , leaving tons of lacing .  the body was thin for the style , almost watery , and did n't linger on the tongue .
appearance : it pours a deep blood red with a fluffy , tight bubbled , head . it is very clear and the head leaves a very sticky lace .  body is watery , especially considering the rich flavours .
terrific retention and tons of great , sticky lace . fantastic .  the mouthfeel is far too thin for the style though , leaving its drinkability only mediocre .

it pours with a thick and creamy head . lots of lacing . the color is a very crisp amber .  i think that the lack of carbonation ultimately hurts this beer ; the extra carbonation would add sum much needed body to this beer , which would help balance the sweetness .

thick two finger tan head with great retention . clingy lacing all the way down to the bottom .  the mouthfeel is on the lighter side of medium bodied with a watery texture , and aggressive carbonation . however , the thin body really detracts from my enjoyment of the rest of the beer .

bought a single at trader joe 's ... great price ... outstanding looking beer from the pour ... a dark coffee appearance with a rich and thick tan head ... lacing is outstanding on my pint glass throughout ... smells of coffee and chocolate ... malts dominate ... a tad of roasted oats in there too ... wow ... very smooth and rich mouthfeel ... a charcoaled and roasted aftertaste which grows with time ... very balanced and full of flavor ... the smoothness of this beer would bring praise from even those who do n't typically like stouts ... enjoyed this one on a cold and dark thursday night ... would highly rec .  this is a pretty dark lager.it 's honey colored , but the head is small and disappears fast.this smells a little hoppy , with some fruitiness and yeast.this is n't a bad tasting lager.it 's hoppier than most with a hint of cooked veggies or fruit.the big problem with this beer is the weak head and the poor m/f.this is very weak and watery , which leads me to say i do n't think i 'd buy this again .

i 've got ta say , it looked sharp in the glass . lacing is gorgeous and the head retention is relatively low but very thick and creamy .  mouthfeel is poor , with not enough carbonation to carry the drink and a thin body . the main flaw ( mouthfeel ) ca n't really be corrected with age .
good 1 inch of clingy foam . looking delectable .  the body was far too thin for a stout , i 've had pale ales that were more mouthfilling .
this beer pours an absolutely gorgeous blackness with a darker tan foam that hangs around quite well .  mouthfeel of quickly fading , no presense beer .

the appearance is beautiful the smell is nice . the taste is ... i ca n't describe it other than saying it tastes like archie and it 's hipster .  very dry throughout the palate , and really quite watery , if not thin . just feels very wet and then leaves very dry .

a : pours a cloudy , dark golden w/ 1.5-inch off-white , foamy head . lots and lots of lacing .  m/d : very light and high carbonation . thin and watery .

750ml bottle that was being sold cheap at the local bottle shop . into the duvel tulip it goes . a- bright and clear golden colored body with a steady stream of carbonation from the `` d '' in the bottom of my glass . a finger of lasting white head forms . not the most interesting beer of its style , but the blowout price is enough to make me go pick up a few more and drink one every so often .  the feel was pretty poor . it was like flat soda .
